{"title_page": "Nabhendu Sen", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2018}}\n'''Nabhendu Sen''' (31 August 1944 \u2013 25 September 2008) was born in Kolkata. He was a Bengali dramatist, sculptor and artist. \n[[File:Nabhendu sen.jpg|thumb|Nabhendu Sen (31 August 1944 \u2013 25 September 2008)]]\n\n==Early life==\nNabhendu Sen studied from the Government college of Art and Craft. He joined ''Nakhatra'' as a set designer and was attracted towards this medium. He wrote his first drama ''Nayan Kabirer Pala'' when he was 24.<ref name=Nayan_Kabir>[http://rangasram.org/nayan-kabirer-pala.html Nayan Kabirer Pala]</ref>\n\n==List of drama performed and published==\n\n1.\tNayan Kabirer Pala(\u09a8\u09af\u09bc\u09a8 \u0995\u09ac\u09bf\u09b0\u09c7\u09b0 \u09aa\u09be\u09b2\u09be) written in 1968, staged by Nakshatra 1969, Direction: Shamayal Ghosh, published in [[Bohurupee]] 1971, reprinted in Bahurupee 1981 and broadcast from Calcutta Doordarshan Center in 1974. This drama was received very well by the critics and is still talked about.<ref name=\"google_e_book\">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DZ9zvZc09UcC&pg=PA170 | title=Indian Drama in English | first=Kaustav | last=Charaborty | publisher=PHI Learning | year=2011 | isbn=9788120342897 | accessdate=27 October 2018 }}</ref>\n\n2.\tShamabeto Sawal Jabab, written in 1975, staged by Krantikal 1975, Direction: Self, published in Group Theatre 1978\n\n3.\tPantomime, written in 1976-1977 (story line: Dibyendu palit), staged by Krantikal 1978, Direction: Self, published in Bahurupee 1980\n\n4.\tTaalpatar Shepai / Dwijabhumi / Sujan Choukider, written on 1980, staged in 81 by Krantikal, Direction: Self, published in Group Theatre 1982\n\n5.\tAbhimukh,<ref name=samstab>[http://www.theatresamstab.org/profile.html Samstab -The Group]</ref> written in 1983, staged by Shangstab 1984, Direction:  Dwijen Bandopadhya, published in Bahurupee 1987\n\n6.\tMallabhumi,<ref name=\"samstab\"/> written in 1984, staged by Shangstab 1984, Direction: Dwijen Bandopadhya, staged by Krantikal 1985, Direction: Dulal Chakravarti \" Published in one-act drama collection \"Nirbachito Dash\"  edited by  Satya Bhaduri. Mallabhumi has been selected in the syllabus of Extra Departmental Course,  Jadavpur University, for the year 2005-2006\n\n7.\tPrajayini, written in 1984, published in NatyaPatra (Kathakriti) 1998\n\n8.\tShatru Sampatti written in 1986, staged by Natyodol  2000, Direction: Sanjeeb Roy, published in Bahurupee 1998\n\n9.\tAdab (story:[[Samaresh Basu]]) written in 1987\u20131988, staged by Bokaro Natya Academy & Krantikal 1988, Direction: Self, published in  Asamayer Natya Bhabna 2000\n\n10.\tBhamma, based on [[Uncle Vanya]] by Chekov, written in 88, staged by Gandhar 1989, Direction: Asit    Mukhopadhay published in  SAS Natyapatra 2003\n\n11.\tIshtikutum written in 1989 (A part of novel Balidan by [[Atin Bandyopadhyay]]), staged by Krantikal 1990,     Direction: Self, published in Shudhu Theatre 1991\n\n12.\tPostmortem, written in 1992, staged by Bokaro Natya Akademy & Krantikal 1993, Direction:Self, published in  Group Theatre 2001\n\n13.\tArchimedeser Mrityu, written in 1993 staged by Krantikal, Direction:Self, published in SAS Natyapatra 2000\n\n14.\tTulshi baner bagh written in 1992-1993 staged by Bokaro Natya Academy & Krantikal 1993, Direction: Self, published in NatyaPatra (Kathakriti) 1999 & in the one-act drama collection \"Nirbachito Panch \" edited by Satya Bhaduri\n \n15.\t Samapatan written in 1977(as Badhyabhumee) published in SAS Natyapatra 2002\n\n16.\tNeel mati Lal kankad<ref name=\"Anandabazar Patrika - 14 May 2005 - Lal Kankad Periya\">{{cite news|url=http://archives.anandabazar.com/archive/1050514/14play1.htm|title= Lal Kankad Periya |last=Ghosh|first=Biplab Kumar|date=14 May 2005|work=[[Anandabazar Patrika]]}}</ref><ref name=\"The Telegraph - 05Aug2005 - Life, as seen by Ramkinkar Baij\">{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1050805/asp/atleisure/story_5075185.asp|title=Life, as seen by Ramkinkar Baij |last=Ojha|first=Satadru|date=5 August 2005|work=[[The Telegraph (Calcutta)|The Telegraph]]}}</ref> written in 2004, staged by Mukhomukhi 2005, Direction:  Biplab Bandopadhya, published in SAS Natyapatra 2005\n\n==Awards==\nAwarded the prize of Outstanding Dramatist of the year 2000 (Full length) by West Bengal Government on 1 October 2002\n\n==Books published==\nNatyasangraha (Vol. 1)  (Books, Hardcover) Dey's Publishing {{ISBN|978-81-295-1578-0}}\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sen, Nabhendu}}\n[[Category:Bengali theatre personalities]]\n[[Category:Culture of Kolkata]]\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:2008 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2018}}\n'''Nabhendu Sen''' (31 August 1944 \u2013 25 September 2008) was born in Kolkata. He was a Bengali dramatist, Sculptor and Artist. \n[[File:Nabhendu sen.jpg|thumb|Nabhendu Sen (31 August 1944 \u2013 25 September 2008)]]\n\n==Early life==\nNabhendu Sen studied from the Government college of Art and Craft. He joined ''Nakhatra'' as a set designer and was attracted towards this medium. He wrote his first drama ''Nayan Kabirer Pala'' when he was 24.<ref name=Nayan_Kabir>[http://rangasram.org/nayan-kabirer-pala.html Nayan Kabirer Pala]</ref>\n\n==List of drama performed and published==\n\n1.\tNayan Kabirer Pala(\u09a8\u09af\u09bc\u09a8 \u0995\u09ac\u09bf\u09b0\u09c7\u09b0 \u09aa\u09be\u09b2\u09be) written in 1968, staged by Nakshatra 1969, Direction: Shamayal Ghosh, published in [[Bohurupee]] 1971, reprinted in Bahurupee 1981 and broadcast from Calcutta Doordarshan Center in 1974. This drama was received very well by the critics and is still talked about.<ref name=\"google_e_book\">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DZ9zvZc09UcC&pg=PA170 | title=Indian Drama in English | first=Kaustav | last=Charaborty | publisher=PHI Learning | year=2011 | isbn=9788120342897 | accessdate=27 October 2018 }}</ref>\n\n2.\tShamabeto Sawal Jabab, written in 1975, staged by Krantikal 1975, Direction: Self, published in Group Theatre 1978\n\n3.\tPantomime, written in 1976-1977 (story line: Dibyendu palit), staged by Krantikal 1978, Direction: Self, published in Bahurupee 1980\n\n4.\tTaalpatar Shepai / Dwijabhumi / Sujan Choukider, written on 1980, staged in 81 by Krantikal, Direction: Self, published in Group Theatre 1982\n\n5.\tAbhimukh,<ref name=samstab>[http://www.theatresamstab.org/profile.html Samstab -The Group]</ref> written in 1983, staged by Shangstab 1984, Direction:  Dwijen Bandopadhya, published in Bahurupee 1987\n\n6.\tMallabhumi,<ref name=\"samstab\"/> written in 1984, staged by Shangstab 1984, Direction: Dwijen Bandopadhya, staged by Krantikal 1985, Direction: Dulal Chakravarti \" Published in one-act drama collection \"Nirbachito Dash\"  edited by  Satya Bhaduri. Mallabhumi has been selected in the syllabus of Extra Departmental Course,  Jadavpur University, for the year 2005-2006\n\n7.\tPrajayini, written in 1984, published in NatyaPatra (Kathakriti) 1998\n\n8.\tShatru Sampatti written in 1986, staged by Natyodol  2000, Direction: Sanjeeb Roy, published in Bahurupee 1998\n\n9.\tAdab (story:[[Samaresh Basu]]) written in 1987-1988, staged by Bokaro Natya Academy & Krantikal 1988, Direction: Self, published in  Asamayer Natya Bhabna 2000\n\n10.\tBhamma, based on [[Uncle Vanya]] by Chekov, written in 88, staged by Gandhar 1989, Direction: Asit    Mukhopadhay published in  SAS Natyapatra 2003\n\n11.\tIshtikutum written in 1989 (A part of novel Balidan by [[Atin Bandyopadhyay]]), staged by Krantikal 1990,     Direction: Self, published in Shudhu Theatre 1991\n\n12.\tPostmortem, written in 1992, staged by Bokaro Natya Akademy & Krantikal 1993, Direction:Self, published in  Group Theatre 2001\n\n13.\tArchimedeser Mrityu, written in 1993 staged by Krantikal, Direction:Self, published in SAS Natyapatra 2000\n\n14.\tTulshi baner bagh written in 1992-1993 staged by Bokaro Natya Academy & Krantikal 1993, Direction: Self, published in NatyaPatra (Kathakriti) 1999 & in the one-act drama collection \"Nirbachito Panch \" edited by Satya Bhaduri\n \n15.\t Samapatan written in 1977(as Badhyabhumee) published in SAS Natyapatra 2002\n\n16.\tNeel mati Lal kankad<ref name=\"Anandabazar Patrika - 14 May 2005 - Lal Kankad Periya\">{{cite news|url=http://archives.anandabazar.com/archive/1050514/14play1.htm|title= Lal Kankad Periya |last=Ghosh|first=Biplab Kumar|date=14 May 2005|work=[[Anandabazar Patrika]]}}</ref><ref name=\"The Telegraph - 05Aug2005 - Life, as seen by Ramkinkar Baij\">{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1050805/asp/atleisure/story_5075185.asp|title=Life, as seen by Ramkinkar Baij |last=Ojha|first=Satadru|date=5 August 2005|work=[[The Telegraph (Calcutta)|The Telegraph]]}}</ref> written in 2004, staged by Mukhomukhi 2005, Direction:  Biplab Bandopadhya, published in SAS Natyapatra 2005\n\n==Awards==\nAwarded the prize of Outstanding Dramatist of the year 2000 (Full length) by West Bengal Government on 1 October 2002\n\n==Books Published==\nNatyasangraha (Vol. 1)  (Books, Hardcover) Dey's Publishing {{ISBN|978-81-295-1578-0}}\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sen, Nabhendu}}\n[[Category:Bengali theatre personalities]]\n[[Category:Culture of Kolkata]]\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:2008 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "cap, punct", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nabhendu_Sen"}
{"title_page": "Paul H. Ramsey", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{no footnotes|date=November 2019}}\n{{More citations needed|date=November 2019}}\n}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name=Paul Hubert Ramsey\n|birth_date= {{Birth date|1905|2|2}}\n|death_date= {{death date and age|1982|2|15|1905|2|2}}\n|image=\n|caption=\n|nickname=''Sheik''\n|birth_place=[[Springfield, Ohio]]\n|death_place=[[Coronado, California]]\n|allegiance=[[United States|United States of America]]\n|branch=[[United States Navy]]\n|serviceyears=1927-1966\n|rank=[[Vice admiral (United States)|Vice Admiral]]\n|unit=\n|commands=[[VF-2|Fighter Squadron 2 (VF-2)]]\n|battles= [[World War II]]\n*[[Battle of the Coral Sea]]\n[[Korean War]]\n|awards=[[Navy Cross (United States)|Navy Cross]]\n|relations=\n|laterwork=\n}}\n'''Paul Hubert Ramsey''' was a World War II [[naval aviator]] of [[United States Navy]] (USN).\n\n==Early career==\nRamsey graduated from [[United States Naval Academy]] in 1927 and earned his wings in 1930. In 1930's he served on carriers [[USS Lexington (CV-2)|Lexington]] and [[USS Saratoga (CV-3)|Saratoga]]. He was promoted to [[Lieutenant Commander]] on 1 July 1941 and became the [[commanding officer]] of [[VF-2|Fighter Squadron 2 (VF-2)]]. During the early stage of [[Pacific War]], his [[executive officer]] was [[Lieutenant (navy)|Lieutenant]] [[James H. Flatley|James Flatley]]. They both participated in the [[Battle of the Coral Sea]] in May 1942, however Flatley was transferred to [[VF-42|Fighter Squadron 42 (VF-42)]] just prior to the battle but managed to get permission to participate in the operation. At the time of the battle, VF-2 was assigned to carrier Lexington.\n\n==Coral Sea==\nOn 7 May, Lieutenant Commander Ramsey led a group of [[Grumman F4F Wildcat]] fighters to escort [[Douglas TBD Devastator]] from [[VT-2]] in the attack that sank light carrier [[Japanese aircraft carrier Sh\u014dh\u014d|''Sh\u014dh\u014d'']]. In response to sinking of ''Sh\u014dh\u014d'', [[Imperial Japanese Navy]] (IJN) main carrier force launched a night strike on USN carriers composed of 15 [[Nakajima B5N]] and 12 [[Aichi D3A]] bombers. Ramsey led a group of F4F Wildcats to intercept. He set up an ambush in heavy overcast weather, which resulted in numerous losses of IJN aircraft and some of their most experience pilots. He personally destroyed two B5N [[torpedo bombers]].\n\nThe following day, on 8 May, Lieutenant Commander Ramsey was involved in Combat Air Patrol over friendly carriers. His group of F4F Wildcats spotted an approaching formation of D3A [[dive bombers]] at a higher altitude. However, they were unable to climb in time to intercept, due to the poor climb rate of F4F Wildcat and relatively high altitude difference. After the enemy dive bombers made their attack on the USN carriers, he and his wingman spotted [[Mitsubishi A6M Zero]] at a lower altitude and dived on it. They hit the Zero but he managed to escape into a cloud. Moments later, Ramsey spotted another lone Zero, which he managed to shot down.\n\n==Later career==\nAfter Coral Sea, he returned to the Washington, United States where in April 1943 he was appointed director of the flight test division at the Anacostia Naval Air Station. He later commanded the carrier [[USS Philippine Sea (CV-47)|Philippine Sea]] during the [[Korean War]]. He retired from USN in 1966.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n; Sources\n* {{cite book\n |last=Lundstrom\n |first=John B. \n |year=2005 |edition=New \n |chapter= \n |title=The First Team: Pacific Naval Air Combat from Pearl Harbor to Midway \n |publisher=Naval Institute Press \n |location=Annapolis, Maryland \n |isbn=1-59114-471-X\n}}\n* {{cite book \n |last=Lundstrom \n |first=John B. \n |year=2005 \n |edition=New \n |chapter= \n |title=First Team and the Guadalcanal Campaign: Naval Fighter Combat from August to November 1942\n |publisher=Naval Institute Press \n |location=Annapolis, Maryland \n |isbn=1-59114-472-8\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/46954226/paul-hubert-ramsey\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ramsey, Paul H.}}\n[[Category:United States Naval Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Naval Aviators]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{no footnotes|date=November 2019}}\n{{More citations needed|date=November 2019}}\n}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name=Paul Hubert Ramsey\n|birth_date= {{Birth date|1905|2|2}}\n|death_date= {{death date and age|1982|2|15|1905|2|2}}\n|image=\n|caption=Flatley [then Commander] in the cockpit of a Grumman F6F-3 Hellcat on board USS ''Yorktown'' (CV-10), October 1943.\n|nickname=''Sheik''\n|birth_place=[[Springfield, Ohio]]\n|death_place=[[Coronado, California]]\n|allegiance=[[United States|United States of America]]\n|branch=[[United States Navy]]\n|serviceyears=1927-1966\n|rank=[[Vice admiral (United States)|Vice Admiral]]\n|unit=\n|commands=[[VF-2|Fighter Squadron 2 (VF-2)]]\n|battles= [[World War II]]\n*[[Battle of the Coral Sea]]\n[[Korean War]]\n|awards=[[Navy Cross (United States)|Navy Cross]]\n|relations=\n|laterwork=\n}}\n'''Paul Hubert Ramsey''' was a World War II [[naval aviator]] of [[United States Navy]] (USN).\n\n==Early career==\nRamsey graduated from [[United States Naval Academy]] in 1927 and earned his wings in 1930. In 1930's he served on carriers [[USS Lexington (CV-2)|Lexington]] and [[USS Saratoga (CV-3)|Saratoga]]. He was promoted to [[Lieutenant Commander]] on 1 July 1941 and became the [[commanding officer]] of [[VF-2|Fighter Squadron 2 (VF-2)]]. During the early stage of [[Pacific War]], his [[executive officer]] was [[Lieutenant (navy)|Lieutenant]] [[James H. Flatley|James Flatley]]. They both participated in the [[Battle of the Coral Sea]] in May 1942, however Flatley was transferred to [[VF-42|Fighter Squadron 42 (VF-42)]] just prior to the battle but managed to get permission to participate in the operation. At the time of the battle, VF-2 was assigned to carrier Lexington.\n\n==Coral Sea==\nOn 7 May, Lieutenant Commander Ramsey led a group of [[Grumman F4F Wildcat]] fighters to escort [[Douglas TBD Devastator]] from [[VT-2]] in the attack that sank light carrier [[Japanese aircraft carrier Sh\u014dh\u014d|''Sh\u014dh\u014d'']]. In response to sinking of ''Sh\u014dh\u014d'', [[Imperial Japanese Navy]] (IJN) main carrier force launched a night strike on USN carriers composed of 15 [[Nakajima B5N]] and 12 [[Aichi D3A]] bombers. Ramsey led a group of F4F Wildcats to intercept. He set up an ambush in heavy overcast weather, which resulted in numerous losses of IJN aircraft and some of their most experience pilots. He personally destroyed two B5N [[torpedo bombers]].\n\nThe following day, on 8 May, Lieutenant Commander Ramsey was involved in Combat Air Patrol over friendly carriers. His group of F4F Wildcats spotted an approaching formation of D3A [[dive bombers]] at a higher altitude. However, they were unable to climb in time to intercept, due to the poor climb rate of F4F Wildcat and relatively high altitude difference. After the enemy dive bombers made their attack on the USN carriers, he and his wingman spotted [[Mitsubishi A6M Zero]] at a lower altitude and dived on it. They hit the Zero but he managed to escape into a cloud. Moments later, Ramsey spotted another lone Zero, which he managed to shot down.\n\n==Later career==\nAfter Coral Sea, he returned to the Washington, United States where in April 1943 he was appointed director of the flight test division at the Anacostia Naval Air Station. He later commanded the carrier [[USS Philippine Sea (CV-47)|Philippine Sea]] during the [[Korean War]]. He retired from USN in 1966.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n; Sources\n* {{cite book\n |last=Lundstrom\n |first=John B. \n |year=2005 |edition=New \n |chapter= \n |title=The First Team: Pacific Naval Air Combat from Pearl Harbor to Midway \n |publisher=Naval Institute Press \n |location=Annapolis, Maryland \n |isbn=1-59114-471-X\n}}\n* {{cite book \n |last=Lundstrom \n |first=John B. \n |year=2005 \n |edition=New \n |chapter= \n |title=First Team and the Guadalcanal Campaign: Naval Fighter Combat from August to November 1942\n |publisher=Naval Institute Press \n |location=Annapolis, Maryland \n |isbn=1-59114-472-8\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/46954226/paul-hubert-ramsey\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ramsey, Paul H.}}\n[[Category:United States Naval Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Naval Aviators]]\n", "name_user": "Path-x21", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_H._Ramsey"}
{"title_page": "It (film series)", "text_new": "{{short description|American horror film series}}\n{{Infobox media franchise\n| title = ''It''\n| image = IT (2017 film) logo.svg\n| caption = Official logo, used since the [[It (2017 film)|2017 film]]\n| creator = {{plainlist|\n* [[New Line Cinema]]\n* [[Vertigo Entertainment]]\n* [[KatzSmith Productions]]\n}}\n| origin = ''[[It (novel)|It]]''\n| owner = [[Warner Bros. Pictures]]\n| films = * {{nowrap|''[[It (2017 film)|It]]''}}\n* {{nowrap|''[[It Chapter Two]]''}}\n| soundtracks = * {{nowrap|''[[It (2017 film)#Music|It (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack)]]''}}\n* {{nowrap|''[[It Chapter Two#Music|It Chapter Two (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack)]]''}}\n| novels = ''It''\n}}\n\n'''''It''''' is a series of American [[horror film]]s. The series consists of two films and is the second adaptation of the [[It (novel)|original novel]] by [[Stephen King]], after [[Tommy Lee Wallace]]'s [[It (miniseries)|1990 miniseries]]. The first installment was the film ''[[It (2017 film)|It]]'', released in 2017 by [[Warner Bros. Pictures]]. The franchise centers around a group of seven children living in [[Derry (Stephen King)|Derry, Maine]], who are terrorized by an [[It (character)|eponymous being]] only to face their own personal demons in the process. This being returns to haunt the children every 27 years. The second installment, ''[[It Chapter Two]]'' follows the group 27 years after the events of the first installment.\n\nThe film series received generally positive critical reception and has grossed a combined $1.1{{nbsp}}billion against a combined budget of $114{{nbsp}}million, becoming the [[List of highest-grossing horror films#Top 25 highest-grossing horror film franchises and film series|sixth-highest-grossing horror franchise ever]].\n\n==Films==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center; width:100%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"column\" style=\"width:12%\"| Film\n! U.S. release date\n! Director(s)\n! Writer(s)\n! Producer(s)\n|-\n!colspan=\"6\" style=\"background-color:#ccccff;\" | Films\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[It (2017 film)|It]]''\n| September 8, 2017\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Andy Muschietti]]\n| Chase Palmer, [[Cary Joji Fukunaga|Cary Fukunaga]] & [[Gary Dauberman]]\n| [[Seth Grahame-Smith]], David Katzenberg, [[Roy Lee]], [[Dan Lin]] & [[Barbara Muschietti]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[It Chapter Two]]''\n| September 6, 2019\n| Gary Dauberman\n| Roy Lee, Dan Lin & Barbara Muschietti\n|}\n\n===''It'' (2017)===\n{{Main|It (2017 film)}}\n''It'' (retroactively known as ''It Chapter One'') is a 2017 American [[supernatural horror film]] based on the 1986 [[It (novel)|novel of the same name]] by [[Stephen King]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/stephen-kings-it-release-date-set-by-warner-bros/|title=Stephen King's 'It' Release Date Set by Warner Bros|last=Geier|first=Thom|work=[[TheWrap]]|date=April 22, 2016|accessdate=October 16, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161024120617/http://www.thewrap.com/stephen-kings-it-release-date-set-by-warner-bros/|archivedate=October 24, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> It is the second adaptation of the novel, following a 1990 [[It (miniseries)|television miniseries]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbr.com/stephen-king-it-rating-sequel-plans/|title=It Remake Has a Rating, Plans for a Sequel|last=Staley|first=Brandon|work=[[Comic Book Resources]]|date=February 9, 2017|accessdate=March 31, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170401143822/http://www.cbr.com/stephen-king-it-rating-sequel-plans/|archivedate=April 1, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.ign.com/articles/2017/03/30/it-how-the-stephen-king-remake-compares-to-the-original-tv-miniseries|title=It: How the Stephen King Remake Compares to the Original TV Miniseries|last=Schedeen|first=Jesse|work=[[IGN]]|date=February 9, 2017|accessdate=March 31, 2017}}</ref> The film tells the story of seven children in [[Derry (Stephen King)|Derry, Maine]], who are terrorized by the eponymous being, only to face their own personal demons in the process. [[Jaeden Martell|Jaeden Lieberher]] stars as [[Bill Denbrough]], with [[Bill Skarsg\u00e5rd]] starring as [[It (character)|Pennywise the Dancing Clown]].<ref name=\"Jaeden\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/stephen-kings-it-casts-hollywood-legacy-as-pennywise-the-clown/|title=Stephen King's 'It' Casts Hollywood Legacy as Pennywise the Clown|last=Verhoeven|first=Beatrice|date=June 2, 2016|work=[[The Wrap]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160620073324/http://www.thewrap.com/stephen-kings-it-casts-hollywood-legacy-as-pennywise-the-clown/|archivedate=June 20, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Wyatt Oleff]], [[Jeremy Ray Taylor]], [[Sophia Lillis]], [[Finn Wolfhard]], [[Jack Dylan Grazer]], [[Chosen Jacobs]], [[Nicholas Hamilton]], [[Owen Teague]], [[Jackson Robert Scott]], and Stephen Bogaert are all featured in supporting roles.<ref name=\"Jaeden\" /> [[Principal photography]] began on June 27, 2016, at [[Pinewood Toronto Studios]] and on locations in and around [[Port Hope, Ontario|Port Hope]], [[Oshawa|Oshawa, Ontario]], and [[Riverdale, Toronto]], and ended on September 21, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hitfix.com/the-dartboard/stephen-king-has-an-it-remake-update-for-you|title=Stephen King has an 'It' remake update for you|last=Eggertsen|first=Chris|date=April 13, 2016|work=[[HitFix]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160622101005/http://www.hitfix.com/the-dartboard/stephen-king-has-an-it-remake-update-for-you|archivedate=June 22, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/it-movie-wraps-production/|title='It' Wraps Production with One Last Creepy Photo|last=Keene|first=Allison|date=September 22, 2016|work=[[Collider.com]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160928204639/http://collider.com/it-movie-wraps-production/|archivedate=September 28, 2016|accessdate=September 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://toronto.ctvnews.ca/mansion-in-riverdale-sets-the-scene-for-horror-film-it-1.3029802|title=Mansion in Riverdale sets the scene for horror film 'It'|last=Greenberg|first=Courtney|date=August 15, 2016|work=CTV Toronto|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161002055307/http://toronto.ctvnews.ca/mansion-in-riverdale-sets-the-scene-for-horror-film-it-1.3029802|archivedate=October 2, 2016|accessdate=September 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The film was released on September 8, 2017 and grossed over $700 million worldwide, against a production budget of $35 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/4935221/it-box-office-stephen-king/|title=It Shatters Box Office Records With Massive Opening Weekend|last=Calfas|first=Jennifer|date=September 10, 2017|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=October 10, 2017}}</ref> It is the highest-grossing horror film of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/sep/29/stephen-king-it-the-exorcist-highest-grossing-horror-film-ever|title=Stephen King's It scares off The Exorcist to become highest-grossing horror ever|last=Mumford|first=Gwilym|date=September 29, 2017|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=October 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/10/blade-runner-2049-it-movie-horror-record-despicable-me-3-kingsman-never-say-die-weekend-results-international-box-office-1202184382/|title=\u2018Blade Runner 2049\u2019 Arrives With $50M Overseas; \u2018It\u2019 Tops $600M WW; \u2018Despicable 3\u2019 Hops Past \u2018Zootopia\u2019 \u2013 Intl Box Office|last=Tartaglione|first=Nancy|date=October 8, 2017|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=October 10, 2017}}</ref> It received positive reviews, with critics praising the performances, direction, cinematography and musical score, and many calling it one of the best Stephen King adaptations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/it-review-roundup-1035698|title='It': What the Critics Are Saying|last=Rahman|first=Abid|date=September 6, 2017|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=October 10, 2017}}</ref> In addition, the film was named as one of the best films of 2017 by various critics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/feature/film-critics-list-the-top-10-movies-of-2017|title=Best of 2017: Film Critic Top Ten Lists|last=Dietz|first=Jason|date=December 5, 2017|work=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=December 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== ''It Chapter Two'' (2019) ===\n{{main|It Chapter Two}}\nTalks for an ''It'' sequel began in February 2016. By September 2017, [[New Line Cinema]] announced that it would be released in September 2019, with Dauberman writing the script and Muschietti to direct. [[Principal photography]] began on June 19, 2018, at [[Pinewood Toronto Studios]] and on locations in and around [[Port Hope, Ontario|Port Hope]], [[Oshawa]], and [[Toronto, Ontario]], and wrapped on October 31, 2018. The film is directed by [[Andy Muschietti]] from a screenplay by [[Gary Dauberman]]. Set in 2016, 27 years after the first film, it stars <!-- Do not change; Chastain is top-billed in the film's credits  -->[[Jessica Chastain]], [[James McAvoy]], [[Bill Hader]], [[Isaiah Mustafa]], [[Jay Ryan (actor)|Jay Ryan]], [[James Ransone]], [[Andy Bean (actor)|Andy Bean]], and [[Bill Skarsg\u00e5rd]], who returns as [[It (character)|Pennywise the Dancing Clown]]. ''It Chapter Two'' premiered at the [[Fox Theater, Westwood Village|Regency Village Theater]] in [[Los Angeles]] on August 26, 2019, and was theatrically released in the United States on September 6, 2019. The film received praise for its acting (particularly Hader and Skarsg\u00e5rd) and themes, though criticism was aimed at its runtime and weaker scares compared to its predecessor. Its faithfulness to the novel also drew a polarized response.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/it-chapter-two-review-roundup-what-critics-are-saying-1236289|title='It: Chapter Two': What the Critics Are Saying|author=Schaffstall|first=Katherine|date=September 3, 2019|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=September 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Supercut===\nIn September 2019, Muschietti expressed interest in releasing a \"Supercut\" version of both chapters. This version would combine both films into one with scenes that were left in the editing process. Muschietti also mentioned the possibility of adding two or three new scenes that would be shot for this edition. The existing scenes will not be re-edited. Instead, it will play out as extended versions of both films, with an intermission included to separate the two. The future of this version has not yet been announced, as of April 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VS4x9uVWOBU&t=405s|title=Director Andy Muschietti tells us why he wants to shoot new scenes for IT |date=September 10, 2019|language=en-US|access-date=October 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Future ===\nIn September 2019, Skarsg\u00e5rd spoke of the possibility of a third installment, saying, \"It would have to be the right type of approach to it. The book ends where the second movie ends, so that is the final chapter of this story. There is this interesting aspect of going back in time before all this happened. There might be a story there that might be worth exploring. Obviously that would be a story that's not in the book, it would be a freestanding story, but obviously within the same universe. So, there might be something interesting out of it. I think it would be fun.\"<ref>https://ew.com/movies/2019/09/08/it-chapter-two-pennywise-bill-skarsgard/</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, Dauberman discussed in an interview of the possibility of a third film, saying, \"I do think it's possible. Anything in the Stephen King Universe interests me but there's only so much of the story we could tell in the two movies. There are definitely elements of the novel you could expand on and make its own movie. It's just a question of whether or not people want to see it but I do think It was on this planet for a very, very, very long time and that's a lot of bloodshed and a lot of stories to tell and I think you could do that for sure.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://io9.gizmodo.com/it-chapter-3-1839759979/amp|title=It Chapter 3: Screenwriter Gary Dauberman Says 'It's Possible'|website=io9.gizmodo.com|access-date=2019-11-30}}</ref>\n\n== Development ==\nThe project was in ongoing development since 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2009/mar/13/stephen-king-it-film-adaptation|title=It's coming, as Hollywood plans Stephen King adaptation|last=Opie|first=David|date=March 13, 2009|work=[[The Guardian]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019031106/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2009/mar/13/stephen-king-it-film-adaptation|archivedate=October 19, 2016|accessdate=October 16, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fuse.tv/2016/08/stephen-king-it-movie-complete-guide-pennywise|title=The Complete Guide to the 'It' Remake: Stephen King's Pennywise Is Back|last=Dionne|first=Zach|date=September 30, 2016|work=[[Fuse (TV channel)|Fuse]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018085202/http://www.fuse.tv/2016/08/stephen-king-it-movie-complete-guide-pennywise|archivedate=October 18, 2016|accessdate=October 16, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/warner-bros-remaking-stephen-kings-it/|title=Warner Bros Remaking Stephen King's It|last=Sciretta|first=Peter|date=March 12, 2009|work=[[/Film]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018213742/http://www.slashfilm.com/warner-bros-remaking-stephen-kings-it/|archivedate=October 18, 2016|accessdate=October 16, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The proposed film adaptations had gone through two major phases of planning: initially with [[Cary Joji Fukunaga|Cary Fukunaga]] from 2009 to 2015, with the early contributions of screenwriter [[David Kajganich]], and with [[Andy Muschietti]], with Fukunaga remaining in some capacity due to prior screenplay contributions.<ref name=\"Development\">{{cite web|url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/stephen-king-everything-need-know/|title=Stephen King's It \u2013 everything you need to know|last=Williams|first=Owen|work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|date=August 11, 2016|accessdate=September 28, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160925053809/http://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/stephen-king-everything-need-know/|archivedate=September 25, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/stephen-king-pet-sematary-it-remakes-schrad-66877/|title=Updates on the 'Pet Sematary' and 'It' Remakes|last=Schrader|first=Chris|date=July 1, 2010|work=Screen Rant|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018215511/http://screenrant.com/stephen-king-pet-sematary-it-remakes-schrad-66877/|archivedate=October 18, 2016|accessdate=October 16, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/stephen-king-it-movies-cary-fukunaga-sandy-178091/|title=Stephen King's 'It' Getting Two-Film Adaptation by 'Jane Eyre' Director|last=Schaefer|first=Sandy|date=June 8, 2012|work=Screen Rant|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316153624/http://screenrant.com/stephen-king-it-movies-cary-fukunaga-sandy-178091/|archivedate=March 16, 2016|accessdate=October 16, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/cary-fukunaga-it/#more-312794|title=Cary Fukunaga Explains the Demise of His Unconventional 'IT' Adaptation|last=Fischer|first=Russ|date=September 5, 2015|work=[[/Film]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018214854/http://www.slashfilm.com/cary-fukunaga-it/#more-312794|archivedate=October 18, 2016|accessdate=October 16, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== David Kajganich (2009\u20132010) ===\n{{quote box\n| align = right\n| width = 35%\n| quote = \"The thing about Stephen King's writing is that he draws his characters so well, it's hard not to imagine they're real people. So it honestly didn't occur to me to try to think of actors in those roles. Pennywise is a bit of a different story, though. His manner is so crucial to what's frightening about him, and it's too much fun to imagine all of the nuances different actors could give him. I think there are a hundred actors who could each pull off a fascinating, horrifying Pennywise, and I tried not to get too attached to any one actor in my head. I think the Pennywise in this adaptation is a less self-conscious of his own irony and surreality than was [[Tim Curry]]'s Pennywise. I think it will be harder to laugh at his antics since, under the permissiveness of an R rating, I was able to give him back a lot of his more upsetting moments from the novel, ones that could never be aired on network television.\"\n| source = David Kajganich, on the construction of Pennywise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://liljas-library.com/showinterview.php?id=73|title=David Kajganich \u2013 INTERVIEW|last=Lilja's Library Editors|first=|work=Lilja's Library|date=June 29, 2010|accessdate=September 11, 2017}}</ref>\n}}On March 12, 2009, ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' reported that [[Warner Bros. Pictures]] would be bringing [[Stephen King]]'s novel to the big screen, with David Kajganich to adapt King's novel, while Dan Lin, [[Roy Lee]] and Doug Davison would be producing the piece.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2009/film/features/warner-bros-taps-kajganich-for-it-1118001188/|title=Warner Bros. taps Kajganich for 'It'|last=McNary|first=Dave|date=March 12, 2009|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160719080933/http://variety.com/2009/film/features/warner-bros-taps-kajganich-for-it-1118001188/|archivedate=July 19, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> When Kajganich learned of Warner Bros.' plans to adapt King's novel, he went after the job.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://liljas-library.com/showinterview.php?id=73|title=David Kajganich \u2013 Interview|last=Lilja's Library Editor|first=|date=June 29, 2010|work=Lilja's Library|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808234208/http://liljas-library.com/showinterview.php?id=73|archivedate=August 8, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Knowing that Warner Bros. was committed to adapting ''It'' as a single feature film, Kajganich began to attempt to try to find a structure that would accommodate such a large number of characters in two different time periods, around 120 pages, which was one of Warner Bros.' stipulations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/screenwriter-gives-update-on-big-screen-adaptation-of-stephen-kings-it/|title=Screenwriter Gives Update on Big Screen Adaptation of Stephen King's It|last=Sciretta|first=Peter|date=July 1, 2010|work=[[/Film]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160524144215/http://www.slashfilm.com/screenwriter-gives-update-on-big-screen-adaptation-of-stephen-kings-it/|archivedate=May 24, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Kajganich worked with Lin, Lee, and Davison on ''[[The Invasion (film)|The Invasion]]'' (2007), and he knew they would champion good storytelling, and allow him the time to work out a solid first draft of the screenplay.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popcrunch.com/it-movie/|title=Stephen King's \"It\" Bound For Big Screen|last=Castina|first=|date=July 6, 2010|work=PopCrunch|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160815153332/http://www.popcrunch.com/it-movie/|archivedate=August 15, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Kajganich spoke of the remake being set in the, \"mid-1980s and in the present mirroring the twenty-odd-year gap King uses in the book and with a great deal of care and attention paid to the backstories of all the characters.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dreadcentral.com/news/10860/exclusive-more-on-the-it-remake-rated-r/|title=Exclusive: More on the IT Remake! Rated R?|last=Barton|first=Steve|date=April 5, 2009|work=[[Dread Central]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160804120207/http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/10860/exclusive-more-on-the-it-remake-rated-r/|archivedate=August 4, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nKajganich also mentioned that Warner Bros. wished for the adaptation to be rated R which he furthered by saying, \"we can really honor the book and engage with the traumas that these characters endure.\", while Kajganich spoke of Warner Bros. wanting the adaptation as a single film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/remake-of-stephen-kings-it-will-be-rated-r-and-set-in-the-mid-1980s/|title=Remake of Stephen King's It will be Rated-R and Set in the Mid-1980s|last=Sciretta|first=Peter|date=April 5, 2009|work=[[/Film]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160829002848/http://www.slashfilm.com/remake-of-stephen-kings-it-will-be-rated-r-and-set-in-the-mid-1980s/|archivedate=August 29, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On June 29, 2010, the screenplay was being re-written by Kajganich.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dreadcentral.com/news/18143/early-details-on-the-it-remake/|title=Early Details on the IT Remake|last=Serafini|first=Matt|date=June 30, 2010|work=[[Dread Central]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808233147/http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/18143/early-details-on-the-it-remake/|archivedate=August 8, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He said that his dream choice for Pennywise would be [[Buster Keaton]] if he were still alive, and the Pennywise that Kajganich scripted being \"less self-conscious of his own irony and surreality.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.joblo.com/movie-news/screenwriter-david-kajganich-gives-an-update-on-stephen-kings-it|title=SCREENWRITER DAVID KAJGANICH GIVES AN UPDATE ON STEPHEN KING'S IT|last=Stephens|first=Niki|date=July 1, 2010|work=[[Collider.com]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160804190540/http://www.joblo.com/movie-news/screenwriter-david-kajganich-gives-an-update-on-stephen-kings-it|archivedate=August 4, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Cary Fukunaga (2012\u20132015) ===\n{{quote box\n| align = right\n| width = 35%\n| quote = \"I am in the midst of rewriting the first script now.  We're not working on the second part yet. The first script is just about the kids. It's more like ''[[The Goonies]]'' (1985) meets a horror film. We're definitely honoring the spirit of Stephen King, but the horror has to be modernized to make it relevant. That's my job, right now, on this pass. I'm working on making the horror more about suspense than visualization of any creatures. I just don't think that's scary. What could be there, and the sounds and how it interacts with things, is scarier than actual monsters.\"\n| source = \u2013 Cary Fukunaga, on the development of ''It''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/cary-fukunaga-true-detective-interview/|title=Director Cary Fukunaga Talks TRUE DETECTIVE, Making an 8-Hour Film, Future Seasons, BEASTS OF NO NATION, Modernizing Horror with IT, and More|last=Radish|first=Christina|work=[[Collider.com]]|date=January 11, 2014|accessdate=June 27, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807054534/http://collider.com/cary-fukunaga-true-detective-interview/|archivedate=August 7, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n}}On June 7, 2012, ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]''  had revealed that Cary Fukunaga was boarding the project as director and will co-write the script with Chase Palmer, while Roy Lee and Dan Lin are producing, as with [[Seth Grahame-Smith]] and David Katzenberg of KatzSmith Productions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/stephen-kings-be-adapted-by-334899|title=Stephen King's 'It' to Be Adapted by Cary Fukunaga into Two Films (Exclusive)|last=Kit|first=Borys|date=June 7, 2012|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160706192550/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/stephen-kings-be-adapted-by-334899|archivedate=July 6, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On May 21, 2014, Warner Bros. was announced to have moved the film to its [[New Line Cinema]] division, with overseer duties conducting by New Line's Walter Hamada and Dave Neustadter, along with Vice President of Production at Warner Bros., Niija Kuykendall.<ref name=New>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/stephen-kings-moves-warner-bros-706062|title=Stephen King's 'It' Moves From Warner Bros. to New Line (Exclusive)|last=Kit|first=Borys|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=May 21, 2014|accessdate=June 27, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160730140142/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/stephen-kings-moves-warner-bros-706062|archivedate=July 30, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On December 5, 2014, in an interview with ''[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]]'', Dan Lin announced that the first film will be a [[coming-of-age]] story about the children tormented by [[It (character)|It]] and the second will skip ahead in time as those same characters band together to continue the fight as adults.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/389569-stephen-kings-it-will-shoot-next-summer|title=Stephen King's IT Will Shoot Next Summer|last=Evry|first=Max|date=December 5, 2014|work=Coming Soon|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303172056/http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/389569-stephen-kings-it-will-shoot-next-summer|archivedate=March 3, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Lin also stated that Fukunaga was only committed to directing the first film, though was currently closing a deal to co-write the second. Lin concluded by mentioning King, to which he remarked, \"The most important thing is that [King] gave us his blessing. We didn't want to make this unless he felt it was the right way to go, and when we sent him the script, the response that Cary got back was, 'Go with God, please! This is the version the studio should make.' So that was really gratifying.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2014/12/fukunaga-to-shoot-stephen-kings-it-next-summer.html?mid=twitter_vulture#|title=Cary Fukunaga Will Shoot Stephen King's It Next Summer|last=Buchanan|first=Kyle|date=December 5, 2014|work=[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]]|accessdate=June 27, 2016}}</ref> Lin confirmed that Fukunaga would begin [[principal photography]] in Summer 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/stephen-kings-it-remake-put-on-indefinite-hold-as-director-cary-fukunaga-walks-out-10275542.html|title=Stephen King's It remake put on indefinite hold as director Cary Fukunaga walks out|last=Shepherd|first=Jack|date=May 26, 2015|work=[[The Independent]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161007150949/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/stephen-kings-it-remake-put-on-indefinite-hold-as-director-cary-fukunaga-walks-out-10275542.html|archivedate=October 7, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn February 3, 2015, Fukunaga was interviewed by ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' wherein he spoke about ''It'', while mentioning he has someone in mind for the role of Pennywise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2015/02/03/cary_fukunaga_on_true_detective_season_2_his_adaption_of_stephen_king_s.html|title=Cary Fukunaga on Adapting It, His Musical With Owen Pallett, and #TrueDetectiveSeason2|last=Wickman|first=Forrest|date=February 3, 2015|work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628135946/http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2015/02/03/cary_fukunaga_on_true_detective_season_2_his_adaption_of_stephen_king_s.html|archivedate=June 28, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On March 3, 2015, Fukunaga spoke of the film, particularly noting his goal to find the \"perfect guy to play Pennywise\". Fukunaga also revealed that he, Kajganich and Palmer had changed the names and dates in the script, adding, the spirit is similar to what he'd like to see in cinemas.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3334554/director-seeks-perfect-pennywise-clown/|title='It' Director Seeks \"Perfect Pennywise\" Clown|last=Disgusting|first=Mr|date=March 3, 2015|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624183418/http://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3334554/director-seeks-perfect-pennywise-clown/|archivedate=June 24, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On May 4, 2015, it was officially announced that [[Will Poulter]] had been cast to play Pennywise, after Fukunaga was \"blown away\" by his audition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2015/05/04/will-poulter-it-pennywise|title=Will Poulter cast as Pennywise in Cary Fukunaga's It|last=P. Sullivan|first=Kevin|date=May 4, 2015|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160618220510/http://www.ew.com/article/2015/05/04/will-poulter-it-pennywise|archivedate=June 18, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"WillP\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/will-poutler-pennywise-the-clown-in-new-lines-it-remake-1201446495/|title=Will Poulter to Play the Evil Clown in 'It' Remake (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Kroll|first=Justin|date=May 4, 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160629051959/http://variety.com/2015/film/news/will-poutler-pennywise-the-clown-in-new-lines-it-remake-1201446495/|archivedate=June 29, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Ty Simpkins]] was considered to play one of The Losers' Club members.<ref name=\"Ty\">{{cite web|url=http://movieweb.com/jurassic-world-interview-ty-simpkins/|title=Jurassic World Interview with Ty Simpkins|last=Gallagher|first=Brian|date=February 27, 2016|work=[[MovieWeb]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161025114439/http://movieweb.com/jurassic-world-interview-ty-simpkins/|archivedate=October 25, 2016|accessdate=October 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn May 25, 2015, it was reported that Fukunaga had dropped out as the director of ''It''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/it-cary-fukunaga-director-exits-1201504672/|title='It' Loses Director Cary Fukunaga|last=Kroll|first=Justin|date=May 25, 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160709011956/http://variety.com/2015/film/news/it-cary-fukunaga-director-exits-1201504672/|archivedate=July 9, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> According to [[TheWrap]], Fukunaga clashed with the studio and didn't want to compromise his artistic vision in the wake of budget cuts by New Line, which greenlit the first film at $30&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/cary-fukunaga-out-as-director-of-stephen-kings-it-at-new-line-exclusive/|title=Cary Fukunaga Out as Director of Stephen King's 'It' at New Line (Exclusive)|last=Geier|first=Thom|date=May 25, 2015|work=[[The Wrap]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628034157/https://www.thewrap.com/cary-fukunaga-out-as-director-of-stephen-kings-it-at-new-line-exclusive/|archivedate=June 28, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> However, Fukunaga maintained that wasn't the case, with him stating he had bigger disagreements with New Line over the direction of the story: \"I was trying to make an unconventional horror film. It didn't fit into the algorithm of what they knew they could spend and make money back on based on not offending their standard genre audience.\"<ref name=\"Cary\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/cary-fukunaga-it-exit-1201584416/|title=Cary Fukunaga Offers New Details on Why 'It' Remake Fell Apart|last=Setoodeh|first=Ramin|date=September 2, 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160704095044/http://variety.com/2015/film/news/cary-fukunaga-it-exit-1201584416/|archivedate=July 4, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He made mention that the budget was perfectly fine, as well as his desire to make Pennywise more than just the clown.<ref name=\"Cary\" /> Fukunaga concluded by stating, \"We invested years and so much anecdotal storytelling in it. Chase and I both put our childhood in that story. So our biggest fear was they were going to take our script and bastardize it So I'm actually thankful that they are going to rewrite the script. I wouldn't want them to stealing our childhood memories and using that I was honoring King's spirit of it, but I needed to update it. King saw an earlier draft and liked it.\"<ref name=\"Cary\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2015/08/17/cary-fukunaga-it-movie?hootPostID=b5145d9e2c7e687d8867d1c08604632f|title=Cary Fukunaga opens up about IT departure \u2013 Exclusive|last=P. Sullivan|first=Kevin|date=August 17, 2015|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161108110348/http://www.ew.com/article/2015/08/17/cary-fukunaga-it-movie?hootPostID=b5145d9e2c7e687d8867d1c08604632f|archivedate=November 8, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On Fukunaga's departure, King wrote, \"The remake of ''IT'' may be dead or undead but we'll always have [[Tim Curry]]. He's still floating down in the sewers of Derry.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/stephenking/status/602931191281496064|title=The remake of IT may be dead|last=King|first=Stephen|date=May 25, 2015|work=Twitter|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322192030/https://twitter.com/StephenKing/status/602931191281496064|archivedate=March 22, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.sky.com/story/1490944/it-remake-dead-as-director-walks-away|title=It Remake 'Dead' As Director Walks Away|last=Sky News Editors|first=Justin|date=May 26, 2015|work=[[Sky News]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150528215629/http://news.sky.com/story/1490944/it-remake-dead-as-director-walks-away|archivedate=May 28, 2015|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Andy Muschietti (2015\u20132017) ===\n{{quote box\n| align = right\n| width = 35%\n| quote = \"The way Cary intended to execute the script is something that only he can talk about. I can say my version of ''It'' highly emphasizes Pennywise's most terrifying virtue, which is It's ability to materialise into your worse fear; I want to take people in a journey into Pennywise's world through a disturbing, surrealistic and intoxicating experience that will leave nobody at ease.\"\n| source = \u2013 Andy Muschietti, on his version of ''It''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liljas-library.com/article.php?id=4659|title=IT Emphasizes Pennywise's Most Terrifying Virtue|last=Jorissen|first=Matt|work=Lilja's Library|date=November 6, 2015|accessdate=June 27, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808225514/http://www.liljas-library.com/article.php?id=4659|archivedate=August 8, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n}}On July 16, 2015, it was announced that Andy Muschietti was in negotiations to direct ''It'', with New Line beginning a search for a new writer to tailor a script to Muschietti's vision,<ref name=\"Andr\u00e9s\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/stephen-kings-finds-new-director-809080|title=Stephen King's 'It' Finds New Director (Exclusive)|last=Kit|first=Borys|date=July 16, 2015|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160716124053/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/stephen-kings-finds-new-director-809080|archivedate=July 16, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.empireonline.com/people/andres-muschietti/mama-andres-muschietti-negotiations-direct/|title=Mama's Andr\u00e9s Muschietti in Negotiations To Direct It|last=White|first=James|date=July 17, 2015|work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161003180808/http://www.empireonline.com/people/andres-muschietti/mama-andres-muschietti-negotiations-direct/|archivedate=October 3, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> with the announcement also confirming the possible participation of Muschietti's sister, Barbara Muschietti, as a producer, and Richard Brener joining Hamada, Neustadter and Kuykendall to oversee the project.<ref name=\"Andr\u00e9s\" /> On April 22, 2016, it was indicated that Will Poulter, who was originally tapped to portray Pennywise in Fukunaga's version, had dropped out of the film due to a scheduling conflict and that executives were meeting with actors to portray the antagonist.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/warner-bros-announces-release-date-for-it-1201759274/|title=Warner Bros. Announces Release Date for 'It'|last=Kroll|first=Justin|date=April 22, 2016|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625020838/http://variety.com/2016/film/news/warner-bros-announces-release-date-for-it-1201759274/|archivedate=June 25, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On April 22, 2016, New Line Cinema set the film for a release of September 8, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/04/chips-it-warner-bros-release-dates-2017-1201742518/|title=Warner Bros. Sets 'CHiPs', 'It' & Untitled PG-13 Comedy For 2017|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|date=April 22, 2016|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624041157/http://deadline.com/2016/04/chips-it-warner-bros-release-dates-2017-1201742518/|archivedate=June 24, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/warner-bros-announces-release-date-for-it-1201759274/|title=Warner Bros. Announces Release Date for 'It'|last=Kroll|first=Justin|date=April 22, 2016|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625020838/http://variety.com/2016/film/news/warner-bros-announces-release-date-for-it-1201759274/|archivedate=June 25, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn October 30, 2015, Muschietti was interviewed by ''Variety'' wherein he spoke about his vision of ''It'', while mentioning Poulter was still in the mix for the role of Pennywise: \"[Poulter] would be a great option. For me he is at the top of my list\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/global/muschiettis-to-produce-supernatural-thriller-shadows-exclusive-1201630876/|title=Muschiettis to Produce Supernatural Thriller 'Shadows' (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Mayorga|first=Emilio|date=October 30, 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305002513/http://variety.com/2015/film/global/muschiettis-to-produce-supernatural-thriller-shadows-exclusive-1201630876/|archivedate=March 5, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He confirmed that next summer is the time for them to start shooting. It was decided to shoot ''It'' during the summer months to give them the time to work with the children who have the main roles in the first part of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inquisitr.com/2541256/filming-starts-next-summer-on-remake-of-stephen-kings-it/|title=Filming Starts Next Summer on Remake of Stephen King Classic 'It'|last=Sewell|first=Annie|date=November 4, 2015|work=[[Inquisitr]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160519230246/http://www.inquisitr.com/2541256/filming-starts-next-summer-on-remake-of-stephen-kings-it/|archivedate=May 19, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Muschietti went on to say that \"King described 50s' terror iconography,\" adding that he feels there is a whole world now to \"rediscover, to update.\" He said there won't be any mummies or werewolves and that the \"terrors are going to be a lot more surprising.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3368274/stephen-kings-it-to-film-next-summer/|title=Stephen King's 'It' to Film Next Summer!|last=Disgusting|first=Mr|date=October 31, 2015|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160705165415/http://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3368274/stephen-kings-it-to-film-next-summer/|archivedate=July 5, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On February 19, 2016, at the [[D.I.C.E. Summit|D.I.C.E. Summit 2016]] producer Roy Lee confirmed that Fukunaga and Chase Palmer's original script had been rewritten, with Lee remarking, \"It will hopefully be shooting later this year. We just got the California tax credit Dauberman wrote the most recent draft working with [Muscetti], so it's being envisioned as two movies.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/stephen-king-it-movies-filming-2016/|title=Stephen King's It May Start Filming in 2016; Two Movies Still Planned|last=Jones|first=Mike|date=February 19, 2016|work=Screen Rant|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625070804/http://screenrant.com/stephen-king-it-movies-filming-2016/|archivedate=June 25, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn May 5, 2016, in an interview with [[Collider.com]], David Kajganich expressed uncertainty as to whether drafts of his original screenplay would be used by Dauberman and Muschietti,<ref name=\"Kajganich\">{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/david-kajganich-a-bigger-splash-it-movie-interview/|title='A Bigger Splash' Writer David Kajganich on His Unique Approach to the Remake and 'It'|last=Page|first=Aubrey|date=May 5, 2016|work=[[Collider.com]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160710194841/http://collider.com/david-kajganich-a-bigger-splash-it-movie-interview/|archivedate=July 10, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> with the writer stating, \"We know there's a new director, I don't know myself whether he's going back to any of the previous drafts or writing from scratch. I may not know until the film comes out. I don't know how it works! If you find out let me know.\"<ref name=\"Kajganich\" />\n\nOn June 2, 2016, [[Jaeden Martell|Jaeden Lieberher]] was confirmed to be portraying lead protagonist, Bill Denbrough.<ref name=\"William\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/it-remake-jaeden-lieberher-1201787877/|title='It' Remake to Star 'Midnight Special's\u2019 Jaeden Lieberher|last=Kroll|first=Justin|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=June 2, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701204208/http://variety.com/2016/film/news/it-remake-jaeden-lieberher-1201787877/|archivedate=July 1, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On June 2, 2016, ''The Hollywood Reporter'' reported that [[Bill Skarsg\u00e5rd]] was in final negotiations to star as Pennywise, whose cast will also include [[Finn Wolfhard]], [[Jack Dylan Grazer]], [[Wyatt Oleff]], [[Chosen Jacobs]] and [[Jeremy Ray Taylor]].<ref name=Bill>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/stephen-kings-adaptation-finds-pennywise-898993|title=Stephen King's 'It' Adaptation Finds Its Pennywise the Clown (Exclusive)|last=Kit|first=Borys|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=June 2, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160622160247/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/stephen-kings-adaptation-finds-pennywise-898993|archivedate=June 22, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On June 2, 2016, there was a call for 100 background performers, with the background actor call going from 3 p.m. to 7 p.m. and by 4 p.m. more than 300 people had gone through; the casting call also asked for a marching band and period cars between 1970 and 1989.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northumberlandnews.com/community-story/6704271-hundreds-turn-up-for-stephen-king-s-it-background-actor-cast-call-in-port-hope//|title=Hundreds turn up for Stephen King's 'It' background actor cast call in Port Hope|last=Northumberland News Editor|first=|date=June 2, 2016|work=Northumberland News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160707232022/http://www.northumberlandnews.com/community-story/6704271-hundreds-turn-up-for-stephen-king-s-it-background-actor-cast-call-in-port-hope/|archivedate=July 7, 2016|accessdate=July 10, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On February 18, 2016, ''The Hollywood Reporter'' reported that Owen Teague was set to portray Patrick Hocksetter.<ref name=Hockstetter>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/bloodline-actor-joins-adaptation-stephen-900672|title='Bloodline' Actor Joins Adaptation of Stephen King's 'It' (Exclusive)|last=Kit|first=Borys|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=June 9, 2016|accessdate=January 4, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160619100458/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/bloodline-actor-joins-adaptation-stephen-900672|archivedate=June 19, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On June 21, 2016, it was officially announced that [[Nicholas Hamilton]] had been cast to play Henry Bowers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/06/nicholas-hamilton-joins-stephen-kings-it-the-last-film-festival-gets-theatrical-release-dennis-hopper-1201776453/|title=Nicholas Hamilton in Stephen King's 'It'; Monterey Media Acquires 'The Last Film Festival'|last=Busch|first=Anita|date=June 21, 2016|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160626085111/http://deadline.com/2016/06/nicholas-hamilton-joins-stephen-kings-it-the-last-film-festival-gets-theatrical-release-dennis-hopper-1201776453/|archivedate=June 26, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On June 21, 2016, [[Bloody Disgusting]] reported that [[Javier Botet]] was added to the cast shortly before filming commenced.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/movie/3395895/horror-wizard-javier-botet-to-haunt-mummy-stephen-kings/|title=Horror Wizard Javier Botet to Haunt 'The Mummy' and Stephen King's 'It'|last=Barkan|first=Jonathan|date=June 21, 2016|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625030644/http://bloody-disgusting.com/movie/3395895/horror-wizard-javier-botet-to-haunt-mummy-stephen-kings/|archivedate=June 25, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dreadcentral.com/news/172993/creature-performer-javier-botet-joins-mummy-stephen-kings/|title=Creature Performer Javier Botet Joins The Mummy and Stephen King's It|last=Squires|first=John|date=June 22, 2016|work=[[Dread Central]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160623161735/http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/172993/creature-performer-javier-botet-joins-mummy-stephen-kings/|archivedate=June 23, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On June 22, 2016, ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' reported that Muschietti had chosen actress [[Sophia Lillis]] to portray Beverly Marsh.<ref name=\"Beverly\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/06/it-new-line-sophia-lillis-stephen-king-aunjanue-ellis-pimp-1201777627/|title=Sophia Lillis Joins New Line's 'It' Remake; Aunjanue Ellis Sign on To Christine Crokos' \u2018Pimp'|last=A. Lincoln|first=Ross|date=June 22, 2015|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160627162517/http://deadline.com/2016/06/it-new-line-sophia-lillis-stephen-king-aunjanue-ellis-pimp-1201777627/|archivedate=June 27, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On June 24, 2016, [[Moviepilot]] reported that Stephen Bogaert was added to the cast shortly before filming commenced, with Bogaert portraying Al Marsh, the abusive father of Beverly Marsh.<ref name=\"Bogaert\">{{cite web|url=http://moviepilot.com/posts/3978236|title=Here's The Full Cast List for the New 'IT' Movie|last=Richardson|first=Jancy|date=June 24, 2015|work=[[Moviepilot]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160629070642/http://moviepilot.com/posts/3978236|archivedate=June 29, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn July 22, 2016, Barbara Muschietti was interviewed by ''Northumberland News''{{'}} Karen Longwell, wherein she spoke about the filming locations on ''It'', while mentioning the beauty of Port Hope being one of the reasons as to why it was chosen, while Muschietti added, \"We were looking for an idyllic town, one that would be a strong contrast to the story. Port Hope is the kind of place we all wish we had grown up in: long summers riding bicycles, walks by the lake, a lovely main street, charming homes with green lawns, warm people.\"<ref name=Criss>{{cite web|url=http://www.northumberlandnews.com/news-story/6779167-barbara-muschiette-producer-of-film-based-on-stephen-king-s-novel-it-talks-about-experience-in-p|title=Barbara Muschietti, producer of film based on Stephen King's novel 'It', talks about experience in Port Hope|last=Longwell|first=Karen|work=Northumberland News|date=July 22, 2016|accessdate=July 27, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160725134239/http://www.northumberlandnews.com/news-story/6779167-barbara-muschiette-producer-of-film-based-on-stephen-king-s-novel-it-talks-about-experience-in-p/|archivedate=July 25, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Muschietti also mentioned that 360 extras from the area, from adults to tiny kids, had been involved.<ref name=\"Criss\" />\n\nOn August 11, 2016, at [[The CW]] [[TCA Awards|TCA]] presentation for the upcoming series ''[[Frequency (TV series)|Frequency]]'', producer Dan Lin spoke of the piece's comparison to [[Netflix]]'s ''[[Stranger Things (TV series)|Stranger Things]]'', with Lee describing ''It'' being a \"homage to 80s movies\", while remarking: \"I think a great analogy is actually Stranger Things, and we're seeing it on Netflix right now. It's very much an homage to '80s movies, whether it's classic Stephen King or even [[Steven Spielberg|Spielberg]]. Think about ''[[Stand by Me (film)|Stand by Me]]'' (1986) as far as the bonding amongst the kids. But there is a really scary element in Pennywise.\"<ref name=\"Stranger\">{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/it-movie-stranger-things-dan-lin/|title='It' Producer Dan Lin Says the Remake Is Like 'Stranger Things'|last=Foutch|first=Haleigh|date=August 11, 2016|work=[[Collider.com]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812183907/http://collider.com/it-movie-stranger-things-dan-lin/|archivedate=August 12, 2016|accessdate=August 13, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Lin continued, speaking of how well the young cast has bonded in these first weeks of shooting. Lin stated, \"We clearly had a great dynamic amongst the kids. Really great chemistry is always a challenging thing with a movie like It because you're casting kids who don't have a ton of experience, but it ended up being really natural. Each kid, like a ''[[The Goonies]]'' (1985) or ''Stand by Me'' (1986), has a very specific personality and they're forming the loser's club obviously We've spent a few months getting the kids to bond and now they're going to fight this evil, scary clown.\"<ref name=\"Stranger\" />\n\nOn February 9, 2017, at the press day for ''[[The Lego Batman Movie]]'' (2017), Lin confirmed that ''It'' is going to be rated R by the [[Motion Picture Association of America|MPAA]], to which  he stated to Collider.com{{'}}s Steve Weintraub, \"If you're going to make a \"Rated-R movie\", you have to fully embrace what it is, and you have to embrace the source material. It is a scary clown that's trying to kill kids. They do have a scary clown that's taken over the town of Derry, so it's going to be rated R.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/it-remake-rated-r-sequel-adults/#pennywise|title=Producer Dan Lin Confirms \u2018It\u2019 Rating and Sequel Plans|last=Goldberg|first=Matt|date=February 9, 2017|work=[[Collider.com]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170313125903/http://collider.com/it-remake-rated-r-sequel-adults/#pennywise|archivedate=March 13, 2017|accessdate=March 12, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On March 11, 2017, Muschietti, at the [[SXSW]] festival, spoke of an element of the [[pre-production]] phase in his attempt to keep Skarsg\u00e5rd separated from the film's child actors, wherein the actor wasn't introduced to the young cast until Pennywise's first encounter with the children:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dailydead.com/sxsw-2017-impressions-first-footage-new-footage-annabelle-2/|title=SXSW 2017: Impressions of First Footage from IT & New Footage from ANNABELLE 2|last=Wixson|first=Heather|date=March 12, 2017|work=Daily Dead|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170313131627/http://dailydead.com/sxsw-2017-impressions-first-footage-new-footage-annabelle-2/|archivedate=March 13, 2017|accessdate=March 12, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> \"It was something that we agreed on, and that's how it happened The day that he showed up on the stage, they fucking freaked out. Bill is like, seven-foot high, and I can't describe how scary he looks in person. He's a wiry man, crouching, making sounds, snotting, drooling, speaking in [[Swedish language|Swedish]] sometimes. Terrifying.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theverge.com/2017/3/12/14897214/it-reboot-pennywise-preview-sxsw-2017|title=The new Pennywise terrified the young cast of Stephen King\u2019s IT reboot|last=Farokhmanesh|first=Megan|date=March 12, 2017|work=[[The Verge]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312200748/http://www.theverge.com/2017/3/12/14897214/it-reboot-pennywise-preview-sxsw-2017|archivedate=March 12, 2017|accessdate=March 12, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Muschietti stated that the story had been moved forward, with the scenes with the young Losers Club shifting from the 1950s to the 1980s, while also describing their plot as \"getting much wider,\" with new material not in the novel or the [[It (miniseries)|1990 miniseries]].<ref name=\"SXSW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/daily/sxsw/2017-03-12/sxsw-panel-face-your-fears/|title=SXSW Panel: Face Your Fears|last=Whittaker|first=Richard|date=March 12, 2017|work=[[The Austin Chronicle]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312102610/http://www.austinchronicle.com/daily/sxsw/2017-03-12/sxsw-panel-face-your-fears/|archivedate=March 12, 2017|accessdate=March 13, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> However, Muschietti said he hoped it would still strike the same emotional resonance that the book did for him when he first read it: \"It's all about trying to hit the core and the heart.\"<ref name=\"SXSW\" />\n\nOn July 12, 2017, Muschietti, in an interview with French magazine ''Mad Movies'', spoke of when developing the R rated film, in which allowed him to go into very adult themes, which was championed from the people at New Line Cinema.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mad-movies.com/fr/module/99999735/4495/ca-d-andy-muschietti|title=\u00c7A BY ANDY MUSCHIETTI|last=Mad Movies Editors|first=|date=July 12, 2017|work=Mad Movies|accessdate=July 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3444929/new-pennywise-image-found-french-magazine-cover/|title=New Pennywise Image Found On French Magazine Cover|last=Squires|first=John|date=July 3, 2017|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170704024519/http://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3444929/new-pennywise-image-found-french-magazine-cover/|archivedate=July 4, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He also stated that, \"if you aimed for a PG-13 movie, you had nothing at the end. So we were very lucky that the producers didn't try to stop us. In fact it's more our own moral compass that sometimes showed us that some things lead us in places where we didn't want to go.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3446886/andy-muschietti-talks-holding-nothing-back-r-rated/|title=Andy Muschietti Talks Holding Nothing Back for \"R\"-rated \u2018IT\u2019|last=Squires|first=John|date=July 14, 2017|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170716093735/http://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3446886/andy-muschietti-talks-holding-nothing-back-r-rated/|archivedate=July 16, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flickeringmyth.com/2017/07/it-director-andy-muschietti-on-the-films-r-rating/|title=It director Andy Muschietti on the film\u2019s R rating|last=Collinson|first=Gary|date=July 16, 2017|work=Flickering Myth|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In the same interview, on July 12, 2017, producer Barbara Muschietti added that there was only one scene that was deemed to be too horrific to feature in the new adaptation, in which she stated,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.unilad.co.uk/film/new-it-film-will-contain-scenes-too-intense-for-the-original/|title=New IT Film Will Contain Scenes \u2018Too Intense\u2019 For The Original|last=Murray|first=Emily|date=July 16, 2017|work=[[UniLad]]|accessdate=July 20, 2017}}</ref> \"you won't find the scene where a kid has his back broken and is thrown in the toilets. We thought that the visual translation of that scene had something that was really too much.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehookmag.com/2017/07/new-movie-will-r-rated-adult-themes-143903/|title=The New 'IT' Movie Will Be \"R\" Rated With \"Very Adult Themes\"|last=Naylor|first=Daisy|date=July 16, 2017|work=thehooknew|accessdate=July 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808035223/http://thehookmag.com/2017/07/new-movie-will-r-rated-adult-themes-143903/|archive-date=August 8, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ihorror.com/director-muschetti-talks-advantages-r-rating/|title=IT Director Talks the Advantages of an R Rating|last=Carptenter|first=Michael|date=July 16, 2017|work=iHorror|accessdate=July 20, 2017}}</ref> Muschietti concluded by emphasizing that nothing was removed from the original vision, nor was the violence of any event watered down.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/it-movie-rating-adult-story/|title=IT Director: R Rating Allows Film to Explore \u2018Very Adult Themes\u2019|last=Kennedy|first=Michael|date=July 14, 2017|work=[[Screen Rant]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170717232034/http://screenrant.com/it-movie-rating-adult-story/|archivedate=July 17, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn July 19, 2017, in an interview with ''Variety''{{'}}s Brent Lang, director Muschietti commented of the monstrous forms that It shall be taking, as well as noting the fact that they'll be very different from the incarnations present in King's story, in which he stated,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3448025/various-monsters-will-different-book/|title=Various Monsters in \u2018IT\u2019 Will Be Very Different from the Book|last=Squires|first=John|date=July 19, 2017|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170720010749/http://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3448025/various-monsters-will-different-book/|archivedate=July 20, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> \"The story is the same, but there are changes in the things the kids are scared of. In the book they're children in the 50s, so the incarnations of the monsters are mainly from movies, so it's [[Larry Talbot|Wolf Man]], [[Imhotep (The Mummy)|the Mummy]], [[Frankenstein's monster|Frankenstein]], and [[Count Dracula|Dracula]]. I had a different approach. I wanted to bring out deeper fears, based not only on movie monsters but on childhood traumas.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.joblo.com/horror-movies/news/director-says-stephen-king-s-it-will-not-feature-the-classic-movie-monsters-641|title=ANDY MUSCHIETTI TALKS IT PART 2 & CLASSIC MOVIE MONSTERS|last=Sprague|first=Mike|date=July 19, 2017|work=[[JoBlo.com]]|accessdate=July 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.joe.co.uk/entertainment/theres-new-terrifying-details-about-the-it-film-134555|title=There's new terrifying details about the IT film|last=Moore|first=Paul|date=July 20, 2017|work=[[Joe (website)|Joe]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170720120650/https://www.joe.co.uk/entertainment/theres-new-terrifying-details-about-the-it-film-134555|archivedate=July 20, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> While on the topic of what being the key to a successful horror film, Muschietti concluded by remarking that \"Stay true to what scares you. If you don't respect that, you can't scare anyone.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/it-director-andres-muschietti-two-movies-bill-skarsgard-1202499038/amp/|title=\u2018It\u2019 Director on Tackling the Two R-Rated Movies and Why He Picked Bill Skarsgard for Pennywise|last=Lang|first=Brent|date=July 19, 2017|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170719214312/http://variety.com/2017/film/news/it-director-andres-muschietti-two-movies-bill-skarsgard-1202499038/amp/|archivedate=July 19, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Muschietti explained how Skarsg\u00e5rd caught his attention to embody Pennywise, while pointing out that he didn't want the young cast to spend too much time with the actor when not shooting, and encouraged the cast to \"maintain distance\" between them, wherein Muschietti detailed:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.femalefirst.co.uk/movies/movie-news/andres-muschietti-confirms-prep-date-sequel-1075855.html|title=Andres Muschietti confirms prep date for IT sequel|last=Female First Editors|first=|date=July 20, 2017|work=Female First|accessdate=July 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-gb/entertainment/movies/andres-muschietti-confirms-prep-date-for-it-sequel/ar-AAoulDR|title=Andres Muschietti confirms prep date for IT sequel|last=MSN Editors|first=|date=July 20, 2017|work=[[MSN]]|accessdate=July 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808033345/http://www.msn.com/en-gb/entertainment/movies/andres-muschietti-confirms-prep-date-for-it-sequel/ar-AAoulDR|archive-date=August 8, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> We wanted to carry the impact of the encounters to when the cameras were rolling. The first scene where Bill interacted with the children, it was fun to see how the plan worked. The kids were really, really creeped out by Bill. He's pretty intimidating because he's six-four and has all this makeup.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://popculture.com/movies/2017/07/19/stephen-kings-it-remake-pennywise-bill-skarasgard/|title=Stephen King's 'It' Director Explains How Bill Skarsgard Won Coveted Pennywise Role|last=Cavanaugh|first=Patrick|date=July 19, 2017|work=Pop Culture|accessdate=July 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn February 16, 2016, producer [[Roy Lee]], in an interview with Collider, mentioned a second ''It'' film, remarking, \"[Dauberman] wrote the most recent draft working with [Muschietti], so it's being envisioned as two movies.\"<ref name=\"Muschietti\">{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/it-movie-news-rating/|title=Exclusive: 'It' Movie Hopefully Shooting This Year; Will Be Rated-R|last=Chitwood|first=Adam|date=February 19, 2016|work=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160626211828/http://collider.com/it-movie-news-rating/|archivedate=June 26, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On July 19, 2017, Muschietti revealed that production was set to begin in the spring of 2018, adding,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/it-part-2-director-andy-muschietti/|title='IT' Director Andy Muschietti Says He's Coming Back for a Sequel|last=Foutch|first=Haleigh|date=July 19, 2017|work=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170720053246/http://collider.com/it-part-2-director-andy-muschietti/|archivedate=July 20, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/it-movie-sequel-filming-2018-start/|title=Second IT Movie Adaptation Aims to Start Filming Next Year|last=Zinski|first=Dan|date=July 19, 2017|work=[[Screen Rant]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170721010304/http://screenrant.com/it-movie-sequel-filming-2018-start/|archivedate=July 21, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> \"We'll probably have a script for the second part in January [2018]. Ideally, we would start prep in March. Part one is only about the kids. Part two is about these characters 27 years later as adults, with flashbacks to 1989 when they were kids.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/it-already-has-a-sequel-planned|title=STEPHEN KING'S IT ALREADY HAS A SEQUEL PLANNED|last=Wax|first=Alyse|date=July 20, 2017|work=[[Syfy]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170720065345/http://www.syfy.com/syfywire/it-already-has-a-sequel-planned|archivedate=July 20, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On July 21, 2017, Muschietti spoke of looking forward to having a dialogue in the second film that does not exist within the first, stating, \"... it seems like we're going to do it. It's the second half, it's not a sequel. It's the second half and it's very connected to the first one.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/it-movie-andy-muschietti-interview-sdcc/|title='IT' Director Andy Muschietti on Reinventing Pennywise and Sequel Plans|last=Foutch|first=Haleigh|date=July 21, 2017|work=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|accessdate=July 22, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/news/1683730/why-the-it-movie-left-the-adult-storyline-out-of-the-first-film|title=Why The IT Movie Left The Adult Storyline Out Of The First Film|last=O'Connell|first=Sean|date=July 22, 2017|work=CinemaBlend|accessdate=July 23, 2017}}</ref> Muschietti stated that two cut scenes from the first film will possibly be included in the second, one of which being the fire at the Black Spot from the book.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/it-movie-cut-scenes|title=The 'IT' Movie Had to Cut Two Crazy Scenes to Stay On-Budget|last=Foutch|first=Haleigh|date=July 27, 2017|work=Collider.com|accessdate=July 27, 2017}}</ref> On September 25, 2017, [[New Line Cinema]] announced that the sequel would be released on September 6, 2019,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/it-movie-sequel-release-date-1202570309/|title='It' Sequel Sets September 2019 Release Date|last=McNary|first=Dave|date=September 25, 2017|work=[[Variety.com]]|accessdate=July 25, 2017}}</ref> with [[Gary Dauberman]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/it-sequel-plans-moving-forward-at-new-line-1035456|title='It' Movie Sequel Plans Move Forward at New Line|last=Kit|first=Borys|date=September 7, 2017|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=July 25, 2017}}</ref> and Jeffrey Jurgensen (who later went uncredited)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/are-you-afraid-of-the-dark-movie-release-1202632308/|title=''Are You Afraid Of The Dark?'' Movie Gets October 2019 Release|last=McNary|first=Dave|date=December 6, 2017|publisher=Variety|accessdate=December 6, 2017}}</ref> writing the script. Andy Muschietti returned to direct.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/it-sequel-official-writer-gary-dauberman-1202550077/|title='It' Sequel Moves Ahead With Screenwriter Gary Dauberman|last1=McNary|first1=Dave|date=September 7, 2017|work=Variety|accessdate=September 26, 2017}}</ref> Dauberman would later leave the project to write and direct ''[[Annabelle Comes Home]]'', while [[Jason Fuchs]] was brought in as his replacement.<ref>{{cite web |last=Foutch |first=Haleigh |url=https://collider.com/it-2-script-gary-dauberman-jason-fuchs/|title=''It 2'' Filmmakers on How Jason Fuchs Helped Bring the Sequel Script to the Finish Line |date=July 22, 2019 |work=Collider |accessdate=September 20, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190916055021/http://collider.com/it-2-script-gary-dauberman-jason-fuchs/|archive-date=September 16, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Recurring cast and characters ==\n{{Cast indicator|A|C|O|V|Y}}\n<!--Only put characters that have a roles within both films.-->{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; width:40%;\"\n! rowspan=\"4\" scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |Characters\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:center:\" |Films\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:30%\" |''[[It (2017 film)|It]]''\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:30%\" |''[[It Chapter Two]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |2017\n! scope=\"col\" |2019\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[It (character)|It / Pennywise the Dancing Clown]]\n|colspan=\"2\"|[[Bill Skarsg\u00e5rd]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Bill Denbrough]]\n|[[Jaeden Martell|Jaeden Lieberher]]\n|[[James McAvoy]]<hr>Jaeden Lieberher{{ref|young|Y}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Beverly Marsh]]\n|[[Sophia Lillis]]\n|[[Jessica Chastain]]<hr>Sophia Lillis{{ref|young|Y}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Ben Hanscom\n|[[Jeremy Ray Taylor]]\n|[[Jay Ryan (actor)|Jay Ryan]]<hr>Jeremy Ray Taylor{{ref|young|Y}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Richie Tozier]]\n|[[Finn Wolfhard]]\n|[[Bill Hader]]<hr>Finn Wolfhard{{ref|young|Y}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Eddie Kaspbrak]]\n|[[Jack Dylan Grazer]]\n|[[James Ransone]]<hr>Jack Dylan Grazer{{ref|young|Y}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Stanley Uris\n|[[Wyatt Oleff]]\n|[[Andy Bean (actor)|Andy Bean]]<hr>Wyatt Oleff{{ref|young|Y}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Mike Hanlon\n|[[Chosen Jacobs]]\n|[[Isaiah Mustafa]]<hr>Chosen Jacobs{{ref|young|Y}}<hr>Tristian Levi Cox{{ref|young|Y}}<hr>Torian Matthew{{ref|young|Y}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Henry Bowers\n|[[Nicholas Hamilton]]\n|Teach Grant<hr>Nicholas Hamilton{{ref|young|Y}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Georgie Denbrough]]\n|colspan=\"2\"| [[Jackson Robert Scott]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Patrick Hockstetter\n|colspan=\"2\"| [[Owen Teague]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Alvin Marsh \n|colspan=\"2\"| Stephen Bogaert\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Sonia Kaspbrak / Myra\n|colspan=\"2\"| Molly Atkinson\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Mr. Keene\n|colspan=\"2\"| Joe Bostick\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Gretta Keene\n|[[Megan Charpentier]]\n|Juno Rinaldi<hr>Megan Charpentier{{ref|young|Y}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |The Hobo / The Leper /<br>The Witch\n|colspan=\"2\"| [[Javier Botet]]\n|}\n\n== Additional crew and production details ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:90%;width:40%;\"\n! rowspan=\"3\" |Role\n! colspan=\"2\" |Films\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center; width:12%;\" |''[[It (2017 film)|It]]''\n! style=\"text-align:center; width:12%;\" |''[[It Chapter Two]]''\n|-\n!2017\n!2019\n|-\n!Composer(s)\n|colspan=\"2\"| [[Benjamin Wallfisch]]\n|-\n!Cinematography\n|[[Chung Chung-hoon|Chung-hoon Chung]]\n|Checco Varese\n|-\n!Editor(s)\n|colspan=\"2\"| [[Jason Ballantine]]\n|-\n!Production company\n|[[New Line Cinema]]<hr>[[RatPac-Dune Entertainment]]<hr>[[Vertigo Entertainment]]<hr>Lin Pictures<hr>[[KatzSmith Productions]]\n|New Line Cinema<hr>Double Dream<hr>Vertigo Entertainment<hr>Rideback\n|-\n!Distributor\n| colspan=\"8\" |[[Warner Bros. Pictures]]\n|-\n!Running time\n|135 minutes\n|170 minutes\n|-\n!Release date\n|{{start date|2017|9|8}}\n|{{start date|2019|9|6}}\n|}\n\n== Reception ==\n\n=== Box office performance ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;&quot;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Film\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Release date\n! colspan=\"3\" |Box office gross\n! colspan=\"2\" |Box office ranking\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Budget\n! rowspan=\"2\" |{{Abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n!North America\n!Other territories\n!Worldwide\n!North America\n!Worldwide\n|-\n|''It''\n|September 8, 2017\n|$327,481,748\n|$372,900,000\n|$700,381,748\n|#66\n|#117\n|$35 million\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=it.htm|title=It (2017) \u2013 Box Office Mojo|website=www.boxofficemojo.com|access-date=2019-09-19}}</ref>\n|-\n|''It Chapter Two''\n|September 6, 2019\n|$211,593,228\n|$260,500,000\n|$472,093,228\n|#190\n|#249\n|$79 million\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl1107461633/|title=It: Chapter Two \u2013 Box Office Mojo|website=www.boxofficemojo.com|access-date=2019-12-13}}</ref>\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |Totals\n!${{val|fmt=commas|{{#expr:327481748+211593228}}}}\n!${{val|fmt=commas|{{#expr:372900000+260500000}}}}\n!${{val|fmt=commas|{{#expr:700381748+472093228}}}}\n!\n!\n!$114 million\n!\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Critical response ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" width=\"99%\" border=\"1\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!Film\n![[Rotten Tomatoes]]\n![[Metacritic]]\n![[CinemaScore]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |''It''\n|86% (368 reviews)<ref>{{Citation|title=It (2017)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/it_2017|language=en|access-date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n|69 (49 critics)<ref>{{Citation|title=It|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/it|access-date=2019-09-20}}</ref>\n|B+<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinemascore.com/|title=Home|website=Cinemascore|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-20}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |''It Chapter Two''\n|63% (353 reviews)<ref>{{Citation|title=It Chapter Two (2019)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/it_chapter_two|language=en|access-date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n|58 (52 critics)<ref>{{Citation|title=It: Chapter Two|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/it-chapter-two|access-date=2019-09-20}}</ref>\n|B+<ref name=\":0\" />\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Stephen King's It}}\n{{Media based on Stephen King works}}\n\n[[Category:Horror film series]]\n[[Category:It (novel)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American horror film series}}\n{{Infobox media franchise\n| title = ''It''\n| image = IT (2017 film) logo.svg\n| caption = Official logo, used since the [[It (2017 film)|2017 film]]\n| creator = {{plainlist|\n* [[New Line Cinema]]\n* [[Vertigo Entertainment]]\n* [[KatzSmith Productions]]\n}}\n| origin = ''[[It (novel)|It]]''\n| owner = [[Warner Bros. Pictures]]\n| films = * {{nowrap|''[[It (2017 film)|It]]''}}\n* {{nowrap|''[[It Chapter Two]]''}}\n| soundtracks = * {{nowrap|''[[It (2017 film)#Music|It (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack)]]''}}\n* {{nowrap|''[[It Chapter Two#Music|It Chapter Two (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack)]]''}}\n| novels = ''It''\n}}\n\n'''''It''''' is a series of American [[horror film]]s. The series consists of two films and is the second adaptation of the [[It (novel)|original novel]] by [[Stephen King]], after [[Tommy Lee Wallace]]'s [[It (miniseries)|1990 miniseries]]. The first installment was the film ''[[It (2017 film)|It]]'', released in 2017 by [[Warner Bros. Pictures]]. The franchise centers around a group of seven children living in [[Derry (Stephen King)|Derry, Maine]], who are terrorized by an [[It (character)|eponymous being]] only to face their own personal demons in the process. This being returns to haunt the children every 27 years. The second installment, ''[[It Chapter Two]]'' follows the group 27 years after the events of the first installment.\n\nThe film series grossed a combined $1.1{{nbsp}}billion against a combined budget of $114{{nbsp}}million, and becoming the [[List of highest-grossing horror films#Top 25 highest-grossing horror film franchises and film series|sixth-highest-grossing horror franchise ever]].\n\n==Films==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center; width:100%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"column\" style=\"width:12%\"| Film\n! U.S. release date\n! Director(s)\n! Writer(s)\n! Producer(s)\n|-\n!colspan=\"6\" style=\"background-color:#ccccff;\" | Films\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[It (2017 film)|It]]''\n| September 8, 2017\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Andy Muschietti]]\n| Chase Palmer, [[Cary Joji Fukunaga|Cary Fukunaga]] & [[Gary Dauberman]]\n| [[Seth Grahame-Smith]], David Katzenberg, [[Roy Lee]], [[Dan Lin]] & [[Barbara Muschietti]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[It Chapter Two]]''\n| September 6, 2019\n| Gary Dauberman\n| Roy Lee, Dan Lin & Barbara Muschietti\n|}\n\n===''It'' (2017)===\n{{Main|It (2017 film)}}\n''It'' (retroactively known as ''It Chapter One'') is a 2017 American [[supernatural horror film]] based on the 1986 [[It (novel)|novel of the same name]] by [[Stephen King]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/stephen-kings-it-release-date-set-by-warner-bros/|title=Stephen King's 'It' Release Date Set by Warner Bros|last=Geier|first=Thom|work=[[TheWrap]]|date=April 22, 2016|accessdate=October 16, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161024120617/http://www.thewrap.com/stephen-kings-it-release-date-set-by-warner-bros/|archivedate=October 24, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> It is the second adaptation of the novel, following a 1990 [[It (miniseries)|television miniseries]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbr.com/stephen-king-it-rating-sequel-plans/|title=It Remake Has a Rating, Plans for a Sequel|last=Staley|first=Brandon|work=[[Comic Book Resources]]|date=February 9, 2017|accessdate=March 31, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170401143822/http://www.cbr.com/stephen-king-it-rating-sequel-plans/|archivedate=April 1, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.ign.com/articles/2017/03/30/it-how-the-stephen-king-remake-compares-to-the-original-tv-miniseries|title=It: How the Stephen King Remake Compares to the Original TV Miniseries|last=Schedeen|first=Jesse|work=[[IGN]]|date=February 9, 2017|accessdate=March 31, 2017}}</ref> The film tells the story of seven children in [[Derry (Stephen King)|Derry, Maine]], who are terrorized by the eponymous being, only to face their own personal demons in the process. [[Jaeden Martell|Jaeden Lieberher]] stars as [[Bill Denbrough]], with [[Bill Skarsg\u00e5rd]] starring as [[It (character)|Pennywise the Dancing Clown]].<ref name=\"Jaeden\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/stephen-kings-it-casts-hollywood-legacy-as-pennywise-the-clown/|title=Stephen King's 'It' Casts Hollywood Legacy as Pennywise the Clown|last=Verhoeven|first=Beatrice|date=June 2, 2016|work=[[The Wrap]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160620073324/http://www.thewrap.com/stephen-kings-it-casts-hollywood-legacy-as-pennywise-the-clown/|archivedate=June 20, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Wyatt Oleff]], [[Jeremy Ray Taylor]], [[Sophia Lillis]], [[Finn Wolfhard]], [[Jack Dylan Grazer]], [[Chosen Jacobs]], [[Nicholas Hamilton]], [[Owen Teague]], [[Jackson Robert Scott]], and Stephen Bogaert are all featured in supporting roles.<ref name=\"Jaeden\" /> [[Principal photography]] began on June 27, 2016, at [[Pinewood Toronto Studios]] and on locations in and around [[Port Hope, Ontario|Port Hope]], [[Oshawa|Oshawa, Ontario]], and [[Riverdale, Toronto]], and ended on September 21, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hitfix.com/the-dartboard/stephen-king-has-an-it-remake-update-for-you|title=Stephen King has an 'It' remake update for you|last=Eggertsen|first=Chris|date=April 13, 2016|work=[[HitFix]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160622101005/http://www.hitfix.com/the-dartboard/stephen-king-has-an-it-remake-update-for-you|archivedate=June 22, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/it-movie-wraps-production/|title='It' Wraps Production with One Last Creepy Photo|last=Keene|first=Allison|date=September 22, 2016|work=[[Collider.com]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160928204639/http://collider.com/it-movie-wraps-production/|archivedate=September 28, 2016|accessdate=September 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://toronto.ctvnews.ca/mansion-in-riverdale-sets-the-scene-for-horror-film-it-1.3029802|title=Mansion in Riverdale sets the scene for horror film 'It'|last=Greenberg|first=Courtney|date=August 15, 2016|work=CTV Toronto|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161002055307/http://toronto.ctvnews.ca/mansion-in-riverdale-sets-the-scene-for-horror-film-it-1.3029802|archivedate=October 2, 2016|accessdate=September 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The film was released on September 8, 2017 and grossed over $700 million worldwide, against a production budget of $35 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/4935221/it-box-office-stephen-king/|title=It Shatters Box Office Records With Massive Opening Weekend|last=Calfas|first=Jennifer|date=September 10, 2017|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=October 10, 2017}}</ref> It is the highest-grossing horror film of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/sep/29/stephen-king-it-the-exorcist-highest-grossing-horror-film-ever|title=Stephen King's It scares off The Exorcist to become highest-grossing horror ever|last=Mumford|first=Gwilym|date=September 29, 2017|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=October 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/10/blade-runner-2049-it-movie-horror-record-despicable-me-3-kingsman-never-say-die-weekend-results-international-box-office-1202184382/|title=\u2018Blade Runner 2049\u2019 Arrives With $50M Overseas; \u2018It\u2019 Tops $600M WW; \u2018Despicable 3\u2019 Hops Past \u2018Zootopia\u2019 \u2013 Intl Box Office|last=Tartaglione|first=Nancy|date=October 8, 2017|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=October 10, 2017}}</ref> It received positive reviews, with critics praising the performances, direction, cinematography and musical score, and many calling it one of the best Stephen King adaptations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/it-review-roundup-1035698|title='It': What the Critics Are Saying|last=Rahman|first=Abid|date=September 6, 2017|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=October 10, 2017}}</ref> In addition, the film was named as one of the best films of 2017 by various critics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/feature/film-critics-list-the-top-10-movies-of-2017|title=Best of 2017: Film Critic Top Ten Lists|last=Dietz|first=Jason|date=December 5, 2017|work=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=December 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== ''It Chapter Two'' (2019) ===\n{{main|It Chapter Two}}\nTalks for an ''It'' sequel began in February 2016. By September 2017, [[New Line Cinema]] announced that it would be released in September 2019, with Dauberman writing the script and Muschietti to direct. [[Principal photography]] began on June 19, 2018, at [[Pinewood Toronto Studios]] and on locations in and around [[Port Hope, Ontario|Port Hope]], [[Oshawa]], and [[Toronto, Ontario]], and wrapped on October 31, 2018. The film is directed by [[Andy Muschietti]] from a screenplay by [[Gary Dauberman]]. Set in 2016, 27 years after the first film, it stars <!-- Do not change; Chastain is top-billed in the film's credits  -->[[Jessica Chastain]], [[James McAvoy]], [[Bill Hader]], [[Isaiah Mustafa]], [[Jay Ryan (actor)|Jay Ryan]], [[James Ransone]], [[Andy Bean (actor)|Andy Bean]], and [[Bill Skarsg\u00e5rd]], who returns as [[It (character)|Pennywise the Dancing Clown]]. ''It Chapter Two'' premiered at the [[Fox Theater, Westwood Village|Regency Village Theater]] in [[Los Angeles]] on August 26, 2019, and was theatrically released in the United States on September 6, 2019. The film received praise for its acting (particularly Hader and Skarsg\u00e5rd) and themes, though criticism was aimed at its runtime and weaker scares compared to its predecessor. Its faithfulness to the novel also drew a polarized response.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/it-chapter-two-review-roundup-what-critics-are-saying-1236289|title='It: Chapter Two': What the Critics Are Saying|author=Schaffstall|first=Katherine|date=September 3, 2019|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=September 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Supercut===\nIn September 2019, Muschietti expressed interest in releasing a \"Supercut\" version of both chapters. This version would combine both films into one with scenes that were left in the editing process. Muschietti also mentioned the possibility of adding two or three new scenes that would be shot for this edition. The existing scenes will not be re-edited. Instead, it will play out as extended versions of both films, with an intermission included to separate the two. The future of this version has not yet been announced, as of April 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VS4x9uVWOBU&t=405s|title=Director Andy Muschietti tells us why he wants to shoot new scenes for IT |date=September 10, 2019|language=en-US|access-date=October 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Future ===\nIn September 2019, Skarsg\u00e5rd spoke of the possibility of a third installment, saying, \"It would have to be the right type of approach to it. The book ends where the second movie ends, so that is the final chapter of this story. There is this interesting aspect of going back in time before all this happened. There might be a story there that might be worth exploring. Obviously that would be a story that's not in the book, it would be a freestanding story, but obviously within the same universe. So, there might be something interesting out of it. I think it would be fun.\"<ref>https://ew.com/movies/2019/09/08/it-chapter-two-pennywise-bill-skarsgard/</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, Dauberman discussed in an interview of the possibility of a third film, saying, \"I do think it's possible. Anything in the Stephen King Universe interests me but there's only so much of the story we could tell in the two movies. There are definitely elements of the novel you could expand on and make its own movie. It's just a question of whether or not people want to see it but I do think It was on this planet for a very, very, very long time and that's a lot of bloodshed and a lot of stories to tell and I think you could do that for sure.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://io9.gizmodo.com/it-chapter-3-1839759979/amp|title=It Chapter 3: Screenwriter Gary Dauberman Says 'It's Possible'|website=io9.gizmodo.com|access-date=2019-11-30}}</ref>\n\n== Development ==\nThe project was in ongoing development since 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2009/mar/13/stephen-king-it-film-adaptation|title=It's coming, as Hollywood plans Stephen King adaptation|last=Opie|first=David|date=March 13, 2009|work=[[The Guardian]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019031106/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2009/mar/13/stephen-king-it-film-adaptation|archivedate=October 19, 2016|accessdate=October 16, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fuse.tv/2016/08/stephen-king-it-movie-complete-guide-pennywise|title=The Complete Guide to the 'It' Remake: Stephen King's Pennywise Is Back|last=Dionne|first=Zach|date=September 30, 2016|work=[[Fuse (TV channel)|Fuse]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018085202/http://www.fuse.tv/2016/08/stephen-king-it-movie-complete-guide-pennywise|archivedate=October 18, 2016|accessdate=October 16, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/warner-bros-remaking-stephen-kings-it/|title=Warner Bros Remaking Stephen King's It|last=Sciretta|first=Peter|date=March 12, 2009|work=[[/Film]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018213742/http://www.slashfilm.com/warner-bros-remaking-stephen-kings-it/|archivedate=October 18, 2016|accessdate=October 16, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The proposed film adaptations had gone through two major phases of planning: initially with [[Cary Joji Fukunaga|Cary Fukunaga]] from 2009 to 2015, with the early contributions of screenwriter [[David Kajganich]], and with [[Andy Muschietti]], with Fukunaga remaining in some capacity due to prior screenplay contributions.<ref name=\"Development\">{{cite web|url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/stephen-king-everything-need-know/|title=Stephen King's It \u2013 everything you need to know|last=Williams|first=Owen|work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|date=August 11, 2016|accessdate=September 28, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160925053809/http://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/stephen-king-everything-need-know/|archivedate=September 25, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/stephen-king-pet-sematary-it-remakes-schrad-66877/|title=Updates on the 'Pet Sematary' and 'It' Remakes|last=Schrader|first=Chris|date=July 1, 2010|work=Screen Rant|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018215511/http://screenrant.com/stephen-king-pet-sematary-it-remakes-schrad-66877/|archivedate=October 18, 2016|accessdate=October 16, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/stephen-king-it-movies-cary-fukunaga-sandy-178091/|title=Stephen King's 'It' Getting Two-Film Adaptation by 'Jane Eyre' Director|last=Schaefer|first=Sandy|date=June 8, 2012|work=Screen Rant|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316153624/http://screenrant.com/stephen-king-it-movies-cary-fukunaga-sandy-178091/|archivedate=March 16, 2016|accessdate=October 16, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/cary-fukunaga-it/#more-312794|title=Cary Fukunaga Explains the Demise of His Unconventional 'IT' Adaptation|last=Fischer|first=Russ|date=September 5, 2015|work=[[/Film]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018214854/http://www.slashfilm.com/cary-fukunaga-it/#more-312794|archivedate=October 18, 2016|accessdate=October 16, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== David Kajganich (2009\u20132010) ===\n{{quote box\n| align = right\n| width = 35%\n| quote = \"The thing about Stephen King's writing is that he draws his characters so well, it's hard not to imagine they're real people. So it honestly didn't occur to me to try to think of actors in those roles. Pennywise is a bit of a different story, though. His manner is so crucial to what's frightening about him, and it's too much fun to imagine all of the nuances different actors could give him. I think there are a hundred actors who could each pull off a fascinating, horrifying Pennywise, and I tried not to get too attached to any one actor in my head. I think the Pennywise in this adaptation is a less self-conscious of his own irony and surreality than was [[Tim Curry]]'s Pennywise. I think it will be harder to laugh at his antics since, under the permissiveness of an R rating, I was able to give him back a lot of his more upsetting moments from the novel, ones that could never be aired on network television.\"\n| source = David Kajganich, on the construction of Pennywise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://liljas-library.com/showinterview.php?id=73|title=David Kajganich \u2013 INTERVIEW|last=Lilja's Library Editors|first=|work=Lilja's Library|date=June 29, 2010|accessdate=September 11, 2017}}</ref>\n}}On March 12, 2009, ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' reported that [[Warner Bros. Pictures]] would be bringing [[Stephen King]]'s novel to the big screen, with David Kajganich to adapt King's novel, while Dan Lin, [[Roy Lee]] and Doug Davison would be producing the piece.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2009/film/features/warner-bros-taps-kajganich-for-it-1118001188/|title=Warner Bros. taps Kajganich for 'It'|last=McNary|first=Dave|date=March 12, 2009|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160719080933/http://variety.com/2009/film/features/warner-bros-taps-kajganich-for-it-1118001188/|archivedate=July 19, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> When Kajganich learned of Warner Bros.' plans to adapt King's novel, he went after the job.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://liljas-library.com/showinterview.php?id=73|title=David Kajganich \u2013 Interview|last=Lilja's Library Editor|first=|date=June 29, 2010|work=Lilja's Library|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808234208/http://liljas-library.com/showinterview.php?id=73|archivedate=August 8, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Knowing that Warner Bros. was committed to adapting ''It'' as a single feature film, Kajganich began to attempt to try to find a structure that would accommodate such a large number of characters in two different time periods, around 120 pages, which was one of Warner Bros.' stipulations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/screenwriter-gives-update-on-big-screen-adaptation-of-stephen-kings-it/|title=Screenwriter Gives Update on Big Screen Adaptation of Stephen King's It|last=Sciretta|first=Peter|date=July 1, 2010|work=[[/Film]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160524144215/http://www.slashfilm.com/screenwriter-gives-update-on-big-screen-adaptation-of-stephen-kings-it/|archivedate=May 24, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Kajganich worked with Lin, Lee, and Davison on ''[[The Invasion (film)|The Invasion]]'' (2007), and he knew they would champion good storytelling, and allow him the time to work out a solid first draft of the screenplay.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popcrunch.com/it-movie/|title=Stephen King's \"It\" Bound For Big Screen|last=Castina|first=|date=July 6, 2010|work=PopCrunch|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160815153332/http://www.popcrunch.com/it-movie/|archivedate=August 15, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Kajganich spoke of the remake being set in the, \"mid-1980s and in the present mirroring the twenty-odd-year gap King uses in the book and with a great deal of care and attention paid to the backstories of all the characters.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dreadcentral.com/news/10860/exclusive-more-on-the-it-remake-rated-r/|title=Exclusive: More on the IT Remake! Rated R?|last=Barton|first=Steve|date=April 5, 2009|work=[[Dread Central]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160804120207/http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/10860/exclusive-more-on-the-it-remake-rated-r/|archivedate=August 4, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nKajganich also mentioned that Warner Bros. wished for the adaptation to be rated R which he furthered by saying, \"we can really honor the book and engage with the traumas that these characters endure.\", while Kajganich spoke of Warner Bros. wanting the adaptation as a single film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/remake-of-stephen-kings-it-will-be-rated-r-and-set-in-the-mid-1980s/|title=Remake of Stephen King's It will be Rated-R and Set in the Mid-1980s|last=Sciretta|first=Peter|date=April 5, 2009|work=[[/Film]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160829002848/http://www.slashfilm.com/remake-of-stephen-kings-it-will-be-rated-r-and-set-in-the-mid-1980s/|archivedate=August 29, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On June 29, 2010, the screenplay was being re-written by Kajganich.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dreadcentral.com/news/18143/early-details-on-the-it-remake/|title=Early Details on the IT Remake|last=Serafini|first=Matt|date=June 30, 2010|work=[[Dread Central]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808233147/http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/18143/early-details-on-the-it-remake/|archivedate=August 8, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He said that his dream choice for Pennywise would be [[Buster Keaton]] if he were still alive, and the Pennywise that Kajganich scripted being \"less self-conscious of his own irony and surreality.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.joblo.com/movie-news/screenwriter-david-kajganich-gives-an-update-on-stephen-kings-it|title=SCREENWRITER DAVID KAJGANICH GIVES AN UPDATE ON STEPHEN KING'S IT|last=Stephens|first=Niki|date=July 1, 2010|work=[[Collider.com]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160804190540/http://www.joblo.com/movie-news/screenwriter-david-kajganich-gives-an-update-on-stephen-kings-it|archivedate=August 4, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Cary Fukunaga (2012\u20132015) ===\n{{quote box\n| align = right\n| width = 35%\n| quote = \"I am in the midst of rewriting the first script now.  We're not working on the second part yet. The first script is just about the kids. It's more like ''[[The Goonies]]'' (1985) meets a horror film. We're definitely honoring the spirit of Stephen King, but the horror has to be modernized to make it relevant. That's my job, right now, on this pass. I'm working on making the horror more about suspense than visualization of any creatures. I just don't think that's scary. What could be there, and the sounds and how it interacts with things, is scarier than actual monsters.\"\n| source = \u2013 Cary Fukunaga, on the development of ''It''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/cary-fukunaga-true-detective-interview/|title=Director Cary Fukunaga Talks TRUE DETECTIVE, Making an 8-Hour Film, Future Seasons, BEASTS OF NO NATION, Modernizing Horror with IT, and More|last=Radish|first=Christina|work=[[Collider.com]]|date=January 11, 2014|accessdate=June 27, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807054534/http://collider.com/cary-fukunaga-true-detective-interview/|archivedate=August 7, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n}}On June 7, 2012, ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]''  had revealed that Cary Fukunaga was boarding the project as director and will co-write the script with Chase Palmer, while Roy Lee and Dan Lin are producing, as with [[Seth Grahame-Smith]] and David Katzenberg of KatzSmith Productions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/stephen-kings-be-adapted-by-334899|title=Stephen King's 'It' to Be Adapted by Cary Fukunaga into Two Films (Exclusive)|last=Kit|first=Borys|date=June 7, 2012|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160706192550/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/stephen-kings-be-adapted-by-334899|archivedate=July 6, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On May 21, 2014, Warner Bros. was announced to have moved the film to its [[New Line Cinema]] division, with overseer duties conducting by New Line's Walter Hamada and Dave Neustadter, along with Vice President of Production at Warner Bros., Niija Kuykendall.<ref name=New>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/stephen-kings-moves-warner-bros-706062|title=Stephen King's 'It' Moves From Warner Bros. to New Line (Exclusive)|last=Kit|first=Borys|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=May 21, 2014|accessdate=June 27, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160730140142/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/stephen-kings-moves-warner-bros-706062|archivedate=July 30, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On December 5, 2014, in an interview with ''[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]]'', Dan Lin announced that the first film will be a [[coming-of-age]] story about the children tormented by [[It (character)|It]] and the second will skip ahead in time as those same characters band together to continue the fight as adults.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/389569-stephen-kings-it-will-shoot-next-summer|title=Stephen King's IT Will Shoot Next Summer|last=Evry|first=Max|date=December 5, 2014|work=Coming Soon|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303172056/http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/389569-stephen-kings-it-will-shoot-next-summer|archivedate=March 3, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Lin also stated that Fukunaga was only committed to directing the first film, though was currently closing a deal to co-write the second. Lin concluded by mentioning King, to which he remarked, \"The most important thing is that [King] gave us his blessing. We didn't want to make this unless he felt it was the right way to go, and when we sent him the script, the response that Cary got back was, 'Go with God, please! This is the version the studio should make.' So that was really gratifying.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2014/12/fukunaga-to-shoot-stephen-kings-it-next-summer.html?mid=twitter_vulture#|title=Cary Fukunaga Will Shoot Stephen King's It Next Summer|last=Buchanan|first=Kyle|date=December 5, 2014|work=[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]]|accessdate=June 27, 2016}}</ref> Lin confirmed that Fukunaga would begin [[principal photography]] in Summer 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/stephen-kings-it-remake-put-on-indefinite-hold-as-director-cary-fukunaga-walks-out-10275542.html|title=Stephen King's It remake put on indefinite hold as director Cary Fukunaga walks out|last=Shepherd|first=Jack|date=May 26, 2015|work=[[The Independent]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161007150949/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/stephen-kings-it-remake-put-on-indefinite-hold-as-director-cary-fukunaga-walks-out-10275542.html|archivedate=October 7, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn February 3, 2015, Fukunaga was interviewed by ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' wherein he spoke about ''It'', while mentioning he has someone in mind for the role of Pennywise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2015/02/03/cary_fukunaga_on_true_detective_season_2_his_adaption_of_stephen_king_s.html|title=Cary Fukunaga on Adapting It, His Musical With Owen Pallett, and #TrueDetectiveSeason2|last=Wickman|first=Forrest|date=February 3, 2015|work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628135946/http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2015/02/03/cary_fukunaga_on_true_detective_season_2_his_adaption_of_stephen_king_s.html|archivedate=June 28, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On March 3, 2015, Fukunaga spoke of the film, particularly noting his goal to find the \"perfect guy to play Pennywise\". Fukunaga also revealed that he, Kajganich and Palmer had changed the names and dates in the script, adding, the spirit is similar to what he'd like to see in cinemas.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3334554/director-seeks-perfect-pennywise-clown/|title='It' Director Seeks \"Perfect Pennywise\" Clown|last=Disgusting|first=Mr|date=March 3, 2015|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624183418/http://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3334554/director-seeks-perfect-pennywise-clown/|archivedate=June 24, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On May 4, 2015, it was officially announced that [[Will Poulter]] had been cast to play Pennywise, after Fukunaga was \"blown away\" by his audition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2015/05/04/will-poulter-it-pennywise|title=Will Poulter cast as Pennywise in Cary Fukunaga's It|last=P. Sullivan|first=Kevin|date=May 4, 2015|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160618220510/http://www.ew.com/article/2015/05/04/will-poulter-it-pennywise|archivedate=June 18, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"WillP\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/will-poutler-pennywise-the-clown-in-new-lines-it-remake-1201446495/|title=Will Poulter to Play the Evil Clown in 'It' Remake (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Kroll|first=Justin|date=May 4, 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160629051959/http://variety.com/2015/film/news/will-poutler-pennywise-the-clown-in-new-lines-it-remake-1201446495/|archivedate=June 29, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Ty Simpkins]] was considered to play one of The Losers' Club members.<ref name=\"Ty\">{{cite web|url=http://movieweb.com/jurassic-world-interview-ty-simpkins/|title=Jurassic World Interview with Ty Simpkins|last=Gallagher|first=Brian|date=February 27, 2016|work=[[MovieWeb]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161025114439/http://movieweb.com/jurassic-world-interview-ty-simpkins/|archivedate=October 25, 2016|accessdate=October 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn May 25, 2015, it was reported that Fukunaga had dropped out as the director of ''It''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/it-cary-fukunaga-director-exits-1201504672/|title='It' Loses Director Cary Fukunaga|last=Kroll|first=Justin|date=May 25, 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160709011956/http://variety.com/2015/film/news/it-cary-fukunaga-director-exits-1201504672/|archivedate=July 9, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> According to [[TheWrap]], Fukunaga clashed with the studio and didn't want to compromise his artistic vision in the wake of budget cuts by New Line, which greenlit the first film at $30&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/cary-fukunaga-out-as-director-of-stephen-kings-it-at-new-line-exclusive/|title=Cary Fukunaga Out as Director of Stephen King's 'It' at New Line (Exclusive)|last=Geier|first=Thom|date=May 25, 2015|work=[[The Wrap]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628034157/https://www.thewrap.com/cary-fukunaga-out-as-director-of-stephen-kings-it-at-new-line-exclusive/|archivedate=June 28, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> However, Fukunaga maintained that wasn't the case, with him stating he had bigger disagreements with New Line over the direction of the story: \"I was trying to make an unconventional horror film. It didn't fit into the algorithm of what they knew they could spend and make money back on based on not offending their standard genre audience.\"<ref name=\"Cary\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/cary-fukunaga-it-exit-1201584416/|title=Cary Fukunaga Offers New Details on Why 'It' Remake Fell Apart|last=Setoodeh|first=Ramin|date=September 2, 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160704095044/http://variety.com/2015/film/news/cary-fukunaga-it-exit-1201584416/|archivedate=July 4, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He made mention that the budget was perfectly fine, as well as his desire to make Pennywise more than just the clown.<ref name=\"Cary\" /> Fukunaga concluded by stating, \"We invested years and so much anecdotal storytelling in it. Chase and I both put our childhood in that story. So our biggest fear was they were going to take our script and bastardize it So I'm actually thankful that they are going to rewrite the script. I wouldn't want them to stealing our childhood memories and using that I was honoring King's spirit of it, but I needed to update it. King saw an earlier draft and liked it.\"<ref name=\"Cary\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2015/08/17/cary-fukunaga-it-movie?hootPostID=b5145d9e2c7e687d8867d1c08604632f|title=Cary Fukunaga opens up about IT departure \u2013 Exclusive|last=P. Sullivan|first=Kevin|date=August 17, 2015|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161108110348/http://www.ew.com/article/2015/08/17/cary-fukunaga-it-movie?hootPostID=b5145d9e2c7e687d8867d1c08604632f|archivedate=November 8, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On Fukunaga's departure, King wrote, \"The remake of ''IT'' may be dead or undead but we'll always have [[Tim Curry]]. He's still floating down in the sewers of Derry.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/stephenking/status/602931191281496064|title=The remake of IT may be dead|last=King|first=Stephen|date=May 25, 2015|work=Twitter|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322192030/https://twitter.com/StephenKing/status/602931191281496064|archivedate=March 22, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.sky.com/story/1490944/it-remake-dead-as-director-walks-away|title=It Remake 'Dead' As Director Walks Away|last=Sky News Editors|first=Justin|date=May 26, 2015|work=[[Sky News]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150528215629/http://news.sky.com/story/1490944/it-remake-dead-as-director-walks-away|archivedate=May 28, 2015|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Andy Muschietti (2015\u20132017) ===\n{{quote box\n| align = right\n| width = 35%\n| quote = \"The way Cary intended to execute the script is something that only he can talk about. I can say my version of ''It'' highly emphasizes Pennywise's most terrifying virtue, which is It's ability to materialise into your worse fear; I want to take people in a journey into Pennywise's world through a disturbing, surrealistic and intoxicating experience that will leave nobody at ease.\"\n| source = \u2013 Andy Muschietti, on his version of ''It''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liljas-library.com/article.php?id=4659|title=IT Emphasizes Pennywise's Most Terrifying Virtue|last=Jorissen|first=Matt|work=Lilja's Library|date=November 6, 2015|accessdate=June 27, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808225514/http://www.liljas-library.com/article.php?id=4659|archivedate=August 8, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n}}On July 16, 2015, it was announced that Andy Muschietti was in negotiations to direct ''It'', with New Line beginning a search for a new writer to tailor a script to Muschietti's vision,<ref name=\"Andr\u00e9s\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/stephen-kings-finds-new-director-809080|title=Stephen King's 'It' Finds New Director (Exclusive)|last=Kit|first=Borys|date=July 16, 2015|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160716124053/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/stephen-kings-finds-new-director-809080|archivedate=July 16, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.empireonline.com/people/andres-muschietti/mama-andres-muschietti-negotiations-direct/|title=Mama's Andr\u00e9s Muschietti in Negotiations To Direct It|last=White|first=James|date=July 17, 2015|work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161003180808/http://www.empireonline.com/people/andres-muschietti/mama-andres-muschietti-negotiations-direct/|archivedate=October 3, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> with the announcement also confirming the possible participation of Muschietti's sister, Barbara Muschietti, as a producer, and Richard Brener joining Hamada, Neustadter and Kuykendall to oversee the project.<ref name=\"Andr\u00e9s\" /> On April 22, 2016, it was indicated that Will Poulter, who was originally tapped to portray Pennywise in Fukunaga's version, had dropped out of the film due to a scheduling conflict and that executives were meeting with actors to portray the antagonist.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/warner-bros-announces-release-date-for-it-1201759274/|title=Warner Bros. Announces Release Date for 'It'|last=Kroll|first=Justin|date=April 22, 2016|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625020838/http://variety.com/2016/film/news/warner-bros-announces-release-date-for-it-1201759274/|archivedate=June 25, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On April 22, 2016, New Line Cinema set the film for a release of September 8, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/04/chips-it-warner-bros-release-dates-2017-1201742518/|title=Warner Bros. Sets 'CHiPs', 'It' & Untitled PG-13 Comedy For 2017|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|date=April 22, 2016|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624041157/http://deadline.com/2016/04/chips-it-warner-bros-release-dates-2017-1201742518/|archivedate=June 24, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/warner-bros-announces-release-date-for-it-1201759274/|title=Warner Bros. Announces Release Date for 'It'|last=Kroll|first=Justin|date=April 22, 2016|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625020838/http://variety.com/2016/film/news/warner-bros-announces-release-date-for-it-1201759274/|archivedate=June 25, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn October 30, 2015, Muschietti was interviewed by ''Variety'' wherein he spoke about his vision of ''It'', while mentioning Poulter was still in the mix for the role of Pennywise: \"[Poulter] would be a great option. For me he is at the top of my list\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/global/muschiettis-to-produce-supernatural-thriller-shadows-exclusive-1201630876/|title=Muschiettis to Produce Supernatural Thriller 'Shadows' (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Mayorga|first=Emilio|date=October 30, 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305002513/http://variety.com/2015/film/global/muschiettis-to-produce-supernatural-thriller-shadows-exclusive-1201630876/|archivedate=March 5, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He confirmed that next summer is the time for them to start shooting. It was decided to shoot ''It'' during the summer months to give them the time to work with the children who have the main roles in the first part of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inquisitr.com/2541256/filming-starts-next-summer-on-remake-of-stephen-kings-it/|title=Filming Starts Next Summer on Remake of Stephen King Classic 'It'|last=Sewell|first=Annie|date=November 4, 2015|work=[[Inquisitr]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160519230246/http://www.inquisitr.com/2541256/filming-starts-next-summer-on-remake-of-stephen-kings-it/|archivedate=May 19, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Muschietti went on to say that \"King described 50s' terror iconography,\" adding that he feels there is a whole world now to \"rediscover, to update.\" He said there won't be any mummies or werewolves and that the \"terrors are going to be a lot more surprising.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3368274/stephen-kings-it-to-film-next-summer/|title=Stephen King's 'It' to Film Next Summer!|last=Disgusting|first=Mr|date=October 31, 2015|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160705165415/http://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3368274/stephen-kings-it-to-film-next-summer/|archivedate=July 5, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On February 19, 2016, at the [[D.I.C.E. Summit|D.I.C.E. Summit 2016]] producer Roy Lee confirmed that Fukunaga and Chase Palmer's original script had been rewritten, with Lee remarking, \"It will hopefully be shooting later this year. We just got the California tax credit Dauberman wrote the most recent draft working with [Muscetti], so it's being envisioned as two movies.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/stephen-king-it-movies-filming-2016/|title=Stephen King's It May Start Filming in 2016; Two Movies Still Planned|last=Jones|first=Mike|date=February 19, 2016|work=Screen Rant|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625070804/http://screenrant.com/stephen-king-it-movies-filming-2016/|archivedate=June 25, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn May 5, 2016, in an interview with [[Collider.com]], David Kajganich expressed uncertainty as to whether drafts of his original screenplay would be used by Dauberman and Muschietti,<ref name=\"Kajganich\">{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/david-kajganich-a-bigger-splash-it-movie-interview/|title='A Bigger Splash' Writer David Kajganich on His Unique Approach to the Remake and 'It'|last=Page|first=Aubrey|date=May 5, 2016|work=[[Collider.com]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160710194841/http://collider.com/david-kajganich-a-bigger-splash-it-movie-interview/|archivedate=July 10, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> with the writer stating, \"We know there's a new director, I don't know myself whether he's going back to any of the previous drafts or writing from scratch. I may not know until the film comes out. I don't know how it works! If you find out let me know.\"<ref name=\"Kajganich\" />\n\nOn June 2, 2016, [[Jaeden Martell|Jaeden Lieberher]] was confirmed to be portraying lead protagonist, Bill Denbrough.<ref name=\"William\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/it-remake-jaeden-lieberher-1201787877/|title='It' Remake to Star 'Midnight Special's\u2019 Jaeden Lieberher|last=Kroll|first=Justin|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=June 2, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701204208/http://variety.com/2016/film/news/it-remake-jaeden-lieberher-1201787877/|archivedate=July 1, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On June 2, 2016, ''The Hollywood Reporter'' reported that [[Bill Skarsg\u00e5rd]] was in final negotiations to star as Pennywise, whose cast will also include [[Finn Wolfhard]], [[Jack Dylan Grazer]], [[Wyatt Oleff]], [[Chosen Jacobs]] and [[Jeremy Ray Taylor]].<ref name=Bill>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/stephen-kings-adaptation-finds-pennywise-898993|title=Stephen King's 'It' Adaptation Finds Its Pennywise the Clown (Exclusive)|last=Kit|first=Borys|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=June 2, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160622160247/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/stephen-kings-adaptation-finds-pennywise-898993|archivedate=June 22, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On June 2, 2016, there was a call for 100 background performers, with the background actor call going from 3 p.m. to 7 p.m. and by 4 p.m. more than 300 people had gone through; the casting call also asked for a marching band and period cars between 1970 and 1989.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northumberlandnews.com/community-story/6704271-hundreds-turn-up-for-stephen-king-s-it-background-actor-cast-call-in-port-hope//|title=Hundreds turn up for Stephen King's 'It' background actor cast call in Port Hope|last=Northumberland News Editor|first=|date=June 2, 2016|work=Northumberland News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160707232022/http://www.northumberlandnews.com/community-story/6704271-hundreds-turn-up-for-stephen-king-s-it-background-actor-cast-call-in-port-hope/|archivedate=July 7, 2016|accessdate=July 10, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On February 18, 2016, ''The Hollywood Reporter'' reported that Owen Teague was set to portray Patrick Hocksetter.<ref name=Hockstetter>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/bloodline-actor-joins-adaptation-stephen-900672|title='Bloodline' Actor Joins Adaptation of Stephen King's 'It' (Exclusive)|last=Kit|first=Borys|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=June 9, 2016|accessdate=January 4, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160619100458/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/bloodline-actor-joins-adaptation-stephen-900672|archivedate=June 19, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On June 21, 2016, it was officially announced that [[Nicholas Hamilton]] had been cast to play Henry Bowers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/06/nicholas-hamilton-joins-stephen-kings-it-the-last-film-festival-gets-theatrical-release-dennis-hopper-1201776453/|title=Nicholas Hamilton in Stephen King's 'It'; Monterey Media Acquires 'The Last Film Festival'|last=Busch|first=Anita|date=June 21, 2016|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160626085111/http://deadline.com/2016/06/nicholas-hamilton-joins-stephen-kings-it-the-last-film-festival-gets-theatrical-release-dennis-hopper-1201776453/|archivedate=June 26, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On June 21, 2016, [[Bloody Disgusting]] reported that [[Javier Botet]] was added to the cast shortly before filming commenced.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/movie/3395895/horror-wizard-javier-botet-to-haunt-mummy-stephen-kings/|title=Horror Wizard Javier Botet to Haunt 'The Mummy' and Stephen King's 'It'|last=Barkan|first=Jonathan|date=June 21, 2016|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625030644/http://bloody-disgusting.com/movie/3395895/horror-wizard-javier-botet-to-haunt-mummy-stephen-kings/|archivedate=June 25, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dreadcentral.com/news/172993/creature-performer-javier-botet-joins-mummy-stephen-kings/|title=Creature Performer Javier Botet Joins The Mummy and Stephen King's It|last=Squires|first=John|date=June 22, 2016|work=[[Dread Central]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160623161735/http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/172993/creature-performer-javier-botet-joins-mummy-stephen-kings/|archivedate=June 23, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On June 22, 2016, ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' reported that Muschietti had chosen actress [[Sophia Lillis]] to portray Beverly Marsh.<ref name=\"Beverly\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/06/it-new-line-sophia-lillis-stephen-king-aunjanue-ellis-pimp-1201777627/|title=Sophia Lillis Joins New Line's 'It' Remake; Aunjanue Ellis Sign on To Christine Crokos' \u2018Pimp'|last=A. Lincoln|first=Ross|date=June 22, 2015|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160627162517/http://deadline.com/2016/06/it-new-line-sophia-lillis-stephen-king-aunjanue-ellis-pimp-1201777627/|archivedate=June 27, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On June 24, 2016, [[Moviepilot]] reported that Stephen Bogaert was added to the cast shortly before filming commenced, with Bogaert portraying Al Marsh, the abusive father of Beverly Marsh.<ref name=\"Bogaert\">{{cite web|url=http://moviepilot.com/posts/3978236|title=Here's The Full Cast List for the New 'IT' Movie|last=Richardson|first=Jancy|date=June 24, 2015|work=[[Moviepilot]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160629070642/http://moviepilot.com/posts/3978236|archivedate=June 29, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn July 22, 2016, Barbara Muschietti was interviewed by ''Northumberland News''{{'}} Karen Longwell, wherein she spoke about the filming locations on ''It'', while mentioning the beauty of Port Hope being one of the reasons as to why it was chosen, while Muschietti added, \"We were looking for an idyllic town, one that would be a strong contrast to the story. Port Hope is the kind of place we all wish we had grown up in: long summers riding bicycles, walks by the lake, a lovely main street, charming homes with green lawns, warm people.\"<ref name=Criss>{{cite web|url=http://www.northumberlandnews.com/news-story/6779167-barbara-muschiette-producer-of-film-based-on-stephen-king-s-novel-it-talks-about-experience-in-p|title=Barbara Muschietti, producer of film based on Stephen King's novel 'It', talks about experience in Port Hope|last=Longwell|first=Karen|work=Northumberland News|date=July 22, 2016|accessdate=July 27, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160725134239/http://www.northumberlandnews.com/news-story/6779167-barbara-muschiette-producer-of-film-based-on-stephen-king-s-novel-it-talks-about-experience-in-p/|archivedate=July 25, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Muschietti also mentioned that 360 extras from the area, from adults to tiny kids, had been involved.<ref name=\"Criss\" />\n\nOn August 11, 2016, at [[The CW]] [[TCA Awards|TCA]] presentation for the upcoming series ''[[Frequency (TV series)|Frequency]]'', producer Dan Lin spoke of the piece's comparison to [[Netflix]]'s ''[[Stranger Things (TV series)|Stranger Things]]'', with Lee describing ''It'' being a \"homage to 80s movies\", while remarking: \"I think a great analogy is actually Stranger Things, and we're seeing it on Netflix right now. It's very much an homage to '80s movies, whether it's classic Stephen King or even [[Steven Spielberg|Spielberg]]. Think about ''[[Stand by Me (film)|Stand by Me]]'' (1986) as far as the bonding amongst the kids. But there is a really scary element in Pennywise.\"<ref name=\"Stranger\">{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/it-movie-stranger-things-dan-lin/|title='It' Producer Dan Lin Says the Remake Is Like 'Stranger Things'|last=Foutch|first=Haleigh|date=August 11, 2016|work=[[Collider.com]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812183907/http://collider.com/it-movie-stranger-things-dan-lin/|archivedate=August 12, 2016|accessdate=August 13, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Lin continued, speaking of how well the young cast has bonded in these first weeks of shooting. Lin stated, \"We clearly had a great dynamic amongst the kids. Really great chemistry is always a challenging thing with a movie like It because you're casting kids who don't have a ton of experience, but it ended up being really natural. Each kid, like a ''[[The Goonies]]'' (1985) or ''Stand by Me'' (1986), has a very specific personality and they're forming the loser's club obviously We've spent a few months getting the kids to bond and now they're going to fight this evil, scary clown.\"<ref name=\"Stranger\" />\n\nOn February 9, 2017, at the press day for ''[[The Lego Batman Movie]]'' (2017), Lin confirmed that ''It'' is going to be rated R by the [[Motion Picture Association of America|MPAA]], to which  he stated to Collider.com{{'}}s Steve Weintraub, \"If you're going to make a \"Rated-R movie\", you have to fully embrace what it is, and you have to embrace the source material. It is a scary clown that's trying to kill kids. They do have a scary clown that's taken over the town of Derry, so it's going to be rated R.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/it-remake-rated-r-sequel-adults/#pennywise|title=Producer Dan Lin Confirms \u2018It\u2019 Rating and Sequel Plans|last=Goldberg|first=Matt|date=February 9, 2017|work=[[Collider.com]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170313125903/http://collider.com/it-remake-rated-r-sequel-adults/#pennywise|archivedate=March 13, 2017|accessdate=March 12, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On March 11, 2017, Muschietti, at the [[SXSW]] festival, spoke of an element of the [[pre-production]] phase in his attempt to keep Skarsg\u00e5rd separated from the film's child actors, wherein the actor wasn't introduced to the young cast until Pennywise's first encounter with the children:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dailydead.com/sxsw-2017-impressions-first-footage-new-footage-annabelle-2/|title=SXSW 2017: Impressions of First Footage from IT & New Footage from ANNABELLE 2|last=Wixson|first=Heather|date=March 12, 2017|work=Daily Dead|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170313131627/http://dailydead.com/sxsw-2017-impressions-first-footage-new-footage-annabelle-2/|archivedate=March 13, 2017|accessdate=March 12, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> \"It was something that we agreed on, and that's how it happened The day that he showed up on the stage, they fucking freaked out. Bill is like, seven-foot high, and I can't describe how scary he looks in person. He's a wiry man, crouching, making sounds, snotting, drooling, speaking in [[Swedish language|Swedish]] sometimes. Terrifying.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theverge.com/2017/3/12/14897214/it-reboot-pennywise-preview-sxsw-2017|title=The new Pennywise terrified the young cast of Stephen King\u2019s IT reboot|last=Farokhmanesh|first=Megan|date=March 12, 2017|work=[[The Verge]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312200748/http://www.theverge.com/2017/3/12/14897214/it-reboot-pennywise-preview-sxsw-2017|archivedate=March 12, 2017|accessdate=March 12, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Muschietti stated that the story had been moved forward, with the scenes with the young Losers Club shifting from the 1950s to the 1980s, while also describing their plot as \"getting much wider,\" with new material not in the novel or the [[It (miniseries)|1990 miniseries]].<ref name=\"SXSW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/daily/sxsw/2017-03-12/sxsw-panel-face-your-fears/|title=SXSW Panel: Face Your Fears|last=Whittaker|first=Richard|date=March 12, 2017|work=[[The Austin Chronicle]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312102610/http://www.austinchronicle.com/daily/sxsw/2017-03-12/sxsw-panel-face-your-fears/|archivedate=March 12, 2017|accessdate=March 13, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> However, Muschietti said he hoped it would still strike the same emotional resonance that the book did for him when he first read it: \"It's all about trying to hit the core and the heart.\"<ref name=\"SXSW\" />\n\nOn July 12, 2017, Muschietti, in an interview with French magazine ''Mad Movies'', spoke of when developing the R rated film, in which allowed him to go into very adult themes, which was championed from the people at New Line Cinema.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mad-movies.com/fr/module/99999735/4495/ca-d-andy-muschietti|title=\u00c7A BY ANDY MUSCHIETTI|last=Mad Movies Editors|first=|date=July 12, 2017|work=Mad Movies|accessdate=July 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3444929/new-pennywise-image-found-french-magazine-cover/|title=New Pennywise Image Found On French Magazine Cover|last=Squires|first=John|date=July 3, 2017|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170704024519/http://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3444929/new-pennywise-image-found-french-magazine-cover/|archivedate=July 4, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He also stated that, \"if you aimed for a PG-13 movie, you had nothing at the end. So we were very lucky that the producers didn't try to stop us. In fact it's more our own moral compass that sometimes showed us that some things lead us in places where we didn't want to go.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3446886/andy-muschietti-talks-holding-nothing-back-r-rated/|title=Andy Muschietti Talks Holding Nothing Back for \"R\"-rated \u2018IT\u2019|last=Squires|first=John|date=July 14, 2017|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170716093735/http://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3446886/andy-muschietti-talks-holding-nothing-back-r-rated/|archivedate=July 16, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flickeringmyth.com/2017/07/it-director-andy-muschietti-on-the-films-r-rating/|title=It director Andy Muschietti on the film\u2019s R rating|last=Collinson|first=Gary|date=July 16, 2017|work=Flickering Myth|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In the same interview, on July 12, 2017, producer Barbara Muschietti added that there was only one scene that was deemed to be too horrific to feature in the new adaptation, in which she stated,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.unilad.co.uk/film/new-it-film-will-contain-scenes-too-intense-for-the-original/|title=New IT Film Will Contain Scenes \u2018Too Intense\u2019 For The Original|last=Murray|first=Emily|date=July 16, 2017|work=[[UniLad]]|accessdate=July 20, 2017}}</ref> \"you won't find the scene where a kid has his back broken and is thrown in the toilets. We thought that the visual translation of that scene had something that was really too much.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehookmag.com/2017/07/new-movie-will-r-rated-adult-themes-143903/|title=The New 'IT' Movie Will Be \"R\" Rated With \"Very Adult Themes\"|last=Naylor|first=Daisy|date=July 16, 2017|work=thehooknew|accessdate=July 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808035223/http://thehookmag.com/2017/07/new-movie-will-r-rated-adult-themes-143903/|archive-date=August 8, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ihorror.com/director-muschetti-talks-advantages-r-rating/|title=IT Director Talks the Advantages of an R Rating|last=Carptenter|first=Michael|date=July 16, 2017|work=iHorror|accessdate=July 20, 2017}}</ref> Muschietti concluded by emphasizing that nothing was removed from the original vision, nor was the violence of any event watered down.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/it-movie-rating-adult-story/|title=IT Director: R Rating Allows Film to Explore \u2018Very Adult Themes\u2019|last=Kennedy|first=Michael|date=July 14, 2017|work=[[Screen Rant]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170717232034/http://screenrant.com/it-movie-rating-adult-story/|archivedate=July 17, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn July 19, 2017, in an interview with ''Variety''{{'}}s Brent Lang, director Muschietti commented of the monstrous forms that It shall be taking, as well as noting the fact that they'll be very different from the incarnations present in King's story, in which he stated,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3448025/various-monsters-will-different-book/|title=Various Monsters in \u2018IT\u2019 Will Be Very Different from the Book|last=Squires|first=John|date=July 19, 2017|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170720010749/http://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3448025/various-monsters-will-different-book/|archivedate=July 20, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> \"The story is the same, but there are changes in the things the kids are scared of. In the book they're children in the 50s, so the incarnations of the monsters are mainly from movies, so it's [[Larry Talbot|Wolf Man]], [[Imhotep (The Mummy)|the Mummy]], [[Frankenstein's monster|Frankenstein]], and [[Count Dracula|Dracula]]. I had a different approach. I wanted to bring out deeper fears, based not only on movie monsters but on childhood traumas.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.joblo.com/horror-movies/news/director-says-stephen-king-s-it-will-not-feature-the-classic-movie-monsters-641|title=ANDY MUSCHIETTI TALKS IT PART 2 & CLASSIC MOVIE MONSTERS|last=Sprague|first=Mike|date=July 19, 2017|work=[[JoBlo.com]]|accessdate=July 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.joe.co.uk/entertainment/theres-new-terrifying-details-about-the-it-film-134555|title=There's new terrifying details about the IT film|last=Moore|first=Paul|date=July 20, 2017|work=[[Joe (website)|Joe]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170720120650/https://www.joe.co.uk/entertainment/theres-new-terrifying-details-about-the-it-film-134555|archivedate=July 20, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> While on the topic of what being the key to a successful horror film, Muschietti concluded by remarking that \"Stay true to what scares you. If you don't respect that, you can't scare anyone.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/it-director-andres-muschietti-two-movies-bill-skarsgard-1202499038/amp/|title=\u2018It\u2019 Director on Tackling the Two R-Rated Movies and Why He Picked Bill Skarsgard for Pennywise|last=Lang|first=Brent|date=July 19, 2017|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170719214312/http://variety.com/2017/film/news/it-director-andres-muschietti-two-movies-bill-skarsgard-1202499038/amp/|archivedate=July 19, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Muschietti explained how Skarsg\u00e5rd caught his attention to embody Pennywise, while pointing out that he didn't want the young cast to spend too much time with the actor when not shooting, and encouraged the cast to \"maintain distance\" between them, wherein Muschietti detailed:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.femalefirst.co.uk/movies/movie-news/andres-muschietti-confirms-prep-date-sequel-1075855.html|title=Andres Muschietti confirms prep date for IT sequel|last=Female First Editors|first=|date=July 20, 2017|work=Female First|accessdate=July 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-gb/entertainment/movies/andres-muschietti-confirms-prep-date-for-it-sequel/ar-AAoulDR|title=Andres Muschietti confirms prep date for IT sequel|last=MSN Editors|first=|date=July 20, 2017|work=[[MSN]]|accessdate=July 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808033345/http://www.msn.com/en-gb/entertainment/movies/andres-muschietti-confirms-prep-date-for-it-sequel/ar-AAoulDR|archive-date=August 8, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> We wanted to carry the impact of the encounters to when the cameras were rolling. The first scene where Bill interacted with the children, it was fun to see how the plan worked. The kids were really, really creeped out by Bill. He's pretty intimidating because he's six-four and has all this makeup.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://popculture.com/movies/2017/07/19/stephen-kings-it-remake-pennywise-bill-skarasgard/|title=Stephen King's 'It' Director Explains How Bill Skarsgard Won Coveted Pennywise Role|last=Cavanaugh|first=Patrick|date=July 19, 2017|work=Pop Culture|accessdate=July 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn February 16, 2016, producer [[Roy Lee]], in an interview with Collider, mentioned a second ''It'' film, remarking, \"[Dauberman] wrote the most recent draft working with [Muschietti], so it's being envisioned as two movies.\"<ref name=\"Muschietti\">{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/it-movie-news-rating/|title=Exclusive: 'It' Movie Hopefully Shooting This Year; Will Be Rated-R|last=Chitwood|first=Adam|date=February 19, 2016|work=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160626211828/http://collider.com/it-movie-news-rating/|archivedate=June 26, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On July 19, 2017, Muschietti revealed that production was set to begin in the spring of 2018, adding,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/it-part-2-director-andy-muschietti/|title='IT' Director Andy Muschietti Says He's Coming Back for a Sequel|last=Foutch|first=Haleigh|date=July 19, 2017|work=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170720053246/http://collider.com/it-part-2-director-andy-muschietti/|archivedate=July 20, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/it-movie-sequel-filming-2018-start/|title=Second IT Movie Adaptation Aims to Start Filming Next Year|last=Zinski|first=Dan|date=July 19, 2017|work=[[Screen Rant]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170721010304/http://screenrant.com/it-movie-sequel-filming-2018-start/|archivedate=July 21, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> \"We'll probably have a script for the second part in January [2018]. Ideally, we would start prep in March. Part one is only about the kids. Part two is about these characters 27 years later as adults, with flashbacks to 1989 when they were kids.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/it-already-has-a-sequel-planned|title=STEPHEN KING'S IT ALREADY HAS A SEQUEL PLANNED|last=Wax|first=Alyse|date=July 20, 2017|work=[[Syfy]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170720065345/http://www.syfy.com/syfywire/it-already-has-a-sequel-planned|archivedate=July 20, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On July 21, 2017, Muschietti spoke of looking forward to having a dialogue in the second film that does not exist within the first, stating, \"... it seems like we're going to do it. It's the second half, it's not a sequel. It's the second half and it's very connected to the first one.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/it-movie-andy-muschietti-interview-sdcc/|title='IT' Director Andy Muschietti on Reinventing Pennywise and Sequel Plans|last=Foutch|first=Haleigh|date=July 21, 2017|work=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|accessdate=July 22, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/news/1683730/why-the-it-movie-left-the-adult-storyline-out-of-the-first-film|title=Why The IT Movie Left The Adult Storyline Out Of The First Film|last=O'Connell|first=Sean|date=July 22, 2017|work=CinemaBlend|accessdate=July 23, 2017}}</ref> Muschietti stated that two cut scenes from the first film will possibly be included in the second, one of which being the fire at the Black Spot from the book.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/it-movie-cut-scenes|title=The 'IT' Movie Had to Cut Two Crazy Scenes to Stay On-Budget|last=Foutch|first=Haleigh|date=July 27, 2017|work=Collider.com|accessdate=July 27, 2017}}</ref> On September 25, 2017, [[New Line Cinema]] announced that the sequel would be released on September 6, 2019,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/it-movie-sequel-release-date-1202570309/|title='It' Sequel Sets September 2019 Release Date|last=McNary|first=Dave|date=September 25, 2017|work=[[Variety.com]]|accessdate=July 25, 2017}}</ref> with [[Gary Dauberman]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/it-sequel-plans-moving-forward-at-new-line-1035456|title='It' Movie Sequel Plans Move Forward at New Line|last=Kit|first=Borys|date=September 7, 2017|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=July 25, 2017}}</ref> and Jeffrey Jurgensen (who later went uncredited)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/are-you-afraid-of-the-dark-movie-release-1202632308/|title=''Are You Afraid Of The Dark?'' Movie Gets October 2019 Release|last=McNary|first=Dave|date=December 6, 2017|publisher=Variety|accessdate=December 6, 2017}}</ref> writing the script. Andy Muschietti returned to direct.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/it-sequel-official-writer-gary-dauberman-1202550077/|title='It' Sequel Moves Ahead With Screenwriter Gary Dauberman|last1=McNary|first1=Dave|date=September 7, 2017|work=Variety|accessdate=September 26, 2017}}</ref> Dauberman would later leave the project to write and direct ''[[Annabelle Comes Home]]'', while [[Jason Fuchs]] was brought in as his replacement.<ref>{{cite web |last=Foutch |first=Haleigh |url=https://collider.com/it-2-script-gary-dauberman-jason-fuchs/|title=''It 2'' Filmmakers on How Jason Fuchs Helped Bring the Sequel Script to the Finish Line |date=July 22, 2019 |work=Collider |accessdate=September 20, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190916055021/http://collider.com/it-2-script-gary-dauberman-jason-fuchs/|archive-date=September 16, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Recurring cast and characters ==\n{{Cast indicator|A|C|O|V|Y}}\n<!--Only put characters that have a roles within both films.-->{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; width:40%;\"\n! rowspan=\"4\" scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |Characters\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:center:\" |Films\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:30%\" |''[[It (2017 film)|It]]''\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:30%\" |''[[It Chapter Two]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |2017\n! scope=\"col\" |2019\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[It (character)|It / Pennywise the Dancing Clown]]\n|colspan=\"2\"|[[Bill Skarsg\u00e5rd]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Bill Denbrough]]\n|[[Jaeden Martell|Jaeden Lieberher]]\n|[[James McAvoy]]<hr>Jaeden Lieberher{{ref|young|Y}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Beverly Marsh]]\n|[[Sophia Lillis]]\n|[[Jessica Chastain]]<hr>Sophia Lillis{{ref|young|Y}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Ben Hanscom\n|[[Jeremy Ray Taylor]]\n|[[Jay Ryan (actor)|Jay Ryan]]<hr>Jeremy Ray Taylor{{ref|young|Y}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Richie Tozier]]\n|[[Finn Wolfhard]]\n|[[Bill Hader]]<hr>Finn Wolfhard{{ref|young|Y}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Eddie Kaspbrak]]\n|[[Jack Dylan Grazer]]\n|[[James Ransone]]<hr>Jack Dylan Grazer{{ref|young|Y}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Stanley Uris\n|[[Wyatt Oleff]]\n|[[Andy Bean (actor)|Andy Bean]]<hr>Wyatt Oleff{{ref|young|Y}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Mike Hanlon\n|[[Chosen Jacobs]]\n|[[Isaiah Mustafa]]<hr>Chosen Jacobs{{ref|young|Y}}<hr>Tristian Levi Cox{{ref|young|Y}}<hr>Torian Matthew{{ref|young|Y}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Henry Bowers\n|[[Nicholas Hamilton]]\n|Teach Grant<hr>Nicholas Hamilton{{ref|young|Y}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Georgie Denbrough]]\n|colspan=\"2\"| [[Jackson Robert Scott]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Patrick Hockstetter\n|colspan=\"2\"| [[Owen Teague]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Alvin Marsh \n|colspan=\"2\"| Stephen Bogaert\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Sonia Kaspbrak / Myra\n|colspan=\"2\"| Molly Atkinson\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Mr. Keene\n|colspan=\"2\"| Joe Bostick\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Gretta Keene\n|[[Megan Charpentier]]\n|Juno Rinaldi<hr>Megan Charpentier{{ref|young|Y}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |The Hobo / The Leper /<br>The Witch\n|colspan=\"2\"| [[Javier Botet]]\n|}\n\n== Additional crew and production details ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:90%;width:40%;\"\n! rowspan=\"3\" |Role\n! colspan=\"2\" |Films\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center; width:12%;\" |''[[It (2017 film)|It]]''\n! style=\"text-align:center; width:12%;\" |''[[It Chapter Two]]''\n|-\n!2017\n!2019\n|-\n!Composer(s)\n|colspan=\"2\"| [[Benjamin Wallfisch]]\n|-\n!Cinematography\n|[[Chung Chung-hoon|Chung-hoon Chung]]\n|Checco Varese\n|-\n!Editor(s)\n|colspan=\"2\"| [[Jason Ballantine]]\n|-\n!Production company\n|[[New Line Cinema]]<hr>[[RatPac-Dune Entertainment]]<hr>[[Vertigo Entertainment]]<hr>Lin Pictures<hr>[[KatzSmith Productions]]\n|New Line Cinema<hr>Double Dream<hr>Vertigo Entertainment<hr>Rideback\n|-\n!Distributor\n| colspan=\"8\" |[[Warner Bros. Pictures]]\n|-\n!Running time\n|135 minutes\n|170 minutes\n|-\n!Release date\n|{{start date|2017|9|8}}\n|{{start date|2019|9|6}}\n|}\n\n== Reception ==\n\n=== Box office performance ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;&quot;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Film\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Release date\n! colspan=\"3\" |Box office gross\n! colspan=\"2\" |Box office ranking\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Budget\n! rowspan=\"2\" |{{Abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n!North America\n!Other territories\n!Worldwide\n!North America\n!Worldwide\n|-\n|''It''\n|September 8, 2017\n|$327,481,748\n|$372,900,000\n|$700,381,748\n|#66\n|#117\n|$35 million\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=it.htm|title=It (2017) \u2013 Box Office Mojo|website=www.boxofficemojo.com|access-date=2019-09-19}}</ref>\n|-\n|''It Chapter Two''\n|September 6, 2019\n|$211,593,228\n|$260,500,000\n|$472,093,228\n|#190\n|#249\n|$79 million\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl1107461633/|title=It: Chapter Two \u2013 Box Office Mojo|website=www.boxofficemojo.com|access-date=2019-12-13}}</ref>\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |Totals\n!${{val|fmt=commas|{{#expr:327481748+211593228}}}}\n!${{val|fmt=commas|{{#expr:372900000+260500000}}}}\n!${{val|fmt=commas|{{#expr:700381748+472093228}}}}\n!\n!\n!$114 million\n!\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Critical response ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" width=\"99%\" border=\"1\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!Film\n![[Rotten Tomatoes]]\n![[Metacritic]]\n![[CinemaScore]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |''It''\n|86% (368 reviews)<ref>{{Citation|title=It (2017)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/it_2017|language=en|access-date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n|69 (49 critics)<ref>{{Citation|title=It|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/it|access-date=2019-09-20}}</ref>\n|B+<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinemascore.com/|title=Home|website=Cinemascore|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-20}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |''It Chapter Two''\n|63% (353 reviews)<ref>{{Citation|title=It Chapter Two (2019)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/it_chapter_two|language=en|access-date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n|58 (52 critics)<ref>{{Citation|title=It: Chapter Two|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/it-chapter-two|access-date=2019-09-20}}</ref>\n|B+<ref name=\":0\" />\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Stephen King's It}}\n{{Media based on Stephen King works}}\n\n[[Category:Horror film series]]\n[[Category:It (novel)]]\n", "name_user": "HPDEATHLYHALLOWS4", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added info on critical reception in intro. This series has generally positive reviews and the intro should reflect that .", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/It_(film_series)"}
{"title_page": "Kryethi", "text_new": "{{Template:Albanian tribes sidebar}}\n'''Kryethi''' (altenatively, ''Krytha'', ''Krythi'' and later ''Kruta''; in Latin: ''Crutta'') was an [[Albanian tribes|Albanian tribe]] (''bashk\u00ebsi'') of the Middle Ages in the coastal areas of northern Albania and southern Montenegro.\n\n== History ==\n===Early===\nKryethi was a community based on kinship ties of the same paternal ancestry. They had kin relations (''lidhje fisnore''), but in terms of territorial organization, they were a ''bashk\u00ebsi'' in the sense that at that time they didn't have exclusive communal rights over a given a territory as a ''fis'' did. The name is a compound of Albanian ''krye-'' (head) and ''-thi'' (boar)<ref name=\"Elezi\">{{cite book |last1=Elezi |first1=Mehmet |title=Fjalor i gjuh\u00ebs shqipe |date=2006 |publisher=Gjergj Fishta |isbn=9994387464 |page=756 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5j0_AQAAIAAJ |ref=Elezi}}</ref>. Metaphorically, it means strong headed or decisive. The toponym ''Sfinodol'' that appears near modern [[Svinjare]] in [[Kosovo]] in 1455 could be a Slavic translation of this name via the intermediate form ''Svinoglav'' (literally swine head).<ref name=\"Gjurmime\">{{citation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZqtiAAAAMAAJ| pages=107-11| title=Gjurmime albanologjike| series=Seria e shkencave filologjike| volume=15-16| location=Prishtina|year=1986| publisher=Instituti Albanologjik i Prishtines| oclc= 475280214}}</ref> In Venetian archives it has been spelled as ''Cruetti'' and ''Crutta''\n\nThey are found in the cadaster of Scutari in 1416-7 throughout the coastal areas of [[Albania Veneta]]. Two villages by that name appear in the cadaster. The village ''Crueti'' (Kryethi) with ten households was entirely inhabited by people from this kin community. Its location is unknown. [[Injac Zamputi]] who translated the cadaster in Albanian has placed it between [[Sheldi]] and [[Gajtan, Shkod\u00ebr|Gajtan]]. This village reappears in the same area in the Ottoman defter of 1485. At that time, it was still a community organized with kin relations as a foundation.<ref name=\"Pulaha2\">{{cite journal |last1=Pulaha |first1=Selami |title=Kontribut p\u00ebr studimin e ngulitjes s\u00eb katuneve dhe krijimin e fiseve n\u00eb Shqipe \u0308rine \u0308 e veriut shekujt XV-XVI' [Contribution to the Study of Village Settlements and the Formation of the Tribes of Northern Albania in the 15th century] |journal=Studime Historike |date=1975 |volume=12 |page=124 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=q4khAQAAMAAJ |accessdate=30 January 2020 |ref=Pulaha2}}</ref>\n\nThe village of ''Cruetim'' (spelled alternatively as Kryethim or Krythim in Albanian) also called ''Frankeshi'' appears in the cadaster near the coast. The two ''bashk\u00ebsi'' that lived in the village were those of the Kryethi: Pal Krytha the elder, Pal Krytha the younger, Tom\u00eb Krytha and of the Frankesi: Pal and Tanush Frankeshi. Together with the village of ''Renesi'', they were given free rights to fish in the coastline.<ref name=\"Zamputi\">{{cite book |last1=Zamputi |first1=Injac |title=Regjistri i kadastr\u0113s dhe i koncesioneve p\u0113r rrethin e Shkodr\u00ebs 1416-1417 |date=1977 |publisher=Academy of Sciences of Albania |url=https://www.academia.edu/33718705/AKADEMIA_E_SHKENCAVE_E_REPUBUKES_TE_SHQIPERISE |pages=270 |accessdate=29 January 2020 |ref=Buda}}</ref>\n\nOver 25 households linked to the Kryethi appear in the cadaster. Most didn't live in the villages of the same name but were spread throughout the region. They were Catholic. The abbot Pjet\u00ebr Kryethi (''Petrus Cruettio'') appears as the head of the monastery of [[Shirgj Church|Saint Sergius]] on the banks of [[Buna river]], close to the modern Albania-Montenegro border in 1410 and then in the cadaster of 1416.<ref name=\"Zamputi\"/> Their name is also preserved in microtoponymy like ''Kodra e Kryethiut'' (the hill of Kryethi) in [[Iball\u00eb]] and ''Gropa e Kryethiut'' in [[Rrapsh\u00eb]].<ref name=\"Luli\">{{cite journal |last1=Luli |first1=Fran |title=Disa em\u00ebrtime nga l\u00ebmi i blegtoris\u00eb dhe pasqyrimi i tyre n\u00eb onomastik\u00eb [Some pastoral toponyms and their reflection in anthroponymy] |journal=Gjuha Jon\u00eb |volume=12 |page=33 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oNjqAAAAMAAJ |accessdate=18 March 2020 |ref=Demiraj}}</ref>\n\nIn later times, three villages that were formed by this tribe are attested. The village of Krytha near [[Daj\u00e7, Lezh\u00eb|Daj\u00e7]] appears in 1640 with 20 households. It was a Catholic village that had Saint Demetrius as its patron saint.<ref name=\"Elsie\">{{cite book|last=Elsie|first=Robert|title=Early Albania: A reader of Historical texts, 11th\u201317th centuries|year=2003|location=Wiesbaden|publisher=Otto Harrassowitz Verlag|url=https://books.google.com/?id=_sHmTRCEe7kC&printsec|isbn=9783447047838 |page=186}}</ref> The other two villages are closer to the historical area in which the Kryethi lived in the Middle Ages. ''[[Krute|Krytha e Kat\u00ebrkoll\u00ebs]]'' (Krute in Montenegrin) and ''Krytha e Ulqinit'' (Kruta) both appear in the [[Ulcinj Municipality]] near the Albania-Montenegro border.\n\nVenetian diplomat [[Mariano Bolizza]] who travelled in the area in 1614 recorded that Krytha e Kat\u00ebrkoll\u00ebs had 30 households and 75 men-in-arms commanded by Gjur \u00c7eka. [[Seoca, Montenegro|Seoca]] a village to the north of Krytha was also headed by  a ''Gioan Cruta'' (Gjon Krytha). To the south closer to Krytha e Ulqinit, Gjerana today a neighbourhood of the city of [[Ulcinj]], then a small village was headed by ''Marco Crutta'' with 180 men-in-arms.<ref name=\"3a\">{{cite web |last1=Bolizza |first1=Mariano |title=Report and Description of the Sanjak of Shkodra |url=http://www.albanianhistory.net/1614_Bolizza/index.html |accessdate=28 January 2020 |ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n=== Crutta family ===\nThe fall of Scutari in 1479 and the fall of Dulcigno in 1571 to the Ottomans led many members of this tribe to emigrate in the Venetian-held territory of [[Zadar|Zara]]. Vuco Crutta appears as the military governor of Zara at the end of the 16th century. In 1608-1611, ''Jacobo Crutta Albanese'' was a military commander on the Venetian-Ottoman border. This branch still seems to have maintained relations with northern Albania at this name. Jacobo Crutta's son, Simon was a captain in the Venetian army. In his testament, the family ancestral links to the village of Kakarriq (near [[Lezh\u00eb]]) in Albania are mentioned. In Venetian territories, they first appeared as military commanders and later as their social status rose they increasingly took on diplomatic posts and established themselves in other Venetian territories like [[Venetian Cyprus|Cyprus]]. In Albania, Franciscus Crutta became the Catholic bishop of Shkodra in 1640.<ref name=\"Coralic\">{{cite journal |last1=\u010corali\u0107 |first1=Lovorka |title=The albanian Kruta family and some of its eminent individuals \u2013 a contribution to the research of communications on the eastern adriatic coastline in the early Modern age |journal=HISTORIJSKI ZBORNIK  GOD. LXII |date=2009 |volume=2 |page=389 |url=https://core.ac.uk/reader/14438760 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |ref=Coralic}}</ref>\n\nAs Cyprus and Dulcigno passed in Ottoman control after 1571, they start to appear as diplomats in the embassies of European states in Constantinople. In 1693, a branch of them established itself in [[Beyo\u011flu|Pera]]. Diplomats from this family were [[dragoman]]s in French, Polish, Russian, English and Venetian embassies.<ref name=\"Groot\">{{cite book |last1=de Groot |first1=Alexander H. |editor1-last=van Gelder |editor1-first=G. J. H. |editor2-last=de Moor |editor2-first=Ed |title=Eastward Bound: Dutch Ventures and Adventures in the Middle East |date=1994 |publisher=Rodopi |isbn=9051837178 |page=138 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jDNB294N7AcC&pg=PA138 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |ref=Groot |chapter=Dragomans in Istanbul, 1785-1834}}</ref> [[Antonio Crutta]] belonged to this branch.\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Tribes of Albania]]\n", "text_old": "{{Template:Albanian tribes sidebar}}\n'''Kryethi''' (altenatively, ''Krytha'', ''Krythi'' and later ''Kruta''; in Latin: ''Crutta'') was an [[Albanian tribes|Albanian tribe]] (''bashk\u00ebsi'') of the Middle Ages in the coastal areas of northern Albania and southern Montenegro.\n\n== History ==\n===Early===\nKryethi was a community based on kinship ties of the same paternal ancestry. They had kin relations (''lidhje fisnore''), but in terms of territorial organization, they were a ''bashk\u00ebsi'' in the sense that at that time they didn't have exclusive communal rights over a given a territory as a ''fis'' did. The name is a compound of Albanian ''krye-'' (head) and ''-thi'' (boar)<ref name=\"Elezi\">{{cite book |last1=Elezi |first1=Mehmet |title=Fjalor i gjuh\u00ebs shqipe |date=2006 |publisher=Gjergj Fishta |isbn=9994387464 |page=756 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5j0_AQAAIAAJ |ref=Elezi}}</ref>. Metaphorically, it means strong headed or decisive. The toponym ''Sfinodol'' that appears near modern [[Svinjare]] in [[Kosovo]] in 1455 could be a Slavic translation of this name via the intermediate form ''Svinoglav'' (literally swine head).<ref name=\"Gjurmime\">{{citation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZqtiAAAAMAAJ| pages=107-11| title=Gjurmime albanologjike| series=Seria e shkencave filologjike| volume=15-16| location=Prishtina|year=1986| publisher=Instituti Albanologjik i Prishtines| oclc= 475280214}}</ref> In Venetian archives it has been spelled as ''Cruetti'' and ''Crutta''\n\nThey are found in the cadaster of Scutari in 1416-7 throughout the coastal areas of [[Albania Veneta]]. Two villages by that name appear in the cadaster. The village ''Crueti'' (Kryethi) with ten households was entirely inhabited by people from this kin community. Its location is unknown. [[Injac Zamputi]] who translated the cadaster in Albanian has placed it between [[Sheldi]] and [[Gajtan]]. This village reappears in the same area in the Ottoman defter of 1485. At that time, it was still a community organized with kin relations as a foundation.<ref name=\"Pulaha2\">{{cite journal |last1=Pulaha |first1=Selami |title=Kontribut p\u00ebr studimin e ngulitjes s\u00eb katuneve dhe krijimin e fiseve n\u00eb Shqipe \u0308rine \u0308 e veriut shekujt XV-XVI' [Contribution to the Study of Village Settlements and the Formation of the Tribes of Northern Albania in the 15th century] |journal=Studime Historike |date=1975 |volume=12 |page=124 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=q4khAQAAMAAJ |accessdate=30 January 2020 |ref=Pulaha2}}</ref>\n\nThe village of ''Cruetim'' (spelled alternatively as Kryethim or Krythim in Albanian) also called ''Frankeshi'' appears in the cadaster near the coast. The two ''bashk\u00ebsi'' that lived in the village were those of the Kryethi: Pal Krytha the elder, Pal Krytha the younger, Tom\u00eb Krytha and of the Frankesi: Pal and Tanush Frankeshi. Together with the village of ''Renesi'', they were given free rights to fish in the coastline.<ref name=\"Zamputi\">{{cite book |last1=Zamputi |first1=Injac |title=Regjistri i kadastr\u0113s dhe i koncesioneve p\u0113r rrethin e Shkodr\u00ebs 1416-1417 |date=1977 |publisher=Academy of Sciences of Albania |url=https://www.academia.edu/33718705/AKADEMIA_E_SHKENCAVE_E_REPUBUKES_TE_SHQIPERISE |pages=270 |accessdate=29 January 2020 |ref=Buda}}</ref>\n\nOver 25 households linked to the Kryethi appear in the cadaster. Most didn't live in the villages of the same name but were spread throughout the region. They were Catholic. The abbot Pjet\u00ebr Kryethi (''Petrus Cruettio'') appears as the head of the monastery of [[Shirgj Church|Saint Sergius]] on the banks of [[Buna river]], close to the modern Albania-Montenegro border in 1410 and then in the cadaster of 1416.<ref name=\"Zamputi\"/> Their name is also preserved in microtoponymy like ''Kodra e Kryethiut'' (the hill of Kryethi) in [[Iball\u00eb]] and ''Gropa e Kryethiut'' in [[Rrapsh\u00eb]].<ref name=\"Luli\">{{cite journal |last1=Luli |first1=Fran |title=Disa em\u00ebrtime nga l\u00ebmi i blegtoris\u00eb dhe pasqyrimi i tyre n\u00eb onomastik\u00eb [Some pastoral toponyms and their reflection in anthroponymy] |journal=Gjuha Jon\u00eb |volume=12 |page=33 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oNjqAAAAMAAJ |accessdate=18 March 2020 |ref=Demiraj}}</ref>\n\nIn later times, three villages that were formed by this tribe are attested. The village of Krytha near [[Daj\u00e7, Lezh\u00eb|Daj\u00e7]] appears in 1640 with 20 households. It was a Catholic village that had Saint Demetrius as its patron saint.<ref name=\"Elsie\">{{cite book|last=Elsie|first=Robert|title=Early Albania: A reader of Historical texts, 11th\u201317th centuries|year=2003|location=Wiesbaden|publisher=Otto Harrassowitz Verlag|url=https://books.google.com/?id=_sHmTRCEe7kC&printsec|isbn=9783447047838 |page=186}}</ref> The other two villages are closer to the historical area in which the Kryethi lived in the Middle Ages. ''[[Krute|Krytha e Kat\u00ebrkoll\u00ebs]]'' (Krute in Montenegrin) and ''Krytha e Ulqinit'' (Kruta) both appear in the [[Ulcinj Municipality]] near the Albania-Montenegro border.\n\nVenetian diplomat [[Mariano Bolizza]] who travelled in the area in 1614 recorded that Krytha e Kat\u00ebrkoll\u00ebs had 30 households and 75 men-in-arms commanded by Gjur \u00c7eka. [[Seoca, Montenegro|Seoca]] a village to the north of Krytha was also headed by  a ''Gioan Cruta'' (Gjon Krytha). To the south closer to Krytha e Ulqinit, Gjerana today a neighbourhood of the city of [[Ulcinj]], then a small village was headed by ''Marco Crutta'' with 180 men-in-arms.<ref name=\"3a\">{{cite web |last1=Bolizza |first1=Mariano |title=Report and Description of the Sanjak of Shkodra |url=http://www.albanianhistory.net/1614_Bolizza/index.html |accessdate=28 January 2020 |ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n=== Crutta family ===\nThe fall of Scutari in 1479 and the fall of Dulcigno in 1571 to the Ottomans led many members of this tribe to emigrate in the Venetian-held territory of [[Zadar|Zara]]. Vuco Crutta appears as the military governor of Zara at the end of the 16th century. In 1608-1611, ''Jacobo Crutta Albanese'' was a military commander on the Venetian-Ottoman border. This branch still seems to have maintained relations with northern Albania at this name. Jacobo Crutta's son, Simon was a captain in the Venetian army. In his testament, the family ancestral links to the village of Kakarriq (near [[Lezh\u00eb]]) in Albania are mentioned. In Venetian territories, they first appeared as military commanders and later as their social status rose they increasingly took on diplomatic posts and established themselves in other Venetian territories like [[Venetian Cyprus|Cyprus]]. In Albania, Franciscus Crutta became the Catholic bishop of Shkodra in 1640.<ref name=\"Coralic\">{{cite journal |last1=\u010corali\u0107 |first1=Lovorka |title=The albanian Kruta family and some of its eminent individuals \u2013 a contribution to the research of communications on the eastern adriatic coastline in the early Modern age |journal=HISTORIJSKI ZBORNIK  GOD. LXII |date=2009 |volume=2 |page=389 |url=https://core.ac.uk/reader/14438760 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |ref=Coralic}}</ref>\n\nAs Cyprus and Dulcigno passed in Ottoman control after 1571, they start to appear as diplomats in the embassies of European states in Constantinople. In 1693, a branch of them established itself in [[Beyo\u011flu|Pera]]. Diplomats from this family were [[dragoman]]s in French, Polish, Russian, English and Venetian embassies.<ref name=\"Groot\">{{cite book |last1=de Groot |first1=Alexander H. |editor1-last=van Gelder |editor1-first=G. J. H. |editor2-last=de Moor |editor2-first=Ed |title=Eastward Bound: Dutch Ventures and Adventures in the Middle East |date=1994 |publisher=Rodopi |isbn=9051837178 |page=138 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jDNB294N7AcC&pg=PA138 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |ref=Groot |chapter=Dragomans in Istanbul, 1785-1834}}</ref> [[Antonio Crutta]] belonged to this branch.\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Tribes of Albania]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toGajtan(link changed toGajtan, Shkod\u00ebr) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kryethi"}
{"title_page": "Francis Payne (author)", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian writer}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| image        = \n| imagesize    = \n| name         = Francis Payne\n| caption      = \n| pseudonym    = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth year and age|1953}}\n| birth_place   = [[Scotland]]\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| occupation   = \n| nationality  = [[Australia]]n\n| period       = \n| genre        = [[Speculative fiction]]\n| subject      = \n| movement     = \n| notableworks = \n| spouse       = \n| partner      = \n| children     = \n| relatives    = \n| influences   = \n| influenced   = \n| awards       = \n| signature    = \n| website      = \n}}\n\n'''Francis Payne''' is an [[Australia]]n writer of [[speculative fiction]].\n\n==Biography==\nPayne was born in 1953 in Scotland. In 1967 Payne emigrated to Australia.<ref name=\"EL FP\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ericlindsay.com/ozwriter/payne.htm |title=Francis Payne |publisher=ericlindsay.com |accessdate=2010-12-25 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vEZlX5dD?url=http://www.ericlindsay.com/ozwriter/payne.htm |archivedate=2010-12-25 |url-status=live }}</ref> Payne won his first award in 1978 with his work \"[[Albert's Bellyful]]\" which won the [[Ditmar Award]] for best Australian short fiction.<ref name=\"1978DITMAR\">{{cite web | url = http://www.locusmag.com/SFAwards/Db/Ditmar1978.html#shf | title = The Locus Index to SF Awards: 1978 Ditmar Awards | publisher = [[Locus Online]] | accessdate = 2010-12-25 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020123032810/http://www.locusmag.com/SFAwards/Db/Ditmar1978.html|archivedate=2002-01-23|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 1995 he won the [[Aurealis Award for best horror short story]] with his [[chapbook]] \"[[Olympia (short story)|Olympia]]\" beating works by [[Terry Dowling]], [[Leanne Frahm]], [[Philip Neilsen]], and [[Kaaron Warren]].<ref name=\"NLA OLYMPIA\">{{cite web | url = http://catalogue.nla.gov.au/Record/1099289 | title = Olympia by Francis Payne | publisher = [[National Library of Australia]] | accessdate = 2010-12-25 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"1996AUREALIS\">{{cite web | url = http://www.locusmag.com/SFAwards/Db/Aurealis1996.html#hs | title = The Locus Index to SF Awards: 1996 Aurealis Awards | publisher = [[Locus Online]] | accessdate = 2010-12-25 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020125003716/http://www.locusmag.com/SFAwards/Db/Aurealis1996.html|archivedate=2002-01-25|url-status=dead}}</ref> Payne has a wife and child and is currently living outside [[Melbourne]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], [[Australia]].<ref name=\"EL FP\"/>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 100%;\" border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" background: #f9f9f9;\n|- align=\"center\"\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Year\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Award\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Work\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Category\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Result\n|-\n|1978 || [[Ditmar Award]] || \"[[Albert's Bellyful]]\" || Best Australian short fiction ||bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"|Won<ref name=\"1978DITMAR\"/>\n|-\n|1995 || [[Aurealis Award]] || \"[[Olympia (short story)|Olympia]]\" || [[Aurealis Award for best horror short story|Best horror short story]] ||bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"|Won<ref name=\"1996AUREALIS\"/>\n|}\n\n==Bibliography==\n===Short fiction===\n*\"[[Albert's Bellyful]]\" (1977) in ''[[Yggdrasil (magazine)|Yggdrasil]]'' February 1977\n*\"What the Stone of Ciparri Says\" (1995) in ''[[Bloodsongs]] #6 (ed. Steve Proposch)\n*\"[[Olympia (short story)|Olympia]]\" (1995)\n\n==References==\n'''General'''\n*{{isfdb name|id=14436|name=Francis Payne}}\n\n'''Specific'''\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Payne, Francis}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian male short story writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian writer}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| image        = \n| imagesize    = \n| name         = Francis Payne\n| caption      = \n| pseudonym    = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth year and age|1953}}\n| birth_place   = [[Scotland]]\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| occupation   = \n| nationality  = [[Australia]]n\n| period       = \n| genre        = [[Speculative fiction]]\n| subject      = \n| movement     = \n| notableworks = \n| spouse       = \n| partner      = \n| children     = \n| relatives    = \n| influences   = \n| influenced   = \n| awards       = \n| signature    = \n| website      = \n}}\n\n'''Francis Payne''' is an [[Australia]]n writer of [[speculative fiction]].\n\n==Biography==\nPayne was born in 1953 in Scotland. In 1967 Payne emigrated to Australia.<ref name=\"EL FP\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ericlindsay.com/ozwriter/payne.htm |title=Francis Payne |publisher=ericlindsay.com |accessdate=2010-12-25 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vEZlX5dD?url=http://www.ericlindsay.com/ozwriter/payne.htm |archivedate=2010-12-25 |url-status=live }}</ref> Payne won his first award in 1978 with his work \"[[Albert's Bellyful]]\" which won the [[Ditmar Award]] for best Australian short fiction.<ref name=\"1978DITMAR\">{{cite web | url = http://www.locusmag.com/SFAwards/Db/Ditmar1978.html#shf | title = The Locus Index to SF Awards: 1978 Ditmar Awards | publisher = [[Locus Online]] | accessdate = 2010-12-25 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020123032810/http://www.locusmag.com/SFAwards/Db/Ditmar1978.html|archivedate=2002-01-23|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 1995 he won the [[Aurealis Award for best horror short story]] with his [[chapbook]] \"[[Olympia (short story)|Olympia]]\" beating works by [[Terry Dowling]], [[Leanne Frahm]], [[Philip Neilsen]], and [[Kaaron Warren]].<ref name=\"NLA OLYMPIA\">{{cite web | url = http://catalogue.nla.gov.au/Record/1099289 | title = Olympia by Francis Payne | publisher = [[National Library of Australia]] | accessdate = 2010-12-25 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"1996AUREALIS\">{{cite web | url = http://www.locusmag.com/SFAwards/Db/Aurealis1996.html#hs | title = The Locus Index to SF Awards: 1996 Aurealis Awards | publisher = [[Locus Online]] | accessdate = 2010-12-25 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020125003716/http://www.locusmag.com/SFAwards/Db/Aurealis1996.html|archivedate=2002-01-25|url-status=dead}}</ref> Payne has a wife and child and is currently living outside [[Melbourne]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], [[Australia]].<ref name=\"EL FP\"/>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 100%;\" border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" background: #f9f9f9;\n|- align=\"center\"\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Year\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Award\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Work\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Category\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Result\n|-\n|1978 || [[Ditmar Award]] || \"[[Albert's Bellyful]]\" || Best Australian short fiction ||bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"|Won<ref name=\"1978DITMAR\"/>\n|-\n|1995 || [[Aurealis Award]] || \"[[Olympia (short story)|Olympia]]\" || [[Aurealis Award for best horror short story|Best horror short story]] ||bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"|Won<ref name=\"1996AUREALIS\"/>\n|}\n\n==Bibliography==\n===Short fiction===\n*\"[[Albert's Bellyful]]\" (1977) in ''[[Yggdrasil (magazine)|Yggdrasil]]'' February 1977\n*\"What the Stone of Ciparri Says\" (1995) in ''[[Bloodsongs]] #6 (ed. Steve Proposch)\n*\"[[Olympia (short story)|Olympia]]\" (1995)\n\n==References==\n'''General'''\n*{{isfdb name|id=14436|name=Francis Payne}}\n\n'''Specific'''\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Payne, Francis}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian male short story writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Francis_Payne_(author)"}
{"title_page": "Peak District", "text_new": "{{short description|Upland area in England}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox protected area\n| name = Peak District National Park\n| alt_name = \"The Peak\"\n| iucn_category = V\n| photo = Mam Tor.jpg\n| photo_alt = A view of grass-covered hillside located within a British National Park\n| photo_caption = A view of [[Mam Tor]], Peak District National Park\n| map_image = Peak District National Park UK location map.svg\n| map_caption = Peak District National Park (shaded green) within England\n| location = [[Derbyshire]]<br>[[Cheshire]]<br>[[Greater Manchester]]<br>[[Staffordshire]]<br>[[South Yorkshire]]<br>[[West Yorkshire]]\n| nearest_city = \n| nearest_town = \n| coords = {{coord|53|21|N|1|50|W|region:GB-ENG_source:dewiki|display=inline,title}}\n| area_sqmi = 555\n| designated = {{start date|1951|4|17|df=yes}}\n| visitation_num = Over 10 million\n| visitation_year =\n| visitation_ref = <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/learning-about/news/mediacentrefacts |title=Peak District Local Government|accessdate= 8 November 2016}}</ref> \n| administrator = [[National park authority]]\n| website = {{URL|https://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/}}\n| url = \n| child = \n| embedded = \n}}\n\nThe '''Peak District''' is an [[Highland|upland]] area in England at the southern end of the [[Pennines]]. It is mostly in northern [[Derbyshire]], but also includes parts of [[Cheshire]], [[Greater Manchester]], [[Staffordshire]], [[West Yorkshire]] and [[South Yorkshire]]. An area of great diversity, it is mostly split into the [[Dark Peak]], where most of the [[moorland]] is found and the geology is [[gritstone]], and the [[limestone]] area of the [[White Peak]].\n\nThe Peak District National Park became the first [[National parks of England and Wales|national park]] in the United Kingdom in 1951.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0009/79227/factsheet4-quarrying.pdf |title=Quarrying and mineral extraction in the Peak District National Park |publisher=Peak District National Park Authority |year=2011 |accessdate=17 April 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120127055057/http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0009/79227/factsheet4-quarrying.pdf |archivedate=27 January 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> With its proximity to the cities of [[Manchester]], [[Stoke-on-Trent]], [[Derby]] and [[Sheffield]], and access by road and rail, it attracts millions of visitors every year.<ref>{{cite book |title=Britain |last=Wheeler |first=T. |editor-last=Else |editor-first=D |year=2003 |edition=5th |isbn=1-74059-338-3 |page=42 |quote=The Peak District alone gets 20 million, making it Britain's most-visited park, and the second-busiest in the world. |publisher=[[Lonely Planet]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/learning-about/news/mediacentrefacts |title=Media Centre Facts and Figures |publisher=Peak District National Park Authority |accessdate=4 March 2014}}</ref> It is estimated that 20 million people live within one hour's journey of the Peak District.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/learning-about/news/mediacentrefacts|title=Media Centre Facts and Figures|website=Peak District National Park}}</ref>\n\nInhabited from the [[Mesolithic]] era, evidence exists from the [[Neolithic]], [[Bronze Age|Bronze]] and [[Iron Age]]s. Settled by the [[Roman Britain|Romans]] and [[Anglo-Saxons]], the area remained largely agricultural and mining grew in importance in the medieval era. [[Richard Arkwright]] built his [[cotton mill]]s at the start of the [[Industrial Revolution]]. Quarrying became important as mining declined. Tourism grew after the advent of the railways, visitors attracted by the landscape, [[spa town]]s at [[Buxton]] and [[Matlock Bath]], [[Castleton, Derbyshire|Castleton]]'s show caves, and [[Bakewell]], the national park's only town. \n\nTourism remains important for its towns and villages and their varied attractions, [[country house]]s and heritage sites. Outside the towns, walking on the extensive network of public footpaths, cycle trails, rock climbing and caving are popular pursuits. The Friends of the Peak District's 200-mile [[Peak District|Boundary Walk]] is a new long distance trail addition.\n\n==Geography==\nThe Peak District is at the southern end of the Pennines<ref>{{cite web |title=Location and overview of the Peak District |url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/microsites/sopr/overview/location-and-overview-of-the-peak-district |website=Peak District National Park |publisher=Peak District National Park |accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref> and much of the area is upland above {{convert|1000|ft|m|-2}}. Its high point is  [[Kinder Scout]] at {{convert|2087|ft|m|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Nuttall\">{{cite book |title=The Mountains of England & Wales \u2013 Volume 2: England |last1=Nuttall |first1=J. |last2=Nuttall|first2=A. |year=1990 |publisher=Cicerone |location=Milnthorpe |isbn=1-85284-037-4 |url=http://www.nuttalls.com/mountains/england.htm |accessdate=23 August 2009}}</ref> Despite its name, the landscape generally lacks sharp peaks, and is characterised mostly by rounded hills, [[plateau]]s, valleys, limestone [[Canyon|gorge]]s and gritstone [[escarpment]]s (the \"edges\").<ref name=\"Landscape\">{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/microsites/sopr/landscape|title=Landscape|publisher=Peak District National Park State of the Park|accessdate=28 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Gritstone Edges\">{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrictonline.co.uk/peak-district-gritstone-edges-c101334.html|title=Gritstone Edges|publisher=Peak District Online|accessdate=28 June 2017}}</ref>  The area, mostly rural, is surrounded by conurbations and large urban areas including [[Manchester]], [[Huddersfield]], [[Sheffield]], [[Derby]] and [[Stoke-on-Trent]].\n\nThe [[national park]] has a formal boundary and covers most of the [[Dark Peak]] and [[White Peak]], but the wider Peak District is less well defined.<ref>{{cite web|title=Peak District|url=https://www.heathrowshuttle.com/pages/peak-district|website=Heathrow Shuttle|publisher=Heathrow Shuttle|accessdate=13 February 2018}}</ref> The Dark Peak is largely uninhabited [[moorland]] and gritstone escarpments in the northern Peak District and its eastern and western margins. It encloses the central and southern White Peak which is where most settlements, farmland and limestone gorges are located.<ref>{{cite web|title=Accommodation in Derbyshire and the Peak National Park|url=http://www.derbyshire-peakdistrict.co.uk/accommodation.htm|website=Discover Derbyshire and the Peak District|publisher=Discover Derbyshire and the Peak District|accessdate=12 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Character areas\">{{cite web|url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/learning-about/about-the-national-park/character-areas|publisher=Peak District.gov|title=Character areas|accessdate=14 September 2017|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170914125324/http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/learning-about/about-the-national-park/character-areas|archivedate=14 September 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Three of [[Natural England]]'s [[National Character Area]]s (NCAs) include the landscape. The Dark Peak NCA includes the northern and eastern parts of the Dark Peak while the White Peak NCA covers most of the White Peak. The western margins of the Dark Peak are in the South West Peak NCA, where farmland and pastured valleys are found as well as gritstone edges and moorland.<ref name=\"Character areas\"/><ref name=\"South West Peak\">{{cite web|title=South West Peak|url=http://www.snh.org.uk/wwo/sharinggoodpractice/cci/cci/eastmidlands/053b.htm|website=Scottish Natural Heritage|publisher=Scottish Natural Heritage|accessdate=12 May 2018}}</ref>  Outside the park, the wider Peak District is often considered to include the area approximately between [[Disley]] and Sterndale Moor, and some of the outer fringes and foothills, including the [[River Churnet|Churnet]]<ref>{{cite book|title=Britain|publisher=Martin Walters and Bob Gibbons|pages=220\u2013221|url=https://books.google.com/?id=8Q4fJsgiDZgC&pg=PA220&dq=churnet+valley+edge+of+peak+district#v=onepage&q=churnet%20valley%20edge%20of%20peak%20district&f=false|accessdate=14 February 2018|isbn=9780198504337|year=2003}}</ref> and [[River Derwent, Derbyshire|lower Derwent]] Valleys.<ref name=\"Slow Travel The Peak District\">{{cite book|title=Slow Travel The Peak District|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Za2qCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA201&lpg=PA201&dq=peak+district+lower+derwent+valley#v=onepage&q=peak%20district%20lower%20derwent%20valley&f=false|pages=200\u2013203|publisher=Helen Moat|accessdate=5 October 2017|isbn = 9781784770075|date = 16 February 2016}}</ref> The region is mostly surrounded by lowlands<ref>{{cite web|title=The Peak District|url=http://www.peakdistrictonline.co.uk/the-peak-district-c2672.html|website=Peak District Online|publisher=Peak District Online|accessdate=31 March 2018}}</ref> with gritstone moorlands of the [[South Pennines]] to the north.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://publications.naturalengland.org.uk/publication/511867|publisher=Natural England|title=NCA Profile: 36 Southern Pennines (NE323)|accessdate=14 September 2017}}</ref> \n\nThe national park covers {{convert|555|sqmi|km2}},<ref name=\"Area\">{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrict-education.gov.uk/Fact%20Sheets/fz16pop.htm |title=The Peak District National Park \u2013 Fact Zone |publisher=PDNP Education |year=2000 |accessdate=22 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100308043914/http://www.peakdistrict-education.gov.uk/Fact%20sheets/fz16pop.htm |archivedate=8 March 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> including most of the region in Derbyshire and extends into Staffordshire, Cheshire, Greater Manchester and South and West Yorkshire. The park's northern limits are on the [[A62 road]] between Huddersfield and [[Oldham]], and its southernmost point is on the [[A52 road]] near [[Ashbourne, Derbyshire|Ashbourne]]. The park boundaries were drawn to exclude built-up and industrial areas; in particular [[Buxton]] and the quarries at the end of the [[Peak Dale]] corridor are surrounded on three sides by the park. [[Bakewell]] and many villages are in the national park as is much of the rural west of Sheffield. As of 2010, it is the fifth largest [[National parks of England and Wales|national park in England and Wales]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nationalparks.gov.uk/learningabout/factsandfigures.htm |title=National Park facts and figures |publisher=National Parks |year=2009 |accessdate=13 November 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120111052829/http://www.nationalparks.gov.uk/learningabout/factsandfigures.htm|archivedate=11 January 2012}}</ref> In the UK, designation as a national park means that planning and other functions are provided by a national park authority with additional planning restrictions that provide enhanced protection against inappropriate development. Land within this national park as in other UK parks is in a mix of public and private ownership.\n\nThe [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]], a charity that conserves historic and natural landscapes, owns about 12% of the land in the national park.<ref>''Handbook for Members and Visitors 2004'', [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|The National Trust]].</ref> Its three estates ([[High Peak Estate|High Peak]], [[White Peak Estate|White Peak]] and [[Longshaw Estate|Longshaw]]) include ecologically or geologically significant areas at [[Bleaklow]], [[Derwent Edge]], [[Hope Woodlands]], [[Kinder Scout]], the [[River Manifold|Manifold]] valley, [[Mam Tor]], [[Dovedale]], [[Milldale (Peak District)|Milldale]] and [[Winnats Pass]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/main/w-vh/w-visits/w-findaplace/w-highpeakestate.htm |title=High Peak Estate |publisher=[[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|The National Trust]] |year=2009 |accessdate=22 May 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090426230500/http://nationaltrust.org.uk/main/w-vh/w-visits/w-findaplace/w-highpeakestate.htm |archivedate=26 April 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"South_Peak\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/main/w-ilampark |title=Ilam Park and South Peak Estate |publisher=[[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|The National Trust]] |year=2010 |accessdate=26 September 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100715195938/http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/main/w-ilampark |archivedate=15 July 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/main/w-vh/w-visits/w-findaplace/w-longshawestate.htm |title=Longshaw Estate |publisher=[[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|The National Trust]] |year=2009 |accessdate=22 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090510093420/http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/main/w-vh/w-visits/w-findaplace/w-longshawestate.htm |archivedate=10 May 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The park authority owns around 5%, and other major landowners include several water companies.<ref name=\"Landuse\">{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/learning-about/secondary-resources/factsheets |title=Peak District National Park Authority factsheets |publisher=Peak District National Park Authority |year=2012 |accessdate=4 March 2014}}</ref>\n[[Image:Near the High Peak - pano.jpg|800px|thumb|center|A [[High Peak Estate|High Peak]] panorama between [[Hayfield, Derbyshire|Hayfield]] and [[Chinley]]]]\n\n===Settlements===\nBakewell is the largest settlement and only town in the national park; its five-arched bridge over the River Wye dates from the 13th century.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.places-to-go.org.uk/Bakewell.htm |title=Bakewell |publisher=Places-to-go.org.uk |year=2003 |accessdate=18 June 2009}}</ref> Castleton is the centre of production of the semi-precious mineral [[Blue John (mineral)|Blue John]], while the village of Eyam is known for its self-imposed quarantine during the [[Black Death in England|Black Death]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/wnet/secrets/case_plague/index.html |title=Mystery of the Black Death |publisher=[[Secrets of the Dead]] |accessdate=18 June 2009}}</ref> [[Edale]] is the southern terminus of the [[Pennine Way]], a 268-mile [[National Trails|national trail]] which transverses most of the Pennines and ends at [[Kirk Yetholm]] in the [[Anglo-Scottish border|Scottish border]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationaltrail.co.uk/pennine-way|title=Trail stats, Pennine Way|accessdate=27 May 2019|work=National Trails Homepage|publisher=[[The Countryside Agency]]}}</ref> Other villages within the park include [[Flash, Staffordshire|Flash]], [[Hathersage]], [[Hartington, Derbyshire|Hartington]], [[Ilam, Staffordshire|Ilam]] and [[Tideswell]].\n\nThe towns of [[Glossop]], [[Chapel-en-le-Frith]], Buxton, [[Macclesfield]], [[Leek, Staffordshire|Leek]], Ashbourne, [[Matlock, Derbyshire|Matlock]] and [[Chesterfield]] are on the fringes of the national park. The spa town of Buxton was developed by the [[Duke of Devonshire|Dukes of Devonshire]] as a genteel health resort in the 18th century<ref name=\"Visit Buxton\">{{cite web |url=http://www.visitbuxton.co.uk/ |title=Visit Buxton |publisher=VisitBuxton.co.uk |year=2007 |accessdate=18 June 2009}}</ref> while the [[spa]] at Matlock Bath in the valley of the River Derwent was popularised in the Victorian era. [[Hayfield, Derbyshire|Hayfield]] is at the foot of Kinder Scout, the highest summit in the area. Other towns and villages fringing the park include [[Whaley Bridge]], [[Hadfield, Derbyshire|Hadfield]], [[Tintwistle]], [[Marsden, West Yorkshire|Marsden]], [[Holmfirth]], [[Stocksbridge]], [[Darley Dale]] and [[Wirksworth]].\n\n===Rivers, reservoirs and canals===\nSeveral rivers have their sources on the moorland plateaux of the Dark Peak and the high ridges of the White Peak. Many rivers in the Dark Peak and outer fringes were dammed to create reservoirs for supplying drinking water. Streams were dammed to provide headwater for [[watermill|water driven mills]]; [[weir]]s were built for the same purpose.\nThe reservoirs of the [[Longdendale Chain]] were completed in February 1877 to provide compensation water, ensuring a continuous flow along the [[River Etherow]] which was essential for local industry, and provide drinking water for Manchester.<ref name=\"Quayle\" /> In a report for the [[Manchester City Council|Manchester Corporation]], [[John Frederick Bateman]] wrote in 1846:\n\n{{Quote|Within ten or twelve miles of Manchester, and six or seven miles from the existing reservoirs at Gorton, there is this tract of mountain land abounding with springs of the purest quality. Its physical and geological features offer such peculiar features for the collection, storage and supply of water for the use of the towns in the plains below that I am surprised that they have been overlooked.\n|John Frederick Bateman<ref name=\"Quayle\">{{cite book |last=Quayle |first=Tom |title=Manchester's Water: The Reservoirs in the Hills |year=2006 |publisher=[[Tempus Publishing]] |location=Stroud |isbn=0-7524-3198-6 |page=15}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe western side of the Peak District is drained by the Etherow, [[River Goyt|Goyt]], and [[River Tame, Greater Manchester|Tame]], which are tributaries of the [[River Mersey]]. The north east is drained by tributaries of the [[River Don, South Yorkshire|River Don]]. Of the tributaries of the [[River Trent]] that drain the south and east, the [[River Derwent, Derbyshire|River Derwent]] is the most prominent. It [[Source (river or stream)|rises]] on Bleaklow just east of [[Glossop]] and flows through the [[Upper Derwent Valley]] where it is constrained by the [[Howden Reservoir|Howden]], [[Derwent Reservoir (Derbyshire)|Derwent]] and [[Ladybower Reservoir]]s.<ref>{{cite book |last=Bevan |first=Bill |title=The Upper Derwent: 10,000 Years in a Peak District Valley |year=2004 |publisher=[[Tempus Publishing]] |location=Stroud |isbn=0-7524-2903-5 |pages=141\u2013159}}</ref> The reservoirs of the Upper Derwent Valley were built from the early to mid-20th century to supply drinking water to the [[East Midlands]] and South Yorkshire.\n\nThe [[River Noe]] and the [[River Wye, Derbyshire|River Wye]] are its tributaries.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrictonline.co.uk/content.php?categoryId=1593 |title=River Derwent |publisher=Peak District Online |year=2009 |accessdate=1 July 2009}}</ref> The [[River Manifold]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cressbrook.co.uk/features/manifold.php |title=The Manifold is a sister river to the Dove |work=Peak District Information |publisher=Cressbrook Multimedia |year=2008 |accessdate=1 July 2009}}</ref> and [[River Dove, Central England|River Dove]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cressbrook.co.uk/features/dove.php |title=The Dove is the major river of the South Peak |work=Peak District Information |publisher=Cressbrook Multimedia |year=2008 |accessdate=1 July 2009}}</ref> in the south west, whose sources are on [[Axe Edge Moor]], flow into the Trent, while the [[River Dane]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cressbrook.co.uk/features/dane.php |title=The Dane flows west into Cheshire |work=Peak District Information |publisher=Cressbrook Multimedia |year=2008 |accessdate=1 July 2009}}</ref> flows into the [[River Weaver]] in Cheshire.\n\n[[Image:Bugsworth 058079.jpg|thumb|right|upright|The Bugsworth Basin on the Peak Forest Canal]]\nThere are no canals in the national park, although the [[Standedge Tunnels]] on the [[Huddersfield Narrow Canal]] run underneath the extreme north of it.  Waters from the Dark Peak feed the [[Macclesfield Canal|Macclesfield]], [[Ashton Canal|Ashton]], and Huddersfield Narrow Canals and waters from the White Peak fed the [[Cromford Canal]]. Outside the  park, the [[Peak Forest Canal]] brought [[Lime (material)|lime]] from the quarries at [[Dove Holes]] for the construction industry. It terminated at [[Bugsworth Basin]] and the journey was completed using the [[Peak Forest Tramway]]. \n\nThe Cromford Canal, from [[Cromford]] to the [[Erewash Canal]], served lead mines at [[Wirksworth]] and [[Sir Richard Arkwright]]'s cotton mills. The [[Caldon Canal]] from [[Froghall]] was built to transport limestone from quarries at Cauldon Low for the iron industry and flints for the pottery industry.<ref name=\"Caldon Canal\">{{cite web|title=Caldon Canal|url=https://canalrivertrust.org.uk/enjoy-the-waterways/canal-and-river-network/caldon-canal|website=Canal River Trust|publisher=Canal River Trust|accessdate=1 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Climate===\nMost of the area is more than {{convert|1000|ft|m|-2}} above sea level,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrictinformation.com/features/kinder.php |title=Kinder Scout \u2013 the highest gritstone peak in the Peak District |publisher=Peak District Information |year=2008 |accessdate=21 May 2009}}</ref> in the centre of the country at a latitude of 53\u00b0N resulting in relatively high annual rainfall, averaging {{convert|40.35|in|mm}} in 1999, compared with the rest of England and Wales. The Dark Peak tends to receive more rainfall then the White Peak as it is higher. The higher rainfall does not affect the temperature, which averages the same as the rest of England and Wales at {{convert|10.3|\u00b0C|\u00b0F|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrict-nationalpark.info/place/rivers/climate.html |title=Peak District Climate |publisher=Peak District National Park |year=2003 |accessdate=13 November 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120523234641/http://www.peakdistrict-nationalpark.info/place/rivers/climate.html |archivedate=23 May 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> \n\nDuring the 1970s, the Dark Peak regularly recorded more than 70 days of snowfall. Since then the number of snowfall days has decreased. The hills still see periods of long continuous snow cover in some winters. Snow in mid-December 2009 on some hill summits created snow patches that lasted in some cases until May 2010. In the same winter, the A635 (Saddleworth Moor) and  A57 (Snake Pass) were closed because of lying snow for almost a month. Frost cover is seen for 20\u201330% of the winter on moorland in the Dark Peak and 10% in the White Peak.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepeakdistrict.info/fast/html/peak_district_general_informat.html |title=About the Peak District&nbsp;... |publisher=ThePeakDistrict.info |year=2007 |accessdate=23 May 2009}}</ref> \n\nThe Moorland Indicators of Climate Change Initiative was set up in 2008 to collect data in the area. Students investigated the interaction between people and the moorlands, and their effect on climate change, to discover whether the moorlands are a net carbon sink or source, based on the fact that Britain's upland areas are a significant global carbon store in the form of [[peat]]. Human interaction in terms of direct erosion and fire as well as the effects of global warming are the major variables that they considered.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/learning-about/learning-projects/climatechangeproject |title=Moorland Indicators of Climate Change Initiative 2012 |publisher=Peak District |year=2012 |accessdate=3 April 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120122183958/http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/learning-about/learning-projects/climatechangeproject |archivedate=22 January 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Geology==\nThe Peak is formed almost exclusively from [[sedimentary rock]]s dating from the [[Carboniferous]] period. They comprise the [[Carboniferous Limestone]], overlying [[Gritstone]] and the [[Coal Measures]] which occur only on the extreme margins and infrequent outcrops of [[igneous rock]]s including [[lava]]s, [[tuff]]s and [[volcano|volcanic vent]] [[agglomerate]]s.<ref>Gannon, Paul, ''Rock Trails Peak District:A Hillwalker's Guide to the Geology and Scenery'', Pesda Press, 2011, {{ISBN|978-1-906095-24-6}}</ref> The general [[structural geology|geological structure]] is that of a broad [[dome (geology)|dome]], whose western margins have been most intensely [[fault (geology)|fault]]ed and [[fold (geology)|fold]]ed.  [[Geologic uplift|Uplift]] and [[erosion]] have effectively sliced the top off the dome to reveal a [[concentric]] [[outcrop]] pattern with Coal Measures rocks on the eastern and western margins, Carboniferous Limestone at the core and with rocks of [[Millstone Grit]] outcropping between them. The southern edge of the dome is overlain by [[sandstone]]s of [[Triassic]] age though they barely impinge on the National Park. The White Peak is the central and southern section  where Carboniferous Limestone is found at or near the surface.<ref name=\"NCA Profile: 52 White Peak (NE534)\">{{cite web|title=NCA Profile: 52 White Peak (NE534)|url=http://publications.naturalengland.org.uk/publication/6364771410509824|website=Natural England|publisher=Natural England|accessdate=13 February 2018}}</ref> The Dark Peak to the north, east and west is characterised by Millstone Grit outcrops and broad swathes of moorland.<ref name=\"NCA Profile: 51 Dark Peak (NE378)\">{{cite web|title=NCA Profile: 51 Dark Peak (NE378)|url=http://publications.naturalengland.org.uk/publication/3684793|website=Natural England|publisher=Natural England|accessdate=13 February 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"South West Peak\"/>\n\nEarth movements after the Carboniferous period resulted in the up-doming of the area and, particularly in the west, the folding of the rock strata along north\u2013south axes. The region was raised in a north\u2013south line which resulted in the dome-like shape<ref name=\"Geology_explained\">{{cite book |title=Geology Explained in the Peak District |last=Cope |first=F. W. |year=1976 |isbn=0-7153-6945-8 |publisher=[[David & Charles]]}}</ref> and the [[shale]]s and sandstones were worn away until limestone was exposed. At the end of this period, the Earth's crust sank here which led to the area being covered by sea, depositing a variety of new rocks.<ref name=\"Geology\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cressbrook.co.uk/features/geology.php |title=The Peak District is a very interesting area geologically |work=Peak District Information |publisher=Cressbrook Multimedia |year=2008 |accessdate=24 May 2009}}</ref> Some time after its deposition, mineral veins were formed in the limestone. The veins and rakes have been mined for lead since [[Ancient Rome|Roman times]].<ref name=\"Geology\" />\n[[Image:Thor's cave.jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Thor's Cave]] seen from the [[Manifold Way]]]]\nThe Peak District was covered by ice during at least one of the [[ice age]]s of the last 2&nbsp;million years (probably the [[Anglian (stage)|Anglian]] glaciation of around 450,000 years ago) as evidenced by the patches of glacial till or boulder clay that can be found across the area.  It was not covered by ice during the [[last glacial period]], which peaked around 20,000\u201322,000 years ago. A mix of Irish Sea and Lake District ice abutted against its western margins. Glacial meltwaters eroded a complex of sinuous channels along this margin of the district during this period.<ref>Aitkenhead, N. et al. 2002 British Regional Geology: the Pennines and adjacent areas (4th Edn) (BGS, Nottingham)</ref> Glacial meltwaters contributed to the formation and development of many caves in the limestone area.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Geology of Britain |last=Macdougall |first=D. |year=2006 |isbn=0-520-24824-4 |publisher=University of California Press |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/frozenearthoncef00macd }}</ref> Wild animal herds roamed the area, and their remains have been found in several of the local caves.<ref name=\"Geology\" />\n\nThe different types of rock beneath the soil strongly influence the landscape; they determine the type of [[vegetation]] that will grow, and ultimately the type of animal that will inhabit the area.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Geology of Britain |last=Toghill |first=P. |year=2002 |isbn=1-84037-404-7 |publisher=Crowood Press}}</ref> [[Limestone]] has fissures and is [[Solubility|soluble]] in water, therefore rivers have been able to carve deep, narrow valleys. The rivers then often find routes underground, creating cave systems. Millstone Grit is insoluble but [[Porosity|porous]], absorbing water which seeps through the grits, until it meets the less porous shales beneath, creating [[Spring (hydrosphere)|springs]] where it reaches the surface. The shales are [[Friability|friable]] and easily attacked by [[frost]] and form areas that are vulnerable to [[landslide]]s, as on Mam Tor.<ref name=\"Geology_explained\" />\n\n==Ecology==\nThe gritstone and shale of the Dark Peak supports [[Ericaceae|heather]] moorland and [[blanket bog]] environments, with rough [[Domestic sheep|sheep]] pasture and [[grouse]] shooting being the main land uses, although parts of it also support farming,<ref name=\"NCA Profile: 51 Dark Peak (NE378)\"/> especially the South West Peak NCA.<ref name=\"NCA Profile: 53 South West Peak (NE453)\">{{cite web|title=NCA Profile: 53 South West Peak (NE453)|url=http://publications.naturalengland.org.uk/publication/12392045|website=Natural England|publisher=Natural England|accessdate=26 September 2017}}</ref> The limestone plateaux of the White Peak are more intensively farmed, with mainly dairy usage of improved pastures.<ref name=\"NCA Profile: 52 White Peak (NE534)\"/>  Woodland forms around 8% of the Peak National Park.<ref name=\"Landuse\" /> Natural broad-leaved [[woodland]] is found in the steep-sided, narrow dales of the [[White Peak]] and the deep cloughs of the Dark Peak, while reservoir margins often have coniferous plantations. \n\n===Flora===\n[[Polemonium caeruleum|Jacob's-ladder]] (''Polemonium caeruleum''), a relatively rare species characteristic of limestone dales in the White Peak, has been the county flower of Derbyshire since 2002.<ref name=\"The Flora of Derbyshire.\">{{cite book|last1=Willmott|first1=Alan|last2=Moyes|first2=Nick|title=The Flora of Derbyshire.|publisher=Pisces Publication.|isbn=978-1-874357-65-0}}</ref> It grows in grassland, light woodland, on screes, rock ledges and by streams in [[River Lathkill|Lathkill]], Wolfscote, Taddington, [[River Wye, Derbyshire|Wye]] Dale and other dales.  Pollen evidence from peat bogs indicates that it was widespread throughout Britain just after the last ice-age. Much planted in gardens from where it has established itself in other parts of the area, as a native it is restricted to the White Peak and the [[Yorkshire Dales]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Polemonium caeruleum|url=https://secure.derby.gov.uk/flora/?SpeciesID=1326|website=Derby City Council|publisher=Derby City Council|accessdate=25 April 2018}}</ref> Three [[Endemism|endemic]] vascular plants are found nowhere else in the world: ''[[Rubus durescens]]'' is a bramble found in central Derbyshire;<ref name=\"The Flora of Derbyshire.\"/> Derby hawkweed (''[[Hieracium naviense]]''), found only in [[Winnats Pass]],<ref name=\"The Flora of Derbyshire.\"/> is a native perennial of limestone cliffs that was discovered by J.N. Mills in 1966 and described as a new species in 1968;<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Mills|first1=J.N.|title=A new species of Hieracium in Derbyshire|journal=Watsonia|date=1968|volume=7|issue=1|pages=40\u201342|url=http://archive.bsbi.org.uk/Wats7p40.pdf|accessdate=25 April 2018|publisher=BSBI}}</ref> and leek-coloured hawkweed (''H. subprasinifolium'') was believed extinct but was rediscovered on banks beside the [[Monsal Trail]] in Cheedale in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Extinct plant rediscovered in the Peak District National Park |url=https://www.thestar.co.uk/news/extinct-plant-rediscovered-in-the-peak-district-national-park-1-8739153|website=The Star|publisher=The Star|accessdate=25 April 2018}}</ref>  The endemic Derbyshire feather moss ''[[Thamnobryum angustifolium]]'' occurs in one Derbyshire limestone dale, its sole world location intentionally kept confidential; the colony covers about {{convert|3|m2}} of a rock face with small subsidiary colonies nearby.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.slu.se/Global/externwebben/centrumbildningar-projekt/bryoconservation/Pdf%20ArtFaktablad/Faktablad/Thamnobryum_angustifolium.PDF | title=''Thamnobryum angustifolium'': Derbyshire feather-moss |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151210213710/http://www.slu.se/Global/externwebben/centrumbildningar-projekt/bryoconservation/Pdf%20ArtFaktablad/Faktablad/Thamnobryum_angustifolium.PDF |publisher=Joint Nature Conservation Committee |first=Nick G. |last=Hodgketts |date=March 2001 |archivedate=10 December 2015 |accessdate=2 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Dark Peak's heathlands, bogs, gritstone edges and acid grasslands contain relatively few species and [[Calluna|heather]] (''Calluna vulgaris''), [[Empetrum nigrum|crowberry]] (''Empetrum nigrum''), [[Vaccinium myrtillus|bilberry]] (''Vaccinium myrtillus'') and [[Eriophorum vaginatum|hare's-tail cotton grass]] (''Eriophorum vaginatum'') are dominant on the high moors.<ref name=\"The Flora of Derbyshire.\"/>  After decades of decline due to pollution, ''Sphagnum'' mosses are making a comeback, with species such as ''[[Sphagnum cuspidatum|S. cuspidatum]]'' being particularly dominant.<ref>Walker, M. D. 2019. ''Sphagnum''. Sicklebrook Press.</ref> White Peak habitats include [[calcareous grassland]], ash woodlands and rock outcrops suitable for lime-loving species.<ref name=\"The Flora of Derbyshire.\"/> They include [[Orchis mascula|early purple orchid]] (''Orchis mascula''), [[Epipactis atrorubens|dark-red helleborine]] (''Epipactis atrorubens'') and [[Ophrys insectifera|fly orchid]] (''Ophrys insectifera''), [[Helianthemum nummularium|common rockrose]] (''Helianthemum nummularium''), [[Helianthemum nummularium|spring cinquefoil]] (''Helianthemum nummularium'') and [[Parnassia|grass of parnassus]] (''Parnassia palustris''). Lead rakes, the spoil heaps of ancient mining activity, form another distinctive habitat in the White Peak, supporting a range of rare [[metallophyte]] plants, including the [[Minuartia|spring sandwort]] (''Minuartia verna''; also known as leadwort), [[Thlaspi caerulescens|alpine pennycress]] (''Thlaspi caerulescens'') and [[Viola lutea|mountain pansy]] (''Viola lutea'').<ref name=\"Lead\">{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/lead |title=Biodiversity Action Plan \u2013 The Lead Legacy |publisher=Peak District |year=2004 |accessdate=13 November 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720112405/http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/lead|archivedate=20 July 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Fauna===\n====Mammals====\nMost mammals found in the Peak District are generalists and widespread across the UK, but [[mountain hare]]s on heather moorland in the Dark Peak constitute the only wild population in England. They were re-introduced in the Victorian era for sporting purposes.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.derbyshiremammalgroup.org.uk/species_status/mountain_hare.html |title=MOUNTAIN HARE Lepus timidus |publisher=Derbyshire Mammal Group |date= |accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref>  A feral population of [[Red-necked wallaby|red-necked wallabies]] lived around [[The Roaches]] from the 1940s onwards but may now be extinct.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/environment/nature/naturestudies/the-decline-and-fall-of-the-peak-district-wallabies-8503546.html |title=The decline and fall of the Peak District wallabies |newspaper=The Independent |date=20 February 2013 |first=Michael |last=McCarthy |accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref> [[Red deer]] herds, assumed to be derived from animals escaped from [[Deer park (England)|deer park]]s at [[Lyme Park]] and [[Chatsworth House|Chatsworth]], are established in the upper reaches of the [[River Goyt|Goyt valley]] and on the moors above [[Baslow]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.derbyshiremammalgroup.org.uk/species_status/red_deer.html |title=Red Deer Cervus elaphus |publisher=Derbyshire Mammal Group |date= |accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The Red Deer of the Peak District \u2013 photograph special|url=http://www.derbyshirelife.co.uk/out-about/wildlife/the-red-deer-of-the-peak-district-photograph-special-1-4307436 |newspaper=Derbyshire Life |first=Paul |last=Hobson |date=12 November 2015 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref> and a herd on [[Wharncliffe Crags]] outside the park north of Sheffield may derive from the hunting stock of Wharncliffe Chase.<ref>{{cite book |chapter-url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=DyzwAwAAQBAJ&lpg=PA30&ots=z8EKrt4cA9&dq=Wharncliffe%20Woods%20red%20deer&pg=PA30#v=onepage&q=red%20deer&f=false |chapter=The dynamic influence of history and ecology on the restoration of a major urban heathland at Wharncliffe, South Yorkshire |first1=Ian D. |last1=Rotherham |first2=John C. |last2=Rose |first3=Chris |last3=Percy |publisher=Landscape Conservation Forum |editor-first1=Ian D. |editor-last1=Rotherham |editor-first2=Christine |editor-last2=Handley |title=Wild by Design and Ploughing on Regardless: Landscape Archaeology and Ecology Special Series |date=August 2012 |accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref> [[Biodiversity action plan]]s have been prepared for mountain hare, [[European hare|brown hare]], [[brown long-eared bat]], [[Hazel dormouse|dormouse]], [[Eurasian harvest mouse|harvest mouse]], [[European hedgehog|hedgehog]], [[noctule bat]], [[Eurasian otter|otter]], [[European pine marten|pine marten]], [[European polecat|polecat]], [[soprano pipistrelle]] and [[European water vole|water vole]].<ref name=\"Biodiversity Action Plan Species Found in the Peak District\">{{cite web|title=Biodiversity Action Plan Species Found in the Peak District|url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0003/610716/PDNPA-BAP-Species-Table-240815.pdf|website=Peak District National Park|publisher=Peak District National Park|accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref> The status of the pine marten is unclear, although confirmed sightings have occurred in recent decades in Derbyshire and north Staffordshire<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.derbyshiremammalgroup.org.uk/species_status/pine_marten.html |title=PINE MARTEN Martes martes  |publisher=Derbyshire Mammal Group |date= |accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref> and a specimen from an introduced Welsh population<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-derbyshire-45331872 |title=Mystery of pine marten found dead '100 miles from home' |publisher=BBC |date=28 August 2018 |accessdate=28 August 2018}}</ref> was found dead outside the national park on a road between [[Ripley, Derbyshire|Ripley]] and [[Belper]] in 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.derbyshirewildlifetrust.org.uk/news/rare-pine-marten-discovered-derbyshire |title=Rare pine marten discovered in Derbyshire |publisher=Derbyshire Wildlife Trust |date=24 August 2018 |accessdate=25 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Birds====\nMany of the Peak's bird species are also widespread generalists. The moors of the Dark Peak support breeding populations of a number of upland specialists, such as [[twite]],<ref name=\"pdnp\">{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/looking-after/biodiversity/peak-district-biodiversity/peak-district-species/moorland-species |title= Moorland Species |publisher=Peak District National Park |date= |accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=https://britishbirds.co.uk/article/notes-neglected-colony-twite-central-england/ |title=Notes on a neglected colony of Twite in central England |journal=British Birds |date=15 June 2016 |first1=Jamie |last1=Dunning |first2=Roy |last2=Frost |first3=Steve |last3=Christmas |first4=Mick |last4=Pearson |accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref> [[short-eared owl]],<ref name=\"pdnp\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.derbyshirewildlifetrust.org.uk/species/short-eared-owl |title=Short-eared Owl ''Asio flammeus'' |publisher=Derbyshire Wildlife Trust |date= |accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref> [[European golden plover|golden plover]],<ref name=\"pdnp\" /> [[dunlin]],<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://britishbirds.co.uk/article/recovery-breeding-dunlin-population-peak-district-response-blanket-bog-restoration/ |title=Recovery of a breeding Dunlin population in the Peak District in response to blanket bog restoration |journal=British Birds |date=8 February 2017 |first1=Dave |last1=O\u2019Hara |first2=Jon |last2=Bird |first3=Kate |last3=Hanley |first4=Geoff |last4=Carr |accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref> [[ring ouzel]],<ref name=\"pdnp\" /> [[northern wheatear]]<ref name=\"Peak Birds Project\">{{cite web |url=http://ww2.rspb.org.uk/Images/peakdistrictbirds_tcm9-132780.pdf |title=Where to find birds in the Peak District |publisher=Peak Birds Project  |date= |accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref> and [[merlin (bird)|merlin]].<ref name=\"pdnp\" /> The populations of twite and golden plover are the southernmost confirmed breeding populations in England,<ref name=\"bto\">{{cite book |first1=D.E. |last1=Balmer |first2=S. |last2=Gillings |first3=B.J. |last3=Caffrey |first4=R.L. |last4=Swann |first5=I.S. |last5=Downie |first6=R.J. |last6=Fuller |title=Bird Atlas 2007\u201311: the breeding and wintering birds of Britain and Ireland |publisher=BTO Books |date=2013 |location=Thetford |isbn=978-1-908581-28-0}}</ref> and the Peak District Moors Special Protection Area (SPA) is a European designation for its populations of merlin, golden plover and short-eared owl.<ref name=\"pdnp\" /> The Peak District lacks the concentrations of breeding [[wader]]s found further north in the Pennines, although the moors and their fringes accommodate breeding [[Eurasian curlew|curlew]] and [[Northern lapwing|lapwing]]<ref name=\"Peak Birds Project\" /> as well as less noticeable wading birds including dunlin and [[Common snipe|snipe]].<ref name=\"Peak Birds Project\" />\n\nCommercial [[driven grouse shooting]] occurs on the heather moorlands of the Dark Peak, where the [[red grouse]] population is maintained by gamekeepers employed by shooting estates.<ref name=\"marsland\">{{cite journal |title=Birds of the Peak District |first=Michael |last=Marsland |journal=Bird Study |date=1974 |volume=21 |issue=2 |pages=135\u2013140 |doi=10.1080/00063657409476409 }}</ref><ref name=\"malp\">{{cite web |url=http://ww2.rspb.org.uk/Images/PeakMalpractice_tcm9-132666.pdf |title=Peak Malpractice: What's happening to wildlife in the Peak District National Park? |publisher=RSPB |date=2006 |accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref> A population of [[black grouse]] became extinct in 2000,<ref name=\"bto\" /> but reintroduction was attempted in 2003.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.birdguides.com/articles/black-grouse-in-the-upper-derwent-valley-an-update/ |title=Black Grouse in the Upper Derwent Valley \u2013 an Update |publisher=BirdGuides |date= 21 March 2006 |first=Matthew |last=Capper |accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref> Quarries and rock outcrops provide nest sites for [[peregrine falcon]] and [[common raven]]. Ravens and [[common buzzard]]s are increasingly encountered as their British range expands eastwards, perhaps because of general reductions in persecution. Illegal persecution may be implicated in the limited populations of rare raptors such as [[northern goshawk]], peregrine and [[hen harrier]].<ref name=\"malp\" /> Following the [[RSPB]]'s publication of ''Peak Malpractice'', a 2006 report highlighting wildlife crime,<ref name=\"malp\" /> the Peak District Bird of Prey Initiative was set up in 2011 by conservationists and shooting bodies in an attempt to boost the populations of birds of prey.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0005/1055570/Bird-of-Prey-Initiative-2016-17-Report.pdf |title=Peak District Bird of Prey Initiative \u2013 2016 & 2017 Report |publisher=Peak District Bird of Prey Initiative |date=2018 |accessdate=26 April 2018}}</ref> The park authorities expressed disappointment at the limited results<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/learning-about/news/current-news/peak-district-bird-of-prey-initiative |title=Peak District Bird of Prey Initiative |publisher=Peak District National Park  |date=25 January 2018 |accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref> and the RSPB withdrew from the partnership in January 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rspb.org.uk/about-the-rspb/about-us/media-centre/press-releases/rspb-ends-involvement-in-failed-peak-district-bird-of-prey-initiative/ |title=RSPB ends involvement in failed Peak District Bird of Prey Initiative |publisher=RSPB |date=23 January 2018 |accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nFast-flowing rivers attract specialist species, notably [[grey wagtail]],<ref name=\"marsland\" /> [[White-throated dipper|dipper]],<ref name=\"lgre\">{{cite book |first=Lee G.R. |last=Evans |title=The Ultimate Site Guide to Scarcer British Birds |publisher=BirdGuides |date=2009 |location= |isbn=978-1898110491 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.moorsforthefuture.org.uk/sites/default/files/documents/MFF%20RN01%202004%20Breeding%20bird%20survey%20of%20the%20Peak%20District%20moorlands.pdf |title=Breeding Bird Survey of the Peak District Moorlands:Moors for the Future Research Note No 1 |publisher= Moors for the Future |date=May 2005 |accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref> [[common sandpiper]],<ref name=\"marsland\" /> [[mandarin duck]]<ref name=\"birdreport\" /> and [[Common merganser|goosander]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0005/817772/State-of-Nature-in-the-Peak-District-Report-by-Penny-Anderson-for-Nature-Peak-District.pdf |title=State of Nature in the Peak District |publisher=Nature Peak District |date=2016 |first=Penny |last=Anderson |at=Section 5.22 |accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref>  Wooded and semi-wooded areas attract [[common redstart|redstart]],<ref name=\"Peak Birds Project\" /> [[European pied flycatcher|pied flycatcher]],<ref name=\"Peak Birds Project\" /> [[wood warbler]]<ref name=\"Peak Birds Project\" /> and [[tree pipit]],<ref name=\"marsland\" /> and coniferous plantations house [[Eurasian siskin|siskin]] and [[Red crossbill|common crossbill]].<ref name=\"lgre\" /> Upland reservoirs in the Dark Peak are generally [[Oligotroph|oligotrophic]] and attract few birds, but lower-lying reservoirs on the southern fringes such as [[Carsington Water]] and [[Ogston Reservoir]] regularly attract rare migrants and wintering rarities such as various waders, wildfowl, gulls and terns.<ref name=\"birdreport\" /> The area is regularly overflown by wintering populations of [[pink-footed geese]]<ref name=\"birdreport\">{{cite journal |title=Derbyshire Bird Report |issue=various |publisher=Derbyshire Ornithological Society}}</ref> moving between East Anglia and Morecambe Bay.\n\nDipper, golden plover, hen harrier, merlin and short-eared owl are local [[biodiversity action plan]] priority species.<ref name=\"Biodiversity Action Plan Species Found in the Peak District\"/>\n\n====Other taxa====\nAmphibians and reptiles such as [[Viviparous lizard|common lizard]]s, [[grass snake]]s, [[Northern crested newt|great crested newt]]s and [[Anguis fragilis|slow worm]]s are found in the area.<ref name=\"Biodiversity Action Plan Species Found in the Peak District\"/> The eastern moors are a stronghold for [[Vipera berus|adder]]s.<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.sorby.org.uk/v2/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/SS11_1997_Reptiles_Amphibians_OCRc.pdf  |title=Reptiles and Amphibians of the Sheffield Area and North Derbyshire |publisher=Sorby Natural History Society |location=Sheffield |date=1997 |first=Derek |last=Whiteley |accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nNative fish in the Peak District include [[Atlantic salmon]], [[brown trout]], [[European eel]],<ref name=\"Biodiversity Action Plan Species Found in the Peak District\"/> [[European bullhead|bullhead]], [[brook lamprey]] and [[Thymallus|grayling]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Rivers and Streams|url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0003/158646/Rivers-and-Streams.pdf|website=Peak District National Park|publisher=Peak District National Park|accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref> A possibly unique population of \"wild\" [[rainbow trout]] survives on the [[River Wye, Derbyshire|Derbyshire Wye]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://theriverbeat.blogspot.com/2012/07/wild-rainbows-of-river-wye-derbyshire.html |title=Wild Rainbows of the River Wye, Derbyshire |publisher=The River Beat |type=blog |date=3 July 2012 |accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref> following their introduction at the turn of the 20th century.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.derbyshiretimes.co.uk/sport/angling/rainbows-the-pride-of-the-river-wye-1-483071 |first= |last= |title=Rainbows: the pride of the river Wye |newspaper=Derbyshire Times |date=25 March 2009 |accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nButterflies in the region include the [[dingy skipper]], [[Aricia agestis|brown argus]], [[small blue]] and [[white-letter hairstreak]]. Moths include the [[Stilbia anomala|anomalous]], [[Ceramica pisi|broom moth]], [[dot moth]], [[garden dart]], [[mouse moth]] and [[Spilosoma lubricipeda|white ermine]]. Other invertebrates include the [[Bombus monticola|bilberry bumblebee]], [[Monocephalus|broad groove-head spider]], [[mole cricket]], [[Lipsothrix|northern yellow splinter]], [[Formicoxenus nitidulus|shining guest ant]], [[Meloe violaceus|violet oil beetle]] and [[Austropotamobius pallipes|white-clawed crayfish]].<ref name=\"Biodiversity Action Plan Species Found in the Peak District\"/>\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Kinder plateau.jpg|thumb|right|upright|A view of the [[Edale]] valley from [[Mam Tor]]]]\nThe Peak has been inhabited from the earliest periods of human activity as evidenced by finds of [[Mesolithic]] flint artefacts and [[Palaeogeography|palaeoenvironmental]] evidence from caves in Dovedale and elsewhere. Evidence of [[Neolithic]] activity includes monumental earthworks or [[Tumulus|barrows]] such as that at [[Margery Hill]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eng-h.gov.uk/ArchRev/rev94_5/margery.htm |title=Margery Hill, South Yorkshire |publisher=[[English Heritage]] |year=1994 |accessdate=22 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012232222/http://www.eng-h.gov.uk/ArchRev/rev94_5/margery.htm |archivedate=12 October 2008 }}</ref> \n\nIn the [[Bronze Age]] the area was well populated and farmed, and evidence of these people survives in [[henge]]s such as [[Arbor Low]] near [[Youlgreave]], or the [[Nine Ladies|Nine Ladies stone circle]] at [[Stanton Moor]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Bevan |first=Bill |title=Ancient Peakland |year=2007 |publisher=Halsgrove |location=Wellington |isbn=978-1-84114-593-8}}</ref> In the same period, and into the [[Iron Age]] hillforts such as that at Mam Tor were created. The [[Roman Britain|Romans]] exploited the area's rich mineral veins, exporting lead from the Buxton area along well-used routes. Buxton was a Roman settlement, known as \"[[Aquae Arnemetiae]]\" in recognition of its spring.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.roman-britain.org/places/aquae_arnemetiae.htm |title=Aquae Arnemetiae |publisher=RomanBritain.org |year=2005 |accessdate=22 May 2009}}</ref> .\n\nTheories as to the derivation of the Peak name include that it came from the [[Pecsaetan]] or peaklanders, an [[Anglo-Saxons|Anglo-Saxon]] tribe who inhabited the central and northern parts of the area from the 6th century AD when it was part of the Anglian kingdom of [[Mercia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peakscan.freeuk.com/peak_district_history_.htm |title=Peak District history : Anglo Saxons to Present |publisher=Peakscan |accessdate=28 June 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=A History of Derbyshire, Volume 1 |last=Turbutt |first=G. |year=1999 |publisher=Merton Priory |location=Cardiff |isbn=1-898937-34-6}}</ref> Barrows from the [[Anglo-Saxons|Anglo-Saxon]] period are present, including at [[Benty Grange]], where the [[Benty Grange helmet|eponymous helmet]] was found.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1013767 |desc=Benty Grange hlaew, Monyash |year= |accessdate=10 February 2018}}</ref> \n\n===Mining and quarrying===\n{{See also|Derbyshire lead mining history}}\nIn medieval and early modern times the area was mainly agricultural with sheep farming, rather than arable, the main activity in upland holdings. From the 16th century, the area's mineral and geological wealth became increasingly significant. Not only lead, but coal, [[fluorite]], copper from [[Ecton Mines]], [[zinc]], [[Iron ore|iron]], [[manganese]] and silver have all been mined.<ref>{{cite book |title=Rocks and Scenery of the Peak District |last=Ford |first=T. D. |authorlink=Trevor D. Ford |year=2002 |isbn=1-84306-026-4 |publisher=Landmark Publishing}}</ref> [[Celia Fiennes]], describing her journey through the Peak in 1697, described,\n{{Quote|...&nbsp;craggy hills whose bowells are full of mines of all kinds off black and white and veined marbles, and some have mines of copper, others tinn and leaden mines, in w[hi]ch is a great deale of silver.\n|[[Celia Fiennes]]<ref>{{cite book |title=Through England on a Side Saddle in the Time of William and Mary |last=Fiennes |first=C. |authorlink=Celia Fiennes |year=1888 |publisher=Field and Tuer, The Leadenhall Press |location=London |url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/text/chap_page.jsp?t_id=Fiennes&c_id=15 |accessdate=22 May 2009}}</ref>\n}}\nCoal measures occur on the Peak's western and eastern fringes and evidence of past workings can be found from Glossop to [[The Roaches]], and from [[Stocksbridge]] to [[Baslow]]. The coal measures in the east are at the western edge of the [[South Yorkshire Coalfield]]<ref name=\"The Yorkshire Coalfield\">{{cite web |url=https://hemingfieldcolliery.wordpress.com/the-yorkshire-coalfield/|title=The Yorkshire Coalfield|publisher=The Friends of Hemingfield Colliery|accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref> and those in the west are part of the Cheshire section of the [[Lancashire Coalfield]].<ref name=\"Manchester and Its Region\">{{cite web |url=https://books.google.com/?id=mqXnAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA3&lpg=PA3&dq=south+lancashire+coalfield+cheshire+plain#v=onepage&q=south%20lancashire%20coalfield%20cheshire%20plain&f=false|title=Manchester and Its Region|publisher=The University of Manchester|accessdate=17 September 2017|year=1962}}</ref> Mining started in [[Middle Ages|medieval times]] and was at its most productive in the 18th and early 19th centuries and continued into the early 20th century. The earliest mining took place at and close to [[outcrop]]s where miners followed the seams deeper into the hillsides. At Goyt's Moss and [[Axe Edge Moor|Axe Edge]], deep seams were worked and steam engines raised the coal and dewatered the mines.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.coal.gov.uk/media/EB466/Enviro%2012%20P14.pdf |title=Goyt's Moss and Axe Edge Moor Update |publisher=Environment News 12 |accessdate=13 November 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040726124922/http://www.coal.gov.uk/media/EB466/Enviro%2012%20P14.pdf|archivedate=26 July 2004}}</ref> Coal from the east was used in lead smelting and from the west for lime burning.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrict-nationalpark.info/time/industry/coalmining.html |title=Peak District Coal Mining |publisher=Peak District National Park |year=2003 |accessdate=13 November 2013|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20100809072725/http://www.peakdistrict-nationalpark.info/time/industry/coalmining.html|archivedate=9 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nLead mining peaked in the 17th and 18th centuries; high concentrations were found in the area from this period, as well as discovering peat on Kinder Scout suggesting that lead smelting occurred.<ref name=\"Mining\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thepeakdistrict.info/peak-district-mining.php |title=Mining in the Peak District of Derbyshire Lead and Copper Minerals |publisher=A Taste of the Peak District |accessdate=24 June 2009}}</ref> Lead mining declined from the mid-19th century and the last major mine closed in 1939. Lead is a by-product of fluorite, baryte and calcite mining.<ref name=\"Lead\" /> [[Bell pit]]s were sunk to access ore that lay close to the surface.<ref name=\"Mining\" />\n\nFluorite or fluorspar is called [[Blue John (mineral)|Blue John]] locally, its name possibly from the French ''bleu et jaune'' describing its colour. Blue John is scarce, and now only a few hundred kilograms are mined each year for ornamental and [[lapidary]] use. The [[Blue John Cavern]] in Castleton is a [[show cave]]. Small scale mining takes place in [[Treak Cliff Cavern]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bluejohnstone.co.uk/ |title=Blue John Stone |publisher=BlueJohnStone.co.uk |year=2007 |accessdate=30 June 2009}}</ref>\n\nIndustrial limestone quarrying to make soda ash started around Buxton in 1874. In 1926 the operation became part of [[Imperial Chemical Industries|ICI]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tarmac.co.uk/buxtoncement/companyhistory.aspx |title=The Buxton Story |publisher=[[Tarmac Limited|Tarmac]] |year=2006 |accessdate=1 July 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130505103000/http://www.tarmac.co.uk/buxtoncement/companyhistory.aspx |archivedate=5 May 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Large-scale limestone and gritstone quarrying flourished as lead mining declined, and is an important if contentious industry.  Of the twelve large limestone quarries in operation, [[Tunstead, Derbyshire|Tunstead]] is one of the largest in Europe.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bgs.ac.uk/foundation-web/GenericInd.html |title=Peak District industry |publisher=[[British Geological Survey]] |accessdate=22 May 2009}}</ref> Total limestone output was substantial: at the 1990 peak, 8.5 million tonnes was produced.<ref name=\"Mineral_factsheet\" />\n\n===Textiles===\nTextiles have been exported for hundreds of years. In the 14th century, the area traded in unprocessed wool.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peaklandheritage.org.uk/index.asp?peakkey=30800521 |title=Textiles |publisher=Peakland Heritage |accessdate=23 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071211134344/http://www.peaklandheritage.org.uk/index.asp?peakkey=30800521 |archivedate=11 December 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> There was a number of skilled hand spinners and weavers in the area. By the 1780s, [[Richard Arkwright]] had developed machinery to produce textiles more quickly and to a higher standard. The early Arkwright [[Cotton mill|mills]] were of light construction, narrow, about {{convert|9|ft|m}} wide, and low, the ceiling height was only {{convert|6|to|8|ft}} and were lit by daylight. The new machines were powered by [[water wheel]]s.<ref>{{cite book |title=Cotton Mills of Greater Manchester |last=Williams |first=M. |year=1992 |isbn=0-948789-89-1 |page=49 |publisher=Carnegie Publishing}}</ref> The Peak was the ideal location, with its rivers and humid atmosphere. The local pool of labour was quickly exhausted and [[Litton Mill]] and [[Cressbrook|Cressbrook Mill]] in [[Millers Dale]] brought in children as young as four from the [[workhouse]]s of London as apprentices.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cottontimes.co.uk/childreno1.htm |title=Children of the Revolution |publisher=Cotton Times |accessdate=31 March 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090430143222/http://www.cottontimes.co.uk/childreno1.htm |archivedate=30 April 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAs technology advanced, narrow valleys proved unsuitable for larger steam-driven mills, but the Derbyshire mills remained, trading in finishing and niche products. Glossop benefitted from the textile industry. Its economy was linked closely with a spinning and weaving tradition that had evolved from developments in [[textile manufacture during the Industrial Revolution]]. Until the First World War, Glossop had the headquarters of the largest [[Calico (textile)|textile]] printworks in the world but after the [[Wall Street crash]], its product lines became vulnerable and the industry declined.<ref>{{cite book |title=Small-Town Politics: A Study of Political Life in Glossop  |chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/smalltownpolitic0000birc  |chapter-url-access=registration  |last=Birch |first=A. H. |year=1959 |isbn=0-273-70161-4 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/smalltownpolitic0000birc/page/8 8\u201338] |chapter=2 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]}}</ref>\n\n===Modern history===\nThe [[Mass trespass of Kinder Scout|Kinder Trespass]] in 1932 was a landmark in the campaign for open access to moorland in Britain and eventually led to the formation of Britain's [[national park]]s. Before the trespass, open moorland was closed to all. Moorland estates were the private property of landed gentry who used them for only 12 days a year and were guarded by their gamekeepers.<ref>{{cite web|last=Renton |first=D. |title=Kinder Trespass: Context in 1932 |url=http://kindertrespass.com/index.asp?ID=36 |publisher=The Kinder Trespass 75 organising committee |date=23 February 2007 |accessdate=28 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090221190036/http://kindertrespass.com/index.asp?ID=36 |archivedate=21 February 2009 }}</ref> The Peak District National Park became the United Kingdom's first national park on 17 April 1951. Campaigner [[Ethel Haythornthwaite]] played an important part in the development of the national park. The first [[Long-distance footpaths in the United Kingdom|long-distance footpath]] in the United Kingdom was the [[Pennine Way]], which opened in 1965 and starts at the Nags Head Inn, in Grindsbook Booth, part of [[Edale]] village.\n\n[[Saddleworth Moor]] and [[Wessenden Valley|Wessenden]], above Meltham, gained notoriety after the [[Moors murders]] in the 1960s.\n\n==Economy==\n[[File:Tunstead Quarry - geograph.org.uk - 865006.jpg|right|thumb|Tunsted Quarry]]\nTourism is estimated to provide 500 full-time jobs, 350 part-time jobs and 100 seasonal jobs.<ref name=\"Waugh\">{{cite book |title=Geography An Integrated Approach |last=Waugh |first=D. |year=2000 |edition=3rd |isbn=0-17-444706-X |publisher=[[Wolters Kluwer|Nelson Thornes]]}}</ref>\nIt is a major source of employment for park residents (24%). Manufacturing industries (19%), [[Peak District#Quarrying|quarrying]] (12%) and agriculture (12%) are also important.<ref name=\"Place_called_home\">{{cite web|url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/index/living-in.htm |title=A place called home |publisher=Peak District |year=2009 |accessdate=22 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090519001312/http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/index/living-in.htm |archivedate=19 May 2009 }}</ref> \nThe [[Hope Construction Materials|cement works]] at [[Hope Valley, Derbyshire|Hope]] is the largest single employer in the park.<ref name=\"Mineral_factsheet\">{{cite web|url=http://www.peakdistrict-nationalpark.info/studyArea/factsheets/11.html#4 |title=Peak District National Park: Study Area |publisher=Peak District National Park |year=2003 |accessdate=22 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20050620074557/http://www.peakdistrict-nationalpark.info/studyArea/factsheets/11.html |archivedate=20 June 2005 }}</ref> Limestone is the most important mineral quarried, mainly for roads and cement; shale is extracted for cement at Hope, and several [[gritstone]] quarries are worked for building stone.<ref name=\"Mineral_factsheet\" /> [[Derbyshire lead mining history|Lead mining]] is no longer economic, but [[fluorite]], [[baryte]] and [[calcite]] are extracted from lead veins, and small-scale Blue John mining occurs at Castleton.\n\nThe springs at Buxton and Ashbourne are exploited to produce bottled [[mineral water]], and many [[plantation]]s are managed for [[Lumber|timber]]. Other manufacturing industries include [[David Mellor (cutler)|David Mellor]]'s [[cutlery]] factory in [[Hathersage]], [[Ferodo]] [[brake lining]]s in [[Chapel-en-le-Frith]] and [[Electronics|electronic equipment]] in Castleton. Of the approximately 2,700 farms in the national park, most covering less than {{convert|40|ha|acre}}, 60% of farms are run on a part-time basis where the farmer has a second job.<ref name=\"Waugh\" /> {{Clear}}\n\n==Tourism==\n''De Mirabilibus Pecci'' or ''The Seven Wonders of the Peak'' by [[Thomas Hobbes]] was an early tourist description published in 1636.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bl.uk/learning/langlit/texts/tourists/de/darbyshire.html |title=1678 \u2013 De Mirabilibus Pecci \u2013 Being the Wonders of the Peak in Darby-shire |publisher=[[British Library]] |accessdate=22 May 2009}}</ref> Much scorn was poured on the seven wonders by visitors, including [[Daniel Defoe]] who described the moors by [[Chatsworth, Derbyshire|Chatsworth]] as \"a waste and houling wilderness\" and was particularly contemptuous of [[Peak Cavern]] near Castleton which was known as the 'Devil's Arse'.<ref>{{cite book |title=A tour thro' the whole island of Great Britain, divided into circuits or journies |last=Defoe |first=D. |authorlink=Daniel Defoe |year=1927 |publisher=[[J. M. Dent]] |location=London |url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/text/chap_page.jsp?t_id=Defoe&c_id=30 |accessdate=22 May 2009}}</ref> Visitor numbers did not increase until the [[Victorian era]] when the advent of railways provided access and a cultural appreciation of the [[Picturesque]] and [[Romanticism|Romantic]] developed. [[John Mawe]]'s ''Mineralogy of Derbyshire'' (1802)<ref>{{cite book |title=The Mineralogy of Derbyshire |last=Mawe |first=J. |authorlink=John Mawe |year=1802 |publisher=William Phillips |location=London |url=http://www2.odl.ox.ac.uk/gsdl/cgi-bin/library?e=d&a=d&c=munahi10&cl=CL1.3&d=munahi010-abp |accessdate=22 May 2009}}</ref> and William Adam's ''Gem of the Peak'' (1843)<ref>{{cite book |title=Gem of the Peak or Matlock Bath and its vicinity |last=Adam |first=W. |year=1843 |publisher=[[Longman]] |location=London |url=https://books.google.com/?id=qAEHAAAAQAAJ&dq=Matlock+Bath+and+its+Vicinity&printsec=frontcover#PPR1,M1 |accessdate=22 May 2009}}</ref> generated interest in the area's unique geology.\n\nA tradition of public access and outdoor recreation grew in the area which is  natural hinterland and rural escape for the populations of industrial Manchester and Sheffield, and remains a valuable leisure resource in a largely [[post-industrial economy]]. In a 2005 survey of visitors, 85% of respondents mentioned \"scenery and landscape\" as a reason for visiting.<ref>[http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/microsites/sopr/landscape/landscape-character \"Landscape Character\"] Peak District National Park, retrieved 20 August 2015</ref>\n\n===Buxton===\n[[File:Buxtoncres1.jpg|thumb|left|Buxton Crescent and St Ann's Well]]\nBuxton developed as a spa town because of its geothermal spring which rises at a constant temperature of 28&nbsp;\u00b0C. It was settled by the Romans around AD 78, when it was known as Aquae Arnemetiae, or the spa of the goddess of the grove. [[Bess of Hardwick]] and her husband the [[George Talbot, 6th Earl of Shrewsbury|Earl of Shrewsbury]], \"took the waters\" in 1569, and brought [[Mary, Queen of Scots]], there in 1573.<ref name=\"Buxton06\">{{cite web |url=http://quest.bris.ac.uk/workshops/annual06/Buxton.pdf |title=Things to do in Buxton |publisher=Quantifying and Understanding the Earth System |accessdate=28 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110825112931/http://quest.bris.ac.uk/workshops/annual06/Buxton.pdf |archivedate=25 August 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The town largely grew in importance in the late 18th century when it was developed by the [[Duke of Devonshire|5th Duke of Devonshire]] in style of the spa of [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]].\n\nA resurgence in the 18th century attracted [[Erasmus Darwin|Dr Erasmus Darwin]] and [[Josiah Wedgwood]],<ref>{{cite book |title=The correspondence of Charles Darwin |last=Darwin |first=C. |authorlink=Charles Darwin |year=1985 |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |location=Cambridge |url=https://books.google.com/?id=ao2I3-8PXBgC&pg=PA265&lpg=PA265&dq=levett+darwin |accessdate=28 June 2009|isbn=9780521824132 }}</ref> who were drawn by the reputed healing properties of the waters. The railway reached Buxton in 1863.<ref>{{cite book |title=Railways of the Peak District |last1=Blakemore |first1=B. |last2=Mosley|first2=D. |year=2003 |isbn=1-902827-09-0 |publisher=Great Northern Books}}</ref>\nBuxton's notable buildings are The Crescent (1780\u20131784), modelled on Bath's [[Royal Crescent]], by [[John Carr (architect)|John Carr]], The Devonshire (1780\u20131789), The Natural Baths, and The Pump Room by [[Henry Currey (architect)|Henry Currey]]. The [[Buxton Pavilion Gardens|Pavilion Gardens]] were opened in 1871.<ref name=\"Buxton06\" /> [[Buxton Opera House]] was designed by [[Frank Matcham]] in 1903.\n\n=== Historic buildings ===\nHistoric buildings in the park include [[Chatsworth House]], seat of the Dukes of Devonshire and among Britain's finest stately homes; the medieval [[Haddon Hall]], seat of the [[Duke of Rutland|Dukes of Rutland]]; and [[Lyme Park]], an Elizabethan manor house transformed by an [[Italianate architecture|Italianate]] front. Other historic buildings in the park include [[Eyam Hall]], [[Ilam Park|Ilam Hall]] and [[Tissington Hall]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Halls in the Peak District |url=http://www.peakdistrictonline.co.uk/peak-district-halls-c101023.html |website=Peak District Online |publisher=Peak District Online |accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref> Many villages and towns have fine parish churches, including the 14th-century [[St John the Baptist, Tideswell|Church of St John the Baptist]] at Tideswell, sometimes dubbed the 'Cathedral of the Peak', and the 12th-century [[Church of St Nicholas, Bradfield|Church of St Nicholas]] at [[High Bradfield]]. '[[Little John]]'s Grave' is in the churchyard at [[Hathersage]]. [[Peveril Castle]], overlooking Castleton, was built by the [[Normans]].<ref name=\"Peak District Attractions\">{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrictonline.co.uk/peak-district-attractions-c1736.html|title=Peak District Attractions|publisher=Peak District Online |accessdate=28 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Museums and attractions ===\nInside the park, [[Eyam Museum]] has displays about the village's history during the [[Black Death in England|Black Death]].<ref name=\"Eyam Museum and Plague Village\">{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrictinformation.com/visits/eyammus.php|title=Eyam Museum and Plague Village|publisher=Peak District Information|accessdate=14 September 2017}}</ref> Castleton has four show caves; [[Peak Cavern]], [[Blue John Cavern|Blue John]], [[Treak Cliff Cavern|Treak Cliff]] and [[Speedwell Cavern|Speedwell]]. In the outer fringes, the area's industrial heritage is represented by the [[Peak District Mining Museum|mining museum]] at Matlock Bath with the Temple Lead Mine, the [[Derwent Valley Mills]] [[World Heritage Site]] and [[Brindley Water Mill]] at Leek. Preserved railways such as the [[Peak Rail]], [[Ecclesbourne Valley Railway|Ecclesbourne Valley]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Exploring Duffield & Wirksworth on the Ecclesbourne Valley Line, Derbyshire |url=https://www.derbyshirelife.co.uk/out-about/places/exploring-duffield-wirksworth-on-the-ecclesbourne-valley-line-derbyshire-1-1645078 |website=Derbyshire Life and Countryside |publisher=Derbyshire Life and Countryside |accessdate=23 August 2018}}</ref> and [[Churnet Valley Railway|Churnet Valley]]<ref>{{cite web |title=History of the CVR \u2013 LMS & BR Days \u2013 History of the Churnet Valley Line |url=https://www.churnetvalleyrailway.co.uk/lmsbr |website=Churnet Valley Railway |publisher=Churnet Valley Railway |accessdate=23 August 2018}}</ref> lines, the [[National Tramway Museum]] at [[Crich]] and the [[Cromford Canal]] chart the area's transport history. Matlock Bath also has the show caves and mines of the [[Heights of Abraham]] which can be reached by cable car, and the [[Gulliver's Kingdom]] theme park.<ref name=\"Peak District Attractions\"/> Buxton has an opera house and theatre, museum and art gallery and [[Poole's Cavern]] show cave.<ref name=\"Visit Buxton\"/> Other attractions in the fringes include the [[Alton Towers]] theme park<ref name=\"Peak District Attractions\"/> and the [[Peak Wildlife Park]].\n[[Image:Welldressing Hayfield.jpg|thumb|200px|A [[well dressing]] at Hayfield]]\n[[Well dressing]] ceremonies are held in many villages during the spring and summer months, a tradition said to date from pagan times.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.welldressing.com/extra.php |title=More about Well Dressings |publisher=WellDressing.com |accessdate=18 June 2009}}</ref> Other local customs include [[Castleton Garland Day]] and Ashbourne's [[Royal Shrovetide Football]], played annually since the 12th century. Buxton hosts two opera festivals, the [[Buxton Festival]] and the [[International Gilbert and Sullivan Festival]], and the Buxton Festival Fringe, and the [[Peak Literary Festival]] is held at various locations twice a year. Peak District food specialities include the dessert [[Bakewell pudding]], very different from the nationally available [[Bakewell tart]], and until 2009 the famous cheese [[Stilton (cheese)|Stilton]] and other local cheeses were produced in the village of [[Hartington, Derbyshire|Hartington]].\n\n===Activities===\n[[Image:Mamtor-paragliding.jpg|thumb|right|[[Paragliding]] from Mam Tor]]\nAn extensive network of public footpaths and numerous long-distance trails, over {{convert|1800|mi|km|-2}} in total,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peakdistrict-nationalpark.info/studyArea/factsheets/02.html#problems |title=Peak District National Park: Study Area |publisher=Peak District National Park |accessdate=22 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20050331060949/http://www.peakdistrict-nationalpark.info/studyArea/factsheets/02.html |archivedate=31 March 2005 }}</ref> and large open-access areas are available for hillwalking and hiking.  The [[Pennine Way]] traverses the Dark Peak from Edale to the park's northern boundary just south of [[Standedge]]. [[Bridlepath|Bridleways]] are used by [[mountain biking|mountain bikers]], as well as horse riders. The [[Tissington Trail]] and [[High Peak Trail]], which re-use former railway lines, are well used by walkers, horse riders and cyclists.<ref name=\"Tissington_Trail\" /> The [[Peak District Boundary Walk]] is a circular {{convert|190|mi|adj=on}} walking trail around the national park.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.friendsofthepeak.org.uk/boundary-walk/|title=Boundary Walk|date=2017-10-12|website=Friends of the Peak District|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\nSections of the former rail routes were converted to multi-purpose cycle trails. After the Woodhead Line was closed between [[Hadfield, Derbyshire|Hadfield]] and [[Penistone]] part of the trackbed was used for the [[Longdendale Trail]] section of the [[Trans Pennine Trail]] between Hadfield and [[Woodhead, Derbyshire|Woodhead]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.derbyshire-peakdistrict.co.uk/glossopandlongdendale.htm |title=Glossop/Longdendale Walk |publisher=Discover Derbyshire and the Peak District |accessdate=1 July 2009}}</ref> The Manchester, Buxton, Matlock and Midlands Junction Railway between [[Rowsley]] and Buxton is part of the [[Monsal Trail]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.derbyshire-peakdistrict.co.uk/monsaltrail.htm |title=Monsal Trail |publisher=Discover Derbyshire and the Peak District |accessdate=1 July 2009}}</ref> The trackbed of the Cromford and High Peak Railway is open to the public as the High Peak Trail.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.derbyshire-peakdistrict.co.uk/thehighpeaktrail.htm |title=The High Peak Trail |publisher=Discover Derbyshire and the Peak District |accessdate=1 July 2009}}</ref> The Tissington Trail uses another disused rail line between Buxton and Ashbourne<ref name=\"Tissington_Trail\">{{cite web |url=http://www.derbyshire-peakdistrict.co.uk/tissingtontrail.htm |title=Tissington Trail |publisher=Discover Derbyshire and the Peak District |accessdate=1 July 2009}}</ref> while the [[Manifold Way]] utilises the [[Leek and Manifold Valley Light Railway|former line]] between [[Waterhouses, Staffordshire|Waterhouses]] and [[Hulme End]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Manifold Way |url=https://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/visiting/miles-without-stiles/manifold-way |website=Peak District National Park |publisher=Peak District National Park |accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nLocal authorities run cycle hire centres at Ashbourne, [[Parsley Hay]], [[Middleton-by-Wirksworth|Middleton Top]], the [[Upper Derwent Valley]] and Hulme End.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ohire.co.uk/companies/middleton-top-cycle-hire |title=Middleton Top Cycle hire |date= |accessdate=22 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/visiting/cycle |title=Cycling |publisher=Peak District National Park |date= |accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Manifold Cycle Hire |url=https://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/visiting/cycle/cycle-hire-centres/manifold |website=Peak District National Park |publisher=Peak District National Park |accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref> Wheelchair access is possible at several places on the former railway trails, and cycle hire centres offer vehicles adapted to wheelchair users.<ref name=\"Tissington_Trail\" /> A project to make footpaths more accessible to less-agile walkers has replaced stiles with gates.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.roachescottages.co.uk/activities.htm |title=Local Activities in & around the Peak District National Park |publisher=Roaches Holiday Cottages |accessdate=22 June 2009}}</ref>\n\nGritstone outcrops at Stanage Edge and The Roaches, are recognised as some of the finest [[rock climbing]] sites in the world.<ref name=\"Trekking\">{{cite web |url=http://www.trekking-world.com/regional/england/peak-district |title=Peak District |publisher=Trekking World |accessdate=22 June 2009}}</ref> Limestone is more unstable but provides many testing climbs. [[Thor's Cave]] was explored in the early 1950s by [[Joe Brown (climber)|Joe Brown]] and others. Eleven limestone routes there are listed by the [[British Mountaineering Council|BMC]], ranging in [[Grade (climbing)|grade]] from Very Severe to E7, and several more have been claimed since the guidebook's publication; a few routes are bolted.<ref>{{cite book |title=Rock Climbs in the Peak District: Peak Limestone: South |last=Milburn |first=G. |year=1987 |isbn=0-903908-26-3 |publisher=[[British Mountaineering Council]]}}</ref>\n\n[[Caving]] takes place in the natural caves, potholes and old mine workings found in the limestone of the White Peak. Peak Cavern, the largest and most important cave system, is even linked to the [[Speedwell Cavern|Speedwell]] system at Winnats. The largest potholes are Eldon Hole and Nettle Pot. Many old mine workings were often extensions of natural cave systems. They can be found at Castleton, Winnats, Matlock, [[Stoney Middleton]], Eyam, [[Monyash]] and Buxton.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cressbrook.co.uk/outdoors/potholing.php |title=Pot holing |work=Peak District Information |publisher=Cressbrook Multimedia |year=2008 |accessdate=30 June 2009}}</ref>\n\nReservoirs such as [[Torside Reservoir]], [[Damflask Reservoir]], [[Carsington Water]] and [[Rudyard Lake]] are centres for [[List of water sports|water sports]], including sailing, fishing and [[canoeing]]. Other activities include air sports such as [[hang gliding]] and [[paragliding]], [[birdwatching]], [[fell running]], [[off-roading]], and [[orienteering]].<ref name=\"Trekking\" />\n\n==Transport==\n[[File:Peak District National Park tunnels.svg|thumb|upright|Map showing tunnels beneath the Peak District]]\n\nThe first roads constructed by the [[Roman Britain|Romans]] may have followed existing tracks. The Roman network  linked the settlements and forts of Aquae Arnemetiae (Buxton), [[Chesterfield]], [[Ardotalia]] (Glossop) and Navio ([[Brough and Shatton]]), and beyond.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.roman-britain.org/maps/settlement_intro.htm |title=The Romano-British Settlements |publisher=RomanBritain.org |date=10 September 2010 |accessdate=26 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100928060305/http://www.roman-britain.org/maps/settlement_intro.htm |archivedate=28 September 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Parts of the modern [[A515 road|A515]] and [[A53 road|A53]] roads south of Buxton are believed to follow the routes of Roman roads.\n\n[[Packhorse]] routes criss-crossed the Peak in the Medieval era, and some paved causeways such as the Long Causeway along [[Stanage Edge]] date from this period.  No highways were marked on [[Christopher Saxton]]'s 1579 map of Derbyshire.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peakscan.freeuk.com/routes___stoops___peak_district.htm |title=Peak District Routes, Stoops, Pack Horse Ways, Turnpikes |publisher=Peakscan |year=2008 |accessdate=22 May 2009}}</ref> Bridge-building improved the transport network.\n\nAlthough the introduction of [[Toll road|turnpike roads]] from 1731<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peakdistrict-education.gov.uk/Fact%20Sheets/fz21lgd1.htm |title=Longendale in the Peak National Park |publisher=PDNP Education |year=2000 |accessdate=22 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060104204530/http://www.peakdistrict-education.gov.uk/Fact%20Sheets/fz21lgd1.htm |archivedate=4 January 2006 }}</ref> reduced journey times, the journey from Sheffield to Manchester in 1800 still took 16 hours prompting [[Samuel Taylor Coleridge]] to remark that \"a tortoise could outgallop us!\"<ref name=\"Stainforth\">{{cite book |title=The Peak: Past and Present |last=Stainforth |first=G. |year=1998 |isbn=0-09-475420-9 |publisher=[[Constable & Robinson|Constable]]}}</ref> From around 1815, better quality turnpike roads were built. The [[Snake Pass]], part of the [[A57 road|A57]], was built under the direction of [[Thomas Telford]] in 1819\u201321.<ref name=\"Stainforth\" /> \n\nThe main roads are the A57 between Sheffield and Manchester, the [[A628 road|A628]], Woodhead Pass, between [[Barnsley]] and Manchester via Longdendale, the [[A6 road (England)|A6]] from Derby to Manchester via Buxton, the [[Cat and Fiddle Road]] from Macclesfield to Buxton, and in the north, the [[A635 road|A635]] from Manchester to Barnsley. Roads and lanes are frequently congested and the availability of parking spaces in towns and villages is a significant problem, especially during summer. A congestion charge was proposed in 2005, but was rejected.<ref>{{cite news |last=Giannangeli |first=M. |title=Peak District may be first national park to impose a congestion charge |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1504735/Peak-District-may-be-first-national-park-to-impose-a-congestion-charge.html |work=The Daily Telegraph  |date=5 December 2005 |accessdate=23 May 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Cromford Canal]] opened in 1794, to carry coal, lead and iron ore to the [[Erewash Canal]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.derbyshire-peakdistrict.co.uk/cromfordcanal.htm |title=Cromford Canal |publisher=Discover Derbyshire and the Peak District |accessdate=1 July 2009}}</ref> it was abandoned in 1944. The canal turnpike roads had to compete with railways after 1825.<ref name=\"Stainforth\" /> The first railway, the [[Cromford and High Peak Railway]] from [[High Peak Junction]] to [[Whaley Bridge]], was an industrial line, but passenger services  followed, including the [[Woodhead Line]] (Sheffield to Manchester via Longdendale) and the [[Manchester, Buxton, Matlock and Midlands Junction Railway]]. Several rail lines were closed in the 1960s as a result of the [[Beeching Axe]]. \n\n===Public transport===\n[[Image:Totley Tunnel western portal.jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Totley Tunnel]] on the Manchester to Sheffield line]]\nThe Peak District is accessible by public transport. Train services operate along the [[Hope Valley line]] between Sheffield and Manchester, the [[Derwent Valley line]] between Derby and [[Matlock, Derbyshire|Matlock]], the [[Buxton line|Buxton]] and [[Glossop line|Glossop]] lines, linking them to Manchester, and the [[Huddersfield line]] from Manchester to Huddersfield.<ref name=\"Public Transport \u2013 Peak District National Park Authority\">{{cite web|url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/visiting/publictransport |title=Public Transport \u2013 Peak District National Park Authority |publisher=Peak District |year=2012 |accessdate=3 April 2012}}</ref> Coach services provide access to Matlock, Bakewell and Buxton from Derby, [[Nottingham]] and Manchester through [[High Peak (bus company)|TransPeak]] and [[National Express Coaches|National Express]], and there are regular buses from Sheffield, Glossop, Stoke, [[Leek, Staffordshire|Leek]] and Chesterfield. The nearest airports are [[Manchester Airport|Manchester]], [[Doncaster Sheffield Airport|Doncaster Sheffield]], and [[East Midlands Airport|East Midlands]].<ref name=\"Public Transport \u2013 Peak District National Park Authority\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.essentialtravelguide.com/regional-guides/midlands/peak-district-travel-guide/peak-district-facts/|title=Peak District Quick Facts & Figures|publisher=Essential Travel Guide|accessdate=15 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn rural areas, villages are served by internal transport links. Minibuses operate from the towns to smaller villages. The Hope Valley and Buxton Line trains serve stations at  Hathersage, Hope and Edale.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.derbyshire-peakdistrict.co.uk/publictransportII.htm |title=Public Transport in Derbyshire and the Peak District |publisher=Discover Derbyshire and the Peak District |year=2009 |accessdate=22 June 2009}}</ref>\n\nCycle England invested \u00a31.25&nbsp;million to build and improve cycle routes in the national park for leisure and commuting.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/index/news/news-display-page.htm?id=20324 |title=Pedal power to help residents and visitors lead more active lifestyles \u2013 Peak District National Park Authority |publisher=Peak District |date=7 October 2009 |accessdate=16 October 2009|archivedate=7 July 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707225811/http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/index/news/news-display-page.htm?id=20324 }}</ref> \n\n==Conservation issues==\n[[Image:Derwent walkers.jpg|thumb|right|Walkers above the [[Derwent Reservoir (Derbyshire)|Derwent Reservoir]]]]\nThe proximity of the Peak to major conurbations and urban areas (an estimated 20 million people live within an hour's drive)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bygonederbyshire.co.uk/places/Peak-District-National-Park/article-1772758-detail/article.html |title=Peak District National Park |publisher=ByGoneDerbyshire.co.uk |date=28 January 2010 |accessdate=26 September 2010}}</ref> poses challenges for managing the area. The park authority, the National Trust and other landowners attempt to keep the upland landscape accessible for recreation while protecting it from intensive farming, [[erosion]] and pressure from visitors. Tension exists between the needs of the 38,000 residents,<ref name=\"Place_called_home\" /> the needs of the millions of people who visit,<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite news |last=Moss |first=C. |title=Oops, there goes another bit of Britain |url=https://www.theguardian.com/travel/2004/feb/28/unitedkingdom.guardiansaturdaytravelsection |work=The Guardian  |date=28 February 2004 |accessdate=22 May 2009}}</ref> and conservation requirements.\n\nThe uneven distribution of visitors creates stresses. Dovedale alone receives about two million visitors annually.<ref name=\"South_Peak\" /> Other highly visited areas include Bakewell, Castleton and the [[Hope Valley, Derbyshire|Hope Valley]], Chatsworth, Hartington and the reservoirs of the Upper Derwent Valley.<ref name=\"Tourism_factsheet\">{{cite web|url=http://www.peakdistrict-nationalpark.info/studyArea/factsheets/02.html#whoVisits |title=Tourism in the Peak District National Park |publisher=Peak District National Park |year=2003 |accessdate=22 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20050331060949/http://www.peakdistrict-nationalpark.info/studyArea/factsheets/02.html |archivedate=31 March 2005 }}</ref> More than 60% of visits take place between May and September, with Sunday the busiest day.<ref name=\"Tourism_factsheet\" />\n\nFootpath users in the more popular walking areas have contributed to serious erosion problems, particularly on the fragile [[peat]] moorlands. The use of some paths by mountain bikers is believed to have exacerbated the problem.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peakdistrict-nationalpark.info/studyArea/factsheets/14.html#7 |title=Peak District National Park: Study Area \u2013 Footpath Erosion |publisher=Peak District National Park |accessdate=22 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20050901152656/http://www.peakdistrict-nationalpark.info/studyArea/factsheets/14.html |archivedate=1 September 2005 }}</ref> Measures to contain the damage include the diversion of the official route of the Pennine Way out of Edale, which now goes via Jacob's Ladder rather than following the Grindsbrook, and surfacing moorland footpaths with expensive natural stone paving.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peakdistrict-nationalpark.info/studyArea/factsheets/14.html#9 |title=Peak District National Park: Study Area \u2013 The Pennine Way |publisher=Peak District National Park |accessdate=22 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20050901152656/http://www.peakdistrict-nationalpark.info/studyArea/factsheets/14.html |archivedate=1 September 2005 }}</ref> Some rights of way have been damaged by legal and illegal use by off-road vehicles such as [[Four-wheel drive|4\u00d74s]] and [[trail bike]]s. Campaigners have sought to reduce their impact.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.friendsofthepeak.org.uk/campaigns/take-back-the-tracks/ |title=Take back the tracks |publisher=Friends of the Peak District |date= |accessdate=14 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nLarge-scale limestone quarrying is contentious. Most mineral extraction licences were issued by national government for 90 years in the 1950s and remain legally binding. The park authority has a policy of considering applications for new quarries and licence renewal in the park in terms of the local and national need for the mineral and how unique the source is, in conjunction with the effects on traffic,  residents and the environment.<ref name=\"Mineral_factsheet\" /> Some licences have not been renewed; the RMC Aggregates quarry at [[Eldon Hill]] closed in 1999 and landscaped.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/bap-report2002.pdf |title=Peak District Biodiversity Action Plan |publisher=Peak District |date= October 2002 |accessdate=13 November 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720111424/http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/bap-report2002.pdf|archivedate=20 July 2011}}</ref> Proposals from Stancliffe Stone Ltd to re-open dormant gritstone quarries at Stanton Moor in 1999 became a test case, hotly contested by ecological protesters and residents on the grounds that the development would threaten Bronze Age remains at the Nine Ladies Stone Circle, and damage the natural landscape.<ref name=\"Guardian\" /> In 2007, negotiations took place to relocate the development to Dale View quarry in a less sensitive area.<ref>{{cite news |title=End in sight for quarry wrangle on historic moor |url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/index/news/news-display-page.htm?id=14775 |work=Peak District |date=5 September 2007 |accessdate=12 September 2007|archivedate=20 July 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720112449/http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/index/news/news-display-page.htm?id=14775 }}</ref>\n\n==Peak District in literature and arts==\nThe landscapes of the Peak have inspired writers for centuries. Various places have been identified by Ralph Elliott and others as locations in the 14th-century poem ''[[Sir Gawain and the Green Knight]]''; [[Lud's Church]] is thought to be the [[Green Chapel]].<ref>{{cite book |title=A Companion to the Gawain-Poet |last1=Elliott |first1=R. W. V. |last2=Brewer |first2=Derek |authorlink2=Derek Brewer |last3=Gibson |first3=J. |chapter=Landscape and Geography |year=1999 |isbn=0-85991-529-8 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/companiontogawai0000unse/page/105 105\u2013117] |publisher=[[Derek Brewer|Brewer D. S]] |chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/companiontogawai0000unse/page/105 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Chatsworth showing hunting tower.jpg|thumb|left|[[Chatsworth House]], the setting for a recent adaptation of ''[[Pride and Prejudice]]'']]\nKey scenes in [[Jane Austen]]'s 1813 novel ''[[Pride and Prejudice]]'' are set in the Peak.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gutenberg.org/etext/1342 |title=Pride and Prejudice by Jane Austen |publisher=Project Gutenberg |year=2003 |accessdate=13 September 2007}}</ref>\n''[[Peveril of the Peak]]'' (1823) by [[Walter Scott|Sir Walter Scott]] is a historical novel set at Peveril Castle, Castleton during the reign of [[Charles II of England|Charles II]].<ref>{{PastScape |mnumber=309632 |mname=Peveril Castle |year=2007 |accessdate=12 September 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=The Cambridge Guide to Literature in English |last=Ousby |first=I. |editor=Ousby I |year=1993 |edition=2nd |isbn=0-521-44086-6 |page=[https://archive.org/details/cambridgeguideto00iano_0/page/734 734] |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |url=https://archive.org/details/cambridgeguideto00iano_0/page/734 }}</ref> [[William Wordsworth]] was a frequent visitor to Matlock; the Peak inspired several of his poems, including an 1830 [[sonnet]] to Chatsworth House.<ref name=\"Peak_Experience\">{{cite web |url=http://www.peak-experience.org.uk/tourism/explore-the-guides/peak-experience-guides/peak-film-literature/ |title=Peak Film & Literature |publisher=Peak Experience |accessdate=12 September 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070905105904/http://www.peak-experience.org.uk/tourism/explore-the-guides/peak-experience-guides/peak-film-literature/ |archivedate=5 September 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The village of [[Morton, Derbyshire|Morton]] in [[Charlotte Bront\u00eb]]'s 1847 novel ''[[Jane Eyre]]'' is based on Hathersage, where Bront\u00eb stayed in 1845, and [[Thornfield Hall]] might have been inspired by nearby North Lees Hall.<ref>{{cite book |title=Jane Eyre |last=Bront\u00eb |first=C. |authorlink=Charlotte Bront\u00eb |year=1996 |isbn=0-14-043400-3 |page=[https://archive.org/details/janeeyre00bron_1/page/526 526] |publisher=[[Penguin Books]] |url=https://archive.org/details/janeeyre00bron_1/page/526 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=The Bront\u00ebs |last=Barker |first=J. |authorlink=Juliet Barker |year=1995 |isbn=1-85799-069-2 |pages=451\u2013453 |publisher=[[Weidenfeld & Nicolson]]}}</ref> Snowfield in [[George Eliot]]'s first novel ''[[Adam Bede]]'' (1859) is believed to be based on Wirksworth, where her uncle managed a mill; [[Ellastone]] (as Hayslope) and [[Ashbourne, Derbyshire|Ashbourne]] (as Oakbourne) also feature.<ref name=\"Peak_Experience\" />\n\n[[Beatrix Potter]], the author of [[Peter Rabbit]], visited her uncle [[Edmund Potter]] at his printworks in [[Dinting Vale]]. She copied cloth samples from his pattern book to dress her characters. Mrs Tiggywinkle's shawl, in [[The Tale of Mrs. Tiggy-Winkle]], is based on pattern number 222714.<ref>{{cite web |last=Potter |first=E. |authorlink=Edmund Potter |title=Dinting Vale Printworks cotton sample pattern book |url=http://www.spinningtheweb.org.uk/sea_cat_display.php?irn=3004030&sub=&theme=overview&crumb= |work=Spinning the Web |publisher=[[Manchester City Council]] |year=1892 |accessdate=28 June 2009}}</ref>\n\nChildren's author [[Alison Uttley]] (1884\u20131976) was born at [[Cromford]]; her novel ''A Traveller in Time'', set in [[Dethick, Lea and Holloway|Dethick]], recounts the [[Babington Plot]] to free [[Mary, Queen of Scots]], from imprisonment.<ref name=\"Peakland_Heritage\">{{cite web |url=http://www.peaklandheritage.org.uk/index.asp?peakkey=40600721 |title=Peakland Writers |publisher=Peakland Heritage |year=2008 |accessdate=12 September 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071107175202/http://www.peaklandheritage.org.uk/index.asp?peakkey=40600721 |archivedate=7 November 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Crichton Porteous]] (1901\u201391) set several books in locations in the Peak; ''Toad Hole'', ''Lucky Columbell'' and ''Broken River'' are set in the [[Upper Derwent Valley|Derwent Valley]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aboutderbyshire.co.uk/cms/people/crichton-porteous-derbysh.shtml |title=Crichton Porteous \u2013 Derbyshire Writer |publisher=About Derbyshire |date=3 June 2007 |accessdate=12 September 2007}}</ref> [[Geraldine Brooks (writer)|Geraldine Brooks]]'s first novel, ''[[Year of Wonders]]'' (2001), blends fact and fiction to tell the story of the plague village of Eyam.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://geraldinebrooks.com/the-books/year-of-wonders/|title=Year of Wonders |publisher=GeraldineBrooks.com |year=2007 |accessdate=13 November 2013}}</ref> Eyam also inspired ''Children of Winter'' by children's novelist [[Berlie Doherty]] who has set several other works in the Peak, including ''Deep Secret'', based on the drowning of the villages of [[Derwent, Derbyshire|Derwent]] and [[Ashopton]] by the Ladybower Reservoir, and ''Blue John'', inspired by the cavern at Castleton.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.berliedoherty.com/novelsf.html |title=Berlie Doherty: novels |publisher=BerlieDoherty.com |year=2003 |accessdate=12 September 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070802221528/http://www.berliedoherty.com/novelsf.html |archivedate=2 August 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref>{{Clear}}\n \n[[File:Ladybower.jpg|thumb|right|[[Ladybower Reservoir]] in the Upper Derwent Valley, set location for ''[[The Dam Busters (film)|The Dam Busters]]'']]Many works of crime and horror have been set in the Peak. ''[[The Terror of Blue John Gap]]'' by [[Arthur Conan Doyle|Sir Arthur Conan Doyle]] (1859\u20131930) recounts terrible events at the Blue John mines,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gutenberg.org/etext/537 |title=Tales of Terror and Mystery by Sir Arthur Conan Doyle |publisher=Gutenberg |year=2008 |accessdate=13 September 2007}}</ref> and [[Sherlock Holmes]] investigates the kidnapping of a child in ''[[The Adventure of the Priory School]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ignisart.com/camdenhouse/canon/prio.htm |title=The Adventure of the Priory School |publisher=Camden House \u2013 The Complete Sherlock Holmes |year=1998 |accessdate=13 September 2007}}</ref> Many horror stories by local author [[Robert Murray Gilchrist]] feature Peak settings.<ref name=\"Peak_Experience\" /> [[Stephen Booth (writer)|Stephen Booth]] has written a series of crime novels set in real and imagined Peak locations,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stephen-booth.com/New%20books.htm |title=Stephen Booth \u2013 New Books |publisher=StephenBooth.com |accessdate=12 September 2007}}</ref> while ''In Pursuit of the Proper Sinner'', an [[The Inspector Lynley Mysteries|Inspector Lynley mystery]] by [[Elizabeth George]], is set on the fictional Calder Moor.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.elizabethgeorgeonline.com/books/in_pursuit_of_sinner.htm |title=Novel \u2013 In Pursuit of the Proper Sinner |publisher=Elizabeth George Online |accessdate=12 September 2007}}</ref>\n\nOther writers and poets who lived in or visited the Peak include [[Samuel Johnson]], [[William Congreve]], [[Anna Seward]], [[Jean-Jacques Rousseau]], [[George Gordon Byron, 6th Baron Byron|Lord Byron]], [[Thomas Moore]], [[Richard Furness]], [[D. H. Lawrence]], [[Vera Brittain]], [[Richmal Crompton]] and [[Nathaniel Gould|Nat Gould]].<ref name=\"Peak_Experience\" /><ref name=\"Peakland_Heritage\" /> The landscapes and historic houses are popular settings for film and television. The classic 1955 film ''[[The Dam Busters (film)|The Dam Busters]]'' was filmed at the Upper [[Derwent Reservoir (Derbyshire)|Derwent Valley reservoirs]], where practice flights for the bombing raids on the [[Ruhr (river)|Ruhr]] dams had been made during the Second World War.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0046889/locations |title=Filming locations for The Dam Busters |website=[[Internet Movie Database]] |year=1990 |accessdate=13 September 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn adaptations of ''Pride and Prejudice'', [[Longnor, Staffordshire|Longnor]] has featured as Lambton, and Lyme Park and Chatsworth House have stood in for [[Pemberley]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0112130/locations |title=Filming locations for Pride and Prejudice (1995) |website=[[Internet Movie Database]] |year=1995 |accessdate=12 September 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0414387/locations |title=Filming locations for Pride and Prejudice (2005) |website=[[Internet Movie Database]] |year=2005 |accessdate=12 September 2007}}</ref> Haddon Hall doubled as [[Thornfield Hall]] in two different adaptations of ''Jane Eyre'' and has appeared in several films including ''[[Elizabeth (film)|Elizabeth]]'', ''[[The Princess Bride (film)|The Princess Bride]]'' and ''[[The Other Boleyn Girl (2008 film)|The Other Boleyn Girl]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.haddonhall.co.uk/film.htm |title=Film & Photoshoots |publisher=Haddon Hall |accessdate=22 June 2009}}</ref> The television medical drama ''[[Peak Practice]]'' set in the fictional village of Cardale was filmed in [[Crich]], Matlock and other Peak locations.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0106097/locations |title=Filming locations for Peak Practice |website=[[Internet Movie Database]] |year=1993 |accessdate=12 September 2007}}</ref> The world's longest-running sitcom, ''[[Last of the Summer Wine]]'', was filmed in [[Holmfirth]] and the surrounding [[Holme Valley]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Last of the Summer Wine country, Holmfirth, West Yorkshire |url=https://www.theguardian.com/travel/2009/jun/07/summer-wine-walking-guide-holmfirth |newspaper=The Guardian  |date=7 June 2009|accessdate=2 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Cheshire}}\n*[[Derbyshire moors]]\n*[[List of hills in the Peak District]]\n*[[Forest of High Peak]], a royal hunting reserve in medieval times in the area\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Peak District}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Peak District}}\n<!-- ==============================({{NoMoreLinks}})============================== -->\n<!-- DO NOT ADD MORE LINKS TO THIS ARTICLE. WIKIPEDIA IS NOT A COLLECTION OF LINKS -->\n<!-- If you think that your link might be useful,  instead of placing it here, put -->\n<!-- it on this article's discussion page first. Links that have not been verified -->\n<!--                                WILL BE DELETED                                -->\n<!-- ============================================================================= -->\n*[http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/ Official website of the Peak District National Park Authority]\n*[http://peakdistrict.nationaltrust.org.uk/ Peak District] at [[The National Trust]]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060828212309/http://bgs.ac.uk/foundation-web/Foundation_Home.html Foundations of the Peak] \u2013 geological information at [[British Geological Survey]]\n*[https://www.visitpeakdistrict.com/ Visit Peak District & Derbyshire] official Tourist information\n\n{{National_parks_in_the_UK}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Peak District| ]]\n[[Category:Climbing areas of England]]\n[[Category:Geography of Cheshire]]\n[[Category:Geography of Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Geography of Greater Manchester]]\n[[Category:Geology of Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Geography of Staffordshire]]\n[[Category:National parks in England]]\n[[Category:Parks and open spaces in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Protected areas established in 1951]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Upland area in England}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox protected area\n| name = Peak District National Park\n| alt_name = \"The Peak\"\n| iucn_category = V\n| photo = Mam Tor.jpg\n| photo_alt = A view of grass-covered hillside located within a British National Park\n| photo_caption = A view of [[Mam Tor]], Peak District National Park\n| map_image = Peak District National Park UK location map.svg\n| map_caption = Peak District National Park (shaded green) within England\n| location = [[Derbyshire]]<br>[[Cheshire]]<br>[[Greater Manchester]]<br>[[Staffordshire]]<br>[[South Yorkshire]]<br>[[West Yorkshire]]\n| nearest_city = \n| nearest_town = \n| coords = {{coord|53|21|N|1|50|W|region:GB-ENG_source:dewiki|display=inline,title}}\n| area_sqmi = 555\n| designated = {{start date|1951|4|17|df=yes}}\n| visitation_num = Over 10 million\n| visitation_year =\n| visitation_ref = <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/learning-about/news/mediacentrefacts |title=Peak District Local Government|accessdate= 8 November 2016}}</ref> \n| administrator = [[National park authority]]\n| website = {{URL|https://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/}}\n| url = \n| child = \n| embedded = \n}}\n\nThe '''Peak District''' is an [[Highland|upland]] area in England at the southern end of the [[Pennines]]. It is mostly in northern [[Derbyshire]], but also includes parts of [[Cheshire]], [[Greater Manchester]], [[Staffordshire]], [[West Yorkshire]] and [[South Yorkshire]]. An area of great diversity, it is mostly split into the [[Dark Peak]], where most of the [[moorland]] is found and the geology is [[gritstone]], and the [[limestone]] area of the [[White Peak]].\n\nThe Peak District National Park became the first [[National parks of England and Wales|national park]] in the United Kingdom in 1951.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0009/79227/factsheet4-quarrying.pdf |title=Quarrying and mineral extraction in the Peak District National Park |publisher=Peak District National Park Authority |year=2011 |accessdate=17 April 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120127055057/http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0009/79227/factsheet4-quarrying.pdf |archivedate=27 January 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> With its proximity to the cities of [[Manchester]], [[Stoke-on-Trent]], [[Derby]] and [[Sheffield]], and access by road and rail, it attracts millions of visitors every year.<ref>{{cite book |title=Britain |last=Wheeler |first=T. |editor-last=Else |editor-first=D |year=2003 |edition=5th |isbn=1-74059-338-3 |page=42 |quote=The Peak District alone gets 20 million, making it Britain's most-visited park, and the second-busiest in the world. |publisher=[[Lonely Planet]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/learning-about/news/mediacentrefacts |title=Media Centre Facts and Figures |publisher=Peak District National Park Authority |accessdate=4 March 2014}}</ref> It is estimated that 20 million people live within one hour's journey of the Peak District.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/learning-about/news/mediacentrefacts|title=Media Centre Facts and Figures|website=Peak District National Park}}</ref>\n\nInhabited from the [[Mesolithic]] era, evidence exists from the [[Neolithic]], [[Bronze Age|Bronze]] and [[Iron Age]]s. Settled by the [[Roman Britain|Romans]] and [[Anglo-Saxons]], the area remained largely agricultural and mining grew in importance in the medieval era. [[Richard Arkwright]] built his [[cotton mill]]s at the start of the [[Industrial Revolution]]. Quarrying became important as mining declined. Tourism grew after the advent of the railways, visitors attracted by the landscape, [[spa town]]s at [[Buxton]] and [[Matlock Bath]], [[Castleton, Derbyshire|Castleton]]'s show caves, and [[Bakewell]], the national park's only town. \n\nTourism remains important for its towns and villages and their varied attractions, [[country house]]s and heritage sites. Outside the towns, walking on the extensive network of public footpaths, cycle trails, rock climbing and caving are popular pursuits. The Friends of the Peak District's 200-mile Boundary Walk is a new long distance trail addition.\n\n==Geography==\nThe Peak District is at the southern end of the Pennines<ref>{{cite web |title=Location and overview of the Peak District |url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/microsites/sopr/overview/location-and-overview-of-the-peak-district |website=Peak District National Park |publisher=Peak District National Park |accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref> and much of the area is upland above {{convert|1000|ft|m|-2}}. Its high point is  [[Kinder Scout]] at {{convert|2087|ft|m|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Nuttall\">{{cite book |title=The Mountains of England & Wales \u2013 Volume 2: England |last1=Nuttall |first1=J. |last2=Nuttall|first2=A. |year=1990 |publisher=Cicerone |location=Milnthorpe |isbn=1-85284-037-4 |url=http://www.nuttalls.com/mountains/england.htm |accessdate=23 August 2009}}</ref> Despite its name, the landscape generally lacks sharp peaks, and is characterised mostly by rounded hills, [[plateau]]s, valleys, limestone [[Canyon|gorge]]s and gritstone [[escarpment]]s (the \"edges\").<ref name=\"Landscape\">{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/microsites/sopr/landscape|title=Landscape|publisher=Peak District National Park State of the Park|accessdate=28 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Gritstone Edges\">{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrictonline.co.uk/peak-district-gritstone-edges-c101334.html|title=Gritstone Edges|publisher=Peak District Online|accessdate=28 June 2017}}</ref>  The area, mostly rural, is surrounded by conurbations and large urban areas including [[Manchester]], [[Huddersfield]], [[Sheffield]], [[Derby]] and [[Stoke-on-Trent]].\n\nThe [[national park]] has a formal boundary and covers most of the [[Dark Peak]] and [[White Peak]], but the wider Peak District is less well defined.<ref>{{cite web|title=Peak District|url=https://www.heathrowshuttle.com/pages/peak-district|website=Heathrow Shuttle|publisher=Heathrow Shuttle|accessdate=13 February 2018}}</ref> The Dark Peak is largely uninhabited [[moorland]] and gritstone escarpments in the northern Peak District and its eastern and western margins. It encloses the central and southern White Peak which is where most settlements, farmland and limestone gorges are located.<ref>{{cite web|title=Accommodation in Derbyshire and the Peak National Park|url=http://www.derbyshire-peakdistrict.co.uk/accommodation.htm|website=Discover Derbyshire and the Peak District|publisher=Discover Derbyshire and the Peak District|accessdate=12 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Character areas\">{{cite web|url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/learning-about/about-the-national-park/character-areas|publisher=Peak District.gov|title=Character areas|accessdate=14 September 2017|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170914125324/http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/learning-about/about-the-national-park/character-areas|archivedate=14 September 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Three of [[Natural England]]'s [[National Character Area]]s (NCAs) include the landscape. The Dark Peak NCA includes the northern and eastern parts of the Dark Peak while the White Peak NCA covers most of the White Peak. The western margins of the Dark Peak are in the South West Peak NCA, where farmland and pastured valleys are found as well as gritstone edges and moorland.<ref name=\"Character areas\"/><ref name=\"South West Peak\">{{cite web|title=South West Peak|url=http://www.snh.org.uk/wwo/sharinggoodpractice/cci/cci/eastmidlands/053b.htm|website=Scottish Natural Heritage|publisher=Scottish Natural Heritage|accessdate=12 May 2018}}</ref>  Outside the park, the wider Peak District is often considered to include the area approximately between [[Disley]] and Sterndale Moor, and some of the outer fringes and foothills, including the [[River Churnet|Churnet]]<ref>{{cite book|title=Britain|publisher=Martin Walters and Bob Gibbons|pages=220\u2013221|url=https://books.google.com/?id=8Q4fJsgiDZgC&pg=PA220&dq=churnet+valley+edge+of+peak+district#v=onepage&q=churnet%20valley%20edge%20of%20peak%20district&f=false|accessdate=14 February 2018|isbn=9780198504337|year=2003}}</ref> and [[River Derwent, Derbyshire|lower Derwent]] Valleys.<ref name=\"Slow Travel The Peak District\">{{cite book|title=Slow Travel The Peak District|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Za2qCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA201&lpg=PA201&dq=peak+district+lower+derwent+valley#v=onepage&q=peak%20district%20lower%20derwent%20valley&f=false|pages=200\u2013203|publisher=Helen Moat|accessdate=5 October 2017|isbn = 9781784770075|date = 16 February 2016}}</ref> The region is mostly surrounded by lowlands<ref>{{cite web|title=The Peak District|url=http://www.peakdistrictonline.co.uk/the-peak-district-c2672.html|website=Peak District Online|publisher=Peak District Online|accessdate=31 March 2018}}</ref> with gritstone moorlands of the [[South Pennines]] to the north.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://publications.naturalengland.org.uk/publication/511867|publisher=Natural England|title=NCA Profile: 36 Southern Pennines (NE323)|accessdate=14 September 2017}}</ref> \n\nThe national park covers {{convert|555|sqmi|km2}},<ref name=\"Area\">{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrict-education.gov.uk/Fact%20Sheets/fz16pop.htm |title=The Peak District National Park \u2013 Fact Zone |publisher=PDNP Education |year=2000 |accessdate=22 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100308043914/http://www.peakdistrict-education.gov.uk/Fact%20sheets/fz16pop.htm |archivedate=8 March 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> including most of the region in Derbyshire and extends into Staffordshire, Cheshire, Greater Manchester and South and West Yorkshire. The park's northern limits are on the [[A62 road]] between Huddersfield and [[Oldham]], and its southernmost point is on the [[A52 road]] near [[Ashbourne, Derbyshire|Ashbourne]]. The park boundaries were drawn to exclude built-up and industrial areas; in particular [[Buxton]] and the quarries at the end of the [[Peak Dale]] corridor are surrounded on three sides by the park. [[Bakewell]] and many villages are in the national park as is much of the rural west of Sheffield. As of 2010, it is the fifth largest [[National parks of England and Wales|national park in England and Wales]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nationalparks.gov.uk/learningabout/factsandfigures.htm |title=National Park facts and figures |publisher=National Parks |year=2009 |accessdate=13 November 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120111052829/http://www.nationalparks.gov.uk/learningabout/factsandfigures.htm|archivedate=11 January 2012}}</ref> In the UK, designation as a national park means that planning and other functions are provided by a national park authority with additional planning restrictions that provide enhanced protection against inappropriate development. Land within this national park as in other UK parks is in a mix of public and private ownership.\n\nThe [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]], a charity that conserves historic and natural landscapes, owns about 12% of the land in the national park.<ref>''Handbook for Members and Visitors 2004'', [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|The National Trust]].</ref> Its three estates ([[High Peak Estate|High Peak]], [[White Peak Estate|White Peak]] and [[Longshaw Estate|Longshaw]]) include ecologically or geologically significant areas at [[Bleaklow]], [[Derwent Edge]], [[Hope Woodlands]], [[Kinder Scout]], the [[River Manifold|Manifold]] valley, [[Mam Tor]], [[Dovedale]], [[Milldale (Peak District)|Milldale]] and [[Winnats Pass]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/main/w-vh/w-visits/w-findaplace/w-highpeakestate.htm |title=High Peak Estate |publisher=[[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|The National Trust]] |year=2009 |accessdate=22 May 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090426230500/http://nationaltrust.org.uk/main/w-vh/w-visits/w-findaplace/w-highpeakestate.htm |archivedate=26 April 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"South_Peak\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/main/w-ilampark |title=Ilam Park and South Peak Estate |publisher=[[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|The National Trust]] |year=2010 |accessdate=26 September 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100715195938/http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/main/w-ilampark |archivedate=15 July 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/main/w-vh/w-visits/w-findaplace/w-longshawestate.htm |title=Longshaw Estate |publisher=[[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|The National Trust]] |year=2009 |accessdate=22 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090510093420/http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/main/w-vh/w-visits/w-findaplace/w-longshawestate.htm |archivedate=10 May 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The park authority owns around 5%, and other major landowners include several water companies.<ref name=\"Landuse\">{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/learning-about/secondary-resources/factsheets |title=Peak District National Park Authority factsheets |publisher=Peak District National Park Authority |year=2012 |accessdate=4 March 2014}}</ref>\n[[Image:Near the High Peak - pano.jpg|800px|thumb|center|A [[High Peak Estate|High Peak]] panorama between [[Hayfield, Derbyshire|Hayfield]] and [[Chinley]]]]\n\n===Settlements===\nBakewell is the largest settlement and only town in the national park; its five-arched bridge over the River Wye dates from the 13th century.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.places-to-go.org.uk/Bakewell.htm |title=Bakewell |publisher=Places-to-go.org.uk |year=2003 |accessdate=18 June 2009}}</ref> Castleton is the centre of production of the semi-precious mineral [[Blue John (mineral)|Blue John]], while the village of Eyam is known for its self-imposed quarantine during the [[Black Death in England|Black Death]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/wnet/secrets/case_plague/index.html |title=Mystery of the Black Death |publisher=[[Secrets of the Dead]] |accessdate=18 June 2009}}</ref> [[Edale]] is the southern terminus of the [[Pennine Way]], a 268-mile [[National Trails|national trail]] which transverses most of the Pennines and ends at [[Kirk Yetholm]] in the [[Anglo-Scottish border|Scottish border]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationaltrail.co.uk/pennine-way|title=Trail stats, Pennine Way|accessdate=27 May 2019|work=National Trails Homepage|publisher=[[The Countryside Agency]]}}</ref> Other villages within the park include [[Flash, Staffordshire|Flash]], [[Hathersage]], [[Hartington, Derbyshire|Hartington]], [[Ilam, Staffordshire|Ilam]] and [[Tideswell]].\n\nThe towns of [[Glossop]], [[Chapel-en-le-Frith]], Buxton, [[Macclesfield]], [[Leek, Staffordshire|Leek]], Ashbourne, [[Matlock, Derbyshire|Matlock]] and [[Chesterfield]] are on the fringes of the national park. The spa town of Buxton was developed by the [[Duke of Devonshire|Dukes of Devonshire]] as a genteel health resort in the 18th century<ref name=\"Visit Buxton\">{{cite web |url=http://www.visitbuxton.co.uk/ |title=Visit Buxton |publisher=VisitBuxton.co.uk |year=2007 |accessdate=18 June 2009}}</ref> while the [[spa]] at Matlock Bath in the valley of the River Derwent was popularised in the Victorian era. [[Hayfield, Derbyshire|Hayfield]] is at the foot of Kinder Scout, the highest summit in the area. Other towns and villages fringing the park include [[Whaley Bridge]], [[Hadfield, Derbyshire|Hadfield]], [[Tintwistle]], [[Marsden, West Yorkshire|Marsden]], [[Holmfirth]], [[Stocksbridge]], [[Darley Dale]] and [[Wirksworth]].\n\n===Rivers, reservoirs and canals===\nSeveral rivers have their sources on the moorland plateaux of the Dark Peak and the high ridges of the White Peak. Many rivers in the Dark Peak and outer fringes were dammed to create reservoirs for supplying drinking water. Streams were dammed to provide headwater for [[watermill|water driven mills]]; [[weir]]s were built for the same purpose.\nThe reservoirs of the [[Longdendale Chain]] were completed in February 1877 to provide compensation water, ensuring a continuous flow along the [[River Etherow]] which was essential for local industry, and provide drinking water for Manchester.<ref name=\"Quayle\" /> In a report for the [[Manchester City Council|Manchester Corporation]], [[John Frederick Bateman]] wrote in 1846:\n\n{{Quote|Within ten or twelve miles of Manchester, and six or seven miles from the existing reservoirs at Gorton, there is this tract of mountain land abounding with springs of the purest quality. Its physical and geological features offer such peculiar features for the collection, storage and supply of water for the use of the towns in the plains below that I am surprised that they have been overlooked.\n|John Frederick Bateman<ref name=\"Quayle\">{{cite book |last=Quayle |first=Tom |title=Manchester's Water: The Reservoirs in the Hills |year=2006 |publisher=[[Tempus Publishing]] |location=Stroud |isbn=0-7524-3198-6 |page=15}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe western side of the Peak District is drained by the Etherow, [[River Goyt|Goyt]], and [[River Tame, Greater Manchester|Tame]], which are tributaries of the [[River Mersey]]. The north east is drained by tributaries of the [[River Don, South Yorkshire|River Don]]. Of the tributaries of the [[River Trent]] that drain the south and east, the [[River Derwent, Derbyshire|River Derwent]] is the most prominent. It [[Source (river or stream)|rises]] on Bleaklow just east of [[Glossop]] and flows through the [[Upper Derwent Valley]] where it is constrained by the [[Howden Reservoir|Howden]], [[Derwent Reservoir (Derbyshire)|Derwent]] and [[Ladybower Reservoir]]s.<ref>{{cite book |last=Bevan |first=Bill |title=The Upper Derwent: 10,000 Years in a Peak District Valley |year=2004 |publisher=[[Tempus Publishing]] |location=Stroud |isbn=0-7524-2903-5 |pages=141\u2013159}}</ref> The reservoirs of the Upper Derwent Valley were built from the early to mid-20th century to supply drinking water to the [[East Midlands]] and South Yorkshire.\n\nThe [[River Noe]] and the [[River Wye, Derbyshire|River Wye]] are its tributaries.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrictonline.co.uk/content.php?categoryId=1593 |title=River Derwent |publisher=Peak District Online |year=2009 |accessdate=1 July 2009}}</ref> The [[River Manifold]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cressbrook.co.uk/features/manifold.php |title=The Manifold is a sister river to the Dove |work=Peak District Information |publisher=Cressbrook Multimedia |year=2008 |accessdate=1 July 2009}}</ref> and [[River Dove, Central England|River Dove]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cressbrook.co.uk/features/dove.php |title=The Dove is the major river of the South Peak |work=Peak District Information |publisher=Cressbrook Multimedia |year=2008 |accessdate=1 July 2009}}</ref> in the south west, whose sources are on [[Axe Edge Moor]], flow into the Trent, while the [[River Dane]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cressbrook.co.uk/features/dane.php |title=The Dane flows west into Cheshire |work=Peak District Information |publisher=Cressbrook Multimedia |year=2008 |accessdate=1 July 2009}}</ref> flows into the [[River Weaver]] in Cheshire.\n\n[[Image:Bugsworth 058079.jpg|thumb|right|upright|The Bugsworth Basin on the Peak Forest Canal]]\nThere are no canals in the national park, although the [[Standedge Tunnels]] on the [[Huddersfield Narrow Canal]] run underneath the extreme north of it.  Waters from the Dark Peak feed the [[Macclesfield Canal|Macclesfield]], [[Ashton Canal|Ashton]], and Huddersfield Narrow Canals and waters from the White Peak fed the [[Cromford Canal]]. Outside the  park, the [[Peak Forest Canal]] brought [[Lime (material)|lime]] from the quarries at [[Dove Holes]] for the construction industry. It terminated at [[Bugsworth Basin]] and the journey was completed using the [[Peak Forest Tramway]]. \n\nThe Cromford Canal, from [[Cromford]] to the [[Erewash Canal]], served lead mines at [[Wirksworth]] and [[Sir Richard Arkwright]]'s cotton mills. The [[Caldon Canal]] from [[Froghall]] was built to transport limestone from quarries at Cauldon Low for the iron industry and flints for the pottery industry.<ref name=\"Caldon Canal\">{{cite web|title=Caldon Canal|url=https://canalrivertrust.org.uk/enjoy-the-waterways/canal-and-river-network/caldon-canal|website=Canal River Trust|publisher=Canal River Trust|accessdate=1 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Climate===\nMost of the area is more than {{convert|1000|ft|m|-2}} above sea level,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrictinformation.com/features/kinder.php |title=Kinder Scout \u2013 the highest gritstone peak in the Peak District |publisher=Peak District Information |year=2008 |accessdate=21 May 2009}}</ref> in the centre of the country at a latitude of 53\u00b0N resulting in relatively high annual rainfall, averaging {{convert|40.35|in|mm}} in 1999, compared with the rest of England and Wales. The Dark Peak tends to receive more rainfall then the White Peak as it is higher. The higher rainfall does not affect the temperature, which averages the same as the rest of England and Wales at {{convert|10.3|\u00b0C|\u00b0F|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrict-nationalpark.info/place/rivers/climate.html |title=Peak District Climate |publisher=Peak District National Park |year=2003 |accessdate=13 November 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120523234641/http://www.peakdistrict-nationalpark.info/place/rivers/climate.html |archivedate=23 May 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> \n\nDuring the 1970s, the Dark Peak regularly recorded more than 70 days of snowfall. Since then the number of snowfall days has decreased. The hills still see periods of long continuous snow cover in some winters. Snow in mid-December 2009 on some hill summits created snow patches that lasted in some cases until May 2010. In the same winter, the A635 (Saddleworth Moor) and  A57 (Snake Pass) were closed because of lying snow for almost a month. Frost cover is seen for 20\u201330% of the winter on moorland in the Dark Peak and 10% in the White Peak.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepeakdistrict.info/fast/html/peak_district_general_informat.html |title=About the Peak District&nbsp;... |publisher=ThePeakDistrict.info |year=2007 |accessdate=23 May 2009}}</ref> \n\nThe Moorland Indicators of Climate Change Initiative was set up in 2008 to collect data in the area. Students investigated the interaction between people and the moorlands, and their effect on climate change, to discover whether the moorlands are a net carbon sink or source, based on the fact that Britain's upland areas are a significant global carbon store in the form of [[peat]]. Human interaction in terms of direct erosion and fire as well as the effects of global warming are the major variables that they considered.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/learning-about/learning-projects/climatechangeproject |title=Moorland Indicators of Climate Change Initiative 2012 |publisher=Peak District |year=2012 |accessdate=3 April 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120122183958/http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/learning-about/learning-projects/climatechangeproject |archivedate=22 January 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Geology==\nThe Peak is formed almost exclusively from [[sedimentary rock]]s dating from the [[Carboniferous]] period. They comprise the [[Carboniferous Limestone]], overlying [[Gritstone]] and the [[Coal Measures]] which occur only on the extreme margins and infrequent outcrops of [[igneous rock]]s including [[lava]]s, [[tuff]]s and [[volcano|volcanic vent]] [[agglomerate]]s.<ref>Gannon, Paul, ''Rock Trails Peak District:A Hillwalker's Guide to the Geology and Scenery'', Pesda Press, 2011, {{ISBN|978-1-906095-24-6}}</ref> The general [[structural geology|geological structure]] is that of a broad [[dome (geology)|dome]], whose western margins have been most intensely [[fault (geology)|fault]]ed and [[fold (geology)|fold]]ed.  [[Geologic uplift|Uplift]] and [[erosion]] have effectively sliced the top off the dome to reveal a [[concentric]] [[outcrop]] pattern with Coal Measures rocks on the eastern and western margins, Carboniferous Limestone at the core and with rocks of [[Millstone Grit]] outcropping between them. The southern edge of the dome is overlain by [[sandstone]]s of [[Triassic]] age though they barely impinge on the National Park. The White Peak is the central and southern section  where Carboniferous Limestone is found at or near the surface.<ref name=\"NCA Profile: 52 White Peak (NE534)\">{{cite web|title=NCA Profile: 52 White Peak (NE534)|url=http://publications.naturalengland.org.uk/publication/6364771410509824|website=Natural England|publisher=Natural England|accessdate=13 February 2018}}</ref> The Dark Peak to the north, east and west is characterised by Millstone Grit outcrops and broad swathes of moorland.<ref name=\"NCA Profile: 51 Dark Peak (NE378)\">{{cite web|title=NCA Profile: 51 Dark Peak (NE378)|url=http://publications.naturalengland.org.uk/publication/3684793|website=Natural England|publisher=Natural England|accessdate=13 February 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"South West Peak\"/>\n\nEarth movements after the Carboniferous period resulted in the up-doming of the area and, particularly in the west, the folding of the rock strata along north\u2013south axes. The region was raised in a north\u2013south line which resulted in the dome-like shape<ref name=\"Geology_explained\">{{cite book |title=Geology Explained in the Peak District |last=Cope |first=F. W. |year=1976 |isbn=0-7153-6945-8 |publisher=[[David & Charles]]}}</ref> and the [[shale]]s and sandstones were worn away until limestone was exposed. At the end of this period, the Earth's crust sank here which led to the area being covered by sea, depositing a variety of new rocks.<ref name=\"Geology\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cressbrook.co.uk/features/geology.php |title=The Peak District is a very interesting area geologically |work=Peak District Information |publisher=Cressbrook Multimedia |year=2008 |accessdate=24 May 2009}}</ref> Some time after its deposition, mineral veins were formed in the limestone. The veins and rakes have been mined for lead since [[Ancient Rome|Roman times]].<ref name=\"Geology\" />\n[[Image:Thor's cave.jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Thor's Cave]] seen from the [[Manifold Way]]]]\nThe Peak District was covered by ice during at least one of the [[ice age]]s of the last 2&nbsp;million years (probably the [[Anglian (stage)|Anglian]] glaciation of around 450,000 years ago) as evidenced by the patches of glacial till or boulder clay that can be found across the area.  It was not covered by ice during the [[last glacial period]], which peaked around 20,000\u201322,000 years ago. A mix of Irish Sea and Lake District ice abutted against its western margins. Glacial meltwaters eroded a complex of sinuous channels along this margin of the district during this period.<ref>Aitkenhead, N. et al. 2002 British Regional Geology: the Pennines and adjacent areas (4th Edn) (BGS, Nottingham)</ref> Glacial meltwaters contributed to the formation and development of many caves in the limestone area.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Geology of Britain |last=Macdougall |first=D. |year=2006 |isbn=0-520-24824-4 |publisher=University of California Press |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/frozenearthoncef00macd }}</ref> Wild animal herds roamed the area, and their remains have been found in several of the local caves.<ref name=\"Geology\" />\n\nThe different types of rock beneath the soil strongly influence the landscape; they determine the type of [[vegetation]] that will grow, and ultimately the type of animal that will inhabit the area.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Geology of Britain |last=Toghill |first=P. |year=2002 |isbn=1-84037-404-7 |publisher=Crowood Press}}</ref> [[Limestone]] has fissures and is [[Solubility|soluble]] in water, therefore rivers have been able to carve deep, narrow valleys. The rivers then often find routes underground, creating cave systems. Millstone Grit is insoluble but [[Porosity|porous]], absorbing water which seeps through the grits, until it meets the less porous shales beneath, creating [[Spring (hydrosphere)|springs]] where it reaches the surface. The shales are [[Friability|friable]] and easily attacked by [[frost]] and form areas that are vulnerable to [[landslide]]s, as on Mam Tor.<ref name=\"Geology_explained\" />\n\n==Ecology==\nThe gritstone and shale of the Dark Peak supports [[Ericaceae|heather]] moorland and [[blanket bog]] environments, with rough [[Domestic sheep|sheep]] pasture and [[grouse]] shooting being the main land uses, although parts of it also support farming,<ref name=\"NCA Profile: 51 Dark Peak (NE378)\"/> especially the South West Peak NCA.<ref name=\"NCA Profile: 53 South West Peak (NE453)\">{{cite web|title=NCA Profile: 53 South West Peak (NE453)|url=http://publications.naturalengland.org.uk/publication/12392045|website=Natural England|publisher=Natural England|accessdate=26 September 2017}}</ref> The limestone plateaux of the White Peak are more intensively farmed, with mainly dairy usage of improved pastures.<ref name=\"NCA Profile: 52 White Peak (NE534)\"/>  Woodland forms around 8% of the Peak National Park.<ref name=\"Landuse\" /> Natural broad-leaved [[woodland]] is found in the steep-sided, narrow dales of the [[White Peak]] and the deep cloughs of the Dark Peak, while reservoir margins often have coniferous plantations. \n\n===Flora===\n[[Polemonium caeruleum|Jacob's-ladder]] (''Polemonium caeruleum''), a relatively rare species characteristic of limestone dales in the White Peak, has been the county flower of Derbyshire since 2002.<ref name=\"The Flora of Derbyshire.\">{{cite book|last1=Willmott|first1=Alan|last2=Moyes|first2=Nick|title=The Flora of Derbyshire.|publisher=Pisces Publication.|isbn=978-1-874357-65-0}}</ref> It grows in grassland, light woodland, on screes, rock ledges and by streams in [[River Lathkill|Lathkill]], Wolfscote, Taddington, [[River Wye, Derbyshire|Wye]] Dale and other dales.  Pollen evidence from peat bogs indicates that it was widespread throughout Britain just after the last ice-age. Much planted in gardens from where it has established itself in other parts of the area, as a native it is restricted to the White Peak and the [[Yorkshire Dales]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Polemonium caeruleum|url=https://secure.derby.gov.uk/flora/?SpeciesID=1326|website=Derby City Council|publisher=Derby City Council|accessdate=25 April 2018}}</ref> Three [[Endemism|endemic]] vascular plants are found nowhere else in the world: ''[[Rubus durescens]]'' is a bramble found in central Derbyshire;<ref name=\"The Flora of Derbyshire.\"/> Derby hawkweed (''[[Hieracium naviense]]''), found only in [[Winnats Pass]],<ref name=\"The Flora of Derbyshire.\"/> is a native perennial of limestone cliffs that was discovered by J.N. Mills in 1966 and described as a new species in 1968;<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Mills|first1=J.N.|title=A new species of Hieracium in Derbyshire|journal=Watsonia|date=1968|volume=7|issue=1|pages=40\u201342|url=http://archive.bsbi.org.uk/Wats7p40.pdf|accessdate=25 April 2018|publisher=BSBI}}</ref> and leek-coloured hawkweed (''H. subprasinifolium'') was believed extinct but was rediscovered on banks beside the [[Monsal Trail]] in Cheedale in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Extinct plant rediscovered in the Peak District National Park |url=https://www.thestar.co.uk/news/extinct-plant-rediscovered-in-the-peak-district-national-park-1-8739153|website=The Star|publisher=The Star|accessdate=25 April 2018}}</ref>  The endemic Derbyshire feather moss ''[[Thamnobryum angustifolium]]'' occurs in one Derbyshire limestone dale, its sole world location intentionally kept confidential; the colony covers about {{convert|3|m2}} of a rock face with small subsidiary colonies nearby.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.slu.se/Global/externwebben/centrumbildningar-projekt/bryoconservation/Pdf%20ArtFaktablad/Faktablad/Thamnobryum_angustifolium.PDF | title=''Thamnobryum angustifolium'': Derbyshire feather-moss |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151210213710/http://www.slu.se/Global/externwebben/centrumbildningar-projekt/bryoconservation/Pdf%20ArtFaktablad/Faktablad/Thamnobryum_angustifolium.PDF |publisher=Joint Nature Conservation Committee |first=Nick G. |last=Hodgketts |date=March 2001 |archivedate=10 December 2015 |accessdate=2 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Dark Peak's heathlands, bogs, gritstone edges and acid grasslands contain relatively few species and [[Calluna|heather]] (''Calluna vulgaris''), [[Empetrum nigrum|crowberry]] (''Empetrum nigrum''), [[Vaccinium myrtillus|bilberry]] (''Vaccinium myrtillus'') and [[Eriophorum vaginatum|hare's-tail cotton grass]] (''Eriophorum vaginatum'') are dominant on the high moors.<ref name=\"The Flora of Derbyshire.\"/>  After decades of decline due to pollution, ''Sphagnum'' mosses are making a comeback, with species such as ''[[Sphagnum cuspidatum|S. cuspidatum]]'' being particularly dominant.<ref>Walker, M. D. 2019. ''Sphagnum''. Sicklebrook Press.</ref> White Peak habitats include [[calcareous grassland]], ash woodlands and rock outcrops suitable for lime-loving species.<ref name=\"The Flora of Derbyshire.\"/> They include [[Orchis mascula|early purple orchid]] (''Orchis mascula''), [[Epipactis atrorubens|dark-red helleborine]] (''Epipactis atrorubens'') and [[Ophrys insectifera|fly orchid]] (''Ophrys insectifera''), [[Helianthemum nummularium|common rockrose]] (''Helianthemum nummularium''), [[Helianthemum nummularium|spring cinquefoil]] (''Helianthemum nummularium'') and [[Parnassia|grass of parnassus]] (''Parnassia palustris''). Lead rakes, the spoil heaps of ancient mining activity, form another distinctive habitat in the White Peak, supporting a range of rare [[metallophyte]] plants, including the [[Minuartia|spring sandwort]] (''Minuartia verna''; also known as leadwort), [[Thlaspi caerulescens|alpine pennycress]] (''Thlaspi caerulescens'') and [[Viola lutea|mountain pansy]] (''Viola lutea'').<ref name=\"Lead\">{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/lead |title=Biodiversity Action Plan \u2013 The Lead Legacy |publisher=Peak District |year=2004 |accessdate=13 November 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720112405/http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/lead|archivedate=20 July 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Fauna===\n====Mammals====\nMost mammals found in the Peak District are generalists and widespread across the UK, but [[mountain hare]]s on heather moorland in the Dark Peak constitute the only wild population in England. They were re-introduced in the Victorian era for sporting purposes.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.derbyshiremammalgroup.org.uk/species_status/mountain_hare.html |title=MOUNTAIN HARE Lepus timidus |publisher=Derbyshire Mammal Group |date= |accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref>  A feral population of [[Red-necked wallaby|red-necked wallabies]] lived around [[The Roaches]] from the 1940s onwards but may now be extinct.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/environment/nature/naturestudies/the-decline-and-fall-of-the-peak-district-wallabies-8503546.html |title=The decline and fall of the Peak District wallabies |newspaper=The Independent |date=20 February 2013 |first=Michael |last=McCarthy |accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref> [[Red deer]] herds, assumed to be derived from animals escaped from [[Deer park (England)|deer park]]s at [[Lyme Park]] and [[Chatsworth House|Chatsworth]], are established in the upper reaches of the [[River Goyt|Goyt valley]] and on the moors above [[Baslow]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.derbyshiremammalgroup.org.uk/species_status/red_deer.html |title=Red Deer Cervus elaphus |publisher=Derbyshire Mammal Group |date= |accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The Red Deer of the Peak District \u2013 photograph special|url=http://www.derbyshirelife.co.uk/out-about/wildlife/the-red-deer-of-the-peak-district-photograph-special-1-4307436 |newspaper=Derbyshire Life |first=Paul |last=Hobson |date=12 November 2015 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref> and a herd on [[Wharncliffe Crags]] outside the park north of Sheffield may derive from the hunting stock of Wharncliffe Chase.<ref>{{cite book |chapter-url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=DyzwAwAAQBAJ&lpg=PA30&ots=z8EKrt4cA9&dq=Wharncliffe%20Woods%20red%20deer&pg=PA30#v=onepage&q=red%20deer&f=false |chapter=The dynamic influence of history and ecology on the restoration of a major urban heathland at Wharncliffe, South Yorkshire |first1=Ian D. |last1=Rotherham |first2=John C. |last2=Rose |first3=Chris |last3=Percy |publisher=Landscape Conservation Forum |editor-first1=Ian D. |editor-last1=Rotherham |editor-first2=Christine |editor-last2=Handley |title=Wild by Design and Ploughing on Regardless: Landscape Archaeology and Ecology Special Series |date=August 2012 |accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref> [[Biodiversity action plan]]s have been prepared for mountain hare, [[European hare|brown hare]], [[brown long-eared bat]], [[Hazel dormouse|dormouse]], [[Eurasian harvest mouse|harvest mouse]], [[European hedgehog|hedgehog]], [[noctule bat]], [[Eurasian otter|otter]], [[European pine marten|pine marten]], [[European polecat|polecat]], [[soprano pipistrelle]] and [[European water vole|water vole]].<ref name=\"Biodiversity Action Plan Species Found in the Peak District\">{{cite web|title=Biodiversity Action Plan Species Found in the Peak District|url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0003/610716/PDNPA-BAP-Species-Table-240815.pdf|website=Peak District National Park|publisher=Peak District National Park|accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref> The status of the pine marten is unclear, although confirmed sightings have occurred in recent decades in Derbyshire and north Staffordshire<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.derbyshiremammalgroup.org.uk/species_status/pine_marten.html |title=PINE MARTEN Martes martes  |publisher=Derbyshire Mammal Group |date= |accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref> and a specimen from an introduced Welsh population<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-derbyshire-45331872 |title=Mystery of pine marten found dead '100 miles from home' |publisher=BBC |date=28 August 2018 |accessdate=28 August 2018}}</ref> was found dead outside the national park on a road between [[Ripley, Derbyshire|Ripley]] and [[Belper]] in 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.derbyshirewildlifetrust.org.uk/news/rare-pine-marten-discovered-derbyshire |title=Rare pine marten discovered in Derbyshire |publisher=Derbyshire Wildlife Trust |date=24 August 2018 |accessdate=25 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Birds====\nMany of the Peak's bird species are also widespread generalists. The moors of the Dark Peak support breeding populations of a number of upland specialists, such as [[twite]],<ref name=\"pdnp\">{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/looking-after/biodiversity/peak-district-biodiversity/peak-district-species/moorland-species |title= Moorland Species |publisher=Peak District National Park |date= |accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=https://britishbirds.co.uk/article/notes-neglected-colony-twite-central-england/ |title=Notes on a neglected colony of Twite in central England |journal=British Birds |date=15 June 2016 |first1=Jamie |last1=Dunning |first2=Roy |last2=Frost |first3=Steve |last3=Christmas |first4=Mick |last4=Pearson |accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref> [[short-eared owl]],<ref name=\"pdnp\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.derbyshirewildlifetrust.org.uk/species/short-eared-owl |title=Short-eared Owl ''Asio flammeus'' |publisher=Derbyshire Wildlife Trust |date= |accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref> [[European golden plover|golden plover]],<ref name=\"pdnp\" /> [[dunlin]],<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://britishbirds.co.uk/article/recovery-breeding-dunlin-population-peak-district-response-blanket-bog-restoration/ |title=Recovery of a breeding Dunlin population in the Peak District in response to blanket bog restoration |journal=British Birds |date=8 February 2017 |first1=Dave |last1=O\u2019Hara |first2=Jon |last2=Bird |first3=Kate |last3=Hanley |first4=Geoff |last4=Carr |accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref> [[ring ouzel]],<ref name=\"pdnp\" /> [[northern wheatear]]<ref name=\"Peak Birds Project\">{{cite web |url=http://ww2.rspb.org.uk/Images/peakdistrictbirds_tcm9-132780.pdf |title=Where to find birds in the Peak District |publisher=Peak Birds Project  |date= |accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref> and [[merlin (bird)|merlin]].<ref name=\"pdnp\" /> The populations of twite and golden plover are the southernmost confirmed breeding populations in England,<ref name=\"bto\">{{cite book |first1=D.E. |last1=Balmer |first2=S. |last2=Gillings |first3=B.J. |last3=Caffrey |first4=R.L. |last4=Swann |first5=I.S. |last5=Downie |first6=R.J. |last6=Fuller |title=Bird Atlas 2007\u201311: the breeding and wintering birds of Britain and Ireland |publisher=BTO Books |date=2013 |location=Thetford |isbn=978-1-908581-28-0}}</ref> and the Peak District Moors Special Protection Area (SPA) is a European designation for its populations of merlin, golden plover and short-eared owl.<ref name=\"pdnp\" /> The Peak District lacks the concentrations of breeding [[wader]]s found further north in the Pennines, although the moors and their fringes accommodate breeding [[Eurasian curlew|curlew]] and [[Northern lapwing|lapwing]]<ref name=\"Peak Birds Project\" /> as well as less noticeable wading birds including dunlin and [[Common snipe|snipe]].<ref name=\"Peak Birds Project\" />\n\nCommercial [[driven grouse shooting]] occurs on the heather moorlands of the Dark Peak, where the [[red grouse]] population is maintained by gamekeepers employed by shooting estates.<ref name=\"marsland\">{{cite journal |title=Birds of the Peak District |first=Michael |last=Marsland |journal=Bird Study |date=1974 |volume=21 |issue=2 |pages=135\u2013140 |doi=10.1080/00063657409476409 }}</ref><ref name=\"malp\">{{cite web |url=http://ww2.rspb.org.uk/Images/PeakMalpractice_tcm9-132666.pdf |title=Peak Malpractice: What's happening to wildlife in the Peak District National Park? |publisher=RSPB |date=2006 |accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref> A population of [[black grouse]] became extinct in 2000,<ref name=\"bto\" /> but reintroduction was attempted in 2003.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.birdguides.com/articles/black-grouse-in-the-upper-derwent-valley-an-update/ |title=Black Grouse in the Upper Derwent Valley \u2013 an Update |publisher=BirdGuides |date= 21 March 2006 |first=Matthew |last=Capper |accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref> Quarries and rock outcrops provide nest sites for [[peregrine falcon]] and [[common raven]]. Ravens and [[common buzzard]]s are increasingly encountered as their British range expands eastwards, perhaps because of general reductions in persecution. Illegal persecution may be implicated in the limited populations of rare raptors such as [[northern goshawk]], peregrine and [[hen harrier]].<ref name=\"malp\" /> Following the [[RSPB]]'s publication of ''Peak Malpractice'', a 2006 report highlighting wildlife crime,<ref name=\"malp\" /> the Peak District Bird of Prey Initiative was set up in 2011 by conservationists and shooting bodies in an attempt to boost the populations of birds of prey.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0005/1055570/Bird-of-Prey-Initiative-2016-17-Report.pdf |title=Peak District Bird of Prey Initiative \u2013 2016 & 2017 Report |publisher=Peak District Bird of Prey Initiative |date=2018 |accessdate=26 April 2018}}</ref> The park authorities expressed disappointment at the limited results<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/learning-about/news/current-news/peak-district-bird-of-prey-initiative |title=Peak District Bird of Prey Initiative |publisher=Peak District National Park  |date=25 January 2018 |accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref> and the RSPB withdrew from the partnership in January 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rspb.org.uk/about-the-rspb/about-us/media-centre/press-releases/rspb-ends-involvement-in-failed-peak-district-bird-of-prey-initiative/ |title=RSPB ends involvement in failed Peak District Bird of Prey Initiative |publisher=RSPB |date=23 January 2018 |accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nFast-flowing rivers attract specialist species, notably [[grey wagtail]],<ref name=\"marsland\" /> [[White-throated dipper|dipper]],<ref name=\"lgre\">{{cite book |first=Lee G.R. |last=Evans |title=The Ultimate Site Guide to Scarcer British Birds |publisher=BirdGuides |date=2009 |location= |isbn=978-1898110491 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.moorsforthefuture.org.uk/sites/default/files/documents/MFF%20RN01%202004%20Breeding%20bird%20survey%20of%20the%20Peak%20District%20moorlands.pdf |title=Breeding Bird Survey of the Peak District Moorlands:Moors for the Future Research Note No 1 |publisher= Moors for the Future |date=May 2005 |accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref> [[common sandpiper]],<ref name=\"marsland\" /> [[mandarin duck]]<ref name=\"birdreport\" /> and [[Common merganser|goosander]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0005/817772/State-of-Nature-in-the-Peak-District-Report-by-Penny-Anderson-for-Nature-Peak-District.pdf |title=State of Nature in the Peak District |publisher=Nature Peak District |date=2016 |first=Penny |last=Anderson |at=Section 5.22 |accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref>  Wooded and semi-wooded areas attract [[common redstart|redstart]],<ref name=\"Peak Birds Project\" /> [[European pied flycatcher|pied flycatcher]],<ref name=\"Peak Birds Project\" /> [[wood warbler]]<ref name=\"Peak Birds Project\" /> and [[tree pipit]],<ref name=\"marsland\" /> and coniferous plantations house [[Eurasian siskin|siskin]] and [[Red crossbill|common crossbill]].<ref name=\"lgre\" /> Upland reservoirs in the Dark Peak are generally [[Oligotroph|oligotrophic]] and attract few birds, but lower-lying reservoirs on the southern fringes such as [[Carsington Water]] and [[Ogston Reservoir]] regularly attract rare migrants and wintering rarities such as various waders, wildfowl, gulls and terns.<ref name=\"birdreport\" /> The area is regularly overflown by wintering populations of [[pink-footed geese]]<ref name=\"birdreport\">{{cite journal |title=Derbyshire Bird Report |issue=various |publisher=Derbyshire Ornithological Society}}</ref> moving between East Anglia and Morecambe Bay.\n\nDipper, golden plover, hen harrier, merlin and short-eared owl are local [[biodiversity action plan]] priority species.<ref name=\"Biodiversity Action Plan Species Found in the Peak District\"/>\n\n====Other taxa====\nAmphibians and reptiles such as [[Viviparous lizard|common lizard]]s, [[grass snake]]s, [[Northern crested newt|great crested newt]]s and [[Anguis fragilis|slow worm]]s are found in the area.<ref name=\"Biodiversity Action Plan Species Found in the Peak District\"/> The eastern moors are a stronghold for [[Vipera berus|adder]]s.<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.sorby.org.uk/v2/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/SS11_1997_Reptiles_Amphibians_OCRc.pdf  |title=Reptiles and Amphibians of the Sheffield Area and North Derbyshire |publisher=Sorby Natural History Society |location=Sheffield |date=1997 |first=Derek |last=Whiteley |accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nNative fish in the Peak District include [[Atlantic salmon]], [[brown trout]], [[European eel]],<ref name=\"Biodiversity Action Plan Species Found in the Peak District\"/> [[European bullhead|bullhead]], [[brook lamprey]] and [[Thymallus|grayling]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Rivers and Streams|url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0003/158646/Rivers-and-Streams.pdf|website=Peak District National Park|publisher=Peak District National Park|accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref> A possibly unique population of \"wild\" [[rainbow trout]] survives on the [[River Wye, Derbyshire|Derbyshire Wye]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://theriverbeat.blogspot.com/2012/07/wild-rainbows-of-river-wye-derbyshire.html |title=Wild Rainbows of the River Wye, Derbyshire |publisher=The River Beat |type=blog |date=3 July 2012 |accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref> following their introduction at the turn of the 20th century.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.derbyshiretimes.co.uk/sport/angling/rainbows-the-pride-of-the-river-wye-1-483071 |first= |last= |title=Rainbows: the pride of the river Wye |newspaper=Derbyshire Times |date=25 March 2009 |accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nButterflies in the region include the [[dingy skipper]], [[Aricia agestis|brown argus]], [[small blue]] and [[white-letter hairstreak]]. Moths include the [[Stilbia anomala|anomalous]], [[Ceramica pisi|broom moth]], [[dot moth]], [[garden dart]], [[mouse moth]] and [[Spilosoma lubricipeda|white ermine]]. Other invertebrates include the [[Bombus monticola|bilberry bumblebee]], [[Monocephalus|broad groove-head spider]], [[mole cricket]], [[Lipsothrix|northern yellow splinter]], [[Formicoxenus nitidulus|shining guest ant]], [[Meloe violaceus|violet oil beetle]] and [[Austropotamobius pallipes|white-clawed crayfish]].<ref name=\"Biodiversity Action Plan Species Found in the Peak District\"/>\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Kinder plateau.jpg|thumb|right|upright|A view of the [[Edale]] valley from [[Mam Tor]]]]\nThe Peak has been inhabited from the earliest periods of human activity as evidenced by finds of [[Mesolithic]] flint artefacts and [[Palaeogeography|palaeoenvironmental]] evidence from caves in Dovedale and elsewhere. Evidence of [[Neolithic]] activity includes monumental earthworks or [[Tumulus|barrows]] such as that at [[Margery Hill]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eng-h.gov.uk/ArchRev/rev94_5/margery.htm |title=Margery Hill, South Yorkshire |publisher=[[English Heritage]] |year=1994 |accessdate=22 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012232222/http://www.eng-h.gov.uk/ArchRev/rev94_5/margery.htm |archivedate=12 October 2008 }}</ref> \n\nIn the [[Bronze Age]] the area was well populated and farmed, and evidence of these people survives in [[henge]]s such as [[Arbor Low]] near [[Youlgreave]], or the [[Nine Ladies|Nine Ladies stone circle]] at [[Stanton Moor]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Bevan |first=Bill |title=Ancient Peakland |year=2007 |publisher=Halsgrove |location=Wellington |isbn=978-1-84114-593-8}}</ref> In the same period, and into the [[Iron Age]] hillforts such as that at Mam Tor were created. The [[Roman Britain|Romans]] exploited the area's rich mineral veins, exporting lead from the Buxton area along well-used routes. Buxton was a Roman settlement, known as \"[[Aquae Arnemetiae]]\" in recognition of its spring.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.roman-britain.org/places/aquae_arnemetiae.htm |title=Aquae Arnemetiae |publisher=RomanBritain.org |year=2005 |accessdate=22 May 2009}}</ref> .\n\nTheories as to the derivation of the Peak name include that it came from the [[Pecsaetan]] or peaklanders, an [[Anglo-Saxons|Anglo-Saxon]] tribe who inhabited the central and northern parts of the area from the 6th century AD when it was part of the Anglian kingdom of [[Mercia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peakscan.freeuk.com/peak_district_history_.htm |title=Peak District history : Anglo Saxons to Present |publisher=Peakscan |accessdate=28 June 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=A History of Derbyshire, Volume 1 |last=Turbutt |first=G. |year=1999 |publisher=Merton Priory |location=Cardiff |isbn=1-898937-34-6}}</ref> Barrows from the [[Anglo-Saxons|Anglo-Saxon]] period are present, including at [[Benty Grange]], where the [[Benty Grange helmet|eponymous helmet]] was found.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1013767 |desc=Benty Grange hlaew, Monyash |year= |accessdate=10 February 2018}}</ref> \n\n===Mining and quarrying===\n{{See also|Derbyshire lead mining history}}\nIn medieval and early modern times the area was mainly agricultural with sheep farming, rather than arable, the main activity in upland holdings. From the 16th century, the area's mineral and geological wealth became increasingly significant. Not only lead, but coal, [[fluorite]], copper from [[Ecton Mines]], [[zinc]], [[Iron ore|iron]], [[manganese]] and silver have all been mined.<ref>{{cite book |title=Rocks and Scenery of the Peak District |last=Ford |first=T. D. |authorlink=Trevor D. Ford |year=2002 |isbn=1-84306-026-4 |publisher=Landmark Publishing}}</ref> [[Celia Fiennes]], describing her journey through the Peak in 1697, described,\n{{Quote|...&nbsp;craggy hills whose bowells are full of mines of all kinds off black and white and veined marbles, and some have mines of copper, others tinn and leaden mines, in w[hi]ch is a great deale of silver.\n|[[Celia Fiennes]]<ref>{{cite book |title=Through England on a Side Saddle in the Time of William and Mary |last=Fiennes |first=C. |authorlink=Celia Fiennes |year=1888 |publisher=Field and Tuer, The Leadenhall Press |location=London |url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/text/chap_page.jsp?t_id=Fiennes&c_id=15 |accessdate=22 May 2009}}</ref>\n}}\nCoal measures occur on the Peak's western and eastern fringes and evidence of past workings can be found from Glossop to [[The Roaches]], and from [[Stocksbridge]] to [[Baslow]]. The coal measures in the east are at the western edge of the [[South Yorkshire Coalfield]]<ref name=\"The Yorkshire Coalfield\">{{cite web |url=https://hemingfieldcolliery.wordpress.com/the-yorkshire-coalfield/|title=The Yorkshire Coalfield|publisher=The Friends of Hemingfield Colliery|accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref> and those in the west are part of the Cheshire section of the [[Lancashire Coalfield]].<ref name=\"Manchester and Its Region\">{{cite web |url=https://books.google.com/?id=mqXnAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA3&lpg=PA3&dq=south+lancashire+coalfield+cheshire+plain#v=onepage&q=south%20lancashire%20coalfield%20cheshire%20plain&f=false|title=Manchester and Its Region|publisher=The University of Manchester|accessdate=17 September 2017|year=1962}}</ref> Mining started in [[Middle Ages|medieval times]] and was at its most productive in the 18th and early 19th centuries and continued into the early 20th century. The earliest mining took place at and close to [[outcrop]]s where miners followed the seams deeper into the hillsides. At Goyt's Moss and [[Axe Edge Moor|Axe Edge]], deep seams were worked and steam engines raised the coal and dewatered the mines.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.coal.gov.uk/media/EB466/Enviro%2012%20P14.pdf |title=Goyt's Moss and Axe Edge Moor Update |publisher=Environment News 12 |accessdate=13 November 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040726124922/http://www.coal.gov.uk/media/EB466/Enviro%2012%20P14.pdf|archivedate=26 July 2004}}</ref> Coal from the east was used in lead smelting and from the west for lime burning.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrict-nationalpark.info/time/industry/coalmining.html |title=Peak District Coal Mining |publisher=Peak District National Park |year=2003 |accessdate=13 November 2013|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20100809072725/http://www.peakdistrict-nationalpark.info/time/industry/coalmining.html|archivedate=9 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nLead mining peaked in the 17th and 18th centuries; high concentrations were found in the area from this period, as well as discovering peat on Kinder Scout suggesting that lead smelting occurred.<ref name=\"Mining\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thepeakdistrict.info/peak-district-mining.php |title=Mining in the Peak District of Derbyshire Lead and Copper Minerals |publisher=A Taste of the Peak District |accessdate=24 June 2009}}</ref> Lead mining declined from the mid-19th century and the last major mine closed in 1939. Lead is a by-product of fluorite, baryte and calcite mining.<ref name=\"Lead\" /> [[Bell pit]]s were sunk to access ore that lay close to the surface.<ref name=\"Mining\" />\n\nFluorite or fluorspar is called [[Blue John (mineral)|Blue John]] locally, its name possibly from the French ''bleu et jaune'' describing its colour. Blue John is scarce, and now only a few hundred kilograms are mined each year for ornamental and [[lapidary]] use. The [[Blue John Cavern]] in Castleton is a [[show cave]]. Small scale mining takes place in [[Treak Cliff Cavern]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bluejohnstone.co.uk/ |title=Blue John Stone |publisher=BlueJohnStone.co.uk |year=2007 |accessdate=30 June 2009}}</ref>\n\nIndustrial limestone quarrying to make soda ash started around Buxton in 1874. In 1926 the operation became part of [[Imperial Chemical Industries|ICI]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tarmac.co.uk/buxtoncement/companyhistory.aspx |title=The Buxton Story |publisher=[[Tarmac Limited|Tarmac]] |year=2006 |accessdate=1 July 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130505103000/http://www.tarmac.co.uk/buxtoncement/companyhistory.aspx |archivedate=5 May 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Large-scale limestone and gritstone quarrying flourished as lead mining declined, and is an important if contentious industry.  Of the twelve large limestone quarries in operation, [[Tunstead, Derbyshire|Tunstead]] is one of the largest in Europe.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bgs.ac.uk/foundation-web/GenericInd.html |title=Peak District industry |publisher=[[British Geological Survey]] |accessdate=22 May 2009}}</ref> Total limestone output was substantial: at the 1990 peak, 8.5 million tonnes was produced.<ref name=\"Mineral_factsheet\" />\n\n===Textiles===\nTextiles have been exported for hundreds of years. In the 14th century, the area traded in unprocessed wool.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peaklandheritage.org.uk/index.asp?peakkey=30800521 |title=Textiles |publisher=Peakland Heritage |accessdate=23 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071211134344/http://www.peaklandheritage.org.uk/index.asp?peakkey=30800521 |archivedate=11 December 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> There was a number of skilled hand spinners and weavers in the area. By the 1780s, [[Richard Arkwright]] had developed machinery to produce textiles more quickly and to a higher standard. The early Arkwright [[Cotton mill|mills]] were of light construction, narrow, about {{convert|9|ft|m}} wide, and low, the ceiling height was only {{convert|6|to|8|ft}} and were lit by daylight. The new machines were powered by [[water wheel]]s.<ref>{{cite book |title=Cotton Mills of Greater Manchester |last=Williams |first=M. |year=1992 |isbn=0-948789-89-1 |page=49 |publisher=Carnegie Publishing}}</ref> The Peak was the ideal location, with its rivers and humid atmosphere. The local pool of labour was quickly exhausted and [[Litton Mill]] and [[Cressbrook|Cressbrook Mill]] in [[Millers Dale]] brought in children as young as four from the [[workhouse]]s of London as apprentices.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cottontimes.co.uk/childreno1.htm |title=Children of the Revolution |publisher=Cotton Times |accessdate=31 March 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090430143222/http://www.cottontimes.co.uk/childreno1.htm |archivedate=30 April 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAs technology advanced, narrow valleys proved unsuitable for larger steam-driven mills, but the Derbyshire mills remained, trading in finishing and niche products. Glossop benefitted from the textile industry. Its economy was linked closely with a spinning and weaving tradition that had evolved from developments in [[textile manufacture during the Industrial Revolution]]. Until the First World War, Glossop had the headquarters of the largest [[Calico (textile)|textile]] printworks in the world but after the [[Wall Street crash]], its product lines became vulnerable and the industry declined.<ref>{{cite book |title=Small-Town Politics: A Study of Political Life in Glossop  |chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/smalltownpolitic0000birc  |chapter-url-access=registration  |last=Birch |first=A. H. |year=1959 |isbn=0-273-70161-4 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/smalltownpolitic0000birc/page/8 8\u201338] |chapter=2 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]}}</ref>\n\n===Modern history===\nThe [[Mass trespass of Kinder Scout|Kinder Trespass]] in 1932 was a landmark in the campaign for open access to moorland in Britain and eventually led to the formation of Britain's [[national park]]s. Before the trespass, open moorland was closed to all. Moorland estates were the private property of landed gentry who used them for only 12 days a year and were guarded by their gamekeepers.<ref>{{cite web|last=Renton |first=D. |title=Kinder Trespass: Context in 1932 |url=http://kindertrespass.com/index.asp?ID=36 |publisher=The Kinder Trespass 75 organising committee |date=23 February 2007 |accessdate=28 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090221190036/http://kindertrespass.com/index.asp?ID=36 |archivedate=21 February 2009 }}</ref> The Peak District National Park became the United Kingdom's first national park on 17 April 1951. Campaigner [[Ethel Haythornthwaite]] played an important part in the development of the national park. The first [[Long-distance footpaths in the United Kingdom|long-distance footpath]] in the United Kingdom was the [[Pennine Way]], which opened in 1965 and starts at the Nags Head Inn, in Grindsbook Booth, part of [[Edale]] village.\n\n[[Saddleworth Moor]] and [[Wessenden Valley|Wessenden]], above Meltham, gained notoriety after the [[Moors murders]] in the 1960s.\n\n==Economy==\n[[File:Tunstead Quarry - geograph.org.uk - 865006.jpg|right|thumb|Tunsted Quarry]]\nTourism is estimated to provide 500 full-time jobs, 350 part-time jobs and 100 seasonal jobs.<ref name=\"Waugh\">{{cite book |title=Geography An Integrated Approach |last=Waugh |first=D. |year=2000 |edition=3rd |isbn=0-17-444706-X |publisher=[[Wolters Kluwer|Nelson Thornes]]}}</ref>\nIt is a major source of employment for park residents (24%). Manufacturing industries (19%), [[Peak District#Quarrying|quarrying]] (12%) and agriculture (12%) are also important.<ref name=\"Place_called_home\">{{cite web|url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/index/living-in.htm |title=A place called home |publisher=Peak District |year=2009 |accessdate=22 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090519001312/http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/index/living-in.htm |archivedate=19 May 2009 }}</ref> \nThe [[Hope Construction Materials|cement works]] at [[Hope Valley, Derbyshire|Hope]] is the largest single employer in the park.<ref name=\"Mineral_factsheet\">{{cite web|url=http://www.peakdistrict-nationalpark.info/studyArea/factsheets/11.html#4 |title=Peak District National Park: Study Area |publisher=Peak District National Park |year=2003 |accessdate=22 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20050620074557/http://www.peakdistrict-nationalpark.info/studyArea/factsheets/11.html |archivedate=20 June 2005 }}</ref> Limestone is the most important mineral quarried, mainly for roads and cement; shale is extracted for cement at Hope, and several [[gritstone]] quarries are worked for building stone.<ref name=\"Mineral_factsheet\" /> [[Derbyshire lead mining history|Lead mining]] is no longer economic, but [[fluorite]], [[baryte]] and [[calcite]] are extracted from lead veins, and small-scale Blue John mining occurs at Castleton.\n\nThe springs at Buxton and Ashbourne are exploited to produce bottled [[mineral water]], and many [[plantation]]s are managed for [[Lumber|timber]]. Other manufacturing industries include [[David Mellor (cutler)|David Mellor]]'s [[cutlery]] factory in [[Hathersage]], [[Ferodo]] [[brake lining]]s in [[Chapel-en-le-Frith]] and [[Electronics|electronic equipment]] in Castleton. Of the approximately 2,700 farms in the national park, most covering less than {{convert|40|ha|acre}}, 60% of farms are run on a part-time basis where the farmer has a second job.<ref name=\"Waugh\" /> {{Clear}}\n\n==Tourism==\n''De Mirabilibus Pecci'' or ''The Seven Wonders of the Peak'' by [[Thomas Hobbes]] was an early tourist description published in 1636.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bl.uk/learning/langlit/texts/tourists/de/darbyshire.html |title=1678 \u2013 De Mirabilibus Pecci \u2013 Being the Wonders of the Peak in Darby-shire |publisher=[[British Library]] |accessdate=22 May 2009}}</ref> Much scorn was poured on the seven wonders by visitors, including [[Daniel Defoe]] who described the moors by [[Chatsworth, Derbyshire|Chatsworth]] as \"a waste and houling wilderness\" and was particularly contemptuous of [[Peak Cavern]] near Castleton which was known as the 'Devil's Arse'.<ref>{{cite book |title=A tour thro' the whole island of Great Britain, divided into circuits or journies |last=Defoe |first=D. |authorlink=Daniel Defoe |year=1927 |publisher=[[J. M. Dent]] |location=London |url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/text/chap_page.jsp?t_id=Defoe&c_id=30 |accessdate=22 May 2009}}</ref> Visitor numbers did not increase until the [[Victorian era]] when the advent of railways provided access and a cultural appreciation of the [[Picturesque]] and [[Romanticism|Romantic]] developed. [[John Mawe]]'s ''Mineralogy of Derbyshire'' (1802)<ref>{{cite book |title=The Mineralogy of Derbyshire |last=Mawe |first=J. |authorlink=John Mawe |year=1802 |publisher=William Phillips |location=London |url=http://www2.odl.ox.ac.uk/gsdl/cgi-bin/library?e=d&a=d&c=munahi10&cl=CL1.3&d=munahi010-abp |accessdate=22 May 2009}}</ref> and William Adam's ''Gem of the Peak'' (1843)<ref>{{cite book |title=Gem of the Peak or Matlock Bath and its vicinity |last=Adam |first=W. |year=1843 |publisher=[[Longman]] |location=London |url=https://books.google.com/?id=qAEHAAAAQAAJ&dq=Matlock+Bath+and+its+Vicinity&printsec=frontcover#PPR1,M1 |accessdate=22 May 2009}}</ref> generated interest in the area's unique geology.\n\nA tradition of public access and outdoor recreation grew in the area which is  natural hinterland and rural escape for the populations of industrial Manchester and Sheffield, and remains a valuable leisure resource in a largely [[post-industrial economy]]. In a 2005 survey of visitors, 85% of respondents mentioned \"scenery and landscape\" as a reason for visiting.<ref>[http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/microsites/sopr/landscape/landscape-character \"Landscape Character\"] Peak District National Park, retrieved 20 August 2015</ref>\n\n===Buxton===\n[[File:Buxtoncres1.jpg|thumb|left|Buxton Crescent and St Ann's Well]]\nBuxton developed as a spa town because of its geothermal spring which rises at a constant temperature of 28&nbsp;\u00b0C. It was settled by the Romans around AD 78, when it was known as Aquae Arnemetiae, or the spa of the goddess of the grove. [[Bess of Hardwick]] and her husband the [[George Talbot, 6th Earl of Shrewsbury|Earl of Shrewsbury]], \"took the waters\" in 1569, and brought [[Mary, Queen of Scots]], there in 1573.<ref name=\"Buxton06\">{{cite web |url=http://quest.bris.ac.uk/workshops/annual06/Buxton.pdf |title=Things to do in Buxton |publisher=Quantifying and Understanding the Earth System |accessdate=28 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110825112931/http://quest.bris.ac.uk/workshops/annual06/Buxton.pdf |archivedate=25 August 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The town largely grew in importance in the late 18th century when it was developed by the [[Duke of Devonshire|5th Duke of Devonshire]] in style of the spa of [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]].\n\nA resurgence in the 18th century attracted [[Erasmus Darwin|Dr Erasmus Darwin]] and [[Josiah Wedgwood]],<ref>{{cite book |title=The correspondence of Charles Darwin |last=Darwin |first=C. |authorlink=Charles Darwin |year=1985 |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |location=Cambridge |url=https://books.google.com/?id=ao2I3-8PXBgC&pg=PA265&lpg=PA265&dq=levett+darwin |accessdate=28 June 2009|isbn=9780521824132 }}</ref> who were drawn by the reputed healing properties of the waters. The railway reached Buxton in 1863.<ref>{{cite book |title=Railways of the Peak District |last1=Blakemore |first1=B. |last2=Mosley|first2=D. |year=2003 |isbn=1-902827-09-0 |publisher=Great Northern Books}}</ref>\nBuxton's notable buildings are The Crescent (1780\u20131784), modelled on Bath's [[Royal Crescent]], by [[John Carr (architect)|John Carr]], The Devonshire (1780\u20131789), The Natural Baths, and The Pump Room by [[Henry Currey (architect)|Henry Currey]]. The [[Buxton Pavilion Gardens|Pavilion Gardens]] were opened in 1871.<ref name=\"Buxton06\" /> [[Buxton Opera House]] was designed by [[Frank Matcham]] in 1903.\n\n=== Historic buildings ===\nHistoric buildings in the park include [[Chatsworth House]], seat of the Dukes of Devonshire and among Britain's finest stately homes; the medieval [[Haddon Hall]], seat of the [[Duke of Rutland|Dukes of Rutland]]; and [[Lyme Park]], an Elizabethan manor house transformed by an [[Italianate architecture|Italianate]] front. Other historic buildings in the park include [[Eyam Hall]], [[Ilam Park|Ilam Hall]] and [[Tissington Hall]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Halls in the Peak District |url=http://www.peakdistrictonline.co.uk/peak-district-halls-c101023.html |website=Peak District Online |publisher=Peak District Online |accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref> Many villages and towns have fine parish churches, including the 14th-century [[St John the Baptist, Tideswell|Church of St John the Baptist]] at Tideswell, sometimes dubbed the 'Cathedral of the Peak', and the 12th-century [[Church of St Nicholas, Bradfield|Church of St Nicholas]] at [[High Bradfield]]. '[[Little John]]'s Grave' is in the churchyard at [[Hathersage]]. [[Peveril Castle]], overlooking Castleton, was built by the [[Normans]].<ref name=\"Peak District Attractions\">{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrictonline.co.uk/peak-district-attractions-c1736.html|title=Peak District Attractions|publisher=Peak District Online |accessdate=28 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Museums and attractions ===\nInside the park, [[Eyam Museum]] has displays about the village's history during the [[Black Death in England|Black Death]].<ref name=\"Eyam Museum and Plague Village\">{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrictinformation.com/visits/eyammus.php|title=Eyam Museum and Plague Village|publisher=Peak District Information|accessdate=14 September 2017}}</ref> Castleton has four show caves; [[Peak Cavern]], [[Blue John Cavern|Blue John]], [[Treak Cliff Cavern|Treak Cliff]] and [[Speedwell Cavern|Speedwell]]. In the outer fringes, the area's industrial heritage is represented by the [[Peak District Mining Museum|mining museum]] at Matlock Bath with the Temple Lead Mine, the [[Derwent Valley Mills]] [[World Heritage Site]] and [[Brindley Water Mill]] at Leek. Preserved railways such as the [[Peak Rail]], [[Ecclesbourne Valley Railway|Ecclesbourne Valley]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Exploring Duffield & Wirksworth on the Ecclesbourne Valley Line, Derbyshire |url=https://www.derbyshirelife.co.uk/out-about/places/exploring-duffield-wirksworth-on-the-ecclesbourne-valley-line-derbyshire-1-1645078 |website=Derbyshire Life and Countryside |publisher=Derbyshire Life and Countryside |accessdate=23 August 2018}}</ref> and [[Churnet Valley Railway|Churnet Valley]]<ref>{{cite web |title=History of the CVR \u2013 LMS & BR Days \u2013 History of the Churnet Valley Line |url=https://www.churnetvalleyrailway.co.uk/lmsbr |website=Churnet Valley Railway |publisher=Churnet Valley Railway |accessdate=23 August 2018}}</ref> lines, the [[National Tramway Museum]] at [[Crich]] and the [[Cromford Canal]] chart the area's transport history. Matlock Bath also has the show caves and mines of the [[Heights of Abraham]] which can be reached by cable car, and the [[Gulliver's Kingdom]] theme park.<ref name=\"Peak District Attractions\"/> Buxton has an opera house and theatre, museum and art gallery and [[Poole's Cavern]] show cave.<ref name=\"Visit Buxton\"/> Other attractions in the fringes include the [[Alton Towers]] theme park<ref name=\"Peak District Attractions\"/> and the [[Peak Wildlife Park]].\n[[Image:Welldressing Hayfield.jpg|thumb|200px|A [[well dressing]] at Hayfield]]\n[[Well dressing]] ceremonies are held in many villages during the spring and summer months, a tradition said to date from pagan times.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.welldressing.com/extra.php |title=More about Well Dressings |publisher=WellDressing.com |accessdate=18 June 2009}}</ref> Other local customs include [[Castleton Garland Day]] and Ashbourne's [[Royal Shrovetide Football]], played annually since the 12th century. Buxton hosts two opera festivals, the [[Buxton Festival]] and the [[International Gilbert and Sullivan Festival]], and the Buxton Festival Fringe, and the [[Peak Literary Festival]] is held at various locations twice a year. Peak District food specialities include the dessert [[Bakewell pudding]], very different from the nationally available [[Bakewell tart]], and until 2009 the famous cheese [[Stilton (cheese)|Stilton]] and other local cheeses were produced in the village of [[Hartington, Derbyshire|Hartington]].\n\n===Activities===\n[[Image:Mamtor-paragliding.jpg|thumb|right|[[Paragliding]] from Mam Tor]]\nAn extensive network of public footpaths and numerous long-distance trails, over {{convert|1800|mi|km|-2}} in total,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peakdistrict-nationalpark.info/studyArea/factsheets/02.html#problems |title=Peak District National Park: Study Area |publisher=Peak District National Park |accessdate=22 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20050331060949/http://www.peakdistrict-nationalpark.info/studyArea/factsheets/02.html |archivedate=31 March 2005 }}</ref> and large open-access areas are available for hillwalking and hiking.  The [[Pennine Way]] traverses the Dark Peak from Edale to the park's northern boundary just south of [[Standedge]]. [[Bridlepath|Bridleways]] are used by [[mountain biking|mountain bikers]], as well as horse riders. The [[Tissington Trail]] and [[High Peak Trail]], which re-use former railway lines, are well used by walkers, horse riders and cyclists.<ref name=\"Tissington_Trail\" /> The [[Peak District Boundary Walk]] is a circular {{convert|190|mi|adj=on}} walking trail around the national park.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.friendsofthepeak.org.uk/boundary-walk/|title=Boundary Walk|date=2017-10-12|website=Friends of the Peak District|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\nSections of the former rail routes were converted to multi-purpose cycle trails. After the Woodhead Line was closed between [[Hadfield, Derbyshire|Hadfield]] and [[Penistone]] part of the trackbed was used for the [[Longdendale Trail]] section of the [[Trans Pennine Trail]] between Hadfield and [[Woodhead, Derbyshire|Woodhead]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.derbyshire-peakdistrict.co.uk/glossopandlongdendale.htm |title=Glossop/Longdendale Walk |publisher=Discover Derbyshire and the Peak District |accessdate=1 July 2009}}</ref> The Manchester, Buxton, Matlock and Midlands Junction Railway between [[Rowsley]] and Buxton is part of the [[Monsal Trail]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.derbyshire-peakdistrict.co.uk/monsaltrail.htm |title=Monsal Trail |publisher=Discover Derbyshire and the Peak District |accessdate=1 July 2009}}</ref> The trackbed of the Cromford and High Peak Railway is open to the public as the High Peak Trail.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.derbyshire-peakdistrict.co.uk/thehighpeaktrail.htm |title=The High Peak Trail |publisher=Discover Derbyshire and the Peak District |accessdate=1 July 2009}}</ref> The Tissington Trail uses another disused rail line between Buxton and Ashbourne<ref name=\"Tissington_Trail\">{{cite web |url=http://www.derbyshire-peakdistrict.co.uk/tissingtontrail.htm |title=Tissington Trail |publisher=Discover Derbyshire and the Peak District |accessdate=1 July 2009}}</ref> while the [[Manifold Way]] utilises the [[Leek and Manifold Valley Light Railway|former line]] between [[Waterhouses, Staffordshire|Waterhouses]] and [[Hulme End]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Manifold Way |url=https://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/visiting/miles-without-stiles/manifold-way |website=Peak District National Park |publisher=Peak District National Park |accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nLocal authorities run cycle hire centres at Ashbourne, [[Parsley Hay]], [[Middleton-by-Wirksworth|Middleton Top]], the [[Upper Derwent Valley]] and Hulme End.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ohire.co.uk/companies/middleton-top-cycle-hire |title=Middleton Top Cycle hire |date= |accessdate=22 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/visiting/cycle |title=Cycling |publisher=Peak District National Park |date= |accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Manifold Cycle Hire |url=https://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/visiting/cycle/cycle-hire-centres/manifold |website=Peak District National Park |publisher=Peak District National Park |accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref> Wheelchair access is possible at several places on the former railway trails, and cycle hire centres offer vehicles adapted to wheelchair users.<ref name=\"Tissington_Trail\" /> A project to make footpaths more accessible to less-agile walkers has replaced stiles with gates.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.roachescottages.co.uk/activities.htm |title=Local Activities in & around the Peak District National Park |publisher=Roaches Holiday Cottages |accessdate=22 June 2009}}</ref>\n\nGritstone outcrops at Stanage Edge and The Roaches, are recognised as some of the finest [[rock climbing]] sites in the world.<ref name=\"Trekking\">{{cite web |url=http://www.trekking-world.com/regional/england/peak-district |title=Peak District |publisher=Trekking World |accessdate=22 June 2009}}</ref> Limestone is more unstable but provides many testing climbs. [[Thor's Cave]] was explored in the early 1950s by [[Joe Brown (climber)|Joe Brown]] and others. Eleven limestone routes there are listed by the [[British Mountaineering Council|BMC]], ranging in [[Grade (climbing)|grade]] from Very Severe to E7, and several more have been claimed since the guidebook's publication; a few routes are bolted.<ref>{{cite book |title=Rock Climbs in the Peak District: Peak Limestone: South |last=Milburn |first=G. |year=1987 |isbn=0-903908-26-3 |publisher=[[British Mountaineering Council]]}}</ref>\n\n[[Caving]] takes place in the natural caves, potholes and old mine workings found in the limestone of the White Peak. Peak Cavern, the largest and most important cave system, is even linked to the [[Speedwell Cavern|Speedwell]] system at Winnats. The largest potholes are Eldon Hole and Nettle Pot. Many old mine workings were often extensions of natural cave systems. They can be found at Castleton, Winnats, Matlock, [[Stoney Middleton]], Eyam, [[Monyash]] and Buxton.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cressbrook.co.uk/outdoors/potholing.php |title=Pot holing |work=Peak District Information |publisher=Cressbrook Multimedia |year=2008 |accessdate=30 June 2009}}</ref>\n\nReservoirs such as [[Torside Reservoir]], [[Damflask Reservoir]], [[Carsington Water]] and [[Rudyard Lake]] are centres for [[List of water sports|water sports]], including sailing, fishing and [[canoeing]]. Other activities include air sports such as [[hang gliding]] and [[paragliding]], [[birdwatching]], [[fell running]], [[off-roading]], and [[orienteering]].<ref name=\"Trekking\" />\n\n==Transport==\n[[File:Peak District National Park tunnels.svg|thumb|upright|Map showing tunnels beneath the Peak District]]\n\nThe first roads constructed by the [[Roman Britain|Romans]] may have followed existing tracks. The Roman network  linked the settlements and forts of Aquae Arnemetiae (Buxton), [[Chesterfield]], [[Ardotalia]] (Glossop) and Navio ([[Brough and Shatton]]), and beyond.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.roman-britain.org/maps/settlement_intro.htm |title=The Romano-British Settlements |publisher=RomanBritain.org |date=10 September 2010 |accessdate=26 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100928060305/http://www.roman-britain.org/maps/settlement_intro.htm |archivedate=28 September 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Parts of the modern [[A515 road|A515]] and [[A53 road|A53]] roads south of Buxton are believed to follow the routes of Roman roads.\n\n[[Packhorse]] routes criss-crossed the Peak in the Medieval era, and some paved causeways such as the Long Causeway along [[Stanage Edge]] date from this period.  No highways were marked on [[Christopher Saxton]]'s 1579 map of Derbyshire.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peakscan.freeuk.com/routes___stoops___peak_district.htm |title=Peak District Routes, Stoops, Pack Horse Ways, Turnpikes |publisher=Peakscan |year=2008 |accessdate=22 May 2009}}</ref> Bridge-building improved the transport network.\n\nAlthough the introduction of [[Toll road|turnpike roads]] from 1731<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peakdistrict-education.gov.uk/Fact%20Sheets/fz21lgd1.htm |title=Longendale in the Peak National Park |publisher=PDNP Education |year=2000 |accessdate=22 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060104204530/http://www.peakdistrict-education.gov.uk/Fact%20Sheets/fz21lgd1.htm |archivedate=4 January 2006 }}</ref> reduced journey times, the journey from Sheffield to Manchester in 1800 still took 16 hours prompting [[Samuel Taylor Coleridge]] to remark that \"a tortoise could outgallop us!\"<ref name=\"Stainforth\">{{cite book |title=The Peak: Past and Present |last=Stainforth |first=G. |year=1998 |isbn=0-09-475420-9 |publisher=[[Constable & Robinson|Constable]]}}</ref> From around 1815, better quality turnpike roads were built. The [[Snake Pass]], part of the [[A57 road|A57]], was built under the direction of [[Thomas Telford]] in 1819\u201321.<ref name=\"Stainforth\" /> \n\nThe main roads are the A57 between Sheffield and Manchester, the [[A628 road|A628]], Woodhead Pass, between [[Barnsley]] and Manchester via Longdendale, the [[A6 road (England)|A6]] from Derby to Manchester via Buxton, the [[Cat and Fiddle Road]] from Macclesfield to Buxton, and in the north, the [[A635 road|A635]] from Manchester to Barnsley. Roads and lanes are frequently congested and the availability of parking spaces in towns and villages is a significant problem, especially during summer. A congestion charge was proposed in 2005, but was rejected.<ref>{{cite news |last=Giannangeli |first=M. |title=Peak District may be first national park to impose a congestion charge |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1504735/Peak-District-may-be-first-national-park-to-impose-a-congestion-charge.html |work=The Daily Telegraph  |date=5 December 2005 |accessdate=23 May 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Cromford Canal]] opened in 1794, to carry coal, lead and iron ore to the [[Erewash Canal]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.derbyshire-peakdistrict.co.uk/cromfordcanal.htm |title=Cromford Canal |publisher=Discover Derbyshire and the Peak District |accessdate=1 July 2009}}</ref> it was abandoned in 1944. The canal turnpike roads had to compete with railways after 1825.<ref name=\"Stainforth\" /> The first railway, the [[Cromford and High Peak Railway]] from [[High Peak Junction]] to [[Whaley Bridge]], was an industrial line, but passenger services  followed, including the [[Woodhead Line]] (Sheffield to Manchester via Longdendale) and the [[Manchester, Buxton, Matlock and Midlands Junction Railway]]. Several rail lines were closed in the 1960s as a result of the [[Beeching Axe]]. \n\n===Public transport===\n[[Image:Totley Tunnel western portal.jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Totley Tunnel]] on the Manchester to Sheffield line]]\nThe Peak District is accessible by public transport. Train services operate along the [[Hope Valley line]] between Sheffield and Manchester, the [[Derwent Valley line]] between Derby and [[Matlock, Derbyshire|Matlock]], the [[Buxton line|Buxton]] and [[Glossop line|Glossop]] lines, linking them to Manchester, and the [[Huddersfield line]] from Manchester to Huddersfield.<ref name=\"Public Transport \u2013 Peak District National Park Authority\">{{cite web|url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/visiting/publictransport |title=Public Transport \u2013 Peak District National Park Authority |publisher=Peak District |year=2012 |accessdate=3 April 2012}}</ref> Coach services provide access to Matlock, Bakewell and Buxton from Derby, [[Nottingham]] and Manchester through [[High Peak (bus company)|TransPeak]] and [[National Express Coaches|National Express]], and there are regular buses from Sheffield, Glossop, Stoke, [[Leek, Staffordshire|Leek]] and Chesterfield. The nearest airports are [[Manchester Airport|Manchester]], [[Doncaster Sheffield Airport|Doncaster Sheffield]], and [[East Midlands Airport|East Midlands]].<ref name=\"Public Transport \u2013 Peak District National Park Authority\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.essentialtravelguide.com/regional-guides/midlands/peak-district-travel-guide/peak-district-facts/|title=Peak District Quick Facts & Figures|publisher=Essential Travel Guide|accessdate=15 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn rural areas, villages are served by internal transport links. Minibuses operate from the towns to smaller villages. The Hope Valley and Buxton Line trains serve stations at  Hathersage, Hope and Edale.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.derbyshire-peakdistrict.co.uk/publictransportII.htm |title=Public Transport in Derbyshire and the Peak District |publisher=Discover Derbyshire and the Peak District |year=2009 |accessdate=22 June 2009}}</ref>\n\nCycle England invested \u00a31.25&nbsp;million to build and improve cycle routes in the national park for leisure and commuting.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/index/news/news-display-page.htm?id=20324 |title=Pedal power to help residents and visitors lead more active lifestyles \u2013 Peak District National Park Authority |publisher=Peak District |date=7 October 2009 |accessdate=16 October 2009|archivedate=7 July 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707225811/http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/index/news/news-display-page.htm?id=20324 }}</ref> \n\n==Conservation issues==\n[[Image:Derwent walkers.jpg|thumb|right|Walkers above the [[Derwent Reservoir (Derbyshire)|Derwent Reservoir]]]]\nThe proximity of the Peak to major conurbations and urban areas (an estimated 20 million people live within an hour's drive)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bygonederbyshire.co.uk/places/Peak-District-National-Park/article-1772758-detail/article.html |title=Peak District National Park |publisher=ByGoneDerbyshire.co.uk |date=28 January 2010 |accessdate=26 September 2010}}</ref> poses challenges for managing the area. The park authority, the National Trust and other landowners attempt to keep the upland landscape accessible for recreation while protecting it from intensive farming, [[erosion]] and pressure from visitors. Tension exists between the needs of the 38,000 residents,<ref name=\"Place_called_home\" /> the needs of the millions of people who visit,<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite news |last=Moss |first=C. |title=Oops, there goes another bit of Britain |url=https://www.theguardian.com/travel/2004/feb/28/unitedkingdom.guardiansaturdaytravelsection |work=The Guardian  |date=28 February 2004 |accessdate=22 May 2009}}</ref> and conservation requirements.\n\nThe uneven distribution of visitors creates stresses. Dovedale alone receives about two million visitors annually.<ref name=\"South_Peak\" /> Other highly visited areas include Bakewell, Castleton and the [[Hope Valley, Derbyshire|Hope Valley]], Chatsworth, Hartington and the reservoirs of the Upper Derwent Valley.<ref name=\"Tourism_factsheet\">{{cite web|url=http://www.peakdistrict-nationalpark.info/studyArea/factsheets/02.html#whoVisits |title=Tourism in the Peak District National Park |publisher=Peak District National Park |year=2003 |accessdate=22 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20050331060949/http://www.peakdistrict-nationalpark.info/studyArea/factsheets/02.html |archivedate=31 March 2005 }}</ref> More than 60% of visits take place between May and September, with Sunday the busiest day.<ref name=\"Tourism_factsheet\" />\n\nFootpath users in the more popular walking areas have contributed to serious erosion problems, particularly on the fragile [[peat]] moorlands. The use of some paths by mountain bikers is believed to have exacerbated the problem.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peakdistrict-nationalpark.info/studyArea/factsheets/14.html#7 |title=Peak District National Park: Study Area \u2013 Footpath Erosion |publisher=Peak District National Park |accessdate=22 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20050901152656/http://www.peakdistrict-nationalpark.info/studyArea/factsheets/14.html |archivedate=1 September 2005 }}</ref> Measures to contain the damage include the diversion of the official route of the Pennine Way out of Edale, which now goes via Jacob's Ladder rather than following the Grindsbrook, and surfacing moorland footpaths with expensive natural stone paving.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peakdistrict-nationalpark.info/studyArea/factsheets/14.html#9 |title=Peak District National Park: Study Area \u2013 The Pennine Way |publisher=Peak District National Park |accessdate=22 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20050901152656/http://www.peakdistrict-nationalpark.info/studyArea/factsheets/14.html |archivedate=1 September 2005 }}</ref> Some rights of way have been damaged by legal and illegal use by off-road vehicles such as [[Four-wheel drive|4\u00d74s]] and [[trail bike]]s. Campaigners have sought to reduce their impact.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.friendsofthepeak.org.uk/campaigns/take-back-the-tracks/ |title=Take back the tracks |publisher=Friends of the Peak District |date= |accessdate=14 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nLarge-scale limestone quarrying is contentious. Most mineral extraction licences were issued by national government for 90 years in the 1950s and remain legally binding. The park authority has a policy of considering applications for new quarries and licence renewal in the park in terms of the local and national need for the mineral and how unique the source is, in conjunction with the effects on traffic,  residents and the environment.<ref name=\"Mineral_factsheet\" /> Some licences have not been renewed; the RMC Aggregates quarry at [[Eldon Hill]] closed in 1999 and landscaped.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/bap-report2002.pdf |title=Peak District Biodiversity Action Plan |publisher=Peak District |date= October 2002 |accessdate=13 November 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720111424/http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/bap-report2002.pdf|archivedate=20 July 2011}}</ref> Proposals from Stancliffe Stone Ltd to re-open dormant gritstone quarries at Stanton Moor in 1999 became a test case, hotly contested by ecological protesters and residents on the grounds that the development would threaten Bronze Age remains at the Nine Ladies Stone Circle, and damage the natural landscape.<ref name=\"Guardian\" /> In 2007, negotiations took place to relocate the development to Dale View quarry in a less sensitive area.<ref>{{cite news |title=End in sight for quarry wrangle on historic moor |url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/index/news/news-display-page.htm?id=14775 |work=Peak District |date=5 September 2007 |accessdate=12 September 2007|archivedate=20 July 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720112449/http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/index/news/news-display-page.htm?id=14775 }}</ref>\n\n==Peak District in literature and arts==\nThe landscapes of the Peak have inspired writers for centuries. Various places have been identified by Ralph Elliott and others as locations in the 14th-century poem ''[[Sir Gawain and the Green Knight]]''; [[Lud's Church]] is thought to be the [[Green Chapel]].<ref>{{cite book |title=A Companion to the Gawain-Poet |last1=Elliott |first1=R. W. V. |last2=Brewer |first2=Derek |authorlink2=Derek Brewer |last3=Gibson |first3=J. |chapter=Landscape and Geography |year=1999 |isbn=0-85991-529-8 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/companiontogawai0000unse/page/105 105\u2013117] |publisher=[[Derek Brewer|Brewer D. S]] |chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/companiontogawai0000unse/page/105 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Chatsworth showing hunting tower.jpg|thumb|left|[[Chatsworth House]], the setting for a recent adaptation of ''[[Pride and Prejudice]]'']]\nKey scenes in [[Jane Austen]]'s 1813 novel ''[[Pride and Prejudice]]'' are set in the Peak.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gutenberg.org/etext/1342 |title=Pride and Prejudice by Jane Austen |publisher=Project Gutenberg |year=2003 |accessdate=13 September 2007}}</ref>\n''[[Peveril of the Peak]]'' (1823) by [[Walter Scott|Sir Walter Scott]] is a historical novel set at Peveril Castle, Castleton during the reign of [[Charles II of England|Charles II]].<ref>{{PastScape |mnumber=309632 |mname=Peveril Castle |year=2007 |accessdate=12 September 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=The Cambridge Guide to Literature in English |last=Ousby |first=I. |editor=Ousby I |year=1993 |edition=2nd |isbn=0-521-44086-6 |page=[https://archive.org/details/cambridgeguideto00iano_0/page/734 734] |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |url=https://archive.org/details/cambridgeguideto00iano_0/page/734 }}</ref> [[William Wordsworth]] was a frequent visitor to Matlock; the Peak inspired several of his poems, including an 1830 [[sonnet]] to Chatsworth House.<ref name=\"Peak_Experience\">{{cite web |url=http://www.peak-experience.org.uk/tourism/explore-the-guides/peak-experience-guides/peak-film-literature/ |title=Peak Film & Literature |publisher=Peak Experience |accessdate=12 September 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070905105904/http://www.peak-experience.org.uk/tourism/explore-the-guides/peak-experience-guides/peak-film-literature/ |archivedate=5 September 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The village of [[Morton, Derbyshire|Morton]] in [[Charlotte Bront\u00eb]]'s 1847 novel ''[[Jane Eyre]]'' is based on Hathersage, where Bront\u00eb stayed in 1845, and [[Thornfield Hall]] might have been inspired by nearby North Lees Hall.<ref>{{cite book |title=Jane Eyre |last=Bront\u00eb |first=C. |authorlink=Charlotte Bront\u00eb |year=1996 |isbn=0-14-043400-3 |page=[https://archive.org/details/janeeyre00bron_1/page/526 526] |publisher=[[Penguin Books]] |url=https://archive.org/details/janeeyre00bron_1/page/526 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=The Bront\u00ebs |last=Barker |first=J. |authorlink=Juliet Barker |year=1995 |isbn=1-85799-069-2 |pages=451\u2013453 |publisher=[[Weidenfeld & Nicolson]]}}</ref> Snowfield in [[George Eliot]]'s first novel ''[[Adam Bede]]'' (1859) is believed to be based on Wirksworth, where her uncle managed a mill; [[Ellastone]] (as Hayslope) and [[Ashbourne, Derbyshire|Ashbourne]] (as Oakbourne) also feature.<ref name=\"Peak_Experience\" />\n\n[[Beatrix Potter]], the author of [[Peter Rabbit]], visited her uncle [[Edmund Potter]] at his printworks in [[Dinting Vale]]. She copied cloth samples from his pattern book to dress her characters. Mrs Tiggywinkle's shawl, in [[The Tale of Mrs. Tiggy-Winkle]], is based on pattern number 222714.<ref>{{cite web |last=Potter |first=E. |authorlink=Edmund Potter |title=Dinting Vale Printworks cotton sample pattern book |url=http://www.spinningtheweb.org.uk/sea_cat_display.php?irn=3004030&sub=&theme=overview&crumb= |work=Spinning the Web |publisher=[[Manchester City Council]] |year=1892 |accessdate=28 June 2009}}</ref>\n\nChildren's author [[Alison Uttley]] (1884\u20131976) was born at [[Cromford]]; her novel ''A Traveller in Time'', set in [[Dethick, Lea and Holloway|Dethick]], recounts the [[Babington Plot]] to free [[Mary, Queen of Scots]], from imprisonment.<ref name=\"Peakland_Heritage\">{{cite web |url=http://www.peaklandheritage.org.uk/index.asp?peakkey=40600721 |title=Peakland Writers |publisher=Peakland Heritage |year=2008 |accessdate=12 September 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071107175202/http://www.peaklandheritage.org.uk/index.asp?peakkey=40600721 |archivedate=7 November 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Crichton Porteous]] (1901\u201391) set several books in locations in the Peak; ''Toad Hole'', ''Lucky Columbell'' and ''Broken River'' are set in the [[Upper Derwent Valley|Derwent Valley]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aboutderbyshire.co.uk/cms/people/crichton-porteous-derbysh.shtml |title=Crichton Porteous \u2013 Derbyshire Writer |publisher=About Derbyshire |date=3 June 2007 |accessdate=12 September 2007}}</ref> [[Geraldine Brooks (writer)|Geraldine Brooks]]'s first novel, ''[[Year of Wonders]]'' (2001), blends fact and fiction to tell the story of the plague village of Eyam.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://geraldinebrooks.com/the-books/year-of-wonders/|title=Year of Wonders |publisher=GeraldineBrooks.com |year=2007 |accessdate=13 November 2013}}</ref> Eyam also inspired ''Children of Winter'' by children's novelist [[Berlie Doherty]] who has set several other works in the Peak, including ''Deep Secret'', based on the drowning of the villages of [[Derwent, Derbyshire|Derwent]] and [[Ashopton]] by the Ladybower Reservoir, and ''Blue John'', inspired by the cavern at Castleton.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.berliedoherty.com/novelsf.html |title=Berlie Doherty: novels |publisher=BerlieDoherty.com |year=2003 |accessdate=12 September 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070802221528/http://www.berliedoherty.com/novelsf.html |archivedate=2 August 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref>{{Clear}}\n \n[[File:Ladybower.jpg|thumb|right|[[Ladybower Reservoir]] in the Upper Derwent Valley, set location for ''[[The Dam Busters (film)|The Dam Busters]]'']]Many works of crime and horror have been set in the Peak. ''[[The Terror of Blue John Gap]]'' by [[Arthur Conan Doyle|Sir Arthur Conan Doyle]] (1859\u20131930) recounts terrible events at the Blue John mines,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gutenberg.org/etext/537 |title=Tales of Terror and Mystery by Sir Arthur Conan Doyle |publisher=Gutenberg |year=2008 |accessdate=13 September 2007}}</ref> and [[Sherlock Holmes]] investigates the kidnapping of a child in ''[[The Adventure of the Priory School]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ignisart.com/camdenhouse/canon/prio.htm |title=The Adventure of the Priory School |publisher=Camden House \u2013 The Complete Sherlock Holmes |year=1998 |accessdate=13 September 2007}}</ref> Many horror stories by local author [[Robert Murray Gilchrist]] feature Peak settings.<ref name=\"Peak_Experience\" /> [[Stephen Booth (writer)|Stephen Booth]] has written a series of crime novels set in real and imagined Peak locations,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stephen-booth.com/New%20books.htm |title=Stephen Booth \u2013 New Books |publisher=StephenBooth.com |accessdate=12 September 2007}}</ref> while ''In Pursuit of the Proper Sinner'', an [[The Inspector Lynley Mysteries|Inspector Lynley mystery]] by [[Elizabeth George]], is set on the fictional Calder Moor.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.elizabethgeorgeonline.com/books/in_pursuit_of_sinner.htm |title=Novel \u2013 In Pursuit of the Proper Sinner |publisher=Elizabeth George Online |accessdate=12 September 2007}}</ref>\n\nOther writers and poets who lived in or visited the Peak include [[Samuel Johnson]], [[William Congreve]], [[Anna Seward]], [[Jean-Jacques Rousseau]], [[George Gordon Byron, 6th Baron Byron|Lord Byron]], [[Thomas Moore]], [[Richard Furness]], [[D. H. Lawrence]], [[Vera Brittain]], [[Richmal Crompton]] and [[Nathaniel Gould|Nat Gould]].<ref name=\"Peak_Experience\" /><ref name=\"Peakland_Heritage\" /> The landscapes and historic houses are popular settings for film and television. The classic 1955 film ''[[The Dam Busters (film)|The Dam Busters]]'' was filmed at the Upper [[Derwent Reservoir (Derbyshire)|Derwent Valley reservoirs]], where practice flights for the bombing raids on the [[Ruhr (river)|Ruhr]] dams had been made during the Second World War.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0046889/locations |title=Filming locations for The Dam Busters |website=[[Internet Movie Database]] |year=1990 |accessdate=13 September 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn adaptations of ''Pride and Prejudice'', [[Longnor, Staffordshire|Longnor]] has featured as Lambton, and Lyme Park and Chatsworth House have stood in for [[Pemberley]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0112130/locations |title=Filming locations for Pride and Prejudice (1995) |website=[[Internet Movie Database]] |year=1995 |accessdate=12 September 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0414387/locations |title=Filming locations for Pride and Prejudice (2005) |website=[[Internet Movie Database]] |year=2005 |accessdate=12 September 2007}}</ref> Haddon Hall doubled as [[Thornfield Hall]] in two different adaptations of ''Jane Eyre'' and has appeared in several films including ''[[Elizabeth (film)|Elizabeth]]'', ''[[The Princess Bride (film)|The Princess Bride]]'' and ''[[The Other Boleyn Girl (2008 film)|The Other Boleyn Girl]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.haddonhall.co.uk/film.htm |title=Film & Photoshoots |publisher=Haddon Hall |accessdate=22 June 2009}}</ref> The television medical drama ''[[Peak Practice]]'' set in the fictional village of Cardale was filmed in [[Crich]], Matlock and other Peak locations.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0106097/locations |title=Filming locations for Peak Practice |website=[[Internet Movie Database]] |year=1993 |accessdate=12 September 2007}}</ref> The world's longest-running sitcom, ''[[Last of the Summer Wine]]'', was filmed in [[Holmfirth]] and the surrounding [[Holme Valley]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Last of the Summer Wine country, Holmfirth, West Yorkshire |url=https://www.theguardian.com/travel/2009/jun/07/summer-wine-walking-guide-holmfirth |newspaper=The Guardian  |date=7 June 2009|accessdate=2 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Cheshire}}\n*[[Derbyshire moors]]\n*[[List of hills in the Peak District]]\n*[[Forest of High Peak]], a royal hunting reserve in medieval times in the area\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Peak District}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Peak District}}\n<!-- ==============================({{NoMoreLinks}})============================== -->\n<!-- DO NOT ADD MORE LINKS TO THIS ARTICLE. WIKIPEDIA IS NOT A COLLECTION OF LINKS -->\n<!-- If you think that your link might be useful,  instead of placing it here, put -->\n<!-- it on this article's discussion page first. Links that have not been verified -->\n<!--                                WILL BE DELETED                                -->\n<!-- ============================================================================= -->\n*[http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/ Official website of the Peak District National Park Authority]\n*[http://peakdistrict.nationaltrust.org.uk/ Peak District] at [[The National Trust]]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060828212309/http://bgs.ac.uk/foundation-web/Foundation_Home.html Foundations of the Peak] \u2013 geological information at [[British Geological Survey]]\n*[https://www.visitpeakdistrict.com/ Visit Peak District & Derbyshire] official Tourist information\n\n{{National_parks_in_the_UK}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Peak District| ]]\n[[Category:Climbing areas of England]]\n[[Category:Geography of Cheshire]]\n[[Category:Geography of Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Geography of Greater Manchester]]\n[[Category:Geology of Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Geography of Staffordshire]]\n[[Category:National parks in England]]\n[[Category:Parks and open spaces in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Protected areas established in 1951]]\n", "name_user": "JulieGough", "label": "safe", "comment": "Link to other page", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peak_District"}
{"title_page": "Onward (film)", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|reason=Persistent addition of [[WP:INTREF|unsourced or poorly sourced content]]|small=yes}}\n{{short description|2020 film directed by Dan Scanlon}}\n{{Use American English|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Onward\n| image          = Onward poster.jpg\n| border         = no\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Dan Scanlon]]\n| producer       = [[Kori Rae]]\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* Dan Scanlon\n* Jason Headley\n* [[Keith Bunin]]\n}}\n| story          = {{Plainlist|\n* Dan Scanlon\n* Keith Bunin\n* Jason Headley\n}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Tom Holland (actor)|Tom Holland]]\n* [[Chris Pratt]]\n* [[Julia Louis-Dreyfus]]\n* [[Octavia Spencer]]\n}}\n| music          = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Mychael Danna]]<ref name=\"DannaScore\">{{cite web |url=http://filmmusicreporter.com/2019/04/16/mychael-jeff-danna-to-score-pixars-onward/ |title=Mychael & Jeff Danna to Score Pixar's 'Onward' \u2013 Film Music Reporter |publisher=|access-date=April 17, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417121323/http://filmmusicreporter.com/2019/04/16/mychael-jeff-danna-to-score-pixars-onward/|archive-date=April 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Jeff Danna]]<ref name=\"DannaScore\" />\n}}\n| cinematography = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Sharon Calahan]]\n* Adam Habib\n}}\n| editing        = Catherine Apple<ref>{{cite web|title=Catherine Apple|date=December 7, 2019|url=https://collider.com/how-does-pixar-make-movies-ccxp/|publisher=collider|accessdate=December 8, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191207221911/https://collider.com/how-does-pixar-make-movies-ccxp/|archive-date=December 7, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Walt Disney Pictures]]\n* [[Pixar Animation Studios]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures|Walt Disney Studios<br />Motion Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2020|2|21|[[Berlin International Film Festival|Berlinale]]|2020|3|6|United States}}\n| runtime        = 103 minutes<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.berlinale.de/en/programme/programme/detail.html?film_id=202012642|title=Programme - Onward|website=[[Berlin International Film Festival|Berlinale]]|language=en|access-date=2020-02-16}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $175\u2013200 million<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/box-office-onward-international-coronavirus-1203527183/|title=Box Office: 'Onward' Debuts to $28 Million Overseas Amid Coronavirus Outbreak|author=Rebecca Rubin|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=March 8, 2020|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308192742/https://variety.com/2020/film/news/box-office-onward-international-coronavirus-1203527183/|archive-date=March 8, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| gross          = $103.2 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl3433267713/?ref_=bo_hm_rs |title=Onward (2020) |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |access-date=April 10, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229183631/https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl3433267713/?ref_=bo_hm_rs |archive-date=February 29, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Onward''''' is a 2020 American [[computer-animated]] [[urban fantasy]] film produced by [[Pixar Animation Studios]] for [[Walt Disney Pictures]]. The film is directed by [[Dan Scanlon]], produced by [[Kori Rae]] from a screenplay written by Scanlon, Jason Headley, and [[Keith Bunin]], and stars the voices of [[Tom Holland (actor)|Tom Holland]], [[Chris Pratt]], [[Julia Louis-Dreyfus]], and [[Octavia Spencer]]. Set in a suburban fantasy world, the film follows two elf brothers who set out on a quest to find an artifact that will bring back their deceased father.<ref name=\"Synopsis\">{{cite news |url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/pixar-disney-untitled-suburban-fantasy-world-unicorns-d23-1202496455/ |title=D23: Pixar Announces Untitled Quest Movie Set in 'Suburban Fantasy World' |last=Variety staff |date=July 14, 2017 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=July 21, 2017 |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170715013545/https://variety.com/2017/film/news/pixar-disney-untitled-suburban-fantasy-world-unicorns-d23-1202496455/|archive-date=July 15, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe film premiered at the [[70th Berlin International Film Festival]] on February 21, 2020 and was released in the United States on March 6. It received generally positive reviews from critics and has grossed $103 million worldwide. The film's financial shortcomings were attributed to the [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], which resulted in theaters around the globe being closed. Like several other films released in March, it was made available digitally two weeks after its theatrical release.\n\n==Plot==\nIn a world inhabited by [[Legendary creature|mythical creatures]], magic was once commonplace, though difficult to master. After technological advances over the years, magic became obsolete and was largely discarded.\n\nIn a time equivalent to the modern day, Ian Lightfoot, an [[elf]] high-schooler lacking self-confidence, and his older brother Barley, a history and [[role-playing game]] fanatic, live in the city of New Mushroomton. Their father Wilden died shortly before Ian was born, and their mother Laurel has a new boyfriend, [[centaur]] police officer Colt Bronco, whom both Ian and Barley dislike.\n\nOn Ian's sixteenth birthday, Laurel gives the brothers a gift from Wilden: a magical staff, a rare gem, and a letter describing a \"visitation spell\" that can resurrect their father for a single day. Ian accidentally succeeds in casting the spell, but only the lower half of Wilden's body is reformed before the gem disintegrates. The brothers embark on a quest to acquire another gem and complete the spell, taking Barley's beloved [[van]] \"Guinevere\". Finding the boys gone, Laurel leaves to find them.\n\nIan and Barley visit the [[Manticore]]\u2019s Tavern, named for a monster possessing a map to the gem. The tavern has become a [[family restaurant]] managed by the Manticore, legally named The Manticore, also known as \"Corey\". Arguing with Ian over the map, The Manticore realizes how boring her life has become and drives the customers away in a fit of rage, accidentally setting fire to the restaurant and the map. The brothers' only clue to the gem is a children's menu suggesting \"Raven's Point\", a nearby mountain. Laurel later arrives at the scene and befriends The Manticore, who agrees to help her. The Manticore warns that the brothers' journey may awaken a curse that can only be defeated by her special sword, which she and Laurel steal from a [[Pawnbroker|pawn shop]]. \n\nTraveling to the mountains, Ian and Barley narrowly escape the police and a [[Outlaw motorcycle club|motorcycle gang]] of [[pixies]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sims |first1=David |title=Pixar Needs to Make More Movies Like 'Onward' |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2020/02/onward-movie-review-dan-scanlon-chris-pratt/606736/ |website=The Atlantic |accessdate=22 March 2020 |date=21 February 2020}}</ref>, relying on Ian's newly awakened spell-casting abilities and Barley's role-playing game instincts. \"Raven's Point\" leads them on a trail indicated by a series of [[raven]] statues, but Colt follows them, calling in reinforcements. Barley sacrifices Guinevere to cause a landslide, blocking their pursuers. Following the statues, the brothers descend through a cave and avoid a series of traps and deadly creatures, surfacing to find themselves in front of Ian's high school. Ian lashes out at Barley for leading them on a wild goose chase and walks away with Wilden. \n\nRereading his list of things he always wished to do with his father, Ian realizes that Barley has been a father figure throughout his entire life, and returns to make amends. Barley discovers the gem inside a historic fountain and retrieves it, unwittingly triggering the curse The Manticore spoke of, which turns the high school into an artificial dragon bent on claiming the gem. Ian faces the artificial dragon, but his staff is knocked into the ocean; he reforms it from a splinter and continues the fight. The Manticore flies in carrying Laurel, who plunges the magic sword into the artificial dragon's heart, buying Ian time to cast the visitation spell and fully reform Wilden's body. Ian sends Barley ahead to give his goodbye to Wilden, and holds off the artificial dragon long enough for Laurel to destroy it. After Wilden dissipates, Barley tells Ian that their father is proud of him, and the brothers share a hug.\n\nIan's confidence and spell-casting improve and he surprises Barley by painting his new van, the \"Guinevere 2\", while they both improve their relationship with Colt. The Manticore reopens her tavern in its original spirit, drawing in customers with tales of past adventures, and Ian and Barley continue questing.\n\n==Voice cast==\n{{cast listing|\n* [[Tom Holland (actor)|Tom Holland]] as Ian Lightfoot,<ref name=VarietyDec2018/><ref name=firstlook /> a teenaged [[elf]] who is Barley's younger brother and Laurel and Wilden's son.\n* [[Chris Pratt]] as Barley Lightfoot,<ref name=VarietyDec2018/><ref name=firstlook>{{cite web |url=https://www.pixarpost.com/2019/05/pixar-onward-first-look.html |title=Breaking: First Look at Characters Ian and Barley Lightfoot from Pixar's Suburban Fantasy Film, 'Onward' (In Theaters March 6, 2020) |author=Pixar Post |publisher=|access-date=May 29, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190529172427/https://www.pixarpost.com/2019/05/pixar-onward-first-look.html|archive-date=May 29, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Ian's older brother, and Laurel and Wilden's son who longs for a magical quest.\n* [[Julia Louis-Dreyfus]] as Laurel Lightfoot,<ref name=VarietyDec2018/><ref name=firstlook /><ref name=\"Clips\">{{cite web |url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/news/pixar-onward-chris-pratt-tom-holland/ |title=D23: Pixar Brings New Onward Clips |last=White |first=James |date=August 25, 2019 |website=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]] |accessdate=August 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190825105550/https://www.empireonline.com/movies/news/pixar-onward-chris-pratt-tom-holland/|archive-date=August 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> the widowed mother of Ian and Barley.\n* [[Octavia Spencer]] as The \"Corey\" Manticore, a [[manticore]] restaurant owner and former adventurer whom Ian and Barley go to for help on their quest.\n* [[Mel Rodriguez]] as Colt Bronco, a [[centaur]] police officer and Laurel's new husband.<ref name=twit3600/>\n* [[Kyle Bornheimer]] as Wilden Lightfoot, Ian and Barley's late father and Laurel's late husband.<ref name=\"WholeCast\" />\n* [[Lena Waithe]] as Specter, a [[cyclops]] police officer.<ref name=twit3600/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://insidethemagic.net/2020/02/onward-first-openly-lgbtq-bt1/|title=Disney-Pixar's \"Onward\" Will Feature the First Openly LGBTQ Character|date=February 22, 2020|via=Inside the Magic|access-date=February 22, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222040111/https://insidethemagic.net/2020/02/onward-first-openly-lgbtq-bt1/|archive-date=February 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2020/02/24/pixars-first-out-gay-character-to-be-voiced-by-lena-waithe-in-onward/|title=Pixar's first out gay character to be voiced by Lena Waithe in 'Onward'|last=Frishberg|first=Hannah|date=February 24, 2020|website=[[New York Post]]|access-date=February 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225133013/https://nypost.com/2020/02/24/pixars-first-out-gay-character-to-be-voiced-by-lena-waithe-in-onward/|archive-date=February 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Ali Wong]] as Gore, a [[faun]] police officer.<ref name=twit3600>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/pixaronward/status/1206620188709273600|title=Behold: Character posters for #PixarOnward, including newly-announced cast @AliWong, @LenaWaithe, and @_MelRodriguez_.\u2728 Check back tomorrow to see the brand-new trailer for the film|via=[[Twitter]]|access-date=December 16, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191217032256/https://twitter.com/pixaronward/status/1206620188709273600|archive-date=December 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Grey DeLisle|Grey Griffin]] as Dewdrop, a [[pixie]] and the leader of the Pixie Dusters [[Outlaw motorcycle club|biker gang]].\n* [[Tracey Ullman]] as Grecklin, a [[gremlin]] pawn shop owner.<ref name=\"WholeCast\" />\n* [[Wilmer Valderrama]] as Gaxton, an elf and college friend of Wilden.<ref name=\"WholeCast\" />\n* George Psarras as Avel, an elf police officer.<ref name=\"WholeCast\" />\n* [[John Ratzenberger]] as Fenwick, a cyclops construction worker.<ref name=\"WholeCast\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/snyde/ny-stars-attend-the-world-premiere-of-disney-pixar-onward-20200219-547inowgbnbhxnnziyywj3eu6a-photogallery.html|title=Stars attended the world premiere of Disney Pixar's \"Onward\" at the El Capitan Theatre on Feb. 18, 2020 in Hollywood, Calif.|website=New York Daily News|accessdate=February 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221191311/https://www.nydailynews.com/snyde/ny-stars-attend-the-world-premiere-of-disney-pixar-onward-20200219-547inowgbnbhxnnziyywj3eu6a-photogallery.html|archive-date=February 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Production ==\n===Development===\nIn July 2017, Pixar announced a \"suburban fantasy world\" film at the [[D23 Expo]], with Scanlon directing and Rae producing.<ref name=\"Synopsis\"/> The film was inspired by the death of Scanlon's father, when he and his brother were younger, and their relationship. He decided to write the story after hearing an audio clip of his father.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3025627/pixar-suburban-fantasy-film-dan-scanlon/ |title=Pixar's New 'Suburban Fantasy' Sounds Like A Real Tearjerker |last=Bell |first=Crystal |date=July 17, 2017 |website=[[MTV News]] |publisher=[[MTV]]|access-date=April 6, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170718003125/http://www.mtv.com/news/3025627/pixar-suburban-fantasy-film-dan-scanlon/|archive-date=July 18, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> On December 12, 2018, the title was revealed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/pixar-moves-forward-with-suburban-fantasy-film-onward-cast-includes-chris-pratt-tom-holland |title=Pixar Moves Forward with Suburban Fantasy Film 'Onward'; Cast Includes Chris Pratt, Tom Holland |last=Weiss |first=Josh |date=December 12, 2018 |website=[[Syfy]] |publisher=[[NBCUniversal Cable Entertainment Group]] |accessdate=December 12, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181212222813/https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/pixar-moves-forward-with-suburban-fantasy-film-onward-cast-includes-chris-pratt-tom-holland|archive-date=December 12, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2019, Headley and Bunin were hired to rewrite the screenplay.\n\n===Casting===\nOn December 12, 2018, Holland, Pratt, Louis-Dreyfus and Spencer were announced as starring in the film.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/onward-pixar-movie-chris-pratt-tom-holland-julia-louis-dreyfus-octavia-spencer-cast-1202518598/ |title=Pixar's 'Onward' To Star Chris Pratt, Tom Holland, Julia Louis-Dreyfus & Octavia Spencer |last=Hipes |first=Patrick |date=December 12, 2018 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |accessdate=December 12, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181212221000/https://deadline.com/2018/12/onward-pixar-movie-chris-pratt-tom-holland-julia-louis-dreyfus-octavia-spencer-cast-1202518598/|archive-date=December 12, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> While having recorded most of their lines separately, Holland and Pratt did some of their recording sessions together since, according to Scanlon, \"they've worked together before and hung out together\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Falcone |first1=Dana Rose |title=See Chris Pratt, Julia Louis-Dreyfus & Tom Holland as Elves in Disney-Pixar's Onward: First Look! |url=https://www.people.com/movies/chris-pratt-julia-louis-dreyfus-tom-holland-onward/ |website=People |date=May 29, 2019|access-date=May 30, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190529215133/https://people.com/movies/chris-pratt-julia-louis-dreyfus-tom-holland-onward/|archive-date=May 29, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> According to Rae, Holland and Pratt improvised some of their lines while recording together.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.digitalspy.com/movies/a30415714/tom-holland-chris-pratt-onward-cast-interview/ |title=Marvel's Tom Holland and Chris Pratt being cast in Onward was \"dumb luck\" |date=January 6, 2020 |access-date=February 22, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222042437/https://www.digitalspy.com/movies/a30415714/tom-holland-chris-pratt-onward-cast-interview/ |archive-date=February 22, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On December 17, 2019, Wong, Waithe and Rodriguez joined the cast of the film.<ref name=twit3600/> On February 18, 2020, Valderrama, Ullman, Bornheimer, Psarras and Ratzenberger were revealed to have been cast on the film.<ref name=\"WholeCast\"/>\n\n===Music===\nOn April 16, 2019, [[Mychael Danna|Mychael]] and [[Jeff Danna]] were revealed to be the film's composers.<ref name=\"DannaScore\"/> On February 12, 2020, [[Brandi Carlile]] revealed she recorded the song \"Carried Me With You\" for the film's end credits. She co-wrote it with Phil and Tim Hanseroth.<ref name=\"variety1\">{{cite news |last1=Willman |first1=Chris |title=Brandi Carlile Records Theme Song for Pixar Pic 'Onward' |url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/brandi-carlile-records-theme-song-pixar-onward-1203502224/ |accessdate=17 February 2020 |publisher=Variety |date=12 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200214151349/https://variety.com/2020/film/news/brandi-carlile-records-theme-song-pixar-onward-1203502224/ |archive-date=February 14, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The film's soundtrack was released on February 28, 2020.<ref name=\"variety1\"/>\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline = '''''Onward: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack'''''\n| extra_column = Performer\n| all_music = [[Mychael Danna]] and [[Jeff Danna]], except where noted\n| total_length = 1:02:32\n\n| title1 = Carried Me with You\n| writer1 = [[Brandi Carlile]], Phil and Tim Hanseroth\n| extra1 = Carlile\n| length1 = 3:33\n\n| title2 = Quests of Yore\n| length2 = 0:52\n\n| title3 = The World Was Full of Wonder\n| length3 = 1:37\n\n| title4 = A Little Magic\n| length4 = 0:43\n\n| title5 = Bad Dragon\n| length5 = 1:03\n\n| title6 = New Ian\n| length6 = 2:36\n\n| title7 = My Mighty Steed\n| length7 = 0:22\n\n| title8 = My Birthday Is Cancelled\n| length8 = 0:44\n\n| title9 = Wish I Could Spend the Day with You\n| length9 = 1:46\n\n| title10 = The Visitation Spell\n| length10 = 3:35\n\n| title11 = The Spell\n| length11 = 1:06\n\n| title12 = The Spell Only Lasts One Day\n| length12 = 0:56\n\n| title13 = Find Another Phoenix Gem\n| length13 = 0:49\n\n| title14 = Going on a Quest\n| length14 = 0:24\n\n| title15 = Laurel in Pursuit\n| length15 = 0:44\n\n| title16 = The Manticore's Tavern\n| length16 = 0:43\n\n| title17 = Tavern Remodeling\n| length17 = 1:12\n\n| title18 = The Map to Raven's Point\n| length18 = 1:45\n\n| title19 = Two Teenage Elves\n| length19 = 0:38\n\n| title20 = Magnora Gantuan!\n| length20 = 0:32\n\n| title21 = Baby Legs\n| length21 = 0:41\n\n| title22 = Pixie Dusters\n| length22 = 1:18\n\n| title23 = The Guardian Curse\n| length23 = 0:42\n\n| title24 = Driving Test\n| length24 = 3:17\n\n| title25 = Dance Fight\n| length25 = 2:22\n\n| title26 = Path of Peril\n| length26 = 0:41\n\n| title27 = Pawn Shop\n| length27 = 0:28\n\n| title28 = Tracking Guinevere\n| length28 = 1:04\n\n| title29 = Bottomless Pit\n| length29 = 0:56\n\n| title30 = The Trust Bridge\n| length30 = 1:20\n\n| title31 = Follow Your Gut\n| length31 = 0:52\n\n| title32 = Running from the Cops\n| length32 = 1:59\n\n| title33 = Sacrifice\n| length33 = 0:59\n\n| title34 = Just a Beat Up Old Van\n| length34 = 1:36\n\n| title35 = The Cave\n| length35 = 0:54\n\n| title36 = Accelior!\n| length36 = 0:26\n\n| title37 = Boom Bastia!\n| length37 = 0:47\n\n| title38 = Barley's Last Memory of Dad\n| length38 = 0:58\n\n| title39 = Led Us to Our Victory!\n| length39 = 1:49\n\n| title40 = The Truth Comes Out\n| length40 = 0:39\n\n| title41 = Share My Life with Him\n| length41 = 3:24\n\n| title42 = Battling the Dragon\n| length42 = 3:03\n\n| title43 = Voltar Thunderseer!\n| length43 = 0:59\n\n| title44 = Dad\n| length44 = 2:52\n\n| title45 = Magic Returns\n| length45 = 2:48\n}}\n\n===Deleted scene===\nThere was a storyboard scene where Ian, Barley, and Wilden are joined with a goat girl in the journey. Ian and the goat girl come across a booth hosted by three evil mermaids. The mermaids sing their mesmerizing song to lure the two into staying in one of three houses put for rent. Ian tries to silence them with the staff but the spell is too weak. When Ian and the goat girl are finally in a trance, the mermaids place them in one of the houses. The house they are in starts to sink into the ground. \n\nThe goat girl was omitted because the filmmakers want the film to focus on the relationship between Ian and Barley. The scene itself was removed because the filmmakers felt it was too grim.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://ew.com/movies/onward-deleted-scene-sirens-jenny-tom-holland |title = Exclusive: 'Onward' deleted scene summons sirens and a lost character}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://io9.gizmodo.com/onward-deleted-scene-features-a-capitalist-twist-on-the-1842526629 | title=Onward Deleted Scene Features a Capitalist Twist on the Siren Song}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n===Theatrical===\n''Onward'' premiered at the [[70th Berlin International Film Festival]] on February 21, 2020.<ref name=premiere>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/berlin-film-festival-lineup-competition-announced-revealed-live-1202845048/|website=[[Deadline.com]]|last=Wiseman|first=Andreas|date=January 29, 2020|title=Berlin Competition Lineup: Kelly Reichardt, Sally Potter, Abel Ferrara, Christian Petzold; Disney's 'Onward' & Hillary Clinton Also Heading To Fest|accessdate=February 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130153631/https://deadline.com/2020/01/berlin-film-festival-lineup-competition-announced-revealed-live-1202845048/|archive-date=January 30, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It was released in the United States on March 6.<ref name=\"VarietyDec2018\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/chris-pratt-tom-holland-julia-louis-dreyfus-octavia-spencer-onward-1203088174/ |title=Chris Pratt, Tom Holland, Julia Louis-Dreyfus, Octavia Spencer to Voice Pixar's 'Onward' |last1=McNary |first1=Dave |date=December 12, 2018 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |accessdate=December 12, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181212222451/https://variety.com/2018/film/news/chris-pratt-tom-holland-julia-louis-dreyfus-octavia-spencer-onward-1203088174/|archive-date=December 12, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> A new short film titled ''[[Playdate with Destiny]]'', centered around [[Maggie Simpson]] of ''[[The Simpsons]]'', appears before the feature film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/simpsons-short-film/|title=New 'The Simpsons' Short Film To Play In Theaters In Front of Pixar's 'Onward'|date=February 28, 2020|access-date=February 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228181730/https://www.slashfilm.com/simpsons-short-film/|archive-date=February 28, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B9GRqCFnI6M/|title=Maggie Simpson is speechless... Playdate with Destiny, a new Simpsons short film before Disney & Pixar's Onward. Exclusively in theaters! #TheSimpsons|author=thesimpsons on [[Instagram]]|date=February 27, 2020|access-date=February 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228061700/https://www.instagram.com/p/B9GRqCFnI6M/|archive-date=February 28, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n''Onward'' was released [[Digital distribution|digitally]] on the night of March 20, 2020 and became available for [[Disney+]] subscribers on April 3, 2020 in the United States. The announcement followed Disney's earlier than planned release of ''[[Frozen II]]'' on Disney+ due to the  [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://collider.com/onward-digital-release-disney-plus-details/ |title=Pixar's ''Onward'' Is Getting an Early Digital and Disney+ Release |website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]] |last=Gemmill |first=Allie|date=March 20, 2020 |accessdate=March 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Over its first week of home release, the film was the sixth-most watched on [[Prime Video|Amazon Prime]] and second-most on the [[iTunes Store]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.indiewire.com/2020/03/farewell-box-office-premium-vod-charts-bloodshot-onward-birds-of-prey-1202220714/ |title='Farewell, Box Office: This Was the Week That Premium VOD Charts Took Flight|website=[[IndieWire]]|first=Tom|last= Brueggemann |date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> In Australia, it will be released on Disney+ on April 24, 2020.<ref name=\"ausrelease\">{{cite web|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2020/03/airdate-onward.html|title=Airdate: ''Onward''|work=TV Tonight|last=Knox|first=David|date=31 March 2020|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Marketing==\nIn May 2019, two stills from the film, featuring Barley, Ian and their mother, were revealed. The following day, the film's teaser poster was released, and the teaser trailer debuted during [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s broadcast of the [[2019 NBA Finals]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/onward-disney-pixar-trailer-poster-1202624788/ |title=Disney/Pixar 'Onward' Bows First-Look Trailer During NBA Finals Game 1 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |last=Haring |first=Bruce |date=May 30, 2019 |accessdate=June 12, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190531044356/https://deadline.com/2019/05/onward-disney-pixar-trailer-poster-1202624788/|archive-date=May 31, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The trailer was also shown with ''[[Toy Story 4]]'' and ''[[Spider-Man: Far From Home]]''. Official trailers were released in October and December 2019.\n\n== Lawsuit ==\nIn January 2020, San Francisco tattoo artist Sweet Cecily Daniher filed a copyright lawsuit against Disney, Pixar, and ''Onward'' producer Kori Rae. In September 2018, Pixar rented Daniher's \"Vanicorn\", a van decorated with a unicorn-themed mural, for use in a one-day festival. She learned about the production of ''Onward'' in May 2019 and, after seeing images of the van used by Ian and Barley Lightfoot in the film, came to believe that Pixar had copied the design of the Vanicorn in violation of her rental agreement with the company, as well as the [[Digital Millennium Copyright Act]], the [[Visual Artists Rights Act]], and the California Artists Protection Act. She sought in her suit to prohibit distribution of the film and any infringing advertisements or merchandise.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/disney-sued-by-artist-unicorn-adorned-van-pixars-onward-1274131|title=Artist Sues Disney, Pixar Over Unicorn-Adorned Van in 'Onward'|last=Cullins|first=Ashley|date=January 28, 2020|website=The Hollywood Reporter|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129154442/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/disney-sued-by-artist-unicorn-adorned-van-pixars-onward-1274131|archive-date=January 29, 2020|access-date=February 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''Onward'' grossed $61.6 million in the United States and Canada, and $41.6 million in other territories, for a worldwide total of $103.2 million.<ref name=\"BOM\"/> It was speculated the gross for the film was significantly [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema|affected by the coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2020/mar/16/coronavirus-cinema-audiences-decline-film-industry |title=Cinema audiences drop dramatically as coronavirus restrictions bite |access-date=March 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317010316/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2020/mar/16/coronavirus-cinema-audiences-decline-film-industry |archive-date=March 17, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/onward-the-hunt-invisible-man-box-office-coronavirus-1203534409/ |title=Box Office: 'Onward' Leads as Coronavirus Stunts North American Sales |access-date=March 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314224942/https://variety.com/2020/film/news/onward-the-hunt-invisible-man-box-office-coronavirus-1203534409/ |archive-date=March 14, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.digitalspy.com/movies/a31659709/onward-box-office-bloodshot-coronavirus-cinemas/ |title=Bloodshot and Onward suffer during worst US box office weekend in 22 years |date=March 16, 2020 |access-date=March 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324144029/https://www.digitalspy.com/movies/a31659709/onward-box-office-bloodshot-coronavirus-cinemas/ |archive-date=March 24, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn the United States and Canada, the film was released alongside ''[[The Way Back (2020 film)|The Way Back]]'' and the wide expansion of ''[[Emma (2020 film)|Emma]]'', and was projected to gross $45\u201350 million from 4,200 theaters in its opening weekend.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/onward-ben-affleck-the-way-back-box-office-coronavirus-1202873492/ |title=Disney-Pixar's 'Onward' Eyes $100M Global Start, Even With Coronavirus Concerns |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |first2=Nancy |last2=Tartaglione |date=March 3, 2020 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=March 4, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304013005/https://deadline.com/2020/03/onward-ben-affleck-the-way-back-box-office-coronavirus-1202873492/ |archive-date=March 4, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The film held early advance screenings on February 29, and made $650,000 from 470 theaters.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2020/03/01/onward-pixar-my-hero-academia-impractical-jokers-wendy-weekend-box-office/#449321631858 |title= Weekend Box Office: 'Onward' Sells Out, 'My Hero Academia' Surprises And 'Wendy' Flops |author= Scott Mendleson |date= March 1, 2020 |accessdate= March 4, 2020 |website= [[Forbes]] |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303203235/https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2020/03/01/onward-pixar-my-hero-academia-impractical-jokers-wendy-weekend-box-office/#449321631858 |archive-date= March 3, 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref> It then made $12.1 million on its first day, including $2 million from Thursday night previews. The film went on to debut to $39.1 million, topping the box office but marking the third-ever lowest start for a Pixar film.<ref name=opening>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/onward-opening-weekend-disney-pixar-coronavirus-invisible-man-1202876016/ |title='Onward' Seeing Blas\u00e9 $40M Domestic Opening, $68M WW: Are Coronavirus Fears Impacting B.O.? \u2013 Sunday Update |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |date=March 7, 2020 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=March 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307021204/https://deadline.com/2020/03/onward-opening-weekend-disney-pixar-coronavirus-invisible-man-1202876016/ |archive-date=March 7, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=IndieWireOpen>{{cite web|title=Pixar's 'Onward' Opens to Modest Box Office With Weekend Down $100 Million From Last Year|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2020/03/pixar-onward-box-office-weekend-1202216191/|publisher=[[IndieWire]]|date=March 7, 2020|accessdate=March 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312131725/https://www.indiewire.com/2020/03/pixar-onward-box-office-weekend-1202216191/|archive-date=March 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> While the film remained in first in its second weekend, it dropped 73% to $10.5 million (the worst-ever second weekend for a Pixar film), and was part of the lowest total-grossing weekend since October 1998, with all films combining for just $55.3 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/vin-diesel-bloodshot-i-still-believe-the-hunt-weekend-box-office-coronavirus-1202882333/|title=Weekend Box Office Headed To 22-Year-Low At $58M+ As Coronavirus Fears Grip Nation|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|author=Anthony D'Alessandro|accessdate=March 15, 2020|date=March 15, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315033857/https://deadline.com/2020/03/vin-diesel-bloodshot-i-still-believe-the-hunt-weekend-box-office-coronavirus-1202882333/|archive-date=March 15, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In the film's third weekend, due to the mass theater closures around the country, it made $71,000 from 135 locations, mostly [[drive-in theater|drive-ins]].<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://deadline.com/2020/03/coronavirus-drive-in-movie-theaters-exhibition-shutdown-onward-1202890329/ |title=Drive-Ins Continue To Post Best Ticket Sales In Weekend Box Office Wiped Out By Theater Closures |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |date=March 23, 2020 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=March 24, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 87% based on 270 reviews, with an average rating of 7.14/10. The website's critics consensus reads: \"It may suffer in comparison to Pixar's classics, but ''Onward'' makes effective use of the studio's formula \u2013 and stands on its own merits as a funny, heartwarming, dazzlingly animated adventure.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/onward/|title=Onward (2020)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|access-date=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307020101/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/onward|archive-date=March 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 61 out of 100, based on 55 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/onward|title=Onward Reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|access-date=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314085753/https://www.metacritic.com/movie/onward|archive-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"A\u2013\" on an A+ to F scale (tied with ''[[Cars 2]]'' for the lowest score received by a Pixar film), and [[PostTrak]] reported filmgoers gave it 4.5 out of 5 stars.<ref name=opening/>\n\n[[Richard Roeper]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' called ''Onward'' a step back for Pixar, giving it 2/4 stars. He said, \"The story fluctuates between the uninspired and the just plain weird and then gets even weirder.\" While he praised the animation and said that the movie \"begins with an intriguing premise\", he concluded that it \"doesn't come close to fully fleshing out the possibilities\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/2020/2/27/21152865/onward-review-worst-pixar-movie-disney-tom-holland-chris-pratt|title='Onward' a step backward for Disney-Pixar|last=Roeper|first=Richard|date=March 17, 2020|website=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311015050/https://chicago.suntimes.com/2020/2/27/21152865/onward-review-worst-pixar-movie-disney-tom-holland-chris-pratt|archive-date=March 11, 2020|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n[[Peter Bradshaw]] of [[The Guardian]] gave it 3/5 stars, and called the movie \"a likable family comedy that finds an easy rhythm without effort\" although felt that movie's \"attitude towards death\" is not radically powerful as in ''[[Coco (2017 film)|Coco]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2020/mar/06/onward-review-pixar-conjures-big-screen-adventure-with-wizard-quest-story|title=Onward review \u2013 Pixar conjures big-screen adventure with wizard quest story|last=Bradshaw|first=Peter|date=17 March 2020|website=theguardian.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317081813/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2020/mar/06/onward-review-pixar-conjures-big-screen-adventure-with-wizard-quest-story|archive-date=March 17, 2020|access-date=}}</ref> In a same star review [[Peter Travers]] of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' said \"It\u2019s no ''Toy Story'' \u2014 but the animation juggernaut\u2019s latest, about two elf brothers on a quest, is still worth your while.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-reviews/onward-movie-review-pixar-960479/|title='Onward' Review: Pixar's Elf-Family Fantasy Is Light on Company's Magic|last=Travers|first=Peter|date=8 March 2020|website=Rollingstone.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318070138/https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-reviews/onward-movie-review-pixar-960479/|archive-date=March 18, 2020|access-date=}}</ref> [[James Berardinelli]], in his review  praised its originality, emotional weight and called it \"engaging and enjoyable\", and that \"There\u2019s something here for everyone\", though concluded that it isn't a next Disney/Pixar classic.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.reelviews.net/reelviews/onward |title=Onward (United States, 2020) |last=Berardinelli |first=James |date=6 March 2020 |website=Reelviews |access-date=March 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318072235/https://www.reelviews.net/reelviews/onward |archive-date=March 18, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Ban and censorship ===\n<!-- There is a likelihood the film was banned in these countries for the depiction of necromancy, as the LGBT reference is very minor and can be cut. -->\nThe film was banned in the [[Arab world|Arab]] countries of [[Kuwait]], [[Oman]], [[Qatar]], and [[Saudi Arabia]], as one female cyclops police officer character in the film named Specter (voiced by Lena Waithe) briefly indicates that she is a [[lesbian]]. The scene in question is a brief scene in which Colt Bronco is lamenting about how Ian and Barley Lightfoot do not respect him as a father figure. Specter then replies to him by saying, \"It's not easy being a new parent\u2014my girlfriend's daughter got me pulling my hair out, okay?\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/disney-onward-banned-multiple-middle-east-markets-lesbian-lgbt-reference-1202876168/|title=Disney/Pixar's 'Onward' Banned In Multiple Middle East Countries Due To Lesbian Reference|last=Wiseman|first=Andreas|date=March 6, 2020|website=Deadline|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307021916/https://deadline.com/2020/03/disney-onward-banned-multiple-middle-east-markets-lesbian-lgbt-reference-1202876168/|archive-date=March 7, 2020|access-date=March 6, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/onward-banned-lesbian-kuwait-oman-qatar-saudi-arabia-1203526359/|title='Onward' Banned in Several Middle East Countries Due to Lesbian Reference|last=McNary|first=Dave|date=March 6, 2020|website=Variety|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307131642/https://variety.com/2020/film/news/onward-banned-lesbian-kuwait-oman-qatar-saudi-arabia-1203526359/|archive-date=March 7, 2020|access-date=March 6, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2020/03/onward-banned-middle-east-gay-reference-1202216026/|title='Onward' Banned in Multiple Middle Eastern Countries, Censored in Russia for Gay Reference|last=Lattanzio|first=Ryan|date=March 6, 2020|website=Indie Wire|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319030705/https://www.indiewire.com/2020/03/onward-banned-middle-east-gay-reference-1202216026/|archive-date=March 19, 2020|access-date=March 6, 2020}}</ref> Homosexual acts are criminalized in these four aforementioned countries, which are predominantly Muslim, although Kuwait does not criminalize female homosexual acts. However, this ban is not universal, and the film has been screened in [[Bahrain]], the [[United Arab Emirates]], [[Lebanon]], and [[Egypt]].\n\nIn [[Russia]], where the [[Russian gay propaganda law|gay propaganda law]] officially criminalizes the dissemination of LGBT-related content to minors under 18, the Russian dub, handled by [[Disney Character Voices International]], changed the line to \"It's not easy being a new parent\u2014my partner's daughter got me pulling my hair out, okay?\" instead. The Russian dub also avoided referring to Specter with gender-specific pronouns.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official|https://movies.disney.com/onward}}\n* {{IMDb title|7146812}}\n\n{{Disney theatrical animated features}}\n{{Pixar}}\n{{Dan Scanlon}}\n\n[[Category:2020 3D films]]\n[[Category:2020 computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:2020 fantasy films]]\n[[Category:2020s American animated films]]\n[[Category:2020s animated films]]\n[[Category:2020s computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:2020s fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:American 3D films]]\n[[Category:American animated fantasy films]]\n[[Category:American computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:American fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Animated comedy films]]\n[[Category:Cartoon controversies]]\n[[Category:Censored films]]\n[[Category:Epic fantasy films]]\n[[Category:Films about brothers]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Dan Scanlon]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Jeff Danna]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Mychael Danna]]\n[[Category:Films set on fictional planets]]\n[[Category:High fantasy films]]\n[[Category:LGBT-related animated films]]\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema]]\n[[Category:Pixar animated films]]\n[[Category:Walt Disney Pictures films]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-protected|reason=Persistent addition of [[WP:INTREF|unsourced or poorly sourced content]]|small=yes}}\n{{short description|2020 film directed by Dan Scanlon}}\n{{Use American English|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Onward\n| image          = Onward poster.jpg\n| border         = no\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Dan Scanlon]]\n| producer       = [[Kori Rae]]\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* Dan Scanlon\n* Jason Headley\n* [[Keith Bunin]]\n}}\n| story          = {{Plainlist|\n* Dan Scanlon\n* Keith Bunin\n* Jason Headley\n}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Tom Holland (actor)|Tom Holland]]\n* [[Chris Pratt]]\n* [[Julia Louis-Dreyfus]]\n* [[Octavia Spencer]]\n}}\n| music          = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Mychael Danna]]<ref name=\"DannaScore\">{{cite web |url=http://filmmusicreporter.com/2019/04/16/mychael-jeff-danna-to-score-pixars-onward/ |title=Mychael & Jeff Danna to Score Pixar's 'Onward' \u2013 Film Music Reporter |publisher=|access-date=April 17, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417121323/http://filmmusicreporter.com/2019/04/16/mychael-jeff-danna-to-score-pixars-onward/|archive-date=April 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Jeff Danna]]<ref name=\"DannaScore\" />\n}}\n| cinematography = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Sharon Calahan]]\n* Adam Habib\n}}\n| editing        = Catherine Apple<ref>{{cite web|title=Catherine Apple|date=December 7, 2019|url=https://collider.com/how-does-pixar-make-movies-ccxp/|publisher=collider|accessdate=December 8, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191207221911/https://collider.com/how-does-pixar-make-movies-ccxp/|archive-date=December 7, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Walt Disney Pictures]]\n* [[Pixar Animation Studios]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures|Walt Disney Studios<br />Motion Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2020|2|21|[[Berlin International Film Festival|Berlinale]]|2020|3|6|United States}}\n| runtime        = 103 minutes<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.berlinale.de/en/programme/programme/detail.html?film_id=202012642|title=Programme - Onward|website=[[Berlin International Film Festival|Berlinale]]|language=en|access-date=2020-02-16}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $175\u2013200 million<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/box-office-onward-international-coronavirus-1203527183/|title=Box Office: 'Onward' Debuts to $28 Million Overseas Amid Coronavirus Outbreak|author=Rebecca Rubin|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=March 8, 2020|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308192742/https://variety.com/2020/film/news/box-office-onward-international-coronavirus-1203527183/|archive-date=March 8, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| gross          = $103.2 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl3433267713/?ref_=bo_hm_rs |title=Onward (2020) |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |access-date=April 10, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229183631/https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl3433267713/?ref_=bo_hm_rs |archive-date=February 29, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Onward''''' is a 2020 American [[computer-animated]] [[urban fantasy]] film produced by [[Pixar Animation Studios]] for [[Walt Disney Pictures]]. The film is directed by [[Dan Scanlon]], produced by [[Kori Rae]] from a screenplay written by Scanlon, Jason Headley, and [[Keith Bunin]], and stars the voices of [[Tom Holland (actor)|Tom Holland]], [[Chris Pratt]], [[Julia Louis-Dreyfus]], and [[Octavia Spencer]]. Set in a suburban fantasy world, the film follows two elf brothers who set out on a quest to find an artifact that will bring back their deceased father.<ref name=\"Synopsis\">{{cite news |url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/pixar-disney-untitled-suburban-fantasy-world-unicorns-d23-1202496455/ |title=D23: Pixar Announces Untitled Quest Movie Set in 'Suburban Fantasy World' |last=Variety staff |date=July 14, 2017 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=July 21, 2017 |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170715013545/https://variety.com/2017/film/news/pixar-disney-untitled-suburban-fantasy-world-unicorns-d23-1202496455/|archive-date=July 15, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe film premiered at the [[70th Berlin International Film Festival]] on February 21, 2020 and was released in the United States on March 6. It received generally positive reviews from critics and has grossed $103 million worldwide. The film's financial shortcomings were attributed to the [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], which resulted in theaters around the globe being closed. Like several other films released in March, it was made available digitally two weeks after its theatrical release.\n\n==Plot==\nIn a world inhabited by [[Legendary creature|mythical creatures]], magic was once commonplace, though difficult to master. After technological advances over the years, magic became obsolete and was largely discarded.\n\nIn a time equivalent to the modern day, Ian Lightfoot, an [[elf]] high-schooler lacking self-confidence, and his older brother Barley, a history and [[role-playing game]] fanatic, live in the city of New Mushroomton. Their father Wilden died shortly before Ian was born, and their mother Laurel has a new boyfriend, [[centaur]] police officer Colt Bronco, whom both Ian and Barley dislike.\n\nOn Ian's sixteenth birthday, Laurel gives the brothers a gift from Wilden: a magical staff, a rare gem, and a letter describing a \"visitation spell\" that can resurrect their father for a single day. Ian accidentally succeeds in casting the spell, but only the lower half of Wilden's body is reformed before the gem disintegrates. The brothers embark on a quest to acquire another gem and complete the spell, taking Barley's beloved [[van]] \"Guinevere\". Finding the boys gone, Laurel leaves to find them.\n\nIan and Barley visit the [[Manticore]]\u2019s Tavern, named for a monster possessing a map to the gem. The tavern has become a [[family restaurant]] managed by the Manticore, legally named The Manticore, also known as \"Corey\". Arguing with Ian over the map, The Manticore realizes how boring her life has become and drives the customers away in a fit of rage, accidentally setting fire to the restaurant and the map. The brothers' only clue to the gem is a children's menu suggesting \"Raven's Point\", a nearby mountain. Laurel later arrives at the scene and befriends The Manticore, who agrees to help her. The Manticore warns that the brothers' journey may awaken a curse that can only be defeated by her special sword, which she and Laurel steal from a [[Pawnbroker|pawn shop]]. \n\nTraveling to the mountains, Ian and Barley narrowly escape the police and a [[Outlaw motorcycle club|motorcycle gang]] of [[pixies]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sims |first1=David |title=Pixar Needs to Make More Movies Like 'Onward' |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2020/02/onward-movie-review-dan-scanlon-chris-pratt/606736/ |website=The Atlantic |accessdate=22 March 2020 |date=21 February 2020}}</ref>, relying on Ian's newly awakened spell-casting abilities and Barley's role-playing game instincts. \"Raven's Point\" leads them on a trail indicated by a series of [[raven]] statues, but Colt follows them, calling in reinforcements. Barley sacrifices Guinevere to cause a landslide, blocking their pursuers. Following the statues, the brothers descend through a cave and avoid a series of traps and deadly creatures, surfacing to find themselves in front of Ian's high school. Ian lashes out at Barley for leading them on a wild goose chase and walks away with Wilden. \n\nRereading his list of things he always wished to do with his father, Ian realizes that Barley has been a father figure throughout his entire life, and returns to make amends. Barley discovers the gem inside a historic fountain and retrieves it, unwittingly triggering the curse The Manticore spoke of, which turns the high school into an artificial dragon bent on claiming the gem. Ian faces the artificial dragon, but his staff is knocked into the ocean; he reforms it from a splinter and continues the fight. The Manticore flies in carrying Laurel, who plunges the magic sword into the artificial dragon's heart, buying Ian time to cast the visitation spell and fully reform Wilden's body. Ian sends Barley ahead to give his goodbye to Wilden, and holds off the artificial dragon long enough for Laurel to destroy it. After Wilden dissipates, Barley tells Ian that their father is proud of him, and the brothers share a hug.\n\nIan's confidence and spell-casting improve and he surprises Barley by painting his new van, the \"Guinevere 2\", while they both improve their relationship with Colt. The Manticore reopens her tavern in its original spirit, drawing in customers with tales of past adventures, and Ian and Barley continue questing.\n\n==Voice cast==\n{{cast listing|\n* [[Tom Holland (actor)|Tom Holland]] as Ian Lightfoot,<ref name=VarietyDec2018/><ref name=firstlook /> a teenaged [[elf]] who is Barley's younger brother and Laurel and Wilden's son.\n* [[Chris Pratt]] as Barley Lightfoot,<ref name=VarietyDec2018/><ref name=firstlook>{{cite web |url=https://www.pixarpost.com/2019/05/pixar-onward-first-look.html |title=Breaking: First Look at Characters Ian and Barley Lightfoot from Pixar's Suburban Fantasy Film, 'Onward' (In Theaters March 6, 2020) |author=Pixar Post |publisher=|access-date=May 29, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190529172427/https://www.pixarpost.com/2019/05/pixar-onward-first-look.html|archive-date=May 29, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Ian's older brother, and Laurel and Wilden's son who longs for a magical quest.\n* [[Julia Louis-Dreyfus]] as Laurel Lightfoot,<ref name=VarietyDec2018/><ref name=firstlook /><ref name=\"Clips\">{{cite web |url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/news/pixar-onward-chris-pratt-tom-holland/ |title=D23: Pixar Brings New Onward Clips |last=White |first=James |date=August 25, 2019 |website=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]] |accessdate=August 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190825105550/https://www.empireonline.com/movies/news/pixar-onward-chris-pratt-tom-holland/|archive-date=August 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> the widowed mother of Ian and Barley.\n* [[Octavia Spencer]] as The \"Corey\" Manticore, a [[manticore]] restaurant owner and former adventurer whom Ian and Barley go to for help on their quest.\n* [[Mel Rodriguez]] as Colt Bronco, a [[centaur]] police officer and Laurel's new husband.<ref name=twit3600/>\n* [[Kyle Bornheimer]] as Wilden Lightfoot, Ian and Barley's late father and Laurel's late husband.<ref name=\"WholeCast\" />\n* [[Lena Waithe]] as Specter, a [[cyclops]] police officer.<ref name=twit3600/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://insidethemagic.net/2020/02/onward-first-openly-lgbtq-bt1/|title=Disney-Pixar's \"Onward\" Will Feature the First Openly LGBTQ Character|date=February 22, 2020|via=Inside the Magic|access-date=February 22, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222040111/https://insidethemagic.net/2020/02/onward-first-openly-lgbtq-bt1/|archive-date=February 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2020/02/24/pixars-first-out-gay-character-to-be-voiced-by-lena-waithe-in-onward/|title=Pixar's first out gay character to be voiced by Lena Waithe in 'Onward'|last=Frishberg|first=Hannah|date=February 24, 2020|website=[[New York Post]]|access-date=February 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225133013/https://nypost.com/2020/02/24/pixars-first-out-gay-character-to-be-voiced-by-lena-waithe-in-onward/|archive-date=February 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Ali Wong]] as Gore, a [[faun]] police officer.<ref name=twit3600>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/pixaronward/status/1206620188709273600|title=Behold: Character posters for #PixarOnward, including newly-announced cast @AliWong, @LenaWaithe, and @_MelRodriguez_.\u2728 Check back tomorrow to see the brand-new trailer for the film|via=[[Twitter]]|access-date=December 16, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191217032256/https://twitter.com/pixaronward/status/1206620188709273600|archive-date=December 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Grey DeLisle|Grey Griffin]] as Dewdrop, a [[pixie]] and the leader of the Pixie Dusters [[Outlaw motorcycle club|biker gang]].\n* [[Tracey Ullman]] as Grecklin, a [[gremlin]] pawn shop owner.<ref name=\"WholeCast\" />\n* [[Wilmer Valderrama]] as Gaxton, an elf and college friend of Wilden.<ref name=\"WholeCast\" />\n* George Psarras as Avel, an elf police officer.<ref name=\"WholeCast\" />\n* [[John Ratzenberger]] as Fenwick, a cyclops construction worker.<ref name=\"WholeCast\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/snyde/ny-stars-attend-the-world-premiere-of-disney-pixar-onward-20200219-547inowgbnbhxnnziyywj3eu6a-photogallery.html|title=Stars attended the world premiere of Disney Pixar's \"Onward\" at the El Capitan Theatre on Feb. 18, 2020 in Hollywood, Calif.|website=New York Daily News|accessdate=February 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221191311/https://www.nydailynews.com/snyde/ny-stars-attend-the-world-premiere-of-disney-pixar-onward-20200219-547inowgbnbhxnnziyywj3eu6a-photogallery.html|archive-date=February 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Production ==\n===Development===\nIn July 2017, Pixar announced a \"suburban fantasy world\" film at the [[D23 Expo]], with Scanlon directing and Rae producing.<ref name=\"Synopsis\"/> The film was inspired by the death of Scanlon's father, when he and his brother were younger, and their relationship. He decided to write the story after hearing an audio clip of his father.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3025627/pixar-suburban-fantasy-film-dan-scanlon/ |title=Pixar's New 'Suburban Fantasy' Sounds Like A Real Tearjerker |last=Bell |first=Crystal |date=July 17, 2017 |website=[[MTV News]] |publisher=[[MTV]]|access-date=April 6, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170718003125/http://www.mtv.com/news/3025627/pixar-suburban-fantasy-film-dan-scanlon/|archive-date=July 18, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> On December 12, 2018, the title was revealed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/pixar-moves-forward-with-suburban-fantasy-film-onward-cast-includes-chris-pratt-tom-holland |title=Pixar Moves Forward with Suburban Fantasy Film 'Onward'; Cast Includes Chris Pratt, Tom Holland |last=Weiss |first=Josh |date=December 12, 2018 |website=[[Syfy]] |publisher=[[NBCUniversal Cable Entertainment Group]] |accessdate=December 12, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181212222813/https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/pixar-moves-forward-with-suburban-fantasy-film-onward-cast-includes-chris-pratt-tom-holland|archive-date=December 12, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2019, Headley and Bunin were hired to rewrite the screenplay.\n\n===Casting===\nOn December 12, 2018, Holland, Pratt, Louis-Dreyfus and Spencer were announced as starring in the film.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/onward-pixar-movie-chris-pratt-tom-holland-julia-louis-dreyfus-octavia-spencer-cast-1202518598/ |title=Pixar's 'Onward' To Star Chris Pratt, Tom Holland, Julia Louis-Dreyfus & Octavia Spencer |last=Hipes |first=Patrick |date=December 12, 2018 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |accessdate=December 12, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181212221000/https://deadline.com/2018/12/onward-pixar-movie-chris-pratt-tom-holland-julia-louis-dreyfus-octavia-spencer-cast-1202518598/|archive-date=December 12, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> While having recorded most of their lines separately, Holland and Pratt did some of their recording sessions together since, according to Scanlon, \"they've worked together before and hung out together\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Falcone |first1=Dana Rose |title=See Chris Pratt, Julia Louis-Dreyfus & Tom Holland as Elves in Disney-Pixar's Onward: First Look! |url=https://www.people.com/movies/chris-pratt-julia-louis-dreyfus-tom-holland-onward/ |website=People |date=May 29, 2019|access-date=May 30, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190529215133/https://people.com/movies/chris-pratt-julia-louis-dreyfus-tom-holland-onward/|archive-date=May 29, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> According to Rae, Holland and Pratt improvised some of their lines while recording together.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.digitalspy.com/movies/a30415714/tom-holland-chris-pratt-onward-cast-interview/ |title=Marvel's Tom Holland and Chris Pratt being cast in Onward was \"dumb luck\" |date=January 6, 2020 |access-date=February 22, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222042437/https://www.digitalspy.com/movies/a30415714/tom-holland-chris-pratt-onward-cast-interview/ |archive-date=February 22, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On December 17, 2019, Wong, Waithe and Rodriguez joined the cast of the film.<ref name=twit3600/> On February 18, 2020, Valderrama, Ullman, Bornheimer, Psarras and Ratzenberger were revealed to have been cast on the film.<ref name=\"WholeCast\"/>\n\n===Music===\nOn April 16, 2019, [[Mychael Danna|Mychael]] and [[Jeff Danna]] were revealed to be the film's composers.<ref name=\"DannaScore\"/> On February 12, 2020, [[Brandi Carlile]] revealed she recorded the song \"Carried Me With You\" for the film's end credits. She co-wrote it with Phil and Tim Hanseroth.<ref name=\"variety1\">{{cite news |last1=Willman |first1=Chris |title=Brandi Carlile Records Theme Song for Pixar Pic 'Onward' |url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/brandi-carlile-records-theme-song-pixar-onward-1203502224/ |accessdate=17 February 2020 |publisher=Variety |date=12 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200214151349/https://variety.com/2020/film/news/brandi-carlile-records-theme-song-pixar-onward-1203502224/ |archive-date=February 14, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The film's soundtrack was released on February 28, 2020.<ref name=\"variety1\"/>\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline = '''''Onward: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack'''''\n| extra_column = Performer\n| all_music = [[Mychael Danna]] and [[Jeff Danna]], except where noted\n| total_length = 1:02:32\n\n| title1 = Carried Me with You\n| writer1 = [[Brandi Carlile]], Phil and Tim Hanseroth\n| extra1 = Carlile\n| length1 = 3:33\n\n| title2 = Quests of Yore\n| length2 = 0:52\n\n| title3 = The World Was Full of Wonder\n| length3 = 1:37\n\n| title4 = A Little Magic\n| length4 = 0:43\n\n| title5 = Bad Dragon\n| length5 = 1:03\n\n| title6 = New Ian\n| length6 = 2:36\n\n| title7 = My Mighty Steed\n| length7 = 0:22\n\n| title8 = My Birthday Is Cancelled\n| length8 = 0:44\n\n| title9 = Wish I Could Spend the Day with You\n| length9 = 1:46\n\n| title10 = The Visitation Spell\n| length10 = 3:35\n\n| title11 = The Spell\n| length11 = 1:06\n\n| title12 = The Spell Only Lasts One Day\n| length12 = 0:56\n\n| title13 = Find Another Phoenix Gem\n| length13 = 0:49\n\n| title14 = Going on a Quest\n| length14 = 0:24\n\n| title15 = Laurel in Pursuit\n| length15 = 0:44\n\n| title16 = The Manticore's Tavern\n| length16 = 0:43\n\n| title17 = Tavern Remodeling\n| length17 = 1:12\n\n| title18 = The Map to Raven's Point\n| length18 = 1:45\n\n| title19 = Two Teenage Elves\n| length19 = 0:38\n\n| title20 = Magnora Gantuan!\n| length20 = 0:32\n\n| title21 = Baby Legs\n| length21 = 0:41\n\n| title22 = Pixie Dusters\n| length22 = 1:18\n\n| title23 = The Guardian Curse\n| length23 = 0:42\n\n| title24 = Driving Test\n| length24 = 3:17\n\n| title25 = Dance Fight\n| length25 = 2:22\n\n| title26 = Path of Peril\n| length26 = 0:41\n\n| title27 = Pawn Shop\n| length27 = 0:28\n\n| title28 = Tracking Guinevere\n| length28 = 1:04\n\n| title29 = Bottomless Pit\n| length29 = 0:56\n\n| title30 = The Trust Bridge\n| length30 = 1:20\n\n| title31 = Follow Your Gut\n| length31 = 0:52\n\n| title32 = Running from the Cops\n| length32 = 1:59\n\n| title33 = Sacrifice\n| length33 = 0:59\n\n| title34 = Just a Beat Up Old Van\n| length34 = 1:36\n\n| title35 = The Cave\n| length35 = 0:54\n\n| title36 = Accelior!\n| length36 = 0:26\n\n| title37 = Boom Bastia!\n| length37 = 0:47\n\n| title38 = Barley's Last Memory of Dad\n| length38 = 0:58\n\n| title39 = Led Us to Our Victory!\n| length39 = 1:49\n\n| title40 = The Truth Comes Out\n| length40 = 0:39\n\n| title41 = Share My Life with Him\n| length41 = 3:24\n\n| title42 = Battling the Dragon\n| length42 = 3:03\n\n| title43 = Voltar Thunderseer!\n| length43 = 0:59\n\n| title44 = Dad\n| length44 = 2:52\n\n| title45 = Magic Returns\n| length45 = 2:48\n}}\n\n===Deleted scene===\nThere was a storyboard scene where Ian, Barley, and Wilden are joined with a goat girl in the journey. Ian and the goat girl come across a booth hosted by three evil mermaids. The mermaids sing their mesmerizing song to lure the two into staying in one of three houses put for rent. Ian tries to silence them with the staff but the spell is too weak. When Ian and the goat girl are finally in a trance, the mermaids place them in one of the houses. The house they are in starts to sink into the ground. \n\nThe goat girl was omitted because the filmmakers want the film to focus on the relationship between Ian and Barley. The scene itself was removed because the filmmakers felt it was too grim.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://ew.com/movies/onward-deleted-scene-sirens-jenny-tom-holland |title = Exclusive: 'Onward' deleted scene summons sirens and a lost character}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://io9.gizmodo.com/onward-deleted-scene-features-a-capitalist-twist-on-the-1842526629 | title=Onward Deleted Scene Features a Capitalist Twist on the Siren Song}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n===Theatrical===\n''Onward'' premiered at the [[70th Berlin International Film Festival]] on February 21, 2020.<ref name=premiere>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/berlin-film-festival-lineup-competition-announced-revealed-live-1202845048/|website=[[Deadline.com]]|last=Wiseman|first=Andreas|date=January 29, 2020|title=Berlin Competition Lineup: Kelly Reichardt, Sally Potter, Abel Ferrara, Christian Petzold; Disney's 'Onward' & Hillary Clinton Also Heading To Fest|accessdate=February 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130153631/https://deadline.com/2020/01/berlin-film-festival-lineup-competition-announced-revealed-live-1202845048/|archive-date=January 30, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It was released in the United States on March 6.<ref name=\"VarietyDec2018\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/chris-pratt-tom-holland-julia-louis-dreyfus-octavia-spencer-onward-1203088174/ |title=Chris Pratt, Tom Holland, Julia Louis-Dreyfus, Octavia Spencer to Voice Pixar's 'Onward' |last1=McNary |first1=Dave |date=December 12, 2018 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |accessdate=December 12, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181212222451/https://variety.com/2018/film/news/chris-pratt-tom-holland-julia-louis-dreyfus-octavia-spencer-onward-1203088174/|archive-date=December 12, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> A new short film titled ''[[Playdate with Destiny]]'', centered around [[Maggie Simpson]] of ''[[The Simpsons]]'', appears before the feature film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/simpsons-short-film/|title=New 'The Simpsons' Short Film To Play In Theaters In Front of Pixar's 'Onward'|date=February 28, 2020|access-date=February 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228181730/https://www.slashfilm.com/simpsons-short-film/|archive-date=February 28, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B9GRqCFnI6M/|title=Maggie Simpson is speechless... Playdate with Destiny, a new Simpsons short film before Disney & Pixar's Onward. Exclusively in theaters! #TheSimpsons|author=thesimpsons on [[Instagram]]|date=February 27, 2020|access-date=February 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228061700/https://www.instagram.com/p/B9GRqCFnI6M/|archive-date=February 28, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n''Onward'' was released [[Digital distribution|digitally]] on the night of March 20, 2020 and became available for [[Disney+]] subscribers on April 3, 2020 in the United States. The announcement followed Disney's earlier than planned release of ''[[Frozen II]]'' on Disney+ due to the  [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://collider.com/onward-digital-release-disney-plus-details/ |title=Pixar's ''Onward'' Is Getting an Early Digital and Disney+ Release |website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]] |last=Gemmill |first=Allie|date=March 20, 2020 |accessdate=March 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Over its first week of home release, the film was the sixth-most watched on [[Prime Video|Amazon Prime]] and second-most on the [[iTunes Store]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.indiewire.com/2020/03/farewell-box-office-premium-vod-charts-bloodshot-onward-birds-of-prey-1202220714/ |title='Farewell, Box Office: This Was the Week That Premium VOD Charts Took Flight|website=[[IndieWire]]|first=Tom|last= Brueggemann |date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> In Australia, it will be released on Disney+ on April 24, 2020.<ref name=\"ausrelease\">{{cite web|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2020/03/airdate-onward.html|title=Airdate: ''Onward''|work=TV Tonight|last=Knox|first=David|date=31 March 2020|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Marketing==\nIn May 2019, two stills from the film, featuring Barley, Ian and their mother, were revealed. The following day, the film's teaser poster was released, and the teaser trailer debuted during [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s broadcast of the [[2019 NBA Finals]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/onward-disney-pixar-trailer-poster-1202624788/ |title=Disney/Pixar 'Onward' Bows First-Look Trailer During NBA Finals Game 1 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |last=Haring |first=Bruce |date=May 30, 2019 |accessdate=June 12, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190531044356/https://deadline.com/2019/05/onward-disney-pixar-trailer-poster-1202624788/|archive-date=May 31, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The trailer was also shown with ''[[Toy Story 4]]'' and ''[[Spider-Man: Far From Home]]''. Official trailers were released in October and December 2019.\n\n== Lawsuit ==\nIn January 2020, San Francisco tattoo artist Sweet Cecily Daniher filed a copyright lawsuit against Disney, Pixar, and ''Onward'' producer Kori Rae. In September 2018, Pixar rented Daniher's \"Vanicorn\", a van decorated with a unicorn-themed mural, for use in a one-day festival. She learned about the production of ''Onward'' in May 2019 and, after seeing images of the van used by Ian and Barley Lightfoot in the film, came to believe that Pixar had copied the design of the Vanicorn in violation of her rental agreement with the company, as well as the [[Digital Millennium Copyright Act]], the [[Visual Artists Rights Act]], and the California Artists Protection Act. She sought in her suit to prohibit distribution of the film and any infringing advertisements or merchandise.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/disney-sued-by-artist-unicorn-adorned-van-pixars-onward-1274131|title=Artist Sues Disney, Pixar Over Unicorn-Adorned Van in 'Onward'|last=Cullins|first=Ashley|date=January 28, 2020|website=The Hollywood Reporter|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129154442/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/disney-sued-by-artist-unicorn-adorned-van-pixars-onward-1274131|archive-date=January 29, 2020|access-date=February 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''Onward'' grossed $61.6 million in the United States and Canada, and $41.6 million in other territories, for a worldwide total of $103.2 million.<ref name=\"BOM\"/> It was speculated the gross for the film was significantly [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema|affected by the coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2020/mar/16/coronavirus-cinema-audiences-decline-film-industry |title=Cinema audiences drop dramatically as coronavirus restrictions bite |access-date=March 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317010316/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2020/mar/16/coronavirus-cinema-audiences-decline-film-industry |archive-date=March 17, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/onward-the-hunt-invisible-man-box-office-coronavirus-1203534409/ |title=Box Office: 'Onward' Leads as Coronavirus Stunts North American Sales |access-date=March 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314224942/https://variety.com/2020/film/news/onward-the-hunt-invisible-man-box-office-coronavirus-1203534409/ |archive-date=March 14, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.digitalspy.com/movies/a31659709/onward-box-office-bloodshot-coronavirus-cinemas/ |title=Bloodshot and Onward suffer during worst US box office weekend in 22 years |date=March 16, 2020 |access-date=March 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324144029/https://www.digitalspy.com/movies/a31659709/onward-box-office-bloodshot-coronavirus-cinemas/ |archive-date=March 24, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn the United States and Canada, the film was released alongside ''[[The Way Back (2020 film)|The Way Back]]'' and the wide expansion of ''[[Emma (2020 film)|Emma]]'', and was projected to gross $45\u201350 million from 4,200 theaters in its opening weekend.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/onward-ben-affleck-the-way-back-box-office-coronavirus-1202873492/ |title=Disney-Pixar's 'Onward' Eyes $100M Global Start, Even With Coronavirus Concerns |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |first2=Nancy |last2=Tartaglione |date=March 3, 2020 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=March 4, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304013005/https://deadline.com/2020/03/onward-ben-affleck-the-way-back-box-office-coronavirus-1202873492/ |archive-date=March 4, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The film held early advance screenings on February 29, and made $650,000 from 470 theaters.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2020/03/01/onward-pixar-my-hero-academia-impractical-jokers-wendy-weekend-box-office/#449321631858 |title= Weekend Box Office: 'Onward' Sells Out, 'My Hero Academia' Surprises And 'Wendy' Flops |author= Scott Mendleson |date= March 1, 2020 |accessdate= March 4, 2020 |website= [[Forbes]] |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303203235/https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2020/03/01/onward-pixar-my-hero-academia-impractical-jokers-wendy-weekend-box-office/#449321631858 |archive-date= March 3, 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref> It then made $12.1 million on its first day, including $2 million from Thursday night previews. The film went on to debut to $39.1 million, topping the box office but marking the third-ever lowest start for a Pixar film.<ref name=opening>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/onward-opening-weekend-disney-pixar-coronavirus-invisible-man-1202876016/ |title='Onward' Seeing Blas\u00e9 $40M Domestic Opening, $68M WW: Are Coronavirus Fears Impacting B.O.? \u2013 Sunday Update |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |date=March 7, 2020 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=March 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307021204/https://deadline.com/2020/03/onward-opening-weekend-disney-pixar-coronavirus-invisible-man-1202876016/ |archive-date=March 7, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=IndieWireOpen>{{cite web|title=Pixar's 'Onward' Opens to Modest Box Office With Weekend Down $100 Million From Last Year|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2020/03/pixar-onward-box-office-weekend-1202216191/|publisher=[[IndieWire]]|date=March 7, 2020|accessdate=March 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312131725/https://www.indiewire.com/2020/03/pixar-onward-box-office-weekend-1202216191/|archive-date=March 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> While the film remained in first in its second weekend, it dropped 73% to $10.5 million (the worst-ever second weekend for a Pixar film), and was part of the lowest total-grossing weekend since October 1998, with all films combining for just $55.3 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/vin-diesel-bloodshot-i-still-believe-the-hunt-weekend-box-office-coronavirus-1202882333/|title=Weekend Box Office Headed To 22-Year-Low At $58M+ As Coronavirus Fears Grip Nation|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|author=Anthony D'Alessandro|accessdate=March 15, 2020|date=March 15, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315033857/https://deadline.com/2020/03/vin-diesel-bloodshot-i-still-believe-the-hunt-weekend-box-office-coronavirus-1202882333/|archive-date=March 15, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In the film's third weekend, due to the mass theater closures around the country, it made $71,000 from 135 locations, mostly [[drive-in theater|drive-ins]].<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://deadline.com/2020/03/coronavirus-drive-in-movie-theaters-exhibition-shutdown-onward-1202890329/ |title=Drive-Ins Continue To Post Best Ticket Sales In Weekend Box Office Wiped Out By Theater Closures |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |date=March 23, 2020 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=March 24, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 87% based on 270 reviews, with an average rating of 7.14/10. The website's critics consensus reads: \"It may suffer in comparison to Pixar's classics, but ''Onward'' makes effective use of the studio's formula \u2013 and stands on its own merits as a funny, heartwarming, dazzlingly animated adventure.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/onward/|title=Onward (2020)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|access-date=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307020101/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/onward|archive-date=March 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 61 out of 100, based on 55 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/onward|title=Onward Reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|access-date=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314085753/https://www.metacritic.com/movie/onward|archive-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"A\u2013\" on an A+ to F scale (tied with ''[[Cars 2]]'' for the lowest score received by a Pixar film), and [[PostTrak]] reported filmgoers gave it 4.5 out of 5 stars.<ref name=opening/>\n\n[[Richard Roeper]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' called ''Onward'' a step back for Pixar, giving it 2/4 stars. He said, \"The story fluctuates between the uninspired and the just plain weird and then gets even weirder.\" While he praised the animation and said that the movie \"begins with an intriguing premise\", he concluded that it \"doesn't come close to fully fleshing out the possibilities\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/2020/2/27/21152865/onward-review-worst-pixar-movie-disney-tom-holland-chris-pratt|title='Onward' a step backward for Disney-Pixar|last=Roeper|first=Richard|date=March 17, 2020|website=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311015050/https://chicago.suntimes.com/2020/2/27/21152865/onward-review-worst-pixar-movie-disney-tom-holland-chris-pratt|archive-date=March 11, 2020|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n[[Peter Bradshaw]] of [[The Guardian]] gave it 3/5 stars, and called the movie \"a likable family comedy that finds an easy rhythm without effort\" although felt that movie's \"attitude towards death\" is not radically powerful as in ''[[Coco (2017 film)|Coco]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2020/mar/06/onward-review-pixar-conjures-big-screen-adventure-with-wizard-quest-story|title=Onward review \u2013 Pixar conjures big-screen adventure with wizard quest story|last=Bradshaw|first=Peter|date=17 March 2020|website=theguardian.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317081813/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2020/mar/06/onward-review-pixar-conjures-big-screen-adventure-with-wizard-quest-story|archive-date=March 17, 2020|access-date=}}</ref> In a same star review [[Peter Travers]] of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' said \"It\u2019s no ''Toy Story'' \u2014 but the animation juggernaut\u2019s latest, about two elf brothers on a quest, is still worth your while.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-reviews/onward-movie-review-pixar-960479/|title='Onward' Review: Pixar's Elf-Family Fantasy Is Light on Company's Magic|last=Travers|first=Peter|date=8 March 2020|website=Rollingstone.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318070138/https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-reviews/onward-movie-review-pixar-960479/|archive-date=March 18, 2020|access-date=}}</ref> [[James Berardinelli]], in his review  praised its originality, emotional weight and called it \"engaging and enjoyable\", and that \"There\u2019s something here for everyone\", though concluded that it isn't a next Disney/Pixar classic.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.reelviews.net/reelviews/onward |title=Onward (United States, 2020) |last=Berardinelli |first=James |date=6 March 2020 |website=Reelviews |access-date=March 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318072235/https://www.reelviews.net/reelviews/onward |archive-date=March 18, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Ban and censorship ===\n<!-- There is a likelihood the film was banned in these countries for the depiction of necromancy, as the LGBT reference is very minor and can be cut. -->\nThe film was banned in the [[Arab world|Arab]] countries of [[Kuwait]], [[Oman]], [[Qatar]], and [[Saudi Arabia]], as one female cyclops police officer character in the film named Specter (voiced by Lena Waithe) briefly indicates that she is a [[lesbian]]. The scene in question is a brief scene in which Colt Bronco is lamenting about how Ian and Barley Lightfoot do not respect him as a father figure. Specter then replies to him by saying, \"It's not easy being a new parent\u2014my girlfriend's daughter got me pulling my hair out, okay?\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/disney-onward-banned-multiple-middle-east-markets-lesbian-lgbt-reference-1202876168/|title=Disney/Pixar's 'Onward' Banned In Multiple Middle East Countries Due To Lesbian Reference|last=Wiseman|first=Andreas|date=March 6, 2020|website=Deadline|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307021916/https://deadline.com/2020/03/disney-onward-banned-multiple-middle-east-markets-lesbian-lgbt-reference-1202876168/|archive-date=March 7, 2020|access-date=March 6, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/onward-banned-lesbian-kuwait-oman-qatar-saudi-arabia-1203526359/|title='Onward' Banned in Several Middle East Countries Due to Lesbian Reference|last=McNary|first=Dave|date=March 6, 2020|website=Variety|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307131642/https://variety.com/2020/film/news/onward-banned-lesbian-kuwait-oman-qatar-saudi-arabia-1203526359/|archive-date=March 7, 2020|access-date=March 6, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2020/03/onward-banned-middle-east-gay-reference-1202216026/|title='Onward' Banned in Multiple Middle Eastern Countries, Censored in Russia for Gay Reference|last=Lattanzio|first=Ryan|date=March 6, 2020|website=Indie Wire|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319030705/https://www.indiewire.com/2020/03/onward-banned-middle-east-gay-reference-1202216026/|archive-date=March 19, 2020|access-date=March 6, 2020}}</ref> Homosexual acts are criminalized in these four aforementioned countries, which are predominantly Muslim, although Kuwait does not criminalize female homosexual acts. However, this ban is not universal, and the film has been screened in [[Bahrain]], the [[United Arab Emirates]], [[Lebanon]], and [[Egypt]].\n\nIn [[Russia]], where the [[Russian gay propaganda law|gay propaganda law]] officially criminalizes the dissemination of LGBT-related content to minors under 18, the Russian dub, handled by [[Disney Character Voices International]], changed the line to \"It's not easy being a new parent\u2014my partner's daughter got me pulling my hair out, okay?\" instead. The Russian dub also avoided referring to Specter with gender-specific pronouns as well.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official|https://movies.disney.com/onward}}\n* {{IMDb title|7146812}}\n\n{{Disney theatrical animated features}}\n{{Pixar}}\n{{Dan Scanlon}}\n\n[[Category:2020 3D films]]\n[[Category:2020 computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:2020 fantasy films]]\n[[Category:2020s American animated films]]\n[[Category:2020s animated films]]\n[[Category:2020s computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:2020s fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:American 3D films]]\n[[Category:American animated fantasy films]]\n[[Category:American computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:American fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Animated comedy films]]\n[[Category:Cartoon controversies]]\n[[Category:Censored films]]\n[[Category:Epic fantasy films]]\n[[Category:Films about brothers]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Dan Scanlon]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Jeff Danna]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Mychael Danna]]\n[[Category:Films set on fictional planets]]\n[[Category:High fantasy films]]\n[[Category:LGBT-related animated films]]\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema]]\n[[Category:Pixar animated films]]\n[[Category:Walt Disney Pictures films]]\n", "name_user": "Poydoo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBan and censorship:also as well?", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Onward_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Francis Moore (geographer)", "text_new": "'''Francis Moore''' (baptized 1708, died in or after 1756) was a British travel writer of the eighteenth century.\n\nMoore was born in [[Worcester|Worcester, England]], but few details are known about his early life. He came into prominence after publishing ''Travels into the Inland Parts of Africa'' in 1738. The [[Abolitionism|abolitionist]] [[Thomas Clarkson]] attributed his commitment to the anti-slavery cause to reading the few experts on Africa of the time, including Moore.<ref>''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography''</ref><ref>Grant, D., viii</ref>\n\n==Account of Africa==\nMoore was appointed a writer (i.e., clerk) by the [[Royal African Company]] in 1730 and sailed for the company's [[Gambia River]] [[entrep\u00f4t]] on July of that year. He left the region in April 1735 after also serving as a factor (agent) for the company. Moore was one of the first Englishmen to travel into the interior of Africa, serving in and visiting numerous towns and trading posts along the Gambia River from its mouth to the [[Guinea Highlands]], hundreds of miles inland.\n\nMoore's observations were published as ''Travels Into the Interior Parts of Africa''. The short account describes in rich detail the physical and cultural geography of the region before the intensification of the [[Atlantic slave trade]] and the resulting depopulation and economic disintegration. Moore's work and Richard Jobson's ''The Golden Trade'' were the only detailed accounts of [[The Gambia|Gambia]] before the colonial period.<ref>Hill, M. H., 353.</ref>\n\nExcerpts from ''Travels Into the Interior Parts of Africa'' were published in several subsequent volumes on exploration and the slave trade, including [[Samuel Johnson]] et al., ''The World Displayed'' (1740); [[Thomas Astley]]\u2019s ''A New General Collection of Voyages and Travels'' (1745); and Elizabeth Donnan\u2019s ''Documents Illustrative of the Slave Trade to America'' (1931).<ref>Hill, M. H., 356-57.</ref>\n\n==Association with Job ben Solomon==\nMoore related the saga of [[Job ben Solomon]], also known as Ayuba Suleiman Diallo, in ''Travels Into the Interior Parts of Africa''. Job was an African aristocrat taken by slavers in 1730 in an incident recorded by Moore. He was enslaved in Maryland until 1733, when he was sent to England after [[James Oglethorpe]] received a letter from him and purchased his freedom. After becoming well-known and respected in London society, Job returned to the Gambia, where he became re-acquainted with Moore.<ref>See Grant, D., ''The Fortunate Slave'', for a detailed account of Diallo and his relationship with Moore.</ref>\n\n==Account of the Georgia Colony==\nMoore sailed to the [[Province of Georgia]] on November, 1735, only four months after returning to England from Gambia, with [[James Oglethorpe]] and over 200 colonists. It was a return trip for Oglethorpe, who had founded the colony in February 1733. Among those also on the voyage were newly ordained brothers [[John Wesley]] and [[Charles Wesley]].<ref>Hill, M. H., 354.</ref><ref>Grant, D., 113.</ref>\n\nMoore served as Oglethorpe's secretary, and as storekeeper at [[Fort Frederica]] on the southern frontier of the Georgia colony. He served in the colony until 1743, visiting his homeland once before permanently returning to England the same year as Oglethorpe.<ref>Grant, D., 187.</ref>\n\nMoore\u2019s early observations in the colony were published under the title ''A Voyage to Georgia''. The account contains some of the most detailed information available on the [[Oglethorpe Plan]] and its implementation. Moore\u2019s account of Georgia is silent on Oglethorpe\u2019s emerging anti-slavery position; however it seems likely that the two men discussed Africa and the slave trade at length, and this may have informed the latter\u2019s views.<ref>Wilson, T. D., 65-66, 72-73.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*\"Francis Moore.\" ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'' online edition (accessed March 9, 2016).\n*Grant, Douglas. ''The Fortunate Slave''. Oxford, UK: Oxford University Press, 1968.\n*Hill, Matthew H. \"Towards a Chronology of the Publications of Francis Moore\u2019s ''Travels into the Inland Parts of Africa.''\" ''History in Africa''. 19 (1992): 353-68.\n*Moore, Francis. ''A Voyage to Georgia''. London: Jacob Robinson, 1744.\n*Moore, Francis. ''Travels Into the Interior Parts of Africa''. Second Edition. London: D. Henry and R. Cave, 1738.\n*Wilson, Thomas D. ''The Oglethorpe Plan: Enlightenment Design in Savannah and Beyond''. Charlottesville, Va.: University of Virginia Press, 2012.\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite book|title=Travels Into the Inland Parts of Africa: Containing a Description of the Several Nations for the Space of Six Hundred Miles Up the River Gambia|author=Moore, F.|date=1738|publisher=Henry|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FmdCAAAAcAAJ|accessdate=2016-03-09}}\n*https://books.google.com/books/about/A_voyage_to_Georgia.html?id=oKxbAAAAQAAJ\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moore, Francis}}\n[[Category:18th-century births]]\n[[Category:1708 births]]\n[[Category:Year of death uncertain]]\n[[Category:18th-century English writers]]\n[[Category:18th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:People from Worcester]]\n", "text_old": "'''Francis Moore''' (baptized 1708, died in or after 1756) was a British travel writer of the eighteenth century.\n\nMoore was born in [[Worcester|Worcester, England]], but few details are known about his early life. He came into prominence after publishing ''Travels into the Inland Parts of Africa'' in 1738. The [[Abolitionism|abolitionist]] [[Thomas Clarkson]] attributed his commitment to the anti-slavery cause to reading the few experts on Africa of the time, including Moore.<ref>''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography''</ref><ref>Grant, D., viii</ref>\n\n==Account of Africa==\nMoore was appointed a writer (i.e., clerk) by the [[Royal African Company]] in 1730 and sailed for the company's [[Gambia River]] [[entrep\u00f4t]] on July of that year. He left the region in April 1735 after also serving as a factor (agent) for the company. Moore was one of the first Englishmen to travel into the interior of Africa, serving in and visiting numerous towns and trading posts along the Gambia River from its mouth to the [[Guinea Highlands]], hundreds of miles inland.\n\nMoore's observations were published as ''Travels Into the Interior Parts of Africa''. The short account describes in rich detail the physical and cultural geography of the region before the intensification of the [[Atlantic slave trade]] and the resulting depopulation and economic disintegration. Moore's work and Richard Jobson's ''The Golden Trade'' were the only detailed accounts of [[The Gambia|Gambia]] before the colonial period.<ref>Hill, M. H., 353.</ref>\n\nExcerpts from ''Travels Into the Interior Parts of Africa'' were published in several subsequent volumes on exploration and the slave trade, including [[Samuel Johnson]] et al., ''The World Displayed'' (1740); [[Thomas Astley]]\u2019s ''A New General Collection of Voyages and Travels'' (1745); and Elizabeth Donnan\u2019s ''Documents Illustrative of the Slave Trade to America'' (1931).<ref>Hill, M. H., 356-57.</ref>\n\n==Association with Job ben Solomon==\nMoore related the saga of [[Job ben Solomon]], also known as Ayuba Suleiman Diallo, in ''Travels Into the Interior Parts of Africa''. Job was an African aristocrat taken by slavers in 1730 in an incident recorded by Moore. He was enslaved in Maryland until 1733, when he was sent to England after [[James Oglethorpe]] received a letter from him and purchased his freedom. After becoming well-known and respected in London society, Job returned to the Gambia, where he became re-acquainted with Moore.<ref>See Grant, D., ''The Fortunate Slave'', for a detailed account of Diallo and his relationship with Moore.</ref>\n\n==Account of the Georgia Colony==\nMoore sailed to the [[Province of Georgia]] on November, 1735, only four months after returning to England from Gambia, with [[James Oglethorpe]] and over 200 colonists. It was a return trip for Oglethorpe, who had founded the colony in February 1733. Among those also on the voyage were newly ordained brothers [[John Wesley]] and [[Charles Wesley]].<ref>Hill, M. H., 354.</ref><ref>Grant, D., 113.</ref>\n\nMoore served as Oglethorpe's secretary, and as storekeeper at [[Fort Frederica]] on the southern frontier of the Georgia colony. He served in the colony until 1743, visiting his homeland once before permanently returning to England the same year as Oglethorpe.<ref>Grant, D., 187.</ref>\n\nMoore\u2019s early observations in the colony were published under the title ''A Voyage to Georgia''. The account contains some of the most detailed information available on the [[Oglethorpe Plan]] and its implementation. Moore\u2019s account of Georgia is silent on Oglethorpe\u2019s emerging anti-slavery position; however it seems likely that the two men discussed Africa and the slave trade at length, and this may have informed the latter\u2019s views.<ref>Wilson, T. D., 65-66, 72-73.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*\"Francis Moore.\" ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'' online edition (accessed March 9, 2016).\n*Grant, Douglas. ''The Fortunate Slave''. Oxford, UK: Oxford University Press, 1968.\n*Hill, Matthew H. \"Towards a Chronology of the Publications of Francis Moore\u2019s ''Travels into the Inland Parts of Africa.''\" ''History in Africa''. 19 (1992): 353-68.\n*Moore, Francis. ''A Voyage to Georgia''. London: Jacob Robinson, 1744.\n*Moore, Francis. ''Travels Into the Interior Parts of Africa''. Second Edition. London: D. Henry and R. Cave, 1738.\n*Wilson, Thomas D. ''The Oglethorpe Plan: Enlightenment Design in Savannah and Beyond''. Charlottesville, Va.: University of Virginia Press, 2012.\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite book|title=Travels Into the Inland Parts of Africa: Containing a Description of the Several Nations for the Space of Six Hundred Miles Up the River Gambia|author=Moore, F.|date=1738|publisher=Henry|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FmdCAAAAcAAJ|accessdate=2016-03-09}}\n*https://books.google.com/books/about/A_voyage_to_Georgia.html?id=oKxbAAAAQAAJ\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moore, Francis}}\n[[Category:18th-century births]]\n[[Category:1708 births]]\n[[Category:Year of death uncertain]]\n[[Category:18th-century English writers]]\n[[Category:18th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:People from Worcester]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Francis_Moore_(geographer)"}
{"title_page": "Festival du Voyageur", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox recurring event\n| name         = Festival du Voyageur\n| native_name  =\n|logo=Logo_voyageur.gif\n| logo_caption \n| participants = \n| attendance   = 93,400\n| area         =\n| budget       =\n| patron       =\n| organised    = <!--\"organized=\" also works-->\n| filing       = <!-- Filing status -->\n| member       =\n| website      = {{URL|heho.ca}}\n| footnotes    =\n}}\n\nThe '''Festival du Voyageur''' is an annual 10-day winter [[festival]] that takes place in [[Winnipeg]], [[Manitoba]], Canada. The event is held during each February in Winnipeg's French Quarter, [[Saint-Boniface, Manitoba|Saint-Boniface]], and is [[Western Canada]]'s largest winter festival. It celebrates Canada's fur-trading past and unique [[French Canadians|French heritage and culture]] through entertainment, arts and crafts, music, exhibits, and displays.\n\n==History==\n[[File: Festival du Voyageur. Whittier Park, St. Boniface, Winnipeg (500149) (12607549554).jpg|alt=Snow sculpture at Festival du Voyageur, with the Fort Gibraltar in the background.|thumb|Snow sculpture at Festival du Voyageur, with the [[Fort Gibraltar]] in the background.]]\n[[File: Sculpture for Festival du Voyageur in Winnipeg, Manitoba.jpg|thumb|Snow sculpture from Festival 2013]]\n[[File: Festival du Voyageur ice sculpture for Red River College.jpg|thumb|Ice sculpture for [[Red River College]] in the [[Exchange District]] from Festival 2014]]\n\nThe idea for a winter festival to celebrate Manitoba's [[Francophonie]] was first proposed by Georges Forest. He became the first official Voyageur. Voyageurs are people who promote the festival<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mhs.mb.ca/docs/people/forest_g.shtml|title=Memorable Manitobans: Georges Forest (1924-1990)|website=www.mhs.mb.ca|accessdate=April 24, 2019}}</ref> in 1967. The proposal was put forth to the city of St. Boniface, but the city's offer was insufficient.<ref name=FDVHistory>{{cite web|title=History of Festival du Voyageur inc.|url=http://festivalvoyageur.mb.ca/en/fdv-inc/about-us2/history/|publisher=FDV Inc|accessdate=January 23, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201181904/http://festivalvoyageur.mb.ca/en/fdv-inc/about-us2/history/|archive-date=February 1, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 1969, the [[mayor]], Ed Turner, and the [[city council]] of Saint-Boniface granted their support under the condition that Festival became an incorporated organization. Judge Robert Trudel became the first president of Festival du/of the Voyageur. \"[[Voyageurs|Voyageur]]\" refers to those who worked for a [[fur trade|fur trading]] company and usually travelled by [[canoe]]. Festival du/of the Voyageur Inc. was incorporated under the [[Companies Act of Manitoba]] on December 18, 1969. It received a city grant of $35,000 but had to give back all profits up to $35,000.{{Citation needed|date=February 2008}}\n\nAt a press conference held January 13, 1970, Mayor Turner announced that the city of Saint-Boniface would present a festival honouring the Voyageur of the fur trading era, in celebration of Manitoba's centennial. The first Festival du/of the Voyageur took place February 26 to March 1, 1970, at Provencher Park, with an estimated attendance of 50,000 people.{{Citation needed|date=January 2014}} Georges Forest was in charge of promoting the event and did so by wearing clothing that represented the Voyageurs. This initiated the tradition of \"Official Voyageurs\", which continues to this day. The 1970 festival lasted four days and featured the walk down Provencher Boulevard, the Governor's Bal and the Voyageur Trading Post.<ref name=FDVHistory/>\n\nA large number of attendees required an unforeseen level of expenditure by festival organizers; by the festival's conclusion, the organization had debt in excess of C$40,000. To remedy their financial situation, the organizers held horse races as a fundraiser in conjunction with the 1971 festival. The 1971 festival was a success, drawing nearly 200,000 guests. However, instead of resolving the financial situation, the fundraiser pushed the organization further into debt.{{Citation needed|date=January 2014}}\n\nThe snow sculpture that won the 1971 event was of a pair of boots and a toque. This sculpture inspired the creation of a mascot, L\u00e9o La Tuque, who was introduced in 1972 and became the trademark of Festival du Voyageur.<ref name=FDVHistory/>\n\nGrants from the city of Winnipeg and the Secretary of State allowed the Festival to make arrangements with their creditors. The name was changed to \"Festival du Voyageur\" (the \"of the\" was dropped). For the 1972 festival, Arthur D'Eschambault was elected president. He hired a number of financial and management directors (most of whom were [[English Canadian|anglophone]]). The festival ran from February 21 to 27, and the profits amounted to C$108.46.\n\nTwo \"school\" voyageurs were appointed in 1977, to visit schools and teach children about the voyageurs and Festival.\n\nIn 1977, construction began on wooden log cabins in Whittier Park to accommodate the festival. The log cabins were constructed to be left there year-round. In 1978, the organization had accumulated enough surplus funds to make Whittier Park the permanent site of the festival. Provencher Park had become too small for the growing number of attendees.  These cabins formed the foundation of the historic reconstruction that became known as Fort Gibraltar.<ref name=FDVHistory/>\n\nIn 1981, the Festival du Voyageur purchased an empty warehouse, located at 768 Tach\u00e9 Avenue, for administrative offices and to be used for an additional venue. The building became known as the Rendez-Vous and eventually came to include a bar named Le Canot.<ref name=FDVHistory/>\n\nFrom February to October 2001, a large house was constructed in Fort Gibraltar for the event. The house is called the Maison du Bourgeois.<ref name=FDVHistory/>\n\nThe Rendez-Vous building on Tach\u00e9 was put up for sale in 2003, and sold in 2006. New administrative offices were found in a building at 233 Provencher Avenue, and it came to also feature a store called the Boutique du voyageur.<ref name=FDVHistory/>\n\nIn 2005, a year-round interpretive centre was built in Fort Gibraltar.<ref name=FDVHistory/>\n\nIn 2011, The Festival was awarded the [[Award of Excellence \u2013 Promotion of Linguistic Duality]] by the [[Office of the Commissioner of Official Languages|Commissioner of Official Languages]] [[Graham Fraser]] for its contribution to the vitality of the Franco-Manitoban Community.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.chrisd.ca/2012/02/22/festival-du-voyageur-award-of-excellence-promotion-of-linguistic-duality/|title=Festival du Voyageur Receives Linguistic Duality Award {{!}} ChrisD.ca|date=February 22, 2012|work=ChrisD.ca|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Attendance ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Attendance levels at the Festival du Voyageur<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/festival-du-voyageur-attendance-numbers-down-from-last-year-1.2969639|title=Second coldest Festival means fewer daytime visit|publisher=CBC News|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n|2018\n|93,400<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chrisd.ca/?s=festival+du+voyageur&submit=Search|title=You searched for festival du voyageur - ChrisD.ca|website=ChrisD.ca|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|2017\n|94,000<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.chrisd.ca/2017/02/27/festival-du-voyageur-2017-attendance/|title=Festival du Voyageur Sees Dip in Attendance {{!}} ChrisD.ca|date=February 27, 2017|work=ChrisD.ca|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|2016\n|102,000<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/2532479/festival-du-voyageur-attendance-up-13-per-cent-over-last-year/|title=Festival du Voyageur attendance up 13 per cent over last year|work=Global News|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|2015\n|91,000\n|-\n|2014\n|100,000\n|-\n|2013\n|97,000\n|-\n|2012\n|95,000\n|-\n|2011\n|97,000\n|}\n\n==Current Operation==\n\nFestival du Voyageur Inc. received $438,174 in 2010 from Industry Canada's two-year Marquee Tourism Events Program (MTEP). In 2011, the festival saw 1,151 volunteers donate 14,393 hours of work.<ref name=ThompsonCitizen>{{cite news|last=Barker|first=John|title=Festival du Voyageur: Not just a celebration for Saint-Boniface|url=http://www.thompsoncitizen.net/article/20120217/THOMPSON0107/302179997/-1/THOMPSON|accessdate=January 23, 2014|newspaper=Thompson Citizen|date=February 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe festival currently employs 13 full-time permanent staff and at the festivals peak employs roughly 200 people.<ref name=FDVHistory/> The typical annual attendance is 100,000 people across all ten days of the festival.<ref name=BigCrowd>{{cite news|title=Festival du Voyageur draws big crowds|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/story/2012/02/20/mb-festival-attendance-winnipeg.html|accessdate=March 4, 2013|publisher=CBC News|date=February 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe 2013 festival saw approximate revenue of $2.9&nbsp;million.<ref name=AnnualReport2013>{{cite web|title=Festival du Voyageur Inc. 2012-2013 ANNUAL REPORT|url=http://festivalvoyageur.mb.ca/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/FDV-2012-2013-Annual-Report-EN-WEB-Compressed.pdf|publisher=FDV, Inc.|accessdate=January 23, 2014|pages=28}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Coureur des bois]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n* {{official website|http://www.festivalvoyageur.mb.ca/}}\n\n[[Category:Winter festivals in Canada]]\n[[Category:Festivals in Winnipeg]]\n[[Category:Recurring events established in 1970]]\n[[Category:Franco-Manitoban culture]]\n[[Category:1970 establishments in Manitoba]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox recurring event\n| name         = Festival du Voyageur\n| native_name  =\n|logo=Logo_voyageur.gif\n| logo_caption =\n| image        = \n| caption      = \n| status       = Active\n| genre        = Winter festival\n| date         = February 14\u201323, 2020\n| begins       =\n| ends         =\n| frequency    = Annually\n| venue        =\n| location     = [[Winnipeg|Winnipeg, Manitoba]], Canada\n| years_active =\n| first        = 1969\n| last         = 2020\n| next         = 2021\n| participants = \n| attendance   = 93,400\n| area         =\n| budget       =\n| patron       =\n| organised    = <!--\"organized=\" also works-->\n| filing       = <!-- Filing status -->\n| member       =\n| website      = {{URL|heho.ca}}\n| footnotes    =\n}}\n\nThe '''Festival du Voyageur''' is an annual 10-day winter [[festival]] that takes place in [[Winnipeg]], [[Manitoba]], Canada. The event is held during each February in Winnipeg's French Quarter, [[Saint-Boniface, Manitoba|Saint-Boniface]], and is [[Western Canada]]'s largest winter festival. It celebrates Canada's fur-trading past and unique [[French Canadians|French heritage and culture]] through entertainment, arts and crafts, music, exhibits, and displays.\n\n==History==\n[[File: Festival du Voyageur. Whittier Park, St. Boniface, Winnipeg (500149) (12607549554).jpg|alt=Snow sculpture at Festival du Voyageur, with the Fort Gibraltar in the background.|thumb|Snow sculpture at Festival du Voyageur, with the [[Fort Gibraltar]] in the background.]]\n[[File: Sculpture for Festival du Voyageur in Winnipeg, Manitoba.jpg|thumb|Snow sculpture from Festival 2013]]\n[[File: Festival du Voyageur ice sculpture for Red River College.jpg|thumb|Ice sculpture for [[Red River College]] in the [[Exchange District]] from Festival 2014]]\n\nThe idea for a winter festival to celebrate Manitoba's [[Francophonie]] was first proposed by Georges Forest. He became the first official Voyageur. Voyageurs are people who promote the festival<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mhs.mb.ca/docs/people/forest_g.shtml|title=Memorable Manitobans: Georges Forest (1924-1990)|website=www.mhs.mb.ca|accessdate=April 24, 2019}}</ref> in 1967. The proposal was put forth to the city of St. Boniface, but the city's offer was insufficient.<ref name=FDVHistory>{{cite web|title=History of Festival du Voyageur inc.|url=http://festivalvoyageur.mb.ca/en/fdv-inc/about-us2/history/|publisher=FDV Inc|accessdate=January 23, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201181904/http://festivalvoyageur.mb.ca/en/fdv-inc/about-us2/history/|archive-date=February 1, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 1969, the [[mayor]], Ed Turner, and the [[city council]] of Saint-Boniface granted their support under the condition that Festival became an incorporated organization. Judge Robert Trudel became the first president of Festival du/of the Voyageur. \"[[Voyageurs|Voyageur]]\" refers to those who worked for a [[fur trade|fur trading]] company and usually travelled by [[canoe]]. Festival du/of the Voyageur Inc. was incorporated under the [[Companies Act of Manitoba]] on December 18, 1969. It received a city grant of $35,000 but had to give back all profits up to $35,000.{{Citation needed|date=February 2008}}\n\nAt a press conference held January 13, 1970, Mayor Turner announced that the city of Saint-Boniface would present a festival honouring the Voyageur of the fur trading era, in celebration of Manitoba's centennial. The first Festival du/of the Voyageur took place February 26 to March 1, 1970, at Provencher Park, with an estimated attendance of 50,000 people.{{Citation needed|date=January 2014}} Georges Forest was in charge of promoting the event and did so by wearing clothing that represented the Voyageurs. This initiated the tradition of \"Official Voyageurs\", which continues to this day. The 1970 festival lasted four days and featured the walk down Provencher Boulevard, the Governor's Bal and the Voyageur Trading Post.<ref name=FDVHistory/>\n\nA large number of attendees required an unforeseen level of expenditure by festival organizers; by the festival's conclusion, the organization had debt in excess of C$40,000. To remedy their financial situation, the organizers held horse races as a fundraiser in conjunction with the 1971 festival. The 1971 festival was a success, drawing nearly 200,000 guests. However, instead of resolving the financial situation, the fundraiser pushed the organization further into debt.{{Citation needed|date=January 2014}}\n\nThe snow sculpture that won the 1971 event was of a pair of boots and a toque. This sculpture inspired the creation of a mascot, L\u00e9o La Tuque, who was introduced in 1972 and became the trademark of Festival du Voyageur.<ref name=FDVHistory/>\n\nGrants from the city of Winnipeg and the Secretary of State allowed the Festival to make arrangements with their creditors. The name was changed to \"Festival du Voyageur\" (the \"of the\" was dropped). For the 1972 festival, Arthur D'Eschambault was elected president. He hired a number of financial and management directors (most of whom were [[English Canadian|anglophone]]). The festival ran from February 21 to 27, and the profits amounted to C$108.46.\n\nTwo \"school\" voyageurs were appointed in 1977, to visit schools and teach children about the voyageurs and Festival.\n\nIn 1977, construction began on wooden log cabins in Whittier Park to accommodate the festival. The log cabins were constructed to be left there year-round. In 1978, the organization had accumulated enough surplus funds to make Whittier Park the permanent site of the festival. Provencher Park had become too small for the growing number of attendees.  These cabins formed the foundation of the historic reconstruction that became known as Fort Gibraltar.<ref name=FDVHistory/>\n\nIn 1981, the Festival du Voyageur purchased an empty warehouse, located at 768 Tach\u00e9 Avenue, for administrative offices and to be used for an additional venue. The building became known as the Rendez-Vous and eventually came to include a bar named Le Canot.<ref name=FDVHistory/>\n\nFrom February to October 2001, a large house was constructed in Fort Gibraltar for the event. The house is called the Maison du Bourgeois.<ref name=FDVHistory/>\n\nThe Rendez-Vous building on Tach\u00e9 was put up for sale in 2003, and sold in 2006. New administrative offices were found in a building at 233 Provencher Avenue, and it came to also feature a store called the Boutique du voyageur.<ref name=FDVHistory/>\n\nIn 2005, a year-round interpretive centre was built in Fort Gibraltar.<ref name=FDVHistory/>\n\nIn 2011, The Festival was awarded the [[Award of Excellence \u2013 Promotion of Linguistic Duality]] by the [[Office of the Commissioner of Official Languages|Commissioner of Official Languages]] [[Graham Fraser]] for its contribution to the vitality of the Franco-Manitoban Community.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.chrisd.ca/2012/02/22/festival-du-voyageur-award-of-excellence-promotion-of-linguistic-duality/|title=Festival du Voyageur Receives Linguistic Duality Award {{!}} ChrisD.ca|date=February 22, 2012|work=ChrisD.ca|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Attendance ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Attendance levels at the Festival du Voyageur<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/festival-du-voyageur-attendance-numbers-down-from-last-year-1.2969639|title=Second coldest Festival means fewer daytime visit|publisher=CBC News|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n|2018\n|93,400<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chrisd.ca/?s=festival+du+voyageur&submit=Search|title=You searched for festival du voyageur - ChrisD.ca|website=ChrisD.ca|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|2017\n|94,000<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.chrisd.ca/2017/02/27/festival-du-voyageur-2017-attendance/|title=Festival du Voyageur Sees Dip in Attendance {{!}} ChrisD.ca|date=February 27, 2017|work=ChrisD.ca|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|2016\n|102,000<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/2532479/festival-du-voyageur-attendance-up-13-per-cent-over-last-year/|title=Festival du Voyageur attendance up 13 per cent over last year|work=Global News|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|2015\n|91,000\n|-\n|2014\n|100,000\n|-\n|2013\n|97,000\n|-\n|2012\n|95,000\n|-\n|2011\n|97,000\n|}\n\n==Current Operation==\n\nFestival du Voyageur Inc. received $438,174 in 2010 from Industry Canada's two-year Marquee Tourism Events Program (MTEP). In 2011, the festival saw 1,151 volunteers donate 14,393 hours of work.<ref name=ThompsonCitizen>{{cite news|last=Barker|first=John|title=Festival du Voyageur: Not just a celebration for Saint-Boniface|url=http://www.thompsoncitizen.net/article/20120217/THOMPSON0107/302179997/-1/THOMPSON|accessdate=January 23, 2014|newspaper=Thompson Citizen|date=February 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe festival currently employs 13 full-time permanent staff and at the festivals peak employs roughly 200 people.<ref name=FDVHistory/> The typical annual attendance is 100,000 people across all ten days of the festival.<ref name=BigCrowd>{{cite news|title=Festival du Voyageur draws big crowds|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/story/2012/02/20/mb-festival-attendance-winnipeg.html|accessdate=March 4, 2013|publisher=CBC News|date=February 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe 2013 festival saw approximate revenue of $2.9&nbsp;million.<ref name=AnnualReport2013>{{cite web|title=Festival du Voyageur Inc. 2012-2013 ANNUAL REPORT|url=http://festivalvoyageur.mb.ca/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/FDV-2012-2013-Annual-Report-EN-WEB-Compressed.pdf|publisher=FDV, Inc.|accessdate=January 23, 2014|pages=28}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Coureur des bois]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n* {{official website|http://www.festivalvoyageur.mb.ca/}}\n\n[[Category:Winter festivals in Canada]]\n[[Category:Festivals in Winnipeg]]\n[[Category:Recurring events established in 1970]]\n[[Category:Franco-Manitoban culture]]\n[[Category:1970 establishments in Manitoba]]\n", "name_user": "2001:1970:4cdc:2100:2855:ffa5:a4dc:99d3", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Festival_du_Voyageur"}
{"title_page": "Indian locomotive class WAM-4", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2019}}{{under construction|altimage=|section=|nosection=|notready=|placedby=[[user:hdmanohar]]|comment=|nocat=|category=}}{{Infobox locomotive\n | name             = Indian Railways WAM-4\n | image            = File:WAM4 Ennore.JPG\n | caption          = AJJ WAM-4 hauling an express train\n | powertype        = Electric\n | builddate        = 1970\u20131983\n | rebuilddate      = 1978\u20131983 to WAG-5\n | gauge            = {{Track gauge|66in|lk=on}}\n | builder          = [[Chittaranjan Locomotive Works]], [[India]]\n | totalproduction  = '''WAM-4:''' 500\n | uicclass         = Co\u2032Co\u2032\n | axleload         = {{convert|18.8|t}}\n | electricsystem   = {{25 kV 50 Hz}} [[Overhead line|Overhead]] \n | collectionmethod = [[Pantograph (rail)|Pantograph]]\n | poweroutput      = {{convert|3640|hp|kW|-1|abbr=on}}\n | maxspeed         = {{convert|110|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}} \n | tractiveeffort   = {{convert|33840|kgf|kN lbf|abbr=on}}\n | operator         = [[Indian Railways]]\n | fleetnumbers     = 20400\u201320699, 21200\u201321399\n | nicknames        = Ananth, RAJATABHA, Surubhi, Navchetna, Sukh Sagar Naveen\n | locale           = All over [[India]]\n}}\n\nThe Indian locomotive class '''WAM-4''' is a class of 25 [[Volt|kV]] [[Alternating current|AC]] [[electric locomotive]]s that was developed in the 1970 by [[Chittaranjan Locomotive Works]] for [[Indian Railways]]. The model name stands for [[5 ft 6 in gauge railway|broad gauge (W)]], '''A'''C Current (A), '''M'''ixed traffic (M) engine, '''4'''th generation (4). WAM4 though an indigenously produced loco was heavily inspired by French box design and naturally favoured a French TM which was the Alstom made TAO TM.A total of 500 WAM-4 were built at CLW between 1978 and 1983, which made them the most numerous class of mainline electric locomotive till it's successor the [[Indian locomotive class WAG-5|WAG-5.]]\n\nThis class proved so successful by virtue of its ruggedness suitable for Indian conditions and simplicity of maintenance, that IR used this basic design for a number of other locos later ([[Indian locomotive class WCAM 1|WCAM-1]], [[Indian locomotive class WAG-5|WAG-5A]], [[Indian locomotive class WCG-2|WCG-2]], and some [[Indian locomotive class WAP-1|WAP]] models). A single WAM-4 can generally haul up to a 24-coach passenger rake. However, with the advent of new 3-phase locos like WAP - 5 and WAP - 7, the WAM - 4 locomotives were relegated to hauling smaller passenger trains. Also, due to the aging fleet the WAM - 4 locomotives are being rapidly scrapped and withdrawn from mainline duties.\n\n== Origins ==\nThe history of WAM-4 begins in early 1970s with the aim of addressing the shortcomings of the previous [[Indian locomotive class WAM-1|WAM-1]]/[[Indian locomotive class WAM-2/3|2]] and [[Indian Railways WAG class|WAG(1-4)]] classes and remove [[Steam locomotive|steam locomotives]] from IR by a target date of 1990. The WAM1s were not great successes as some of their advanced features were unsuitable for Indian conditions \n\nso the designers at [[Research Design and Standards Organisation|RDSO]] and CLW decided to use the following\n\n* Instead of the Bo-Bo bogies of WAM-1/2, ALCO asymmetric Trimount bogies of the [[Indian locomotive class WDM-2|WDM-2]] were provided for better traction and power.\n* Silicon rectifiers with speed control by three series-parallel motor combinations and weak field operation.\n* Auxiliaries from Westinghouse and Kirloskar (compressors), S F India (blowers) and Northey (exhauster)\n* Air brakes for loco and vacuum train brakes fitted as original equipment with [[Rheostatic braking]] also provided\n* MU operation made possible up to 4 units possible.\n\nProduction of these locomotives started in 1970 with #20400 and exactly 500 WAM4s were built in 13 years with #21399 \u201cAnant\u201d being the last one. Production ended on August 3,1983.\n\n== Variants ==\nThis loco class has been seen in many variations, as a lot of workshops and sheds have carried out their own enhancements or modifications to the basic loco design. Although the code indicates a mixed-use loco, most WAM-4's ended up hauling passenger trains. \n\nVariants include\n\n* '''WAM4B or G:''' Freight only (regeared version)\n* '''WAM4D''' or '''DB:''' Dual Braked (Air and Vacuum)\n* '''WAM4E:''' Air Brake only (for both loco and train)\n* '''WAM4H:''' Hitachi Traction Motors instead of Alstom\n* '''WAM4P:''' Passenger only (regeared version)\n* '''WAM4/2S3P:''' 2 TMs in Series, 3 in Parallel\n* '''WAM4/6P:''' 6 traction motors permanently in parallel\n* '''WAM4/6PE:''' Air braked, 6 TMs perm. in parallel\n* '''WAM4/6PDBHS:''' 6 Traction Motors permanently in parallel, Dual Brakes, High Speed\n* '''WAM-4P D:''' Passenger only (dual brakes)\n*'''WAM-4P DB 6P''' and '''WAM-4 6P D:''' These are for superfast trains\n*'''WAM-4P DB 3P and WAM-4 2S-3P:'''  some superfasts, passengers\n\nThe 'DB' or 'D' generally, but perhaps not always, indicates dual-brake capability. 'HS' may be for 'high speed'.'2S', '3P', '6P', etc. indicate traction motors connected in series or parallel. The WAM-4 has six traction motors, and originally they were wired to be available in different configurations at different power settings. At notches up to 14, all motors were in series (at notch 14 all resistors dropping out); up to notch 21 in series-parallel combinations (three pairs of motors in series, the pairs themselves being in parallel); and further notches with all motors in parallel (at notch 30 all motors are in parallel with resistors dropping out). This is the original configuration of the WCAM-x series of locos too.\n\nThe WAM-4 locos were later reconfigured to have all motors always in parallel (6P variants) or with the three series-connected pairs in parallel (2S 3P variants). Some WAM-4 locos from CLW are thought to have had the 2S 3P configuration right from the start. The 2S 3P configuration was better for the mixed traffic loads especially as it allowed the locos to start hauling larger loads without stalling. With increasing use of the WAM-4 locos for passenger traffic the all-parallel configuration was deemed more desirable since it allowed higher speeds and higher acceleration.Now, most of these are used exclusively for passenger traffic.\n\n== Livery ==\nThis loco has the widest variety of liveries, with each loco shed having its own livery\n\nMost of the WAM-4 locos now have their MU capability disabled as [[Research Design and Standards Organization|RDSO]] disapproves of these locos running MU'd over 100&nbsp;km/h.\n<ref>http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-loco2e.html</ref>\n\n== Named Locos<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irfca.org/apps/locos/list?list_type=named&page=10|title=[IRFCA] Indian Railways Locomotive Roster List|website=www.irfca.org|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Named Locos\n!Class\n!Loco Number\n!Name\n!Loco Shed\n!Current status\n!ref\n|-\n|WAM-4\n|20401 \n|   <abbr>BIA</abbr>  \n|Rajatabha  \n|Condemned [07/08/2007]  \n|<ref>https://www.irfca.org/apps/locos/show/4489?list_type=named&page=10</ref>\n|-\n|WAM-4\n|20420   \n|BZA\n|Sukh Sagar Naveen \n|Scrapped\n|<ref>https://www.irfca.org/apps/locos/show/4508?list_type=named&page=10</ref>\n|-\n|WAM-4\n|20615    \n| <abbr>ASN</abbr>  \n|Surubhi \n|Condemned in November 2011\n|<ref>https://www.irfca.org/apps/locos/show/4703?list_type=named&page=10</ref>\n|-\n|WAM-4\n|21320 \n|<abbr>AJJ</abbr>\n|Garuda \n|Plinthed at Rail Soudha, SWR HQ, Hubli [January 2020]  \n|<ref>https://www.irfca.org/apps/locos/show/4908?list_type=named&page=10</ref>\n|-\n|WAM-4\n|21380 \n|<abbr>ASN</abbr> \n|Navchetna  \n|In Inferior service\n|<ref>https://www.irfca.org/apps/locos/show/4968?list_type=named&page=10</ref>\n|-\n|WAM-4\n|21399  \n| <abbr>BSL</abbr> \n|Anant \n|The last WAM-4 ever built. No longer in holdings - assumed withdrawn/scrapped [January 2019\n|<ref>https://www.irfca.org/apps/locos/show/4987?list_type=named&page=10</ref>\n|}\n\n==Loco Sheds still holding WAM-4.==\n*'''Loco Shed Asansol-''' 3\n*'''Loco Shed Ghaziabad-''' 1\n*'''Loco Shed Ludhiana-''' 1\n*'''Loco Shed Jhansi-''' 1\n*'''Loco Shed Kanpur-''' 3\n*'''Loco Shed Tatanagar-''' 4\n*'''Loco Shed Bhilai-''' 4<br/ >In total 17 locomotives as of 01-03-2020 are there but 9 of them are overaged condemned and 8 of them are inferior in service.\n('''Note-'''Before updating the information here anybody should check out the railways current official data first in the  '''Source''' link then change the data.)\n<br/ >'''Source:''' http://elocos.railnet.gov.in/\n\n==Technical specifications<ref>[http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-loco2e.html#loco Indian AC electric loco information]</ref>==\n{| class=wikitable\n|Traction Motors\n|Alstom TAO 659 A1 (575&nbsp;kW, 750 V). Six motors, axle-hung, nose-suspended, force-ventilated. \n|-\n|Gear Ratio\n|15:62 originally (and still for WAM-4 2S3P), now many variations, 21:58 being common for WAM-4 6P locos.\n|-\n|Transformer\n|Heil BOT 3460 A, 22.5 kV / 3460 kVA. \n|-\n|Rectifiers\n|Two silicon rectifier cells, 1270 V / 1000 A each cubicle. \n|-\n|Pantographs\n|Two Faiveley AM-12. \n|-\n|Hauling capacity\n|{{convert|2010|t|abbr=on}} \n|-\n|Current Ratings\n|(WAM-4 6P) 1100A/10min, 750A continuous\n|}<br />\n==Image Gallery==\n<gallery widths=\"180\" heights=\"150\" perrow=\"4\">\nFile:VSKP-Nanded Express exits Moula Ali.jpg|WAM 4 series loco 20491 from Vadodara Shed VSKP-Nanded Express\nFile:WAM4 loco at Moulaali.jpg|WAM 4 series loco 21226 from Visakhapatnam Shed spotted at [[Moula-Ali|Moula Ali]]\nFile:WAM 4 series loco at Visakhapatnam.jpg|WAM 4 series loco 21219 from [[Arakkonam]] Shed spotted at [[Visakhapatnam Junction]]\nFile:13022 (Raxaul-Howrah) Mithila Express 01.jpg|13022 (Raxaul - [[Howrah Junction railway station|Howrah]]) Mithila Express with [[Howrah Junction railway station|HWH]] WAM 4 21281 based at katni shed\nFile:A WAM-4 class Locomotive at Secunderabad.jpg|WAM-4P loco of [[Vijayawada Junction railway station|Vijayawada]] Shed spotted at [[Secunderabad Junction railway station|Secunderabad]]\nFile:WAM 4 with the Malwa Express.jpg|WAM 4 with the [[Malwa Express]]\nFile:12295 (SBC-PNBE) Sanghamitra Express 01.jpg|12295 (SBC-PNBE) Sanghamitra Express from [[Mughalsarai]] Shed\nFile:Howrah bound 12814 (Tatanagar-Howrah) Steel Express.jpg|Howrah bound 12814 (Tatanagar-Howrah) Steel Express with WAM4 series loco of Tata shed\n</gallery>\n\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[History of rail transport in India]]\n*[[Indian Railways]]\n*[[Locomotives of India]]\n*[[Rail transport in India]]\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{Hughes-IndianLocos4}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Indian locomotive class WAM4}}\n*[http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-specs.html#WAG-9 Specifications]\n*[http://www.irfca.org India railway fan club]\n\n{{Broad gauge locomotives of India |state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Electric locomotives of India]]\n[[Category:25 kV AC locomotives]]\n[[Category:Co-Co locomotives]]\n[[Category:Railway locomotives introduced in 1970]]\n[[Category:5 ft 6 in gauge locomotives]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2019}}{{under construction|altimage=|section=|nosection=|notready=|placedby=[[user:hdmanohar]]|comment=|nocat=|category=}}{{Infobox locomotive\n | name             = Indian Railways WAM-4\n | image            = File:WAM4 Ennore.JPG\n | caption          = AJJ WAM-4 hauling an express train\n | powertype        = Electric\n | builddate        = 1970\u20131983\n | rebuilddate      = 1978\u20131983 to WAG-5\n | gauge            = {{Track gauge|66in|lk=on}}\n | builder          = [[Chittaranjan Locomotive Works]], [[India]]\n | totalproduction  = '''WAM-4:''' 500\n | uicclass         = Co\u2032Co\u2032\n | axleload         = {{convert|18.8|t}}\n | electricsystem   = {{25 kV 50 Hz}} [[Overhead line|Overhead]] \n | collectionmethod = [[Pantograph (rail)|Pantograph]]\n | poweroutput      = {{convert|3640|hp|kW|-1|abbr=on}}\n | maxspeed         = {{convert|110|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}} \n | tractiveeffort   = {{convert|33840|kgf|kN lbf|abbr=on}}\n | operator         = [[Indian Railways]]\n | fleetnumbers     = 20400\u201320699, 21200\u201321399\n | nicknames        = Ananth, RAJATABHA, Surubhi, Navchetna, Sukh Sagar Naveen\n | locale           = All over [[India]]\n}}\n\nThe Indian locomotive class '''WAM-4''' is a class of 25 [[Volt|kV]] [[Alternating current|AC]] [[electric locomotive]]s that was developed in the 1970 by [[Chittaranjan Locomotive Works]] for [[Indian Railways]]. The model name stands for [[5 ft 6 in gauge railway|broad gauge (W)]], '''A'''C Current (A), '''M'''ixed traffic (M) engine, '''4'''th generation (4). WAM4 though an indigenously produced loco was heavily inspired by French box design and naturally favoured a French TM which was the Alstom made TAO TM.A total of 500 WAM-4 were built at CLW between 1978 and 1983, which made them the most numerous class of mainline electric locomotive till it's successor the [[Indian locomotive class WAG-5|WAG-5.]]\n\nThis class proved so successful by virtue of its ruggedness suitable for Indian conditions and simplicity of maintenance, that IR used this basic design for a number of other locos later ([[Indian locomotive class WCAM 1|WCAM-1]], [[Indian locomotive class WAG-5|WAG-5A]], [[Indian locomotive class WCG-2|WCG-2]], and some [[Indian locomotive class WAP-1|WAP]] models). A single WAM-4 can generally haul up to a 24-coach passenger rake. However, with the advent of new 3-phase locos like WAP - 5 and WAP - 7, the WAM - 4 locomotives were relegated to hauling smaller passenger trains. Also, due to the aging fleet the WAM - 4 locomotives are being rapidly scrapped and withdrawn from mainline duties.\n\n== Origins ==\nThe history of WAM-4 begins in early 1970s with the aim of addressing the shortcomings of the previous [[Indian locomotive class WAM-1|WAM-1]]/[[Indian locomotive class WAM-2/3|2]] and [[Indian Railways WAG class|WAG(1-4)]] classes and remove [[Steam locomotive|steam locomotives]] from IR by a target date of 1990. The WAM1s were not great successes as some of their advanced features were unsuitable for Indian conditions \n\nso the designers at [[Research Design and Standards Organisation|RDSO]] and CLW decided to use the following\n\n* Instead of the Bo-Bo bogies of WAM-1/2, ALCO asymmetric Trimount bogies of the [[Indian locomotive class WDM-2|WDM-2]] were provided for better traction and power.\n* Silicon rectifiers with speed control by three series-parallel motor combinations and weak field operation.\n* Auxiliaries from Westinghouse and Kirloskar (compressors), S F India (blowers) and Northey (exhauster)\n* Air brakes for loco and vacuum train brakes fitted as original equipment with [[Rheostatic braking]] also provided\n* MU operation made possible up to 4 units possible.\n\nProduction of these locomotives started in 1970 with #20400 and exactly 500 WAM4s were built in 13 years with #21399 \u201cAnant\u201d being the last one. Production ended on August 3,1983.\n\n== Variants ==\nThis loco class has been seen in many variations, as a lot of workshops and sheds have carried out their own enhancements or modifications to the basic loco design. Although the code indicates a mixed-use loco, most WAM-4's ended up hauling passenger trains. \n\nVariants include\n\n* '''WAM4B or G:''' Freight only (regeared version)\n* '''WAM4D''' or '''DB:''' Dual Braked (Air and Vacuum)\n* '''WAM4E:''' Air Brake only (for both loco and train)\n* '''WAM4H:''' Hitachi Traction Motors instead of Alstom\n* '''WAM4P:''' Passenger only (regeared version)\n* '''WAM4/2S3P:''' 2 TMs in Series, 3 in Parallel\n* '''WAM4/6P:''' 6 traction motors permanently in parallel\n* '''WAM4/6PE:''' Air braked, 6 TMs perm. in parallel\n* '''WAM4/6PDBHS:''' 6 Traction Motors permanently in parallel, Dual Brakes, High Speed\n* '''WAM-4P D:''' Passenger only (dual brakes)\n*'''WAM-4P DB 6P''' and '''WAM-4 6P D:''' These are for superfast trains\n*'''WAM-4P DB 3P and WAM-4 2S-3P:'''  some superfasts, passengers\n\nThe 'DB' or 'D' generally, but perhaps not always, indicates dual-brake capability. 'HS' may be for 'high speed'.'2S', '3P', '6P', etc. indicate traction motors connected in series or parallel. The WAM-4 has six traction motors, and originally they were wired to be available in different configurations at different power settings. At notches up to 14, all motors were in series (at notch 14 all resistors dropping out); up to notch 21 in series-parallel combinations (three pairs of motors in series, the pairs themselves being in parallel); and further notches with all motors in parallel (at notch 30 all motors are in parallel with resistors dropping out). This is the original configuration of the WCAM-x series of locos too.\n\nThe WAM-4 locos were later reconfigured to have all motors always in parallel (6P variants) or with the three series-connected pairs in parallel (2S 3P variants). Some WAM-4 locos from CLW are thought to have had the 2S 3P configuration right from the start. The 2S 3P configuration was better for the mixed traffic loads especially as it allowed the locos to start hauling larger loads without stalling. With increasing use of the WAM-4 locos for passenger traffic the all-parallel configuration was deemed more desirable since it allowed higher speeds and higher acceleration.Now, most of these are used exclusively for passenger traffic.\n\n== Livery ==\nThis loco has the widest variety of liveries, with each loco shed having its own livery\n\nMost of the WAM-4 locos now have their MU capability disabled as [[Research Design and Standards Organization|RDSO]] disapproves of these locos running MU'd over 100&nbsp;km/h.\n<ref>http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-loco2e.html</ref>\n\n== Named Locos<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irfca.org/apps/locos/list?list_type=named&page=10|title=[IRFCA] Indian Railways Locomotive Roster List|website=www.irfca.org|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Named Locos\n!Class\n!Loco Number\n!Name\n!Loco Shed\n!Current status\n!ref\n|-\n|WAM-4\n|20401 \n|   <abbr>BIA</abbr>  \n|Rajatabha  \n|Condemned [07/08/2007]  \n|\n|-\n|WAM-4\n|20420   \n|BZA\n|Sukh Sagar Naveen \n|Scrapped\n|\n|-\n|WAM-4\n|20615    \n| <abbr>ASN</abbr>  \n|Surubhi \n|Condemned in November 2011\n|\n|-\n|WAM-4\n|21320 \n|<abbr>AJJ</abbr>\n|Garuda \n|Plinthed at Rail Soudha, SWR HQ, Hubli [January 2020]  \n|\n|-\n|WAM-4\n|21380 \n|<abbr>ASN</abbr> \n|Navchetna  \n|In Inferior service\n|\n|-\n|WAM-4\n|21399  \n| <abbr>BSL</abbr> \n|Anant \n|The last WAM-4 ever built. Air brake only. TAOchi TMs. MU capable. POH at BSL, 29/07/2010. No longer in holdings - assumed withdrawn/scrapped [January 2019\n|\n|}\n\n==Loco Sheds still holding WAM-4.==\n*'''Loco Shed Asansol-''' 3\n*'''Loco Shed Ghaziabad-''' 1\n*'''Loco Shed Ludhiana-''' 1\n*'''Loco Shed Jhansi-''' 1\n*'''Loco Shed Kanpur-''' 3\n*'''Loco Shed Tatanagar-''' 4\n*'''Loco Shed Bhilai-''' 4<br/ >In total 17 locomotives as of 01-03-2020 are there but 9 of them are overaged condemned and 8 of them are inferior in service.\n('''Note-'''Before updating the information here anybody should check out the railways current official data first in the  '''Source''' link then change the data.)\n<br/ >'''Source:''' http://elocos.railnet.gov.in/\n\n==Technical specifications<ref>[http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-loco2e.html#loco Indian AC electric loco information]</ref>==\n{| class=wikitable\n|Traction Motors\n|Alstom TAO 659 A1 (575&nbsp;kW, 750 V). Six motors, axle-hung, nose-suspended, force-ventilated. \n|-\n|Gear Ratio\n|15:62 originally (and still for WAM-4 2S3P), now many variations, 21:58 being common for WAM-4 6P locos.\n|-\n|Transformer\n|Heil BOT 3460 A, 22.5 kV / 3460 kVA. \n|-\n|Rectifiers\n|Two silicon rectifier cells, 1270 V / 1000 A each cubicle. \n|-\n|Pantographs\n|Two Faiveley AM-12. \n|-\n|Hauling capacity\n|{{convert|2010|t|abbr=on}} \n|-\n|Current Ratings\n|(WAM-4 6P) 1100A/10min, 750A continuous\n|}<br />\n==Image Gallery==\n<gallery widths=\"180\" heights=\"150\" perrow=\"4\">\nFile:VSKP-Nanded Express exits Moula Ali.jpg|WAM 4 series loco 20491 from Vadodara Shed VSKP-Nanded Express\nFile:WAM4 loco at Moulaali.jpg|WAM 4 series loco 21226 from Visakhapatnam Shed spotted at [[Moula-Ali|Moula Ali]]\nFile:WAM 4 series loco at Visakhapatnam.jpg|WAM 4 series loco 21219 from [[Arakkonam]] Shed spotted at [[Visakhapatnam Junction]]\nFile:13022 (Raxaul-Howrah) Mithila Express 01.jpg|13022 (Raxaul - [[Howrah Junction railway station|Howrah]]) Mithila Express with [[Howrah Junction railway station|HWH]] WAM 4 21281 based at katni shed\nFile:A WAM-4 class Locomotive at Secunderabad.jpg|WAM-4P loco of [[Vijayawada Junction railway station|Vijayawada]] Shed spotted at [[Secunderabad Junction railway station|Secunderabad]]\nFile:WAM 4 with the Malwa Express.jpg|WAM 4 with the [[Malwa Express]]\nFile:12295 (SBC-PNBE) Sanghamitra Express 01.jpg|12295 (SBC-PNBE) Sanghamitra Express from [[Mughalsarai]] Shed\nFile:Howrah bound 12814 (Tatanagar-Howrah) Steel Express.jpg|Howrah bound 12814 (Tatanagar-Howrah) Steel Express with WAM4 series loco of Tata shed\n</gallery>\n\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[History of rail transport in India]]\n*[[Indian Railways]]\n*[[Locomotives of India]]\n*[[Rail transport in India]]\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{Hughes-IndianLocos4}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Indian locomotive class WAM4}}\n*[http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-specs.html#WAG-9 Specifications]\n*[http://www.irfca.org India railway fan club]\n\n{{Broad gauge locomotives of India |state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Electric locomotives of India]]\n[[Category:25 kV AC locomotives]]