m the Gator Swamp: A Collection of the Greatest Gator Stories Ever Told|publisher= Sports Publishing, LLC|location=Champaign, Illinois|year=2002|isbn=1-58261-514-4}}\n*{{cite book|last=Horne|first=Larry E.|title=Florida Gators IQ|isbn=978-1-4499-8947-7|year=2012}}\n* {{cite journal|first=Ric A.|last=Kabat|jstor=30148092|title=Before the Seminoles: Football at Florida State College, 1902\u20131904|journal=Florida Historical Quarterly|volume=70 |pages=20\u201337|number=1|date=July 1991}}\n* {{cite book|last=McCarthy|first=Kevin M|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_Tk-IQepI6cC|title=Fightin' Gators: A History of University of Florida Football|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|location=Mount Pleasant, South Carolina|year=2000|isbn=978-0-7385-0559-6}}\n* {{cite book|last=McEwen|first=Tom|title=The Gators: A Story of Florida Football|publisher=The Strode Publishers|location=Huntsville, Alabama|year=1974|isbn=0-87397-025-X}}\n* Nash, Noel, ed., ''The Gainesville Sun Presents The Greatest Moments in Florida Gators Football'', Sports Publishing, Inc., Champaign, Illinois (1998).  {{ISBN|1-57167-196-X}}.\n*{{cite book|last=Pleasants|first=Julian M. |title=Gator Tales: An Oral History of the University of Florida|publisher=University of Florida|location=Gainesville, Florida|year=2006}}\n* Proctor, Samuel, & Wright Langley, ''Gator History: A Pictorial History of the University of Florida'', South Star Publishing Company, Gainesville, Florida (1986).  {{ISBN|0-938637-00-2}}.\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{Florida Gators football}}\n{{Florida Gators athletic program navbox}}\n{{Southeastern Conference football navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Florida Gators Football}}\n[[Category:Florida Gators football| ]]\n[[Category:Sports clubs established in 1906]]\n[[Category:1906 establishments in Florida]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NCAA football school\n| TeamName = Florida Gators football\n| CurrentSeason = 2020 Florida Gators football team\n| Image = Florida Gators football logo.svg\n| ImageSize = 175\n| FirstYear = 1906\n| AthleticDirector = [[Scott Stricklin (athletic director)|Scott Stricklin]]\n| HeadCoach = [[Dan Mullen]] \n| HeadCoachYear = 2nd\n| HCWins = 21\n| HCLosses = 5\n| Stadium = [[Ben Hill Griffin Stadium]]\n| StadCapacity = 88,548\n| FieldName = Steve Spurrier-Florida Field\n| StadSurface = Grass\n| Location = [[Gainesville, Florida]]\n| NCAAdivision = I FBS\n| Conference = [[Southeastern Conference]]\n| ConfDivision = Eastern\n| PastAffiliations = [[NCAA Division I-A independent schools|Independent]] (1906\u20131911)<br/>[[Southern Intercollegiate Athletic Association|SIAA]] (1912\u20131921)<br />[[Southern Conference|SoCon]] (1922\u20131932)\n| ATWins = 735 <!-- As of games through 12/30/2019 -->\n| ATLosses = 420 <!-- As of games through 12/30/2019 -->\n| ATTies = 40\n| BowlWins = 24\n| BowlLosses =21\n| NatlTitles = 3 (1996, 2006, 2008)\n| UnNatlTitles = 2 (1984, 1985)\n| NatlFinalist = 1 (1995)\n| ConfTitles = 8 (1991, 1993, 1994, 1995, 1996, 2000, 2006, 2008) \n| DivTitles = 14 (1992, 1993, 1994, 1995, 1996, 1999, 2000, 2003*, 2006, 2008, 2009, 2012*, 2015, 2016)\n| Heismans = 3 ([[Steve Spurrier]], [[Danny Wuerffel]], [[Tim Tebow]])\n| WebsiteName = floridagators.com\n| WebsiteURL = https://floridagators.com/index.aspx?path=football\n| AllAmericans = 32{{refn|group=note|The NCAA records for \"consensus\" All-Americans do not reflect the total number of All-American honors received by Gators football players, only those players who received a majority of the various first-team All-American selections at their position in any given season.  The Gators' first consensus All-American was quarterback [[Steve Spurrier]] in 1966; the thirty-second and most recent was cornerback [[Vernon Hargreaves]] in 2015.<ref>''[http://fs.ncaa.org/Docs/stats/football_records/2015/Awards.pdf NCAA Football Award Winners]'', National Collegiate Athletic Association, Indianapolis, Indiana, pp. 7\u201313 (2015).</ref>}}\n| uniform = File:SEC-Uniform-UF.png\n| FightSong = \"[[The Orange and Blue]]\"\n| MascotDisplay = [[Albert and Alberta Gator|Albert and Alberta]]\n| MarchingBand = [[The Pride of the Sunshine|Pride of the Sunshine]]\n| PagFreeLabel2 = Outfitter\n| PagFreeValue2 = [[Air Jordan|Jordan Brand]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://floridagators.com/news/2017/12/6/general-jordan-brand-welcomes-university-of-florida-to-the-family.aspx|title=Jordan Brand Welcomes University of Florida to Family|website=Florida Gators}}</ref>\n| Rivalries = [[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia]] ([[Florida\u2013Georgia football rivalry|rivalry]])<br />[[LSU Tigers football|LSU]] ([[Florida\u2013LSU football rivalry|rivalry]])<br />[[Tennessee Volunteers football|Tennessee]] ([[Florida\u2013Tennessee football rivalry|rivalry]])<br />[[Auburn Tigers football|Auburn]] ([[Florida\u2013Auburn football rivalry|rivalry]])<br />[[Florida State Seminoles football|Florida State]] ([[Florida\u2013Florida State football rivalry|rivalry]])<br />[[Miami Hurricanes football|Miami]] ([[Florida\u2013Miami football rivalry|rivalry]])\n}}\n\nThe '''Florida Gators football''' program represents the [[University of Florida]] in [[American football|American]] [[college football]]. Florida competes in the [[Football Bowl Subdivision]] (FBS) of the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) and the Eastern Division of the [[Southeastern Conference]] (SEC). They play their home games in [[Steve Spurrier-Florida Field at Ben Hill Griffin Stadium]] (nicknamed \"The Swamp\") on the university's [[Gainesville, Florida|Gainesville]] campus. The team's current head coach is [[Dan Mullen]]. The Gators have won three [[College football national championships in NCAA Division I FBS|national championships]] and eight SEC titles in the 112-season history of Florida football.\n{{TOClimit|3}}\n\n==History ==\n{{main|History of Florida Gators football}}\n{{See also|History of the University of Florida|List of Florida Gators football seasons}}\n\nThe University of Florida was established in Gainesville in 1906 and fielded its first official [[varsity (sports)|varsity]] football team [[1906 Florida Gators football team|that fall]]. In 112 years of football, Florida has played in over 40 [[bowl game]]s; won three national championships ([[1997 Sugar Bowl|1996]], [[2007 BCS National Championship Game|2006]] and [[2009 BCS National Championship Game|2008]]) and eight [[Southeastern Conference]] championships ([[1991 Florida Gators football team|1991]], [[1993 Florida Gators football team|1993]], [[1994 Florida Gators football team|1994]], [[1995 Florida Gators football team|1995]], [[1996 Florida Gators football team|1996]], [[2000 Florida Gators football team|2000]], [[2006 Florida Gators football team|2006]] and [[2008 Florida Gators football team|2008]]) and have produced three [[Heisman Trophy]] winners, more than 90 first-team [[All-American]]s and 50 [[National Football League]] (NFL) first-round [[NFL Draft|draft]] choices.\n\nSince 1906, Florida Football has had 26 head coaches, including three who were inducted into the [[College Football Hall of Fame]] for their coaching success. Its first head coach was [[Jack Forsythe|Pee Wee Forsythe]] with [[Dan Mullen]] becoming the Gators' most recent head coach in 2018.\n\nFlorida Football competed for its first several seasons as an [[NCAA Division I FBS independent schools|independent]] before joining the [[Southern Intercollegiate Athletic Association]] in 1912. They moved to the [[Southern Conference]] in 1922, then left with a dozen other schools to establish the new [[Southeastern Conference]] (SEC) in 1932. Florida is currently one of fourteen member institutions in the SEC, and the football team has competed in the SEC Eastern Division since the league began divisional play in 1992.\n\nFlorida plays an eight-game SEC schedule, with six games against the other Eastern Division teams: [[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia]], [[South Carolina Gamecocks football|South Carolina]], [[Tennessee Volunteers football|Tennessee]], [[Kentucky Wildcats football|Kentucky]], [[Missouri Tigers football|Missouri]] and [[Vanderbilt Commodores football|Vanderbilt]]. The schedule is filled out with an annual game against [[Louisiana State Tigers football|Louisiana State]] and a rotating SEC Western Division team. Until 2003, the Gators also played [[Auburn Tigers football|Auburn]] every season, but contests in the rivalry are now infrequent events as part of the SEC's rotating opponent system.\n\nKey conference rivalries include the annual [[Florida\u2013Georgia football rivalry|Florida\u2013Georgia game]] in [[Jacksonville, Florida]] (usually around [[Halloween]]), the [[Florida\u2013Tennessee football rivalry|Florida\u2013Tennessee rivalry]] (usually mid-September), and the inter-divisional [[Florida\u2013LSU football rivalry|Florida\u2013LSU rivalry]] with their permanent SEC Western Division foe (in early to mid-October).\n\nFlorida has also played in-state rival [[Florida State Seminoles football|Florida State]] every year since 1958, usually facing off in the last game of the regular season. The two teams' emergence as perennial football powers during the 1980s and 1990s helped build the [[Florida\u2013Florida State football rivalry|Florida\u2013Florida State rivalry]] into a game which often has national-title implications. Before 1988, in-state rival [[Miami Hurricanes football|Miami]] was also an annual opponent; due to expanded conference schedules, the [[Florida\u2013Miami football rivalry|Florida\u2013Miami rivalry]] has been renewed only three times in the regular season and twice in bowl games since then. The remaining dates on Florida's regular schedule are filled by non-conference opponents which vary from year to year.\n\n===Home fields===\n{{main|Steve Spurrier-Florida Field at Ben Hill Griffin Stadium}}\nFlorida's outdoor sports teams initially played most of their homes games at a municipal park near downtown Gainesville. In 1911, the university installed bleachers alongside a grassy area on the north edge of the campus and dubbed it University Athletic Field, which was expanded and renamed [[Fleming Field (Gainesville)|Fleming Field]] in 1915.\n\nThe football program finally moved into a modern stadium in 1930, when the university built 22,000 seat [[Florida Field]] just south of Fleming Field. In 1989, the name was extended to \"Florida Field at Ben Hill Griffin Stadium\" to honor alumnus and sports benefactor [[Ben Hill Griffin]]. In 2016, former player and coach [[Steve Spurrier]] was honored by having his name added to the name of the field; it is now officially known as \"Steve Spurrier-Florida Field at Ben Hill Griffin Stadium\". The facility is also commonly known as \"The Swamp\", a nickname that Spurrier coined in 1992, when he was Florida's head ball coach. Florida Field has been renovated and expanded many times over the decades and has a capacity of almost 90,000.\n\nEven after Florida Field was constructed, Florida occasionally scheduled \"home\" game in other cities across the state, most often Tampa or Jacksonville. This practice was common in the early years of the program, when the Gators' home field was smaller and traveling to Gainesville was more difficult. The frequency of these rotating home games had decreased from one or two contests per season in the 1930s to one every few seasons by the 1980s. With the exception of the traditional rivalry game against Georgia, the Gators have not scheduled any home games outside of Gainesville since Florida Field expanded to become the largest football stadium in the state in 1990.\n\n== Conference affiliations ==\nFlorida's football program is a charter member of the [[Southeastern Conference]], which began play in 1933. Before that, the Gators were affiliated with two different conferences after having founded the program without a conference affiliation.<ref name=\"Gitlin2012\">{{cite book|author=Marty Gitlin|title=Florida Gators|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aG90xCiBX8QC&pg=PA14|date=1 September 2012|publisher=ABDO Publishing Company|isbn=978-1-61480-310-2|page=14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://digital.la84.org/digital/collection/p17103coll10|title=CONTENTdm|website=digital.la84.org}}</ref><ref>''2009 Southern Conference Football Media Guide'', [http://www.soconsports.com/fls/4000/socon/files/09fbguide/74-77standings.pdf?SPSID=35576&SPID=1781&DB_OEM_ID=4000  Year-by-Year Standings], Southern Conference, Spartanburg, South Carolina, p. 74 (2009).  Retrieved August 30, 2010.</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eNThHqwUK7kC|title=The USA Today College Football Encyclopedia |first1=Bob |last1=Boyles|first2=Paul|last2=Guido|date=1 January 2009|publisher=Skyhorse Publishing Inc.|via=Google Books|isbn=9781602396777 }}</ref>\n\n* [[NCAA Division I-A independent schools|Independent]] (1906\u20131911) \n* [[Southern Intercollegiate Athletic Association]] (1912\u20131921) \n* [[Southern Conference]] (1922\u20131932)\n* [[Southeastern Conference]] (1933\u2013present)\n\n== Championships ==\n===National championships===\nThe [[Florida Gators football, 1990\u20131999#1996|1996]], [[2006 Florida Gators football team|2006]] and [[2008 Florida Gators football team|2008 Gators]] were ranked number one in the final AP and Coaches Polls and were recognized as consensus national champions after winning postseason national-championship games.<ref>College Football Data Warehouse, [http://cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/national_championships/yearly_results.php?year=1996 1996 National Championships].  Retrieved November 29, 2012.</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Florida Gators|Year|Coach|Selector|Record|Bowl|Opponent|Result}}\n|-\n| [[1996 Florida Gators football team|1996]] || [[Steve Spurrier]] || [[AP Poll|AP]], [[Coaches Poll|Coaches]] || 12\u20131 || [[1997 Sugar Bowl|Sugar Bowl]] (Bowl Alliance National Championship Game) || style=\"white-space: nowrap;\" | [[Florida State Seminoles football|Florida State]] || style=\"white-space: nowrap;\" | '''W''' 52\u201320<ref name=uf96/>\n|-\n| [[2006 Florida Gators football team|2006]] || rowspan=\"2\"|[[Urban Meyer]] || rowspan=\"2\"|AP, Coaches, [[Bowl Championship Series|BCS]] || 13\u20131 || [[2007 BCS National Championship Game|BCS National Championship Game]] || [[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Ohio State]] || '''W''' 41\u201314<ref name=uf06/>\n|-\n| [[2008 Florida Gators football team|2008]] ||  13\u20131 ||[[2009 BCS National Championship Game|BCS National Championship Game]] || [[Oklahoma Sooners football|Oklahoma]] || '''W''' 24\u201314<ref name=uf08/>\n|}\n\nThe [[1984 Florida Gators football team|1984 Gators]] were recognized as national champions by ''[[The Sporting News]]'', ''[[The New York Times]]'' and the Billingsley, DeVold, Dunkel, FACT, Matthews, and [[Jeff Sagarin]] rankings. However, they finished third in the final AP Poll and seventh in the final UPI Coaches Poll behind the [[1984 BYU Cougars football team|BYU Cougars]], who were number one in both major polls and thus considered the national champions in the pre-Bowl Alliance and BCS era.<ref>College Football Data Warehouse, [http://cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/national_championships/yearly_results.php?year=1984 1984 National Championships]. Retrieved November 29, 2012.</ref> The [[1985 Florida Gators football team|1985 Gators]] finished fifth in the final 1985 AP Poll and were recognized as national champion by one minor selector.<ref>College Football Data Warehouse, [http://cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/national_championships/yearly_results.php?year=1985 1985 National Championships].  Retrieved November 29, 2012.</ref> Partially because the football program was on NCAA probation in the mid-1980s, the university has never claimed a share of the national championship for either the 1984 or 1985 season.<ref name=\"1984champs\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.gatorsports.com/article/20091120/COLUMNISTS/911209919?p=all&tc=pgall |title=Do not forget 1984, UF football's first SEC title |last=Dooley |first=Pat |date=20 November 2009 |work=Gainesville Sun |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170308045308/http://www.gatorsports.com/article/20091120/COLUMNISTS/911209919?p=all&tc=pgall |archivedate=8 March 2017 }}</ref>\n\n=== Conference championships ===\n\nFlorida has won a total of eight SEC championships. The Gators won their first championship with a conference record of 5\u20130\u20131 in 1984, but the title was vacated several months after the season ended by the SEC university presidents because of NCAA infractions by the Florida coaching staff under Charley Pell. The 1985 and 1990 teams also finished atop the standings with conference records of 5\u20131 and 6\u20131, respectively, but Florida was ineligible for the championship due to its NCAA probation for rule violations by previous coaching staffs.  The Gators won their first official SEC football championship in 1991.<ref name=ufmediaguide/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Florida Gators|Season|Conference|Coach|Overall Record|Conference Record}}\n|-\n| [[1991 Florida Gators football team|1991]] || rowspan=\"8\" | SEC || rowspan=\"6\" | [[Steve Spurrier]] || 10\u20132 || 7\u20130<ref name=uf91>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/florida/1991-schedule.html |title=1991 Florida Gators |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161005074622/http://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/florida/1991-schedule.html |archivedate=2016-10-05 }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[1993 Florida Gators football team|1993]] || 11\u20132 || 7\u20131<ref name=uf93>{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/florida/1993-schedule.html |title=1993 Florida Gators |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110620182251/http://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/florida/1993-schedule.html |archivedate=2011-06-20 }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[1994 Florida Gators football team|1994]] || 10\u20132\u20131 || 7\u20131<ref name=uf94>{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/florida/1994-schedule.html |title=1994 Florida Gators |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110622174441/http://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/florida/1994-schedule.html |archivedate=2011-06-22 }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[1995 Florida Gators football team|1995]] || 12\u20131 || 8\u20130<ref name=uf95>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/florida/1995-schedule.html |title=1995 Florida Gators |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161005074348/http://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/florida/1995-schedule.html |archivedate=2016-10-05 }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[1996 Florida Gators football team|1996]] || 12\u20131 || 8\u20130<ref name=uf96>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/florida/1996-schedule.html |title=1996 Florida Gators |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161003183458/http://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/florida/1996-schedule.html |archivedate=2016-10-03 }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[2000 Florida Gators football team|2000]] || 10\u20133 || 7\u20131<ref name=uf00>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/florida/2000-schedule.html |title=2000 Florida Gators |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161003185727/http://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/florida/2000-schedule.html |archivedate=2016-10-03 }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[2006 Florida Gators football team|2006]] || rowspan=\"2\" | [[Urban Meyer]] || 13\u20131 || 7\u20131<ref name=uf06>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/florida/2006-schedule.html |title=2006 Florida Gators |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161003184140/http://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/florida/2006-schedule.html |archivedate=2016-10-03}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[2008 Florida Gators football team|2008]] || 13\u20131 || 7\u20131<ref name=uf08>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/florida/2008-schedule.html |title=2008 Florida Gators |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161003185727/http://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/florida/2008-schedule.html |archivedate=2016-10-03 }}</ref>\n|}\n\n=== Division championships ===\n\nWith the addition of Arkansas and South Carolina to the Southeastern Conference in 1992, the conference split into eastern and western divisions and a game between the division winners determined the SEC champion. Florida has made 12 appearances in the [[SEC Championship Game]] (the most by any SEC school), its most recent in 2016. The Gators have won seven of the 12 SEC Championship Games in which they have appeared.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Florida Gators|Season|Division|Opponent|CG result}}\n|-\n| [[Florida Gators football, 1990\u20131999#1992|1992]]\u2020 || rowspan=\"14\" | SEC Eastern || [[1992 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]] || L 21\u201328<ref name=uf92>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/florida/1992-schedule.html |title=1992 Florida Gators |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161003183250/http://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/florida/1992-schedule.html |archivedate=2016-10-03 }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Florida Gators football, 1990\u20131999#1993|1993]] || [[1993 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]] || '''W''' 28\u201313<ref name=uf93/>\n|-\n| [[Florida Gators football, 1990\u20131999#1994|1994]] || [[1994 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]] || '''W''' 24\u201323<ref name=uf94/>\n|-\n| [[Florida Gators football, 1990\u20131999#1995|1995]] || [[1995 Arkansas Razorbacks football team|Arkansas]] || '''W''' 34\u20133<ref name=uf95/>\n|-\n| [[Florida Gators football, 1990\u20131999#1996|1996]] || [[1996 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]] || '''W''' 45\u201330<ref name=uf96/>\n|-\n| [[Florida