04|journal=Florida Historical Quarterly|volume=70 |pages=20\u201337|number=1|date=July 1991}}\n* {{cite book|last=McCarthy|first=Kevin M|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_Tk-IQepI6cC|title=Fightin' Gators: A History of University of Florida Football|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|location=Mount Pleasant, South Carolina|year=2000|isbn=978-0-7385-0559-6}}\n* {{cite book|last=McEwen|first=Tom|title=The Gators: A Story of Florida Football|publisher=The Strode Publishers|location=Huntsville, Alabama|year=1974|isbn=0-87397-025-X}}\n* Nash, Noel, ed., ''The Gainesville Sun Presents The Greatest Moments in Florida Gators Football'', Sports Publishing, Inc., Champaign, Illinois (1998).  {{ISBN|1-57167-196-X}}.\n*{{cite book|last=Pleasants|first=Julian M. |title=Gator Tales: An Oral History of the University of Florida|publisher=University of Florida|location=Gainesville, Florida|year=2006}}\n* Proctor, Samuel, & Wright Langley, ''Gator History: A Pictorial History of the University of Florida'', South Star Publishing Company, Gainesville, Florida (1986).  {{ISBN|0-938637-00-2}}.\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{Florida Gators football}}\n{{Florida Gators athletic program navbox}}\n{{Southeastern Conference football navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Florida Gators Football}}\n[[Category:Florida Gators football| ]]\n[[Category:Sports clubs established in 1906]]\n[[Category:1906 establishments in Florida]]\n", "name_user": "72.243.144.108", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(I gave the Florida fans what they wanted)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Florida_Gators_football"}
{"title_page": "Para-Commando Brigade (Bangladesh)", "text_new": "{{short description|Military unit of the Bangladesh Army}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name                     = Para-Commando Brigade\n| image                         = \n| image_size                    = 250px\n| dates                         = 2016\u2013 present\n| country                       = {{Flagdeco|Bangladesh }} Bangladesh\n| branch                        = {{army|Bangladesh}}\n| type                          = [[Special forces]]\n| role                          = {{plainlist|\n* [[Special Operations]]\n* [[Counter terrorism]]\n* [[Hostage rescue]]\n* [[Special reconnaissance]] \n* [[Counter narcotics]]\n* [[Military intelligence|Intelligence gathering]]\n* [[Counter insurgency]]\n}}\n| motto                         = ''Do or Die''\n| size                          = 3 Battalions\n| garrison                      = Sylhet Cantonment\n| garrison_label                = \n| nickname                      = The Cheetahs\n| patron                        = \n| colors                        = Maroon\n| colors_label                  = \n| march                         = \n| mascot                        = Cheetah\n| battles                       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Bangladesh Liberation War]] \n* [[Chittagong Hill Tracts conflict|Chittagong Hill trucks counter-insurgency]]\n* [[United Nations Peacekeeping]]\n* [[Operation Thunderbolt (2016)|Operation Thunderbolt]]\n* [[Operation Twilight in Sylhet]] <ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/country/operation-twilight-sylhet-militant-den-ends-1382671 |title='Operation Twilight' at Sylhet militant den ends |work=The Daily Star|date=28 March 2017}}</ref>\n* [[January 2019 Bambari clashes|Operation BEKPA 2]] \n}}\n| anniversaries                 = \n| decorations                   = \n| battle_honours                = \n| disbanded                     = \n| commander1                    = Brigadier General Muhsin Alam, NDC, PSC<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ispr.gov.bd/\u09ae\u09b9\u09be\u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u09cd\u09af-\u09b0\u09be\u09b7\u09cd\u099f\u09cd\u09b0\u09aa\u09a4\u09bf-\u0995\u09b0\u09cd-2/ |script-title=bn:\u09ae\u09b9\u09be\u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u09cd\u09af \u09b0\u09be\u09b7\u09cd\u099f\u09cd\u09b0\u09aa\u09a4\u09bf \u0995\u09b0\u09cd\u09a4\u09c3\u0995 \u09e7 \u09aa\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09b0\u09be \u0995\u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u09cd\u09a1\u09cb \u09ac\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u099f\u09be\u09b2\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09a8\u2019\u0995\u09c7 \u099c\u09be\u09a4\u09c0\u09af\u09bc \u09aa\u09a4\u09be\u0995\u09be \u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a6\u09be\u09a8 |website=Inter Services Public Relation Directorate |language=bn}}</ref>\n| notable_commanders            = \n}}\n\nThe '''Para-Commando Brigade''' is an independent special operations brigade of the [[Bangladesh Army]]. The brigade was officially formed on 4 September 2016.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/backpage/dhaka-cafe-attack-recounting-operation-thunderbolt-1427413 |title=Recounting 'Operation Thunderbolt' |work=The Daily Star |date=3 July 2017 |access-date=2017-11-17}}</ref> The brigade got its full structure and strength on 10 October 2019.\n\n==History==\n===Crack Platoon===\nCrack Platoon was a specialized commando unit of Muktibahini during the liberation war of Bangladesh. The commando officer Major [[A.T.M. Haider|A.T.M Haider]] (a former SSG commando in Pakistan Army) formed this unit under the command of sector no-2. Sector commander [[Khaled Mosharraf|Khaled Mosarrof]] personally took care of this unit.\nIn June 1971, commander Khaled made a plan to send commandos in Dhaka city. Because a delegation came from World Bank to visit the East-Pakistan(Now Bangladesh). For that,The Pakistan government was trying to show them, everything was normal in Dhaka. But The commander of sector-2, Khaled Mosarrof was trying to show the whole world that situation was not normal in Dhaka. For that, he along with Commando Major Haider made a plan to launch a commando assault in Dhaka City. They decided to send the specialized platoon-\"Y\" (which was renamed as Crack-Platoon) in Dhaka City. The Commandos successfully launched some operations in Dhaka city and showed the whole world that nothing was normal there.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/star-weekend/chronicles/brave-hearts-73724 |title=Brave Hearts |date=27 March 2015 |work=The Daily Star}}</ref>\n\nThe platoon's operations included:<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/opinion/they-gave-their-today-our-tomorrow-1455394 |title=They gave their today, for our tomorrow |work=The Daily Star |type=Opinion |date=29 August 2017 |access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref>\n# [[Operation Hotel Intercontinental]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/operation-hotel-intercontinental-hit-run-53723 |title=Operation Hotel Intercontinental: \"HIT & RUN\" |work=The Daily Star |date=6 December 2014}}</ref>\n# Operation Five power stations\n# Operation Farmgate\n# Operation Dhanmondi\n# Operation Green road\n\n===Special Warfare Wing===\n{{unsourced section|date=December 2019}}\n[[File:Bangladesh Army Commandos (23113309084).jpg|thumbnail|right|Bangladesh Army Para-Commando troop at Victory Day Parade 2015.]]\nIn 1976, [[Special Warfare Wing]] was established at Chittagong Cantonment. Later, it was shifted to the [[Jalalabad Cantonment|Sylhet]] cantonment. From then this wing started working under the Bangladesh Army [[School of Infantry and Tactics]] (SI&T). This was the first step towards the formation of a special force in Independent Bangladesh. In 1980, the army commando course and the counter-insurgency course was started in special warfare wing. In the same year, the Special Warfare Wing was expanded to special warfare school. The [[Bangladesh Army Airborne School|Army Airborne School]] was established in 1988 at Sylhet Cantonment under Special Warfare Wing. In 1988, the first para training course was started at the Special Warfare School.\n\n===1st Para-Commando Battalion===\nOn 30 June 1992, the 1st Para-Commando Battalion started its journey at [[Jalalabad Cantonment]] of Sylhet.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/city/stay-alert-deal-unexpected-situation-1485727 |title=Stay alert to deal with unexpected situation |work=The Daily Star |date=3 November 2017 |access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref> The flag of the battalion was raised in May 1993. On 1 June 2015, 1st Para-Commando Battalion came out as a full-fledged regiment. After the formation of ad-hoc Para-Commando Brigade on 4 September 2016, they started working under the command of the Brigade.\n\nThe battalion was awarded the national standard on 2 November 2017 as a recognition of their outstanding works.<ref name=\"pcdo\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dailybdnews.net/?p=25355 |script-title=bn:\u099c\u09be\u09a4\u09c0\u09af\u09bc \u09aa\u09a4\u09be\u0995\u09be \u09aa\u09be\u099a\u09cd\u099b\u09c7\u09a8 \u09aa\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09b0\u09be \u0995\u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u09cd\u09a1\u09cb\u09b0\u09be |publisher=Dailybdnews.com |date=2 November 2017 |language=bn |access-date=5 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Structure==\nUnder this brigade's command, there are three Para-Commando battalions. They are:\n* 1st Para-Commando Battalion, headquartered in [[Sylhet]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dsebd.org/pdf/COO_September_08_2011.pdf |title=Brig Gen Zahur given Responsibility of CEO (Current Charge), DSE |publisher=[[Dhaka Stock Exchange]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120516085801/http://dsebd.org/pdf/COO_September_08_2011.pdf |archive-date=16 May 2012}}</ref>\n* 2nd Para-Commando Battalion, headquartered in [[Sreemangal Upazila]], [[Maulavibazar]]\n* 3rd Para-Commando Battalion (Ad-hoc Para-Commando Battalion), [[Sylhet]]\n\nAs typical [[commando]] battalions, these battalions are quite understrength compared to a regular Bangladesh Army infantry battalion, in terms of both manpower and firepower. Each Para-Commando battalion is Consisted of a HQ company and 3 Operations Companies. Each company has separate troops of various specialties i.e. Air Assault, Reconnaissance, Jungle Warfare etc. Battalions also includes of medical, signals and other support personnel, all of whom are airborne and commando qualified.\n\n== Equipment ==\n{{unsourced section|date=December 2019}}\n; Pistols\n* [[QSZ-92]]\n* [[Bersa Thunder 9]]\n* [[Browning Hi-Power]]\n\n; Sub-machine guns\n* [[Heckler & Koch MP5]]\n* [[SIG MPX]]\n* [[Kriss Vector|Kriss Vector GEN II]]\n\n; Assault rifles\n* [[Type 81 assault rifle|BD-08 assault rifle]]\n* [[Type 56 assault rifle]]\n* [[Pindad SS2|Pindad SS2-V5]]\n* [[M4 carbine]]\n* [[Steyr AUG]]\n\n; Sniper rifles\n* [[Dragunov sniper rifle]]\n* [[Barrett M82]]\n* [[M24 Sniper Weapon System]]\n* [[Accuracy International Arctic Warfare]]\n* [[Accuracy International AWM]]\n\n; Machine guns and rocket launchers\n* [[Type 81 assault rifle|BD-08 LMG]]\n* [[Type 69 RPG]]\n\n; Transport\n* [[Polaris Inc.|Polaris]] [[All-terrain vehicle]]\n\n== Operations ==\n[[File:Bangladesh-peacekeepers-04.jpg|alt=|thumb|135x135px|Bangladesh Army Para-Commando member building trust with the locals as part of their UN mission]]\n\n===United Nations peacekeeping===\nBangladesh is participating in different [[United Nations peacekeeping|UN peacekeeping]] missions since 1988. Currently, Bangladesh is one of the largest contributors of the UN peacekeeping operations. Bangladesh Army has deployed its Special Forces in various UN Peacekeeping and Peace Enforcement missions, notably in Ivory Coast, South Sudan, Darfur, Central African Republic, Haiti and Mali. These Special Forces detachments are often tasked with high risk rescue operations and raids against insurgents.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/city/news/bangladeshs-peacekeeping-role-lauded-1688221 |title=Bangladesh's peacekeeping role lauded |work=The Daily Star |date=16 January 2019 |access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/backpage/un-official-praises-bangladeshs-role-1595401 |title=UN official praises Bangladesh's role |work=The Daily Star |date=26 June 2018 |access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Saha |first=Amity |url=http://dailyasianage.com/news/39719/bangladeshs-role-in-intl-peacekeeping |title=Bangladesh's role in int\u00e2\u20ac\u2122l peacekeeping |work=The Asian Age |location=Dhaka |access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref>\n\n=== Dhaka Holey Artisan Bakery hostage crisis ===\n[[File:Para-Commandos during Operation Thunderbolt.jpg|thumb|171x171px|Para-Commandos in action during <nowiki>''</nowiki>Operation Thunderbolt<nowiki>''</nowiki> at Holey Artisan in Gulshan on the morning of July 2, 2016]]\nOn 1 July 2016, five assailants stormed the Holey Artisan Bakery with crude bombs, machetes, ak 22 rifle and pistols, in Dhaka's affluent neighborhood, [[Gulshan Thana|Gulshan 2]], which is extremely popular among expatriates and foreigners, at roughly 9:20&nbsp;pm, taking hostage of the locals and foreigners inside.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160702114529/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-36692613 |archive-date=2 July 2016 |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-36692613 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=2 July 2016 |title=Bangladesh siege: Twenty killed at Holey Artisan Bakery in Dhaka}}</ref> Not realising the gravity of the situation, the initial assault to secure the premises, commenced by [[Dhaka Metropolitan Police]], resulted in the casualties of two police officers in exchanging gunfire with the assailants.\n<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/world/commandos-storm-dhaka-restaurant-several-hostages-rescued-1.2969719 |publisher=[[CTV News]] |title=Commandos storm Dhaka restaurant, several hostages rescued |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=2 July 2016}}</ref> However, Police and the [[Rapid Action Battalion]] acted with celerity in setting up a perimeter around the Bakery to block escape of any assailant.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/03/world/asia/bangladesh-hostage-standoff.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=2 July 2016 |first1=Julfikar Ali |last1=Manik |first2=Geeta |last2=Anand |first3=Ellen |last3=Barry |title=Bangladesh Attack Is New Evidence That ISIS Has Shifted Its Focus Beyond the Mideast}}</ref> After fruitless hours of seeking to bring a peaceful solution to the problem, when the perpetrators refused to communicate with authorities, the realisation set that alternative measures were required.<ref name=\"NYT\" />\n\nAt an early morning meeting on Saturday (2 July), the highest level of Government decided to engage the 1st Commando Battalion. They were flown in from [[Sylhet]] to carry out a counter-assault and free the hostages.<ref name=\"NYT\" /><ref name=\"Telegraph\" /> After gathering intelligence from RAB and the Police forces present on the ground, Commandos initiated their raid (codenamed \"[[2016 Gulshan, Dhaka attack|Operation Thunderbolt]]\"), which began at 7:40&nbsp;am and concluded at 8:30&nbsp;am.<ref name=\"BBC\" /><ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/01/gunmen-attack-restaurant-in-diplomatic-quarter-of-bangladeshi-ca/ |title=20 hostages killed in 'Isil' attack on Dhaka restaurant popular with foreigners |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=2 July 2016 |first1=Andrew |last1=Marszal |first2=Chris |last2=Graham |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701180629/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/01/gunmen-attack-restaurant-in-diplomatic-quarter-of-bangladeshi-ca/ |archive-date=1 July 2016}}</ref> They were successfully able to free 13 hostages and kill the assailants.<ref name=\"Telegraph\" />\n\nDuring the attack, 9 Italians, 7 Japanese, 2 Bangladeshis, 1 Indian, and 1 American were killed by the perpetrators.<ref name=\"BBC\" /><ref name=\"NYT\" />\n\n===Operation Twilight in Sylhet===\n[[File:Para Commando Counter-Terrorism Members during Operation Twilight in Sylhet.png|thumb|Para Commando Counter-Terrorism Members during Operation Twilight in Sylhet]]\nOn Thursday, 23 March 2017, the [[Bangladesh Police]] surrounded a suspected militant hideout in [[Dakshin Surma Upazila]], [[Sylhet]], [[Bangladesh]]. Later, a [[SWAT (Bangladesh)|SWAT team]] joined the police unit from [[Dhaka]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Manik |first=Julfikar Ali |last2=Anand |first2=Geeta |date=26 March 2017 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/26/world/asia/bangladeshi-assault-kills-2-militants-but-fails-to-end-standoff.html |title=Bangladeshi Assault Kills 2 Militants but Fails to End Standoff |work=The New York Times |access-date=2017-03-26}}</ref> The housing complex has two apartment buildings. The Police unit was reinforced with personal from [[Rapid Action Battalion]] on Friday.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news |url=http://bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2017/03/26/it-seems-the-army-has-settled-for-a-long-haul-in-sylhet-to-neutralise-the-militants |title=It seems the army has settled for a long haul in Sylhet to neutralise the militants |work=bdnews24.com |access-date=2017-03-26}}</ref> On Saturday, the 1st Para Commando Battalion took charge of operations and named it Operation Twilight.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n[[Operation Twilight (Bangladesh)|Operation Twilight]] was launched by the 1st Para-Commando Battalion of the adhoc para-commando brigade of the [[Bangladesh Army]] under the command of GOC of [[17th Infantry Division (Bangladesh)|17th Infantry Division]] in [[Jalalabad Cantonment]] Major General [[Anwarul Momen]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://en.prothom-alo.com/bangladesh/news/143389/Blasts-during-Sylhet-hideout-operation-kill-4 |title=Blasts during Sylhet hideout operation kill 6 |work=Prothom Alo |access-date=2017-03-26}}</ref> The main gate of the building was blocked by the militants with a refrigerator with an IED attached to it.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/country/joint-operation-begins-sylhet-militant-den-1381165 |title=3 killed, 31 hurt in blasts outside Sylhet 'militant den' |work=The Daily Star |date=25 March 2017 |access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref> The building had 30 apartments and 150 rooms, the militants were constantly changing their location.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/frontpage/3-killed-sylhet-blasts-1381498 |title=Blasts kill 5 amid raid |work=The Daily Star |date=26 March 2017 |access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref> The operation was launched on Saturday morning around 8am. The Commando unit was being assisted by SWAT and Bangladesh Police.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://en.prothom-alo.com/bangladesh/news/143307/Jt-forces-anti-militant-operation-launched |title=Jt forces' anti-militant 'operation' launched |work=Prothom Alo |access-date=2017-03-26}}</ref> Security forces established a three kilometre perimeter around the militant hideout. The commandos rescued 78 civilians trapped in the building from Thursday.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2017/03/26/gunfire-blasts-heard-as-sylhet-militant-hideout-siege-enters-third-day |title=Gunfire, blasts heard as Sylhet militant hideout siege enters third day |work=bdnews24.com |access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref> Two militants were killed in the initial attack, one of who detonated a suicide vest. The militants had planted [[Improvised explosive device|IEDs]] all over the building which slowed down the military operation.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2017/03/26/two-killed-more-well-trained-militants-inside-says-army-in-sylhet-anti-terror-operation |title=Two killed, more \u2018well-trained\u2019 militants inside, says army in Sylhet |work=bdnews24.com |access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref> Army spokesman, Brigadier General Fakhrul Ahsan, reported that the operation would take more time because of the presence of IEDs in \"strategic points\" in the building. The Bangladesh Army used RPGs and shells to drive the militants out without much success.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/country/sporadic-gunshots-mark-day-3-sylhet-militant-den-raid-1381606 |title=2 militants killed, Sylhet raid to linger: Army |work=The Daily Star |date=26 March 2017 |access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref> The commandos also used Armoured Personnel Carriers in the operation.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/bangladesh-commandos-storm-militants-hideout-in-sylhet-rescue-78-civilians/story-scjqEjp63auHmjsHsTWEpK.html |title=Bangladesh commandos storm militants hideout in Sylhet, rescue 78 civilians |work=Hindustan Times |date=25 March 2017 |access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref> Finally four militants were found dead at the hideout.<ref name=\"dailystar1\">{{cite news |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/country/sporadic-firing-heard-sylhet-raid-rolls-day-4-1382035 |title=4 militants dead at Sylhet den: Army |newspaper=The Daily Star |access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref><ref name=\"dtribune\">{{cite news |url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/crime/2017/03/24/live-police-cordon-off-militant-hideout-sylhet/ |title=Live: Four militants killed as Sylhet raid nears end |newspaper=Dhaka Tribune |access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref>\n\n===Operation BEKPA 2===\nAfter the failure of two countries, Bangladesh Special Forces (BANSF) in the United Nations Peacekeeping Mission has successfully launched an operation against rebel groups in the Central African Republic.\n\nCaptain Tauquir Ahmed of BANSF-3 leads the bloody operation to free the area from rebel party UPC (United municipal La P\u00e9x en Centrifica) with an efficient leadership. At the same time, around 150 prisoners were rescued by the operation.\n===Operation Chiitagong Airport===\nIn 24 February 2019, a Bangladeshi Boeing 737-800 aircraft was hijacked by a gunman on the air. The aircraft was landed to the Chittagong Airport as an emergency landing while it was going to Dubai from Dhaka. A gunman named Palash tried to hijack the aircraft. Though his intention was not clear the authority was trying to negotiate with him. But when everything was failed and then Government ordered the ParaCommando Brigade to Launch an operation. Paracommando brigade members came to the place and launched an operation. The commandos took only eight minutes to make a conclusion. As a result, the hijacker was shoot dead by the commandos, 148 passengers and crew got free from the hostage situation.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/city/biman-bangladesh-airlines-plane-hijacker-killed-swift-operation-8-minute-1706659 |title=A swift operation of 8 minutes |work=The Daily Star |date=24 February 2019 |access-date=2019-06-15}}</ref>\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{commons category|Para-Commando Brigade (Bangladesh)}}\n\n[[Category:Counter-terrorist organizations]]\n[[Category:Military awards and decorations of Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Bangladesh Army]]\n[[Category:Special forces of Bangladesh]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Military unit of the Bangladesh Army}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name                     = Para-Commando Brigade\n| image                         = \n| image_size                    = 250px\n| dates                         = 2016\u2013 present\n| country                       = {{Flagdeco|Bangladesh }} Bangladesh\n| branch                        = {{army|Bangladesh}}\n| type                          = [[Special forces]]\n| role                          = {{plainlist|\n* [[Special Operations]]\n* [[Counter terrorism]]\n* [[Hostage rescue]]\n* [[Special reconnaissance]] \n* [[Counter narcotics]]\n* [[Military intelligence|Intelligence gathering]]\n* [[Counter insurgency]]\n}}\n| motto                         = ''Do or Die''\n| size                          = 3 Battalions\n| garrison                      = Sylhet Cantonment\n| garrison_label                = \n| nickname                      = The Cheetahs\n| patron                        = \n| colors                        = Maroon\n| colors_label                  = \n| march                         = \n| mascot                        = Cheetah\n| battles                       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Bangladesh Liberation War]] \n* [[Chittagong Hill Tracts conflict|Chittagong Hill trucks counter-insurgency]]\n* [[United Nations Peacekeeping]]\n* [[Operation Thunderbolt (2016)|Operation Thunderbolt]]\n* [[Operation Twilight in Sylhet]] <ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/country/operation-twilight-sylhet-militant-den-ends-1382671 |title='Operation Twilight' at Sylhet militant den ends |work=The Daily Star|date=28 March 2017}}</ref>\n* [[January 2019 Bambari clashes|Operation BEKPA 2]] \n}}\n| anniversaries                 = \n| decorations                   = \n| battle_honours                = \n| disbanded                     = \n| commander1                    = Brigadier General Muhsin Alam, NDC, PSC<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ispr.gov.bd/\u09ae\u09b9\u09be\u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u09cd\u09af-\u09b0\u09be\u09b7\u09cd\u099f\u09cd\u09b0\u09aa\u09a4\u09bf-\u0995\u09b0\u09cd-2/ |script-title=bn:\u09ae\u09b9\u09be\u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u09cd\u09af \u09b0\u09be\u09b7\u09cd\u099f\u09cd\u09b0\u09aa\u09a4\u09bf \u0995\u09b0\u09cd\u09a4\u09c3\u0995 \u09e7 \u09aa\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09b0\u09be \u0995\u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u09cd\u09a1\u09cb \u09ac\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u099f\u09be\u09b2\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09a8\u2019\u0995\u09c7 \u099c\u09be\u09a4\u09c0\u09af\u09bc \u09aa\u09a4\u09be\u0995\u09be \u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a6\u09be\u09a8 |website=Inter Services Public Relation Directorate |language=bn}}</ref>\n| notable_commanders            = \n}}\n\nThe '''Para-Commando Brigade''' is an independent special operations brigade of the [[Bangladesh Army]]. The brigade was officially formed on 4 September 2016.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/backpage/dhaka-cafe-attack-recounting-operation-thunderbolt-1427413 |title=Recounting 'Operation Thunderbolt' |work=The Daily Star |date=3 July 2017 |access-date=2017-11-17}}</ref> The brigade got its full structure and strength on 10 October 2019.\n\n==History==\n===Crack Platoon===\nCrack Platoon was a specialized commando unit of Muktibahini during the liberation war of Bangladesh. The commando officer Major [[A.T.M. Haider|A.T.M Haider]] (a former SSG commando in Pakistan Army) formed this unit under the command of sector no-2. Sector commander [[Khaled Mosharraf|Khaled Mosarrof]] personally took care of this unit.\nIn June 1971, commander Khaled made a plan to send commandos in Dhaka city. Because a delegation came from World Bank to visit the East-Pakistan(Now Bangladesh). For that,The Pakistan government was trying to show them, everything was normal in Dhaka. But The commander of sector-2, Khaled Mosarrof was trying to show the whole world that situation was not normal in Dhaka. For that, he along with Commando Major Haider made a plan to launch a commando assault in Dhaka City. They decided to send the specialized platoon-\"Y\" (which was renamed as Crack-Platoon) in Dhaka City. The Commandos successfully launched some operations in Dhaka city and showed the whole world that nothing was normal there.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/star-weekend/chronicles/brave-hearts-73724 |title=Brave Hearts |date=27 March 2015 |work=The Daily Star}}</ref>\n\nThe platoon's operations included:<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/opinion/they-gave-their-today-our-tomorrow-1455394 |title=They gave their today, for our tomorrow |work=The Daily Star |type=Opinion |date=29 August 2017 |access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref>\n# [[Operation Hotel Intercontinental]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/operation-hotel-intercontinental-hit-run-53723 |title=Operation Hotel Intercontinental: \"HIT & RUN\" |work=The Daily Star |date=6 December 2014}}</ref>\n# Operation Five power stations\n# Operation Farmgate\n# Operation Dhanmondi\n# Operation Green road\n\n===Special Warfare Wing===\n{{unsourced section|date=December 2019}}\n[[File:Bangladesh Army Commandos (23113309084).jpg|thumbnail|right|Bangladesh Army Para-Commando troop at Victory Day Parade 2015.]]\nIn 1976, [[Special Warfare Wing]] was established at Chittagong Cantonment. Later, it was shifted to the [[Jalalabad Cantonment|Sylhet]] cantonment. From then this wing started working under the Bangladesh Army [[School of Infantry and Tactics]] (SI&T). This was the first step towards the formation of a special force in Independent Bangladesh. In 1980, the army commando course and the counter-insurgency course was started in special warfare wing. In the same year, the Special Warfare Wing was expanded to special warfare school. The [[Bangladesh Army Airborne School|Army Airborne School]] was established in 1988 at Sylhet Cantonment under Special Warfare Wing. In 1988, the first para training course was started at the Special Warfare School.\n\n===1st Para-Commando Battalion===\nOn 30 June 1992, the 1st Para-Commando Battalion started its journey at [[Jalalabad Cantonment]] of Sylhet.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/city/stay-alert-deal-unexpected-situation-1485727 |title=Stay alert to deal with unexpected situation |work=The Daily Star |date=3 November 2017 |access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref> The flag of the battalion was raised in May 1993. On 1 June 2015, 1st Para-Commando Battalion came out as a full-fledged regiment. After the formation of ad-hoc Para-Commando Brigade on 4 September 2016, they started working under the command of the Brigade.\n\nThe battalion was awarded the national standard on 2 November 2017 as a recognition of their outstanding works.<ref name=\"pcdo\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dailybdnews.net/?p=25355 |script-title=bn:\u099c\u09be\u09a4\u09c0\u09af\u09bc \u09aa\u09a4\u09be\u0995\u09be \u09aa\u09be\u099a\u09cd\u099b\u09c7\u09a8 \u09aa\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09b0\u09be \u0995\u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u09cd\u09a1\u09cb\u09b0\u09be |publisher=Dailybdnews.com |date=2 November 2017 |language=bn |access-date=5 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Structure==\nUnder this brigade's command, there are three Para-Commando battalions. They are:\n* 1st Para-Commando Battalion, headquartered in [[Sylhet]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dsebd.org/pdf/COO_September_08_2011.pdf |title=Brig Gen Zahur given Responsibility of CEO (Current Charge), DSE |publisher=[[Dhaka Stock Exchange]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120516085801/http://dsebd.org/pdf/COO_September_08_2011.pdf |archive-date=16 May 2012}}</ref>\n* 2nd Para-Commando Battalion, headquartered in [[Sreemangal Upazila]], [[Maulavibazar]]\n* 3rd Para-Commando Battalion (Ad-hoc Para-Commando Battalion), [[Sylhet]]\n\nAs typical [[commando]] battalions, these battalions are quite understrength compared to a regular Bangladesh Army infantry battalion, in terms of both manpower and firepower. Each Para-Commando battalion is Consisted of a HQ company and 3 Operations Companies. Each company has separate troops of various specialties i.e. Air Assault, Reconnaissance, Jungle Warfare etc. Battalions also includes of medical, signals and other support personnel, all of whom are airborne and commando qualified.\n\n== Equipment ==\n{{unsourced section|date=December 2019}}\n; Pistols\n* [[QSZ-92]]\n* [[Bersa Thunder 9]]\n* [[Browning Hi-Power]]\n\n; Sub-machine guns\n* [[Heckler & Koch MP5]]\n* [[SIG MPX]]\n* [[Kriss Vector|Kriss Vector GEN II]]\n\n; Assault rifles\n* [[Type 81 assault rifle|BD-08 assault rifle]]\n* [[Type 56 assault rifle]]\n* [[Pindad SS2|Pindad SS2-V5]]\n* [[M4 carbine]]\n* [[Steyr AUG]]\n\n; Sniper rifles\n* [[Dragunov sniper rifle]]\n* [[Barrett M82]]\n* [[M24 Sniper Weapon System]]\n* [[Accuracy International Arctic Warfare]]\n* [[Accuracy International AWM]]\n\n; Machine guns and rocket launchers\n* [[Type 81 assault rifle|BD-08 LMG]]\n* [[Type 69 RPG]]\n\n; Transport\n* [[Polaris Inc.|Polaris]] [[All-terrain vehicle]]\n\n== Operations ==\n[[File:Bangladesh-peacekeepers-04.jpg|alt=|thumb|135x135px|Bangladesh Army Para-Commando member building trust with the locals as part of their UN mission]]\n\n===United Nations peacekeeping===\nBangladesh is participating in different [[United Nations peacekeeping|UN peacekeeping]] missions since 1988. Currently, Bangladesh is one of the largest contributors of the UN peacekeeping operations. Bangladesh Army has deployed its Special Forces in various UN Peacekeeping and Peace Enforcement missions, notably in Ivory Coast, South Sudan, Darfur, Central African Republic, Haiti and Mali. These Special Forces detachments are often tasked with high risk rescue operations and raids against insurgents.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/city/news/bangladeshs-peacekeeping-role-lauded-1688221 |title=Bangladesh's peacekeeping role lauded |work=The Daily Star |date=16 January 2019 |access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/backpage/un-official-praises-bangladeshs-role-1595401 |title=UN official praises Bangladesh's role |work=The Daily Star |date=26 June 2018 |access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Saha |first=Amity |url=http://dailyasianage.com/news/39719/bangladeshs-role-in-intl-peacekeeping |title=Bangladesh's role in int\u00e2\u20ac\u2122l peacekeeping |work=The Asian Age |location=Dhaka |access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref>\n\n=== Dhaka Holey Artisan Bakery hostage crisis ===\n[[File:Para-Commandos during Operation Thunderbolt.jpg|thumb|171x171px|Para-Commandos in action during <nowiki>''</nowiki>Operation Thunderbolt<nowiki>''</nowiki> at Holey Artisan in Gulshan on the morning of July 2, 2016]]\nOn 1 July 2016, five assailants stormed the Holey Artisan Bakery with crude bombs, machetes, ak 22 rifle and pistols, in Dhaka's affluent neighborhood, [[Gulshan Thana|Gulshan 2]], which is extremely popular among expatriates and foreigners, at roughly 9:20&nbsp;pm, taking hostage of the locals and foreigners inside.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160702114529/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-36692613 |archive-date=2 July 2016 |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-36692613 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=2 July 2016 |title=Bangladesh siege: Twenty killed at Holey Artisan Bakery in Dhaka}}</ref> Not realising the gravity of the situation, the initial assault to secure the premises, commenced by [[Dhaka Metropolitan Police]], resulted in the casualties of two police officers in exchanging gunfire with the assailants.\n<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/world/commandos-storm-dhaka-restaurant-several-hostages-rescued-1.2969719 |publisher=[[CTV News]] |title=Commandos storm Dhaka restaurant, several hostages rescued |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=2 July 2016}}</ref> However, Police and the [[Rapid Action Battalion]] acted with celerity in setting up a perimeter around the Bakery to block escape of any assailant.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/03/world/asia/bangladesh-hostage-standoff.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=2 July 2016 |first1=Julfikar Ali |last1=Manik |first2=Geeta |last2=Anand |first3=Ellen |last3=Barry |title=Bangladesh Attack Is New Evidence That ISIS Has Shifted Its Focus Beyond the Mideast}}</ref> After fruitless hours of seeking to bring a peaceful solution to the problem, when the perpetrators refused to communicate with authorities, the realisation set that alternative measures were required.<ref name=\"NYT\" />\n\nAt an early morning meeting on Saturday (2 July), the highest level of Government decided to engage the 1st Commando Battalion. They were flown in from [[Sylhet]] to carry out a counter-assault and free the hostages.<ref name=\"NYT\" /><ref name=\"Telegraph\" /> After gathering intelligence from RAB and the Police forces present on the ground, Commandos initiated their raid (codenamed \"[[2016 Gulshan, Dhaka attack|Operation Thunderbolt]]\"), which began at 7:40&nbsp;am and concluded at 8:30&nbsp;am.<ref name=\"BBC\" /><ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/01/gunmen-attack-restaurant-in-diplomatic-quarter-of-bangladeshi-ca/ |title=20 hostages killed in 'Isil' attack on Dhaka restaurant popular with foreigners |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=2 July 2016 |first1=Andrew |last1=Marszal |first2=Chris |last2=Graham |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701180629/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/01/gunmen-attack-restaurant-in-diplomatic-quarter-of-bangladeshi-ca/ |archive-date=1 July 2016}}</ref> They were successfully able to free 13 hostages and kill the assailants.<ref name=\"Telegraph\" />\n\nDuring the attack, 9 Italians, 7 Japanese, 2 Bangladeshis, 1 Indian, and 1 American were killed by the perpetrators.<ref name=\"BBC\" /><ref name=\"NYT\" />\n\n===Operation Twilight in Sylhet===\nOn Thursday, 23 March 2017, the [[Bangladesh Police]] surrounded a suspected militant hideout in [[Dakshin Surma Upazila]], [[Sylhet]], [[Bangladesh]]. Later, a [[SWAT (Bangladesh)|SWAT team]] joined the police unit from [[Dhaka]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Manik |first=Julfikar Ali |last2=Anand |first2=Geeta |date=26 March 2017 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/26/world/asia/bangladeshi-assault-kills-2-militants-but-fails-to-end-standoff.html |title=Bangladeshi Assault Kills 2 Militants but Fails to End Standoff |work=The New York Times |access-date=2017-03-26}}</ref> The housing complex has two apartment buildings. The Police unit was reinforced with personal from [[Rapid Action Battalion]] on Friday.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news |url=http://bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2017/03/26/it-seems-the-army-has-settled-for-a-long-haul-in-sylhet-to-neutralise-the-militants |title=It seems the army has settled for a long haul in Sylhet to neutralise the militants |work=bdnews24.com |access-date=2017-03-26}}</ref> On Saturday, the 1st Para Commando Battalion took charge of operations and named it Operation Twilight.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n[[Operation Twilight (Bangladesh)|Operation Twilight]] was launched by the 1st Para-Commando Battalion of the adhoc para-commando brigade of the [[Bangladesh Army]] under the command of GOC of [[17th Infantry Division (Bangladesh)|17th Infantry Division]] in [[Jalalabad Cantonment]] Major General [[Anwarul Momen]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://en.prothom-alo.com/bangladesh/news/143389/Blasts-during-Sylhet-hideout-operation-kill-4 |title=Blasts during Sylhet hideout operation kill 6 |work=Prothom Alo |access-date=2017-03-26}}</ref> The main gate of the building was blocked by the militants with a refrigerator with an IED attached to it.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/country/joint-operation-begins-sylhet-militant-den-1381165 |title=3 killed, 31 hurt in blasts outside Sylhet 'militant den' |work=The Daily Star |date=25 March 2017 |access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref> The building had 30 apartments and 150 rooms, the militants were constantly changing their location.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/frontpage/3-killed-sylhet-blasts-1381498 |title=Blasts kill 5 amid raid |work=The Daily Star |date=26 March 2017 |access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref> The operation was launched on Saturday morning around 8am. The Commando unit was being assisted by SWAT and Bangladesh Police.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://en.prothom-alo.com/bangladesh/news/143307/Jt-forces-anti-militant-operation-launched |title=Jt forces' anti-militant 'operation' launched |work=Prothom Alo |access-date=2017-03-26}}</ref> Security forces established a three kilometre perimeter around the militant hideout. The commandos rescued 78 civilians trapped in the building from Thursday.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2017/03/26/gunfire-blasts-heard-as-sylhet-militant-hideout-siege-enters-third-day |title=Gunfire, blasts heard as Sylhet militant hideout siege enters third day |work=bdnews24.com |access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref> Two militants were killed in the initial attack, one of who detonated a suicide vest. The militants had planted [[Improvised explosive device|IEDs]] all over the building which slowed down the military operation.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2017/03/26/two-killed-more-well-trained-militants-inside-says-army-in-sylhet-anti-terror-operation |title=Two killed, more \u2018well-trained\u2019 militants inside, says army in Sylhet |work=bdnews24.com |access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref> Army spokesman, Brigadier General Fakhrul Ahsan, reported that the operation would take more time because of the presence of IEDs in \"strategic points\" in the building. The Bangladesh Army used RPGs and shells to drive the militants out without much success.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/country/sporadic-gunshots-mark-day-3-sylhet-militant-den-raid-1381606 |title=2 militants killed, Sylhet raid to linger: Army |work=The Daily Star |date=26 March 2017 |access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref> The commandos also used Armoured Personnel Carriers in the operation.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/bangladesh-commandos-storm-militants-hideout-in-sylhet-rescue-78-civilians/story-scjqEjp63auHmjsHsTWEpK.html |title=Bangladesh commandos storm militants hideout in Sylhet, rescue 78 civilians |work=Hindustan Times |date=25 March 2017 |access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref> Finally four militants were found dead at the hideout.<ref name=\"dailystar1\">{{cite news |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/country/sporadic-firing-heard-sylhet-raid-rolls-day-4-1382035 |title=4 militants dead at Sylhet den: Army |newspaper=The Daily Star |access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref><ref name=\"dtribune\">{{cite news |url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/crime/2017/03/24/live-police-cordon-off-militant-hideout-sylhet/ |title=Live: Four militants killed as Sylhet raid nears end |newspaper=Dhaka Tribune |access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref>\n\n===Operation BEKPA 2===\nAfter the failure of two countries, Bangladesh Special Forces (BANSF) in the United Nations Peacekeeping Mission has successfully launched an operation against rebel groups in the Central African Republic.\n\nCaptain Tauquir Ahmed of BANSF-3 leads the bloody operation to free the area from rebel party UPC (United municipal La P\u00e9x en Centrifica) with an efficient leadership. At the same time, around 150 prisoners were rescued by the operation.\n===Operation Chiitagong Airport===\nIn 24 February 2019, a Bangladeshi Boeing 737-800 aircraft was hijacked by a gunman on the air. The aircraft was landed to the Chittagong Airport as an emergency landing while it was going to Dubai from Dhaka. A gunman named Palash tried to hijack the aircraft. Though his intention was not clear the authority was trying to negotiate with him. But when everything was failed and then Government ordered the ParaCommando Brigade to Launch an operation. Paracommando brigade members came to the place and launched an operation. The commandos took only eight minutes to make a conclusion. As a result, the hijacker was shoot dead by the commandos, 148 passengers and crew got free from the hostage situation.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/city/biman-bangladesh-airlines-plane-hijacker-killed-swift-operation-8-minute-1706659 |title=A swift operation of 8 minutes |work=The Daily Star |date=24 February 2019 |access-date=2019-06-15}}</ref>\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{commons category|Para-Commando Brigade (Bangladesh)}}\n\n[[Category:Counter-terrorist organizations]]\n[[Category:Military awards and decorations of Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Bangladesh Army]]\n[[Category:Special forces of Bangladesh]]\n", "name_user": "Squad 71", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOperation Twilight in Sylhet", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Para-Commando_Brigade_(Bangladesh)"}
{"title_page": "List of democratic socialists", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\nThis is a partial list of notable [[democratic socialists]].\n\n=== Politicians ===\n==== Heads of government ====\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Salvador Allende]], President of Chile (1970\u20131973){{sfn|Patsouras|2005|p=265|ps=: \"In Chile, where a large democratic socialist movement was in place for decades, a democratic socialist, Salvadore Allende, led a popular front electoral coalition, including Communists, to victory in 1970.\"}}<ref name=\"Medina\">{{cite book|last=Medina|first=Eden|title=Cybernetic Revolutionaries: Technology and Politics in Allende's Chile|date=2014|publisher=MIT Press|page=39|quote=[...] in Allende's democratic socialism.}}</ref><ref name=\"Winn\">{{cite book|last=Winn|first=Peter|title=Victims of the Chilean Miracle: Workers and Neoliberalism in the Pinochet Era, 1973\u20132002|date=2004|publisher=Duke University Press|page=16|quote=The Allende government that Pinochet overthrew in 1973 had been elected in 1970 on a platform of pioneering a democratic road to a democratic socialism.}}</ref>\n* [[Jacobo \u00c1rbenz]], President of Guatemala (1951\u20131954)<ref>[[Stephen Schlesinger|Stephen, Schlesinger]] (3 June 2011). [https://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/04/opinion/04schlesinger.html?_r=0 \"Ghosts of Guatemala's Past\"]. ''[[The New York Times]]''. Retrieved 21 July 2014.</ref>\n* [[Jacinda Ardern]], Prime Minister of New Zealand (2017\u2013present)<ref name=\"NZHerald\">{{cite web|last=Dann|first=Liam|title=Liam Dann: Not another Jacinda Ardern column|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/business/news/article.cfm?c_id=3&objectid=11898381|work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|accessdate=10 November 2017|date=6 August 2017}}</ref> \u2013 disputed<ref name=\"The Spinoff\">{{cite web|last=Mapp|first=Wayn|title=Jacinda Ardern is no radical, but the 21st-century face of Blair's Third Way|url=https://thespinoff.co.nz/politics/15-01-2018/jacinda-ardern-is-no-radi