wn''. Stanford University Press. p. 18.</ref>\n* [[James Callaghan]], Prime Minister of the United Kingdom (1976\u20131979)<ref>Williams, Shirley (27 March 2005). [https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/commentators/shirley-williams-he-was-the-embodiment-of-democratic-socialism-530047.html \"Shirley Williams: He was the embodiment of democratic socialism\"]. ''The Independent''. Retrieved 13 February 2020.</ref><ref>Morgan, Kenneth (5 June 2007). [https://www.gresham.ac.uk/lecture/transcript/print/leadership-and-change-prime-ministers-in-the-post-war-world-james-callaghan/ \"Leadership and Change: Prime Ministers in the Post-War World \u2013 James Callaghan\"]. Gresham College. Retrieved 13 February 2020. \"He believed himself to be a Democratic Socialist.\"</ref><ref>Clark, Neil (30 September 2007). [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2007/sep/20/howjimcallaghanchangedthe \"How Jim Callaghan changed the world\"]. ''The Guardian''. Retrieved 13 February 2020.</ref><ref>Williams, Shirley (3 December 2009). ''Climbing The Bookshelves: The Autobiography of Shirley Williams''. Hachette UK. {{ISBN|978-0-7481-1612-6}}. \"Jim Callaghan's political life ran in tandem with the rise and the decline of democratic socialism.\"</ref> \u2013 disputed<ref>Loades, David, ed. (10 July 2003). ''Reader's Guide to British History''. Routledge. {{ISBN|978-1-5795-8242-5}}.</ref><ref>Coates, Ken, ed. (31 October 2008). ''What Went Wrong?: Explaining the Fall of the Labour Government''. Spokesman Books. {{ISBN|978-0-8512-4754-0}}.</ref><ref>Steele, Tom; Taylor, Richard (21 April 2011). ''British Labour and Higher Education, 1945 to 2000: Ideologies, Policies and Practice''. Bloomsbury Publishing. {{ISBN|978-1-4411-3606-0}}. {{ASIN|B017PNUIJM}}. \"James Callaghan, a long-standing centre-right figure in the Labour Party [...].\"</ref>\n* [[Hugo Ch\u00e1vez]], President of Venezuela (1999\u20132013)<ref>{{cite web|title=Hugo Chavez|url=http://berkleycenter.georgetown.edu/people/hugo-chav